<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Coalition to Educate America, Press Conference on the NEA, July 1, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#400040" LINK="#400000" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#828282">
<!-- Coalition to Educate America.  Join our efforts, against all odds, to free American education from the vice-grip of the teacher unions and other special interests.  We shall overcome!  -->
<CENTER>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>The Coalition to Educate America Presents...<p>
<IMG SRC="../../gifs/logosm.gif" ALT="Coalition to Educate America" height=30><P>

THE PRESS CONFERENCE ON THE NATIONAL EDUCATION
ASSOCIATION<BR> July 1, 1996, National Press Club</FONT></B><P>
<A HREF="nea.tsp"><img src="../../gifs/tsmedium.gif" border=0 alt="True Speech"></A><BR>
<img src="http://www.schoolreport.com/cea/gifs/importan.gif"><A HREF="nea.tsp"><FONT SIZE=4>Sit back and listen to the Press Conference on the NEA (66 minutes)</A><a href="http://www.dspg.com"><BR>with the True Speech player (download player)</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/archives/teacherunions/1996/resptojuly1.htm">Read the NEA's Response!</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.c-span.org" >Order the video tape from C-SPAN at 1800-CSPAN98, # 073324. </A></FONT><BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
</CENTER>
<img src="armstr.gif" align=left alt="Armstrong Williams"><B>Armstrong Williams</B>: Good morning and welcome.  We have gathered here this morning
as the National Education Association convenes in this city for
its 1996 Convention in order to illustrate not just locally, but
nationally, the complete and utter hypocrisy that the NEA represents.
 In fact, many have labeled the NEA, the National Extortionist
Association.  In fact, you will be hearing from a number of individuals
who represent not only the field of education, but administrators
and parents as well.  Each one of them will describe, in no uncertain
terms, how an organization, whose initial purpose was to work
toward improving public education in America but in reality has
only served its only self-serving, plundering interests, destroying
our public schools and leaving them in a tragic state of ruin.
 <BR>

<P>
You know, in all fairness, when I was asked to make a few remarks
to kick off this press conference, I remember thinking to myself,
in the name of fairness and objectivity, &quot;How can I introduce
an aspect of impartiality into the subject of the National Education
Association.&quot;  &quot;Perhaps,&quot; I thought, &quot;I would
tell the American people how successfully the NEA works with low-income
families to help better educate their children to ensure them
the best possible start in life.&quot;  But of course, that would
not be true, since the NEA has recently helped strike down measures
such as school voucher programs that would allow less fortunate
children to attend private schools, vaguely claiming that the
programs violate the Constitution.  Well, then I said &quot;Well&#133;
think some more, there's <I>got</I> to be something there.&quot;
 I thought, &quot;Surely, I can mention how the NEA cooperates
with parents to develop the best possible curriculum, for intellectually
stimulating our children.&quot;  But once again, I had to come
to the realization that this too, is not true. For in all honesty,
the NEA has time and time again, illustrated its reluctance to
cooperate with parents, allowing them little say and involvement
in educating their children.<BR>

<P>
Suddenly, I really had to face the hard core facts, that no matter
how hard I tried to find some positive aspect in regards to the
NEA, it just could not be done.  However, what I did find, was
this organization has cleverly pulled the wool over the eyes of
America, causing us to turn a blind eye towards an organization
that thinks that it, and it alone, knows what is best when it
comes for the education of your children.  <BR>

<P>
What is even more interesting is that the two corners of the blanket
are being securely gripped by the two occupants of the White House.
 And I don't say that lightly.  What else is new?  After all,
their daughter does not attend public school.<BR>

<P>
What this press conference truly is, is a call to arms.  A call
to parents across this country, to stand together in order to
put an end to the self-serving interest of the NEA, and to bring
education and school choice back where it belongs: with the parents.
 Let's stop being walked on, and let's start doing the walking.
<BR>

<P>
It is my pleasure (applause).  And by the way, those of you who
don't know, I am Armstrong Williams, syndicated talk-show host
and columnist, but just an ordinary American who is concerned
about where education is headed in this country.  It's because
I love our children and the future that they could have in this
country, that I stand here today, with the forces that are here,
to see if we cannot change the educational system in this country
and change the NEA, once and for all.<BR>

<P>
Now, here's the format for this morning.  We have assembled some
very distinguished speakers.  I will introduce each speaker, and
the speakers have prepared remarks.  For those of you who are
members of the media, you can read their remarks in their entirety
out on the table.  We will ask that each speaker take 2-3 minutes
of opening remarks and then participate in an exchange with the
media.<BR>
<P>
Our first speaker, is Charlene Haar.  Ms. Haar is the co-author
of the 1994 book, <I>The NEA and the AFT: Teacher Unions in Power
and Politics</I>, with Dr. Myron Lieberman and Leo Troy.  A winner
of the distinguished South Dakota Teacher of the Year (<I>corrected</I>)
award, she currently serves as the President of the non-profit,
Education Policy Institute. Ms. Haar has written several articles
on the teacher unions and the national PTA.  Her book on the National
PTA will be published next year.  It is my distinct pleasure to
welcome you to this very important forum and I extend to you Ms.
Charlene Haar.  It's yours&#133; (applause)<BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<img src="haar2.gif" align=right alt="Charlene Haar"><B>Charlene Haar:</B>Thank you Armstrong.  Good morning.<BR>

<P>
Our meeting this morning is on the 2nd day of the 75th annual
convention of the NEA.  Amid all the praises, talk and press releases,
the public, the media and yes, even the delegates are likely to
miss the tremendous gap between NEA rhetoric and the reality of
what the NEA and its state and local affiliates are doing.  The
most urgent need at this convention is for <I>scrutiny</I> of
this huge teacher union conglomerate.  <BR>

<P>
Before you hear from several experts, who are especially knowledgeable
about various aspects of the National Education Association, 
I want to make three points.<BR>

<P>
First, the NEA is a huge <U>political</U> machine - far larger
and more powerful than most people know.
<P>
Second, The NEA uses deceptive tactics to make policy-makers and
members of the public accept their agenda.
<P>
Third, Despite their rhetoric about &quot;restructuring,&quot;
the NEA routinely blocks and sabotages efforts for meaningful
reform in education.<BR>

<P>
NEA has written the book - excuse me books on political action
(<I>shows NEA political manuals</I>).  Thousands of NEA-paid,
full-time political organizers are at work in every Congressional
District in America.  School boards, judges, county officials,
state legislators and of course federal candidates are elected
with the help of the National Education Association and its affiliates.
 The NEA employs more full time political operatives than our
two major political parties combined.<BR>
<img src="haar.gif" align=left>
<P>
At the local, state and national level, NEA revenues are about
$1 billion every year and it spends most of that money on political
programs, political consulting, communications with political
messages, and various campaign activities.<BR>

<P>
NEA-PAC is nearly a $6 million operation; in addition, a network
of NEA state and local affiliate political action committees (PACs),
pour millions into races at every level of our government; after
all buying allegiances pays off.<BR>

<P>
Second:  NEA is deceitful even to its own members.  Catchy advertising
and warm fuzzy pictures are paid-for-images which create another
myth, that unions care about kids.  Unions don't care for children!
 If you doubt this, look at the new business items - review the
candidate questionnaires.  They are all about MONEY - how to get
more.<BR>

<P>
And third:  What hypocrites the NEA are!   It publishes two manuals
on how to sabotage school board efforts to contract out services.
 Meanwhile, the NEA itself contracts out services - about 17%.
 The NEA's assertion that &quot;efficiency,&quot; &quot;competition,&quot;
 &quot;productivity,&quot; and &quot;accountability,&quot; would
hurt children is false; their concern is to protect the union
bureaucracy.<BR>

<P>
And here's a stack of teacher union/school district contracts
- noticeably absent are provisions for improving education for
our children.<BR>

<P>
NEA is now in the process of deunionizing its own terminology
while tightening its grip on American education.  New NEA convention
materials emphasize partnerships - expect your pockets to be picked
in any partnership with the NEA. <BR>

<P>
 By successfully defining the education reform debate in &quot;care-more
pay-more&quot; terms instead of outcomes and accountability, the
NEA is trying to convince politicians and the public, that more
money must be spent for education.  In fact, thousands of NEA
officers and staff are paid over $100,000 a year in salary and
benefits.  <U>They</U> are the beneficiaries of NEA programs;
the children of the United States are the losers. (applause)<BR>

<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P><B>Armstrong Williams:</B> Our next speaker is John Berthoud.  John Berthoud is Vice President
of the Alexis de Tocqueville Institution in Alexandria Virginia.
 Mr. Berthoud is also an adjunct lecturer at George Washington
University here in the nation's capitol where he teaches graduate
level courses on budgetary politics.  His works and writings have
appeared in publications such as the <I>Wall Street Journal, The
Washington Post, Investor's Business Daily, The Washington Times,
Public Interest, and Human Events</I>.  I very balanced gentleman,
I would say.  Mr. Berthoud holds a Ph.D. from Yale University,
an MA in International Affairs from Columbia, and a BA from Georgetown.
 Let us welcome our next speaker, John Berthoud. (applause)<BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<img src="berth2.gif" align=right alt="John Berthoud"><B>John Berthoud:</B> Thank you very much, Armstrong.  Good morning.  <BR>

<P>
One would be hard-pressed to find a legislative and political
agenda more damaging to the interests of America's children than
that of the National Education Association.  This is the clear
conclusion of three Tocqueville Institution studies of the NEA.
<BR>

<P>
We have conducted a detailed fiscal review of the NEA's <I>Legislative
Program for the 104<SUP>th</SUP> Congress</I> and this morning,
I'd like to outline the <I>Legislative Program's</I> impact on
1) deficits and 2) entitlements - two obvious areas of concern
for children.  We have also done two fiscal profiles of the Members
of Congress that NEA-PAC is supporting and opposing and I'll provide
a summary of these findings.<BR>

<P>
In our analysis of the <I>NEA Legislative Program</I>, we matched
the proposals in their wish list to CBO cost estimates of corresponding
bills and came to several stunning conclusions.  Most significantly,
we found that if every item was enacted, federal spending would
increase by at least $702 billion per year.<BR>

<P>
I should stress that we believe this figure is a conservative
estimate.<BR>

<P>
If not funded by deficits, the NEA agenda would translate into
an annual tax increase of $10,554 on a family of four.  The tax
increase would be 13 times the size of that in the 1993 budget
package.<BR>

<P>
While the NEA claims they'd like to lower the federal deficit,
given the magnitude of the funds required, we believe that the
much more likely result of adoption of the NEA Agenda would be
a) a large tax increase <I>and</I> b) a substantial increase in
the federal deficit.<BR>

<P>
The NEA of course tries to claim that it is more than a mere union
- they argue that much of its agenda is driven by the best interests
of children.  This contention however, is completely contradicted
by analyzing their entitlements agenda.  On issues like Social
Security and Medicare, their <I>Legislative Program</I> again
is diametrically opposed to the interests of America's kids. 
Let me give you several examples:<BR>

<P>
All told, the NEA would expand Social Security benefits for today's
retirees by $126.8 billion per year.<BR>

<P>
For each dollar in new spending on children and education that
the NEA proposes (over $24 billion annually), it advocates $5.24
in new spending on Social Security.<BR>

<P>
While the debate in Washington is (correctly, I'd argue) about
how much and how fast to raise the Social Security retirement
age, NEA is advocating lowering the retirement age.<BR>

<P>
For Medicare, they oppose many common-sense reforms such as means-testing.
<BR>

<P>
In sum, our major entitlement programs face grave fiscal imbalances
in the coming years which will require big sacrifices by today's
children and the NEA not only is doing nothing to correct these
problems but is seriously adding to them.<BR>

<P>
The NEA backs up their advocacy of big government with their campaign
contributions.  The Tocqueville Institution has done two analyses
on this issue - one which we just released last week.<BR>

<P>
In our new study, we have looked at NEA-PAC contributions to 1996
House and Senate candidates.  From January 1995 through the end
of April 1996, the NEA's Political Action Committee has contributed
$643,030 to Congressional candidates.<BR>

<P>
Analyzing the Members running in 1996 who have served in the 104<SUP>th</SUP>
Congress, it is clear that the NEA is financing candidates who
have voted to expand government, while opposing those who have
voted to cut it.  NEA-backed Senate and the House candidates on
average voted during the first session of the 104<SUP>th</SUP>
Congress to increase annual federal spending by $30.4 billion
and $28.9 billion respectively.  The Senate and House candidates
that the NEA is opposing voted to cut government by $31.8 billion
and $32.4 billion respectively.<BR>

<P>
Clearly, despite the NEA's rhetoric that their fiscal agenda is
just to stop draconian cuts in government, in reality the net
cuts made by the Members they are working to defeat have been
modest - about 2 percent of total federal spending.<BR>

<P>
While NEA-backed Members have voted for increases about as big
as the cuts voted for by NEA-opposed Members, there is more to
the story.  Of course, many NEA-supported Members did not have
an opportunity to vote for the spending increase legislation they
are espousing.<BR>

<P>
We can get a better idea of the real agendas of NEA-backed Members
by looking at their legislative wish lists - the bills these Members
are sponsoring and cosponsoring.  We have done that in an earlier
study of NEA-PAC contributions to House Members running for re-election
in 1994 and found that the average NEA-backed Member had an agenda
to increase federal spending by $302 billion per year.<BR>

<P>
Thus, the NEA is spending hundreds of thousands of dollars in
PAC money to a) defeat Members who have voted for modest cuts
in the size of government, and b) support Members who have voted
for modest increases, but who if given control of the legislative
agenda would radically expand government - by about 20 percent.
<BR>

<P>
This portrait of the NEA is not pretty, but this is what the numbers
tell us.  The political and legislative agenda of the NEA would
a) increase taxes, b) increase deficits, and c) greatly add to
the coming crises of our major entitlement programs.  The net
result is devastation for America's children. (applause)<BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<B>Armstrong Williams:</B> Thank you John.  You know it is important that you understand
today that this is, and it is an assault on the NEA, is not partisan.
 It's bipartisan. People from all walks of life have realized
what a devastating impact the NEA has had on education in this
country.  <BR>
<P>
Our next speaker, is Otis Troupe. Currently, Mr. Troupe is Executive
Director of Otis Troupe and Associates, a consulting firm that
specializes in the design and development of government programs.
 He was auditor of this city, of Washington D.C., for 13 years.
 Quite controversial, I would say, but honest, always had integrity,
and always told it exactly how he saw it, and reported it that
way. Now Mr. Troupe holds an MBA from Columbia University, JD
from Boston College Law, and a Bachelors from Yale.  Mr. Troupe
is a product of the D.C. schools. A &quot;product,&quot; I emphasize,
and comes from a family of school teachers.  He now serves on
the board of directors for FOCUS, Friends of Choice in Urban Schools,
a local group dedicated to bringing choice to the District of
Columbia.   It is my pleasure to welcome Otis Troupe. (applause)
<BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<img src="troupe.gif" align=left alt="Otis Troupe"><B>Otis Troupe:</B>Thank you very much Mr. Williams.  As you noted, I am a product
of the D.C. public school system.  In September of 1962, D.C.
public schools, public education in Washington D.C., put me on
the campus of Yale University.  I would entreat each of you to
think of the most inspiring, up the economic up the social ladder,
story of America, story of your own ethnicity perhaps, of your
own background in a big city.  Think of the most inspiring story
you have ever heard, and I will guarantee you that a clean, efficient,
uncorrupted, unmeddled with public school system was part of that
experience.  As I think of great numbers of my own group, Thurgood
Marshall, Ralph Bunche, all owe the things that they were able
to accomplish, to a strong program of public education. <BR>

<P>
That brings me now, to my particular posture.  I am very active
on the local level.  I will say to you that what I see on the
local level in my analysis of D.C. public schools strikes me as
a microcosm of what is going on nationally. What we have is a
failing system of delivery of education.  We have high parental
confusion and disenchantment. We have very, very low teacher morale.
We have a widespread, widespread perception, negative perception
of personal honesty and political motivations of both the superintendent
and the elected board, and the D.C. public school system, regrettably,
 is characterized by a bloated, administrative layer, whose only
priority is its own continuation.  I offer you this as a parallel
to the public education quandary in deliverance that we have here
in this country today.  We are putting entirely too many dollars
into areas that do not put the dollars directly to the children.
 And the waste is documentable.  I say to you that the reason
I offer my background as the auditor in my bio is that I reviewed
the numbers for these people for 12, 13 years.  The level of self-dealing,
the level of empire building, the level of political chicanery,
the level of application of dollars for personal, political agendas,
is nothing short of criminal.<BR>

<P>
I say to you that what was brought into the dialogue on voucher
schools and independent schools recently, by the NEA, regrettably,
they weighed in on the side of the people who frankly were holding
our children hostage to our own tax dollars.<BR>

<P>
If you look at the opponents to independent reform schools in
D.C., what you see is the NEA nationally, the Teamsters nationally,
the elected body of school officials, much of the elected body
of municipal officials, and the Washington teachers union.  Quite
frankly, very few of those people have any of their children in
public education in Washington D.C.  Fully 80 percent of our own
teachers' union sends their children elsewhere.  Let me say also,
let me direct you to one chilling statistic.  In our own University
of the District of Columbia, the level of remediation, in other
words, the time it takes an incoming freshman from our own public
school system to stop doing remedial and pre-college work, increased
in the past 10 years from 1 year, 1 month to 2 years, 9 months.
 What that says, ladies and gentleman, is that the public university
is doing the job of the public schools.  Every year we graduate
9,200-9,300 young people.  Believe me, 8,000 of them read below
the seventh grade level, do math below the fifth grade level.
 <BR>

<P>
To this, we offer, that there is a widespread disenchantment and
frankly disrespect for the leadership and output of D.C. public
schools. And out of this, is an increasing disposition by parents
groups, groups of concerned citizens groups to create an atmosphere
where any good-faith experiment in alternative education ought
to be given a chance.  I am very happy to talk to you on a number
of subjects having to do with vouchers and independents, that's
my committee.  What I will say, however, is that one of the things
we are trying to put in place in Washington D.C., and then also
was fought by the NEA and the education establishment, is that
we want to give a priority to new schools, publicly funded non-profit
academies, started up around partnerships between veteran and
big-city school teachers, administratively sophisticated churches,
and perhaps other sorts of citizens' groups.  This will move the
dollars from our tax payers to our principals and teachers, our
educators,  our troops in the trenches, and officially, what it
does, is bypasses the existence of the centralized, wasteful,
down-town, administrative bloat.<BR>

<P>
The standard party-line from the NEA is that these sorts of schools
will destroy public education as we know it.  I offer you just
this one thing to think about, and that is, that the only way
this program of alternative schools, whether vouchers, whether
 charters, whether any other financial construct; the only way
that they will work is if parents see the success and continue
to make those choices.  And that's what my organization works
for. (applause)<BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<B>Armstrong Williams:</B> Man&#133; Was that compelling or what?  This man spoke not only
from experience, but from the heart.  And I was just captivated
to think that our public universities are doing the jobs of the
high schools.  Two and a half years to nine months remedial courses.
 You think about that.  The answer is right here.  <BR>

<P>
Our next speaker is Clint Bolick.  Clint Bolick is the Vice President
and Director of Litigation for the Institute for Justice.  Mr.
Bolick successfully defended the nation's first school voucher
program in Milwaukee and while he continues to fight for Milwaukee's
expanded choice program, he litigates for school choice in Cleveland,
our nation's second school voucher program.  Mr. Bolick, someone
I know and respect, know well and consider a friend, has authored
several books and articles including the recently published <I>Affirmative
Action Fraud</I>, and what a fraud it is, <I>Can We Restore The
American Civil Rights Vision</I>, and <I>Grassroots Tyranny: The
Limits of Federalism</I>. It is now my pleasure to introduce Clint
Bolick.<BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<img src="bolick.gif" align=right alt="Clint Bolick"><B>Clint Bolick:</B> Thank you Armstrong.  I am predicting a sudden surge in C-SPAN's
ratings for having him as master of ceremonies.  And Charlene,
congratulations on an outstanding event.<BR>

<P>
I am here because I represent school children; little children
in Cleveland and Milwaukee, two of the nation's worst urban school
systems. I represent low-income children in those two cities.
 Those systems, the statistics are just staggering.  They are
beyond the ordinary person's comprehension.  In Milwaukee, for
parents, excuse me, for families on public assistance, 15 percent
graduate the Milwaukee public schools.<BR>

<P>
Cleveland recently became the largest school district in the United
States to be ordered by a federal court to be placed under the
supervision of the state. In Cleveland, 7 percent of the school
district students graduate on time and pass the senior proficiency
examination; a 1 in 14 ratio.  The same ratio, I might add, of
students in the Cleveland public schools who were victimized by
crime every year.  So you have an even chance to be a crime victim
or a proficient graduate. Pretty pathetic. In fact, there were
twice as many assault victims in the Cleveland public schools
last year as there were proficient graduates.  <BR>

<P>
These kids need help, they need it now, and they need it desperately.
 And happily, in both places, there are school choice programs
that are allowing these little kids to take a share, a share of
their public funds to private schools that have been chosen for
them by their parents. The program has been operational since
1990 in Milwaukee. It was expanded by a bipartisan majority of
the legislature last year fifteen fold, and to include religious
schools.  In Cleveland, the scholarship program was legislated
to begin this November, and 6,500 hundred families applied for
1,500 low-income scholarships for Cleveland's schools.<BR>

<P>
These are the programs that offer the greatest promise of educational
reform in the United States.  &quot;Why,&quot; you might ask,
&quot;do these little kids need a lawyer?&quot; It seems that
they need teachers, they need parents, they need a caring community.
They have all of those things, but unfortunately, they need a
lawyer because they are being subjected to harassment and to challenge
by the most reactionary and powerful special interest in America,
the National Education Association.  If there was a truth in advertising
law in the United States, the NEA would be going down in flames
right now because this group has become the school-yard bullies
of the 1990s.  For the first time in their lives, these little
kids have the chance to go to good schools, to safe schools, to
schools chosen for them by their parents, and these thugs are
absolutely dead set to make sure these kids never get there.<BR>

<P>
We're slugging these cases our in the Ohio and Wisconsin courts
right now and the statements of the unions are extremely revealing.
 In the Cleveland case, which I argued last week in Columbus Ohio,
last Monday, a week ago today, the NEA brief said that these school
choice programs were really a &quot;money laundering scheme,&quot;
the money going from the state to the religious schools.  The
sister organization, the American Federation of Teachers, described
parents as quote, &quot;inconsequential conduits,&quot; end quote,
for the transmission of aid from the state to the religious schools.
 Well I have this to say to the AFT and the NEA: these parents
are not conduits and they are <B>emphatically</B> not inconsequential
because if this reform succeeds, their vice-grip monopoly over
public education is going to be broken and parents, rather than
bureaucrats, will be the primary determinants of where low-income
children will go to school.<BR>

<P>
It is going to be a long fight. It is a David verses Goliath fight,
but Goliath was slayed in the bible and so too will he be slayed
in the court-room.  And I have just one final word to say to the
NEA.  On behalf of low-income families across the United States,
&quot;Let Our Children Go.&quot; Thank you. (applause)<BR>
<P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<B>Armstrong Williams: </B>You know, you really have to wonder, and hopefully we can get
into this during the Q and A, how this organization has been allowed
to destroy so much of this country.  Who are those in Washington
that continue to support what is detrimental to our children and
our parents? Those questions need to be addressed. How did the
NEA become so bloated, so powerful?  And whose interests is it
supporting if it is not the interests of families and America?
 Those are questions that need to be asked and addressed.  <BR>

<P>
Listen to this&#133; I don't know about you, but it makes me furious,
it makes me very angry, and it makes me want to do something.
 This meeting today should be a call to action by decent people
who are sick and tired, sick and tired of this disgusting educational
system. And hopefully, from this meeting today, we will not just
sit around and talk about it, we will do something about it.<BR>

<P>
Our next speaker is Raymond LaJeunesse. Mr. LaJeunesse is a senior
staff attorney with the National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation.
 In over two decades, he has been involved with a number of landmark
legal cases. He was the trial appellate counsel for the plaintiff
non-union employees and presented oral arguments to the U.S. Supreme
Court in Lehnert vs. Ferris Faculty Association. It is my pleasure
to introduce Mr. LaJeunesse, who is with us today&#133; And I
have to tell you, it is very upsetting America. This is really,
really sad that something like this could happen in the United
States of America. If we were talking about some foreign country,
maybe so, but not in America, where freedom is cherished.  Mr.
LaJeunesse is our speaker now, and thank you for allowing me get
that off my chest because it just, just got me going.  Sir, please.
(applause)<BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<img src="lajeun.gif" align=left alt="Raymond LaJeunesse"><b>Raymond LaJeunesse:</B> Thank you Armstrong, and thank you Charlene for allowing me this
opportunity to participate in this important forum.<BR>

<P>
We've already heard several myths that the NEA spreads about itself;
another is that it is a democratic organization. Democratic organizations,
however, do not coerce individuals into subsidizing their political
and ideological activities.  As Thomas Jefferson said, quote,
&quot;To compel a man to furnish contributions of money for the
propagation of opinions which he disbelieves, is sinful and tyrannical.&quot;
(Quoted in I. Brant, <I>James Madison: The Nationalist</I>, p.354
(1948)).<BR>

<P>
The NEA coerces financial support of its political and ideological
activities in two ways. First, the NEA has a standing policy that
its affiliates should negotiate agreements that include &quot;[m]embership
in the association or the payment of a fair -share fee as a condition
of employment&quot;  (National Education Association, <I>NEA Handbook
1994-1995</I>,  p. 303). Twenty-one states and the District of
Columbia have laws that permit such compulsory unionism agreements.
According to the NEA's own figures, approximately 23,000 teachers
and educational support personnel are compelled to pay its so-called
&quot;agency fees&quot; to keep their jobs (National Education
Association, <I>Strategic Plan and Budget Fiscal Year: 1995-1996
</I>iii (1995)).<BR>

<P>
Until the National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation successfully
sued for teachers  challenging that practice (<I>Abood v. Detroit
Board of Education, </I>431 U.S. 209 (1977); <I>Lehnert v. Ferris
Faculty Association</I> - MEA-NEA, 500 U.S. 507 (1991)), the NEA
and its affiliates with impunity spent the compulsory dues and
agency fees of objecting members and nonmembers on its political,
lobbying , and other ideological activities. These expenditures
were beyond the direct contributions to candidates from the NEA's
voluntary political action funds.<BR>

<P>
Since the Foundation was established in 1968, it has brought some
668 cases for teachers against the teachers' unions. Of those
cases, 365 are still open and 303 are closed. Of the closed cases,
270 have resulted in a fee reduction for the plaintiff teachers.
In one of those cases, the NEA and its state and local affiliates
were only able to prove that less than 10% of their expenditures
from general treasury funds was for lawfully chargeable bargaining
activities (<I>Lehnert v. Ferris Faculty Association</I> - MEA-NEA,
643 F. Supp. 1306 (W.D. Mich 1986), <I>aff'd</I>, 881 F.2d 1388
(6<SUP>th</SUP> Cir. 1989), <I>aff'd in part, rev'd in part, </I>500
U.S. 507 (1991)). Even today, after all this litigation, the NEA
uses a phony &quot;arbitration&quot; scheme to prevent objecting
agency-fee payers from finding out exactly how their coerced fees
are spent (<I>See Bromley v. Michigan Education Association -
NEA</I>, 82 F.3d 686 (6<SUP>th</SUP> Cir. 1996).<BR>

<P>
The second way in which the NEA coerces financial support of its
political and ideological activities is through the fine print
in its membership applications. The membership application form
used by most, if not all, NEA state affiliates contains fine print
in which the teacher signing it agrees that &quot;[m]embership
is continued unless I reverse this authorization in writing between
August 1 and August 31, of any year.&quot; Union members, of course,
have no right to obtain a dues reduction if they object to the
purposes for which their dues are spent. Moreover, rank-and-file
members of the NEA do not decide how dues are spent. The officers
and professional staff of the NEA and its affiliates make those
decisions.<BR>

<P>
Hundreds of teachers who contacted the Foundation for assistance
have told us that the NEA's locals do not point out the fine print
in the membership applications when they sign up new members.
Moreover, where agency fees are an option, local NEA officials
- and, sadly, school management - often fail to tell teachers
that they have any option other than full membership, misleading
them into signing membership applications. Teachers are not told
how their dues will be spent before they sign these applications.
After teachers find out that their dues are being used for purposes
they oppose, the union tells them that they cannot resign until
the following August.<BR>

<P>
For example, in late 1994 the Michigan Education Association imposed
a 3-year, $30 a year assessment on its members for an image building
program. When members tried to resign to avoid paying the first
year's assessment, the MEA told them, &quot;sorry, you have to
pay it, because you can't resign until next August.&quot;<BR>

<P>
The National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation does its best
to help teachers in fighting and correcting these pernicious,
undemocratic practices. However, our financial and staff resources
are limited. Moreover, we help not just teachers, but workers
in all professions and industries whose rights are violated by
compulsory unionism arrangements.<BR>

<P>
Litigation is expensive. The Foundation is a &quot;David&quot;
compared with the NEA's &quot;Goliath.&quot; The Foundation's
annual budget of almost $200 million, and each of its state affiliates
has a budget of almost $200 million, and each of its state affiliates
has a budget of millions or tens of millions of dollars. Consequently,
the Foundation cannot possibly provide legal assistance to every
teacher who asks for our help. Public exposure of the NEA's &quot;dirty
little secrets&quot; is necessary - to get the word out to teachers
that they do not have subsidize the NEA's political and ideological
activities - and to inform the public that the NEA is not the
democracy it pretends to be. (applause) <BR>

<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<B>Armstrong Williams: </B>Our next speaker is Allyson Tucker. Allyson Tucker directs the
Washington office of the Center for the Study of Popular Culture
and is the Executive Director of the Center's Individual Rights
Foundation, a national public interest law firm. Allyson manages
a network of pro-bono affiliate attorneys who, like herself, are
dedicated to protecting individual liberties and ensuring free
speech.  Allyson has written extensively on topics ranging from
education to civil rights and legal reform.  Ms. Allyson Tucker.
<BR>

<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<P>
<img src="tucker.gif" align=right alt="Allyson Tucker"><b>Allyson Tucker: </B>Thank you Armstrong and thank you Charlene also, for putting this
wonderful event together.  <BR>

<P>
I am here as a guest to dispel another NEA myth and that myth
is that the NEA supports charter schools. Throughout the NEA convention,
you are going to hear this week that the NEA is launching a new
project, and that project is their Charter School Initiative.
 <BR>

<P>
The Charter School Initiative is a five year, and I quote, &quot;exploration
into the concept of whether charter schools can contribute to
the improvement of our nation's schools.&quot;  And it's gotten
a lot of press&#133; we support charter schools and we're all
in favor of them and we're doing everything we can to help. This
is simply not the case, and I'm here to explain to you why this
is not the case.<BR>

<P>
A charter school, for anyone who doesn't know, is a public school
created by different teachers, parents or otherwise qualified
individuals, and is largely free from state and district oversight.
 Charter schools create an alternative for public schooling where
schools are granted significant autonomy and are held accountable
for results.  The charter is essentially a contract negotiated
between the individuals starting the school and the special body
authorized to approve the charter.  The charter specifies how
the schools are to be run, what will be taught, how success will
be measured, and what students will achieve.<BR>

<P>
Unlike other public schools, parents specifically request the
charter schools and if the school fails to attract students or
if the charter fails to meet the terms of the charter, the charter
school can be closed and the charter can be revoked.<BR>

<P>
The charter school phenomenon has been sweeping the nation and
transforming America's schools. In the little over four years
since the first charter school law was passed in 1991, twenty-four
states have enacted some from of charter school legislation. As
of the beginning of the 1995-96 school year, over 290 charter
schools have opened their doors to students from across the socio-economic
spectrum. The educational results in states with strong charter
school provisions are astounding. States with well-crafted legislation
have experienced enhanced educational opportunities for poor and
minority children, distinctive and innovative educational programs,
enthusiastic responses from teachers flourishing in their new
found freedom from bureaucratic red tape, remarkable commitment
from parents, long waiting lists to get into the charter schools,
and unusual educational partnerships.<BR>

<P>
Minnesota enacted the first charter school law followed in rapid
succession by California in 1993; Colorado, Georgia, Massachusetts,
New Mexico, and Wisconsin in 1993; Arizona, Hawaii, Kansas, and
Michigan in 1994; Alaska, Arkansas, Delaware, Louisiana, New Hampshire,
New Jersey, Rhode Island, Texas and Wyoming in 1995, and, most
recently, New Jersey in 1996. Six of the states, including Arizona,
California, Colorado, Massachusetts, Michigan and Minnesota have
strong charter school provisions, and not surprisingly, host over
95% of the charter schools up and running, serving more than 30,000
students. By contrast, in the ten states with the weakest charter
school provisions, there are a total of less than 50 charter schools
up and operating.<BR>

<P>
The states with weak or ineffective bills can largely blame the
NEA, AFT and the educational special interests. From 1991-1993
these groups simply opposed charter school bills when they appeared.
In 1994 and 1995, these groups, seeing the tremendous effect of
charter schools and decentralized education, switched tactics.
They began a dual course of voicing support for charters yet destroying
the concept through the legislation, which they agreed to &quot;help
draft.&quot; Thus, the states with educational establishment support
enacted almost meaningless laws and the charter school debate
became centered not on the charter school concept itself, but
instead on specific provisions in each particular piece of legislation.
<BR>

<P>
Several factors make a charter school bill effective. These factors
include the ability of two or more official governing bodies to
approve the charter; the authorization of any individual or group,
including religious groups or parents, to attempt to organize
a charter proposal; automatic exemption from state and local regulations
(as opposed to case-by-case or individual  appeals processes);
fiscal autonomy for the school, essentially giving the school
complete control of the funding allocated for the particular school;
legal autonomy, no or high limits on the number of charter schools
that can be created; and the ability of the charter school to
hire non-certified teachers and other employees.<BR>

<P>
For years, the NEA adamantly opposed any educational reform, like
charter schools, that put control of their children's education
into the hands of parents. They ran negative advertisements in
states with legislatures debating charter schools, threatened
and sanctioned legislators who voted for charter school legislation,
and led campaigns warning voters that charter schools would destroy
public education. States continued to pass strong legislation
that created autonomous charter schools and the proven benefits
of charter schools turned out to be substantial. Realizing that
they could not defeat the revolutionary charter school concept,
the NEA about face - they now claim to support charter school
legislation as long as it is &quot;properly crafted.&quot; What
the NEA considers to be a properly crafted charter school law
in reality is weak legislation that does little or nothing to
create strong, autonomous charter schools that offer children
real options.  The NEA's tactic was brilliant - because of the
NEA's alleged support for the idea, the statement &quot;I now
support charter schools&quot; now means nothing.<BR>
<P>
<I>Questions and answers can be found on the recording or video.  We encourage you to support C-SPAN by purchasing video #073324 from 1-800-CSPAN-98.</I>
<P>
