<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  Schools for expelled students offering second chance at success.  Charter school directory now available.  New Jersey counts on math committees.  Washington DC schools - a national embarrassment.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> Schools for expelled students offering second chance at success</B><br><B> Opportunities for private schools expected to grow rapidly</B><p>Last session Texas lawmakers made it easier for schools to rid themselves of discipline problems so more attention could be given to students who want to learn.  At the same time, the Legislature ensured that Texas would not give up on expelled students by turning them out on the streets with no chance to continue their education in academics and responsibility.  <br>The result of these efforts are the Juvenile Justice Alternative Education Programs. Under the new law, students in the 22 largest Texas counties are automatically suspended from traditional school for certain offenses, including weapons  violations.  It is the responsibility of the county, however, to educate these children. Funds are provided by the school district which would have paid for their education if the kids were still in school.<br>In most of the counties, juvenile probation departments have arranged with the school districts themselves to provide this education in a separate setting.  However, 8 counties have decided to contract with private vendors to educate these young people. These include Dallas, Travis, Bexar and Harris counties. These large counties solicited bids from service providers similar to the way the Houston ISD solicited schools to relieve its overcrowding problem in a particular neighborhood.<p>Currently the largest JJAEP has 121 students, but is conceivable that large counties could be looking to place as many as 5-700 juveniles in the near future.  This growing population will provide an opportunity for private entities to provide academic (and potentially vocational) training to this important population. In addition, 25 smaller counties have voluntarily started JJAEPs.  As more counties provide such programs, it is likely the private sector will increasingly be called upon to participate in educating this group of teenagers.<p><B> Charter school directory now available</B><p>The Center for Education Reform is publishing its third edition of the National Charter School Directory. For the 1996-97 school year, charter schools will serve more than 100,000 children in 480 schools.  The directory is a comprehensive listing of charter schools nationwide.  Call 202 822-9000 to order a copy.<p><B> New Jersey counts on math committees</B><p>According to the Philadelphia Inquirer, New Jersey has decided to replace teaching of math by repetition with a program that encourages problem solving and math by group. Other goals include: Use a variety of estimation strategies and recognize situations in which estimation is appropriate.  The National Council of Teachers of Math is responsible for these new benchmarks which will serve to lower standards of competency.<p><B> Washington DC schools - a national embarrassment</B><br> <br>The Washington, DC school system has been given an F by the DC Financial Control Board which called the capitals school district an utter failure.  In addition to the poor performance by DC students, area new media estimate the DC  system has wasted $50 million in taxpayer money. <p><br>
