<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  Survey describes crime in Americas schools</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p>The 1996 edition of Update on Violence published by the Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention contains the results of interviews with Americas students regarding violence.  The students selected for interview reflected students in grades 6-12 nationally.  The survey, undertaken in 1993,  asked students about violence, including attacks robberies, and bullying in school.  The surveyors asked students if they had been victims or witnessed violent acts.  The researchers concluded:<p><B> Younger students are more likely to be victimized and to worry about crime</B><br>Fifteen percent of students in grades 6-8 reported being victims of violence vs. 8% of students in grades 9-12.  Almost one in three (32%) of students in grades 6-8 worried about becoming a victim vs. 20% of older students.<p><B> Students at large schools more likely to experience violence</B><br>An incredible 75% of students at schools with 600 or more students were aware of violence in their school. Three in five students in schools with fewer than 300 students reported knowing of such incidents.<p><B> Females are almost as likely to carry weapons as males</B><br>The 1993 survey revealed that 3% of students carried some weapon to school to protect themselves vs.  2% in 1989 (according to an unrelated prior survey). Both surveys found that males are only slightly more prone to carry a weapon than females.<p><B> Gang presence results in more weapons in school</B><br>Thirty-one percent of students in grades 6-12 who knew of no gangs in school reported knowing of weapons in school.  Sixty-two percent of students who knew of gangs in school said they knew of weapons in school. <p><B> Violence is more likely in schools with drug dealers</B><br>One-quarter of students said it was easy to get controlled substances at school including alcohol and marijuana.  Students who said there were drug dealers on campus were far more likely to report incidents of physical attack (61% vs. 39%), robbery (23% vs. 9%) and bullying (73% vs. 53%).<p>
<br>
