<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  Austin area district wants private schools to help ease overcrowding.  Dallas ISD approves district charter for low income families. Dont feel good about flagging academics.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> Austin area district wants private schools to help ease overcrowding</B><p>The Lake Travis school board has approved a plan where students could use vouchers to attend the public or private school of their choice.  The Lake Travis school district lies west of Austin and has  2,900 students enrolled.  The district was one of only 37 school districts in Texas to earn an exemplary ranking from the Texas Education Agency.  <p>Under the Lake Travis plan, a portion of the per student funding from state and local sources would follow students to schools they select.  Lake Travis board members have said the plan is necessary because residents recently voted down a bond issue to be used for additional school facilities.  The vouchers would allow the district to educate its students at a lower cost per pupil without new capital expenditures.  <p>Initially, the amount of the voucher was set at $3,750, well below the $4,800 the Lake Travis school district currently spends per  student, excluding debt service.  In approving the plan,  however, the board agreed to set the level of the voucher at a later date.   The school board has asked Education Commissioner Mike Moses to approve the plan.  <p><B> Dallas ISD approves district charter for low income families</B><p>The slots for all 20 Open Enrollment charter schools have already been filled.  In the last legislative session, lawmakers approved the establishment of a maximum of 20 such schools chartered by the state.  Legislators also gave school districts the authority to charter an unlimited number of schools at the local level.  The Prairie Creek Academy may be the first Texas school to be chartered in this manner.  Prairie Creek is designed to help low-income children with limited English speaking ability.  Prairie Creek kids will attend school three weeks longer than other DISD children, and will be taught in class rooms limited to 15 students.<p><B> Dont feel good about flagging academics</B><p>Psychologist William Coulson, one of the founders of the self-esteem movement, is recanting.  Today, Coulson is encouraging teachers to emphasize academics over feeling good about themselves.  Recent research shows this about-face is a smart move.<p>A review of classroom techniques that tracked 7,000 students at 139 schools across the country revealed that models focusing on self-esteem resulted in lower academic scores than any other models. The best instructional methods, the study found, stressed effective teaching of academics. These successful strategies did not attempt to make children feel good except by rewarding good work.<p>Apart from the study, leading researchers on self-esteem including Morris Rosenburg, Thomas Moeller and Alfie Kohn, conclude that self-esteem does nothing to enhance academic success. Worse, according to a 1996 study in Psychological Review, an artificial emphasis on self-esteem can increase anti-social behavior, including violence.  In fact, the study refutes the commonly held belief that low-self esteem is a contributor to violence, contending that violence may be caused when real life events contradict highly favorable views of oneself.<br>
<br>
