<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  J.C. Watts touts CEF at Dallas luncheon.  Charter schools are on the move.  Private market filling educational void.  Quotable.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> J.C. Watts touts CEF at Dallas luncheon.</B><p>Oklahoma Congressman J.C. Watts, Jr. served as keynote speaker at a fund-raiser for the Childrens Education Fund on Oct. 24.   Rep. Watts was a featured speaker at the 1996 Republican Convention in San Diego and is the first African-American Republican to be elected south the Mason-Dixon line since Reconstruction.  Watts called school choice simply common sense and praised the efforts of the CEF to help low income children in Dallas County.  The CEF thanks Rep. Watts and all attendees for their participation.<p><B> Charter schools are on the move</B><br>This fall more than 80,000 children are attending more than 400 charter schools in 13 states.  According to a survey by the Hudson Institute, most of the children attending these new schools are those who generally do not succeed in a traditional setting.  Most children are minority students, 20% have limited English proficiency and many are disabled.<p>As expected, charter schools are serving a variety of students and meeting a variety of needs. Among the news on charters: <p>Bostons Pioneer Institute found that charters are reaching kids dismissed as difficult to teach. Massachusetts charters schools are serving a higher percentage of minority students, low income children and bilingual kids than the average public school.<p>Formerly Mean Joe Green wants to start a charter school in Florida for troubled black males.<p><B> Private market filling educational void</B><p>According to Montgomery Securities, an investment banking and securities firm, publicly traded education-oriented companies provide a classic investment opportunity.  Montgomery bases this bullishness on what it calls an all-time high in dissatisfaction with traditional public schools. This sentiment is heightened, the firms analysts say, because down-sized parents realize now more than ever that superior education is the key to economic opportunity.  <p>According to Montgomery, the U.S. education system compares poorly against its competitors globally. Montgomerys research reveals that the U.S. spends more than $600 billion on education annually, more than is spent on national defense.  This figure is larger than the GDP of Spain, Canada or Brazil.  About 75% of the cost of the countrys education is funded publicly, although only half of all public funds are directed to classroom employees and 3% are spent on texts and materials. <p>Montgomery knows of  no other service industry spending 50% of every dollar outside of where the service is being rendered, unless it is subsidized by the government. <p><B> Quotable</B><br>I am fascinated by (your school choice bill) and am having my staff analyze it.  Im concerned the traditional Democratic party establishment has not given you more encouragement.  The visionary is rarely embraced by the status quo.<br>Gov. Bill Clinton in a letter to Wisconsin State Rep. Polly Williams, Oct. 10, 1990.<br>
<br>
