<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  Houston ISD sets ground breaking contract with private school.  Don't let the new SAT scores fool you.  Union magazine addresses charter schools.  Dallas schools most in need of improvement are in inner-city.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> Houston ISD sets ground breaking contract with private school.</B><p>In a move that could have implications for taxpayers statewide, the Houston school district is paying a private school to educate 200 of its students. The arrangement, in the form of a contract, was undertaken because H.I.S.D. could not provide facilities for the 200 school children.  The Varnett School, which is located in southwest Houston, has agreed to teach the children for $3,575 per student.  Average tuition at the school is currently $4,050 per student.  It cost the H.I.S.D. $4,677 to teach a single student during the 1994-95 school year.  This cost excludes capital expenditures and debt service.  <p>By allowing Varnett to teach 200 of the districts children, the H.I.S.D. is saving money for each student in the contract while avoiding the capital and financing costs associated with a new or renovated school.<p>The Houston teachers union, however, has yet to see the silver lining.  They damn well better have certified teachers over there, the Houston Chronicle quoted the president of the Houston Federation of Teachers as saying.<br>So while union leaders worry about losing their grip over 200 children, teachers at Varnett will be placing fewer than 20 students in each classroom, and doing it cheaper than the H.I.S.D.^ <p>Don't let the new SAT scores fool you<p><B> Thanks to what the College Board calls recentering, SAT scores are both higher and more confusing.  Due to tinkering by the purveyors of the exam, last years average score of 428 verbal and 482 math will this year result in scores of 504 and 506.  The new recentering not only inflates these mediocre scores, it gives the appearance students are doing equally well in reading and math.  This hocus-pocus makes it impossible to compare historical scores with the new and improved recentered figures. Furthermore, the new test is easier, calculators are permitted and students have longer to complete the exam.<br>And if that wasnt enough, the College Board has made it possible to have a perfect score while missing four questions.  Prior to this finagling, a perfect score meant perfect - missing zero questions.  It sounds like the College Board needs tutoring in each of its own subjects.</B><p><B> Union magazine addresses charter schools</B><p>Charter schools are the cover story in the Fall 1996 issue of ATPE News, the magazine of the Association of Professional Educators.  The ATPE has generally supported charter schools in Texas, and the story provides an interesting insight into two charter schools opening this year.  All 20 slots for Open Enrollment charter schools have been filled, although not every school will open this year.  Removing the cap on the number of these innovative schools the state allows could revolutionize education in Texas.<p><B> Dallas schools most in need of improvement are in inner-city</B><p>A 1995 study of community needs revealed that the quality of pubic schools was of more concern to inner-city residents than residents in any other section of the county.  The study was prepared by the University of Texas at Dallas in conjunction with several area non-profit agencies.  For example, in West Dallas and  neighborhoods south of the Trinity, 12.5%, 15.5% and 13.1% of residents respectively identified the quality of public schools as a major problem.  Only 9.7% of Dallas County residents as whole viewed public schools as a big problem. <p>The number of high school drop outs was also viewed as a major problem in the three communities, with responses of 21.2%, 29.6% and 28%.  Other problems viewed as major by the three impoverished neighborhoods included access to good jobs, teenage substance abuse, unsupervised children and unemployment.<p>
<br>
