<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>   CEF starts school with 314 kids! Houston school superintendent finds solution to overcrowding. Milwaukees choice program helps narrow learning gap for minority students. New Yorkers start CEF-style program.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> CEF starts school with 314 kids!</B><p>This fall, more than 300 low-income children are attending schools their parents selected with help from the CEF.  This is an increase in enrollment of 40% over last year! Thanks to all supporters of CEF for opening doors for children in our community. <p><B> Houston school superintendent finds solution to overcrowding</B> <p>Houston voters tired of rising property taxes last month rejected a $390 million bond issue. Meanwhile, school administrators have been mulling over plans to relieve overcrowding in Houston schools. According to the Houston Chronicle, one of the ideas proposed by Houston Superintendent Rod Paige is to contract with non-district schools to teach H.I.S.D. children.  Under the plan, students who could not attend their assigned school because of overcrowding would have the option of attending a private school. <p>Superintendent Paige notes the district already is engaged in such contract for service.  For example, the district pays non-district schools to teach special education children and students who have been expelled. The proposal has not been acted upon. Whether or not the school board adopts the superintendents idea, the innovative proposal is sure should get administrators in  Texas school districts thinking. Expensive new construction at taxpayer expense is not the only answer to overcrowding.<p><B> Milwaukees choice program helps narrow learning gap for minority students</B><p>According to a study by Harvard University and the University of Houston, Milwaukees publicly funded pilot choice program provides tangible benefits to urban school children. The study discovered that after three years in the program, students scored higher on reading and math tests than comparable public school students.  The gap was wider for fourth year students.  According to Jay Greene, the UH assistant professor who co-authored the study, the difference in academic performance is substantial.  According to Greene, if similar success was achieved by all minority students nationwide, the gap in test scores between whites and minorities students would be narrowed by one-third to one-half. <p>The study compared students who were accepted into the program with those who applied but were turned down due to a lack of space. The Harvard-UH study refutes a prior study which concluded there was no difference in performance between students in and out of the program. The former study, however, compared the low-income minority students in the choice program with a cross-section of Milwaukee students more than twice as wealthy.  The latest study provides a more accurate comparison.<p><B> New Yorkers start CEF-style program</B><p>Low-income parents in Albany, Schenectady and Troy are the latest to have the power to select schools they want their children to attend. A group aligned with Change-NY is funding the program called A Better Choice. <p>There are more than 30 privately funded tuition assistance programs in America. Like the CEF, they all depend on you!<br> 
<br>
