  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>   Charter schools are happening in Texas. Is emphasis on TAAS at the expense of learning? Semi-frugality in school budgets. Punishing unhappy parents. Making the grade regardless.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> Charter schools are happening in Texas</B><p>The Renaissance Charter School in Irving has opened its doors as the first school of its kind in Texas. Four hundred students are enrolled in this school, a population which includes special education, at-risk, low-income and ESL students.  More than 85% of the educators at Renaissance have Masters degrees and 30% are doctorates or doctoral candidates. Each student at Renaissance is a career and technology student.  Children from seven districts will attend the new school. The Dallas CAN! Academy, is scheduled to open in September.  Dallas CAN! already operates a half-day program for dropouts<br>Starting a charter school in Texas is not easy.  The timing of funding makes it difficult to secure leases and have equipment and supplies ready for students.  Furthermore, there is no provision in Texas law to pay for capital costs related to charter schools. Charter schools are public school free to be managed at the campus level.<p><B> Is emphasis on TAAS at the expense of learning?</B><p>Reading scores of  Dallas school district students taking the Iowa Basic Skills Test declined in every grade but one last year.  Only sixth graders showed year-over-year improvement in reading on the national test.  No DISD grade level scored above 50 in 1996, the national average for the Iowa test. Math scores were mixed with some grades showing improvement, however, the highest score in math was 54.4 by Dallas 4th graders. <br>According to a newspaper report, even district researchers admitted that an accountability system which focuses solely on the TAAS test results in the TAAS being heavily emphasized.  Some Texas parents have been critical of time spent on preparing for the TAAS test at the expense of other studies.<br> <br><B> Semi-frugality in school budgets</B><p>The Dallas Catholic Diocese employs about 8 part time and full workers to oversee its school district of 14,000 students.  Recently, the Dallas public school system announced it was cutting 62 central administrative positions in the interest of fiscal responsibility. The DISD has 10 times as many students as the Catholic schools, indicating that the district would employ 80 central office personnel if the district was as efficient as the Diocese.  Yet, the DISD cuts alone involve 8 times as many positions as required to operate the entire Catholic Diocese.<br>Offsetting part of the districts savings is the hiring of a deputy superintendent, a chief of staff and the re-assignment of two high level administrators, actions that will cost taxpayers more than $400,000.  Some board members told the Dallas Morning News they believed central administrative costs could be cut further. <br>Are big city school districts simply too large to be efficient and accountable?<p><B> Punishing unhappy parents</B><p>Parents caught intentionally enrolling their children in the wrong school district are subject to a $500 fine in Illinois.  Have Illinois politicians considered what is causing such widespread dissatisfaction that it takes a law to make parents behave?<p><B> Making the grade regardless</B><p>School officials in Summerville, Mass. are proposing eliminating failing grades and converting numerical grades to A,B and C. Under the proposal even letter grades would be downplayed  and more weight placed on progress reports. Such thinking runs counter to Americans thirst for more, not less, accountability from school officials, teachers and students. <br>
<br>
