<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>   An opportunity to ask hard questions?</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B>  An opportunity to ask hard questions?</B><p>A roving committee established by Gov. George Bush is taking Texans' pulse on how we feel about property taxes.  Because property taxes have been increasingly relied upon to pay for government schooling in Texas, any change in the property tax structure will likely impact public education in some way.  While we are reconsidering the property tax, why not consider other topics relating to education?  For example:<p><LI>Is a school system which ignores the realities of modern life such as dual working parents and single parents adequate for the 21st Century?<br><LI>Is a centralized, bureaucratic management style appropriate for a system that exhibits few if any economies of scale?<br><LI>Is such a system equipped to manage the varied needs of individual campuses within its district?  <br><LI>If we know that children learn differently, why are all schools structured the same?<br><LI>Based on the rewards offered, why is there a much stronger incentive for a teacher to be an administrator than to be an excellent teacher?<br><LI>Are the primary beneficiaries of education policy the employees or the customers?<br><LI>Is a state funded system equipped to adequately assess the performance of its own schools?<br><LI>Are "inputs" such as number of counselors, student to teacher ratios, and content of  textbooks emphasized at the expense of results?<br><LI>Based on the track record of the last 40 years, to what degree should decisions regarding education be divided among appointed and elected officials versus teachers and parents?<br><LI>Can the performance of Texas public school children be readily compared with children in private schools or in other states?<br><LI>Are athletics emphasized at the expense of academics?<br><LI>Is the traditional model of the large junior high and even larger high school effective today?   <P>Based on a speech by Chester E. Finn, Jr., a professor of education and public policy at Vanderbilt University, and co-chair of the Educational Excellence Network, a project of the Hudson Institute. <br>
<br>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, Children's Education Fund<BR>P.O. Box 225748<BR>Dallas, Texas 75222-5748</ADDRESS><P><A HREF="MAILTO:CEF@schoolreport.com">e-mail (CEF@schoolreport.com)</A></P><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A></P></body></html>
