<html>
  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  Local enrollment growth serves as reminder alternatives are available. Demand swamps supply for Cleveland voucher program. Change in the wind?</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> Local enrollment growth serves as reminder alternatives are available</B><p>The eight new schools in Dallas largest school district will not be enough to house all new incoming students this year.  The Dallas ISD enrolled 149,000 students last year, but expects 5,000 more in the fall.  To handle the influx of students the district plans to install 46 portable classrooms to supplement capacity from the new schools.  Another 76 portables will be moved to other campuses. As bond issues are proving increasingly unpopular with voters, school districts will be called upon to manage resources more efficiently. As schools become larger, some big city school districts are learning that breaking large schools into smaller schools can improve results.  In addition, new Texas law allows the formation of charter schools on or off of existing campuses. One unexpected result of the charter movement could be to effectively increase the capacity of their school districts.  As more charter schools form away from existing campuses, more spots open up in traditional public schools.<p><B> Clevelands pilot vouchers awarded to low-income applicants as demand swamps supply for state funded program</B><p>Fifteen percent of eligible Cleveland elementary students applied for state vouchers available under a new pilot program.  Under the new plan, 27,500 students entering grades K-3 could apply for 1,500 vouchers worth $2,250 each.  The 1,500 students receiving the vouchers can use them to attend the school of their choice. Of the more than 6,200 students applying for the program, 3,423 applicants were considered economically disadvantaged.  Because Ohio law requires low-income students to be given priority in the lottery for vouchers, all students receiving vouchers were from low -income families. Half of low-income applicants did not receive a voucher. The pilot program is the first time publicly funded vouchers have been available in Ohio.  <p><B> Change in the wind?</B><p>The number of children being home schooled has jumped from 15-20,000 in the 1970s to an estimated 600,000 today.  This willingness to try a radical new approach to education coupled with inexpensive and powerful educational technology leads Britton Manasco of Reason magazine to believe traditional, one-size-fits-all education is growing obsolete.  Whether more families home school or not, the author believes enhanced technologies such as the Internet, educational software and easy access to research material will continue to encourage alternatives to traditional government-run schools. Manasco also submits that these new technologies are not destined to isolate children. If appropriately used, he believes, technology can bring children and families together to form dance clubs, sports leagues, study groups and specialized classes. The author concludes that as alternatives to traditional schooling become cheaper and more popular, the education establishment will have no alternative but to change.<br>
<br>
