<html>
  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  Study reveals urban minorities benefit most from Catholic schools. Research highlights benefits of New York privately funded tuition assistance program.</FONT></A></H3><HR>  <p><B> Study reveals urban minorities benefit most from Catholic schools.</B><p>A November 1995 report published by the National Bureau of Economic Research reveals that those most likely to benefit from a Catholic school education are minorities attending big-city schools.  The papers author, Derek Neal of the University of Chicago, used data from the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth and National Catholic Education Association to examine what influence Catholic secondary schools had on graduation rates and subsequent wages.  <p>Mr. Neal concludes there is evidence that while urban whites and suburban students can benefit from secondary Catholic schools in terms of future wages and graduation prospects, benefits are measurably greater for urban minorities.  Among urban blacks and Hispanics the probability of graduating from high school rises from .62 to at least .88 when the representative public school student is placed in a Catholic secondary school.   Also, urban minorities attending Catholic schools experience higher college graduation rates and higher future wages.  Such results, the author concludes, indicate there is larger disparity between the quality of urban public and Catholic schools than between public and Catholic schools in rural areas or suburbs.<p>The study also found that Catholic secondary schools are already concentrated in urban areas, indicating that resources are already in place to assist urban school children.<p><B> Research highlights benefits of New York privately funded tuition assistance program</B><p>In the June edition of the Phi Delta Kappan a research professor at the University of Washingtons School of Public Affairs discusses his study of the Student-Sponsor Partnership Program in New York City.  Under the program, sponsors pay the tuition for low-income minority students to attend New Yorks Catholic high schools. The study compared the educational experiences of these students with those enrolled in traditional New York City public schools. Among the findings: <p><UL><LI>Partnership  schools (the private schools) have a strong incentive to have a clear mission statement which is easy to explain to parents.  This requires campus administrators to focus on what children will experience rather than subtleties of education technique.<br><LI>Once a Partnership school has established an identity, the staff has strong incentive to avoid upheaval.<br><LI>Demands of economic survival make teachers concerned about performance of the school as a whole.<br><LI>Staff members know keeping their jobs depends on their own performance, making them quick to seek advice from co-workers.<br><LI>Most children have a strong incentive to succeed in school to avoid upheaval at home (due to the inconvenience of changing schools).<br><LI>Parents who choose a school implicitly give that school a grant of parental authority which increases the schools leverage over its students.</UL><br>Likewise, Partnership schools have leverage in dealing with parents.<br>Bullet^<LI>Partnership schools have no reluctance to make demands on parents.<br><LI>Partnership schools are confident in calling upon parents to play an important role in their childrens lives.<br><LI>Higher income parents who have the capacity to remove their children from public schools are most likely to develop close relationships with teachers and administrators.  Low-income parents who have little choice over schools seldom have strong feelings of loyalty toward compulsory attendance schools. Partnership schools, however, often provide a sense of commitment enabling them to earn loyalty.<br><LI>Students in Partnership schools often benefit from the schools need to create a defined image and reputation.<br><LI>Students gain from being a situation requiring them to make commitments. <br><LI>Students are more susceptible to being influenced by a chosen school.<br><LI>Partnership schools gain leverage over students as they accept the schools demands.<br><LI>For the majority of Partnership school students, the need to stick to their commitments influenced their behavior and changed their attitudes.^<br>For students who seldom observe any adults other than teachers at work, the message these adults send is a powerful one. Teachers in compulsory attendance schools who feel they have little control over conditions of their work send a far different message than teachers linked in a common enterprise.<br>
<br>
