<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  American mayors enter fight to improve schools. Tired of watching middle-class flee, mayors seek solutions. NBA support is a slam dunk for inner-city kids. Mandates up, state support down </FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B>  American mayors enter fight to improve schools. Tired of watching middle-class flee, mayors seek solutions.</B>  <p>Understanding that urban problems such as juvenile crime, unemployment and economic development are not unrelated to sub-par urban schools, mayors are taking action.  Although school boards  are traditionally in charge of these vast big city school systems, some urban leaders are no longer content to watch from the sidelines. In fact, those attending a recent mayors conference in Cleveland vowed to concentrate more on school-related problems including crime, truancy, discipline, job training and even changes in curriculum.<br>Cleveland Mayor Michael White, tired of being foiled by the elected school board ran a slate of candidates to gain more control over school policies. Chicago Mayor Richard Dailey has been the most aggressive of his peers in addressing school-related problems. Last year he received the go-ahead from the legislature to take over Chicagos schools.  Today that school system is being run by a board appointed by (and accountable to) the mayor. Mayor Dailey believes good schools will bring Chicago a competitive advantage over other big cities.<p><B> NBA support is a slam dunk for inner-city kids</B><p>Representatives from four NBA basketball teams have helped expand opportunity for urban school children.  The Orlando Magic Youth Foundation recently committed $30,000 for tuition assistance in Central Florida.  In San Antonio, the foundation of Spur star David Robinson presented the San Antonio private scholarship plan with a check for $20,000.  Meanwhile, in Arizona, the Phoenix Suns Charities pledged $20,000 for privately funded scholarships in Phoenix.  Atlanta Hawks coach Lenny Wilkins was one of the original board members of Atlantas Childrens Education Foundation. The coachs fervent support for academic excellence helped the Atlanta program become a success.  Coach Wilkens recently retired from the Atlanta foundations board.<p><B> Mandates up, state support down</B><p>Local school districts have been increasingly forced to comply with the state unfunded mandates which have helped drive the cost of public education higher in Texas.  As state mandates have increased, however, the states share of total school funding has been reduced.<br>
<br>
