<html>
  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  Good news, bad news and cooking the books. Homeowners share of school taxes continues to grow.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> Good news, bad news and cooking the books</B><p>First the good news.   Fewer students in Texas are failing the state-mandated TAAS exam these days, and improvement is being made in Dallas schools as well.  A couple of years ago more than half of DISD students in grades 3-8 failed the TAAS.  The latest results show that more than half of Dallas students are now passing the exam, including 70% of sixth graders and 54% of eighth graders.  The bad news is that given the emphasis placed on the TAAS, too many students are still failing the test.  Only 53% of eighth graders passed the social studies exam.  Meanwhile, third and fourth grade reading scores actually fell.  Perhaps most troubling of all, a whopping 16,000 Dallas students have not taken (and will not take) the 1996 TAAS. Thats 25% percent of DISD students who are exempt from the TAAS.  Such a large number of exemptions distorts TAAS results and sends the wrong message to children who are told not to bother with the states exam. <p><B> Homeowners share of school taxes continues to grow</B><p>In fiscal 1992 taxes on residential property accounted for 37.72%of all school taxes.  By fiscal 1995, residential property taxes represented 43.52% percent of the total. The Citizens Commission on Property Tax Relief is holding hearings across the state on the subject of property tax relief.<br>Not only is the homeowner (who is responsible for about 90% of all residential property taxes) paying a larger share of property taxes, the property tax itself has been increasingly relied upon to fund school district budgets.  For example, in the 1984-85 school year, state aid represented 52.2% of state and local school revenues.  But by 1995-96, the states share of funding fell to 46.8%.  While this shift in funding has occurred, total spending for education has grown rapidly.  State and local spending on education totaled $8.7 billion in 1984-85 but will rise to an expected $17.9 billion by 1996-97.  Property taxes per student have also grown rapidly, especially in the 1980s.<p><br>
<br>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, Children's Education Fund<BR>P.O. Box 225748<BR>Dallas, Texas 75222-5748</ADDRESS><P><A HREF="MAILTO:CEF@schoolreport.com">e-mail (CEF@schoolreport.com)</A></P><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A></P></body></html>
