</DOCHDR>
<html>
  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BACKGROUND="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/gifs/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><H3><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/updates.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Education Updates"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="CEF Home"></A>  CEF Education Updates</H3></P><H3><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/cef/edupdates/apple3.gif" WIDTH=14 HEIGHT=15>  U.S. produces the worlds least efficient schools. Ex-superintendent starts institute for education reform. Teachers say Feds dont know best about special needs children. Is violence on the increase? Ask the teachers.</FONT></A></H3><HR> <p><B> U.S. produces the worlds least efficient schools</B><p>Based on money spent and results obtained, America is the least efficient of the industrialized nations in teaching reading. This is the conclusion reached by education professor Herbert J. Walberg of the University of Illinois and Joseph L. Bast, president of the Heartland Institute. According to the pair, the U.S. does a good job of getting children ready for school.  The language mastery of Americas preschool students has steadily improved over the years.  Even 9-year-old American students are second only to children from Finland in their ability to read.  The bad news is, the longer the U.S. education system has our children the further they lag behind our international competitors. <p>For example, American students progress in reading between the age of  9 and 14 was the worst among 16 nations based on a study by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.  Despite their slow progress, the U.S. spends more per primary school student than 13 other countries (Cost data were not available for three nations). This combination of high spending and slow improvement makes the U.S. school system the least efficient of those studied.<p><B> Ex-superintendent starts institute for education reform</B><p>Former Milwaukee school superintendent Howard Fuller has opened the Institute for the Transformation of Learning at Marquette University.  The institutes goal is to fundamentally change the way learning is approached in the United States.  According to Fuller, Americas current education system is designed to serve the needs of 19th Century industrial America. The institute will promote a re-thinking of the entire system.  This summer the institute will open two neighborhood-based learning centers in Milwaukee inner-city churches.  These neighborhood centers will make information technology available to many of the citys poorest children.<p><B> Teachers say Feds dont know best about special needs children.</B><p>Once again, teachers know one policy doesnt suit every child A survey of 1,500 teachers by a leading Texas teacher association revealed that 68% of teachers with special education children in their classrooms dont believe the federally mandated practice of "inclusion" is working.   Inclusion means placing special education children in the traditional classroom regardless of a childs particular needs or the teachers abilities and training.  Unfortunately, what benefits some children has been imposed universally. Teachers say they are not trained to teach these children and that inclusion takes teaching time away from traditional classroom activities. <p>Certainly, for too long children with special needs were completely isolated from other children, often to their determent.  But now the pendulum has swung too far the other direction, thanks to federal government intervention.  The new policy pays no heed to parents wishes or school resources and capabilities.  And paperwork pertaining to special education students is never-ending.   Parents who want their children "mainstreamed" in the regular classroom should be paired with teachers who are gifted (and trained) in that area. Parents who understand that their child needs to spend as much time as possible with a special education professional should have that option as well.  That means less attention should be placed on rigidity, attendance zones and one-size-fits-all policies.  More emphasis  should be put on doing what works to educate our children.<p><B> Is violence on the increase? Ask the teachers</B><p>Almost three quarters of Texas teachers say violence is on the increase in their districts.  This 72% figure has not changed since teachers were asked the same question in 1994.<br>
<br>
