<A ID="E11E9" NAME="E11E9">
<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  June 7, 1996 -- New math subtracts from educational excellence. New solutions not higher taxes. Is &quot;site-based decision making&quot; a hoax?</FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>New math subtracts from educational excellence</B></H4>
<P> Math instruction isn't adding up in California.  In 1994, more than 50 percent of freshmen in California state universities needed remedial help in the subject, up from about 30 percent in 1989.  This in part reflects the long term downward trend in math aptitude nationally.  SAT math scores in the U.S. have fallen from 492 to 478 over three decades.  Half of math students in Japan do as well as the top 5 percent of math students in America.  </P>
<P>California has long tried to boost student performance by tinkering with curriculum. The latest change was undertaken in 1992.  But the new standards do not add up.  Rather than emphasizing competence in math, the new math focuses on cooperative work, discussion groups, exploration of chance of use of calculators and computers.  Whatever happened to multiplication and fractions?  </P>
<P>Proponents of the new math argue that the approach beats the old school of drill, drill, drill.  The problem with that argument, however,  is that California's math curriculum has been moving away from, not towards, old fashioned ciphering for years.</P>
<P>Some parents who are finding that their children can't do math without a calculator are fed up.  In Vista, Calfornia parents protested when the new math books emphasized group work over simple problem solving.   But at least one text book publisher is investing in back to basics.  Saxon Publishers is giving away $10 million in text books in an attempt to promote real math instead of the squishy stuff.  Thus far, those who use the Saxon texts are getting results.  A Georgia school system jumped from 53rd in the state in math to first using books from the old fasioned publisher.   Yet, in the Golden State, all math books must meet the new criteria, so Saxon's books are banned. This combination of watered down curriculum and centralized (vs. local) decision-making regarding text book selection is a great way to ensure failure.</P>
<H4><B>New solutions not higher taxes</B></H4>
<P> Although the total property tax levy has increased from $3.6 billion in 1984 to $9.0 billion in 1995, a leading teachers' association is calling for members to be vocal in their support of further tax increases and new bond issues (ATPE News, Summer 1996).  The group has legitimate concerns about classroom overcrowding but is relying on the same old solutions for improvement.   </P>
<P>Education reforms which encourage the private sector to absorb the increasing student populations can ease the burden on overtaxed Texans while providing expanding educational opportunities for all children. </P>
<H4><B>Is &quot;site-based decision making&quot; a hoax?</B></H4>
<P>&quot;Site-based decision making&quot; is all the rage.  The idea is to allow those closest to the children - parents, teachers and principals - the freedom to run their own public schools. That's  a great idea if those concerned have real ability to make decisions that matter.</P>
<P>Site-based decision making was born in 1993 in a bit of legislative irony. That's when  Texas lawmakers mandated that schools run their own show. Almost half of teachers, however, say the idea is not working.  Forty-five percent of teachers in a recent poll said they did not think site-based decision making is, or will be effective.  This makes the idea suspect that teachers and parents are suddenly empowered. </P>
<P>It is more effective to remove constraints than legislate freedom. </P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, Children's Education Fund
