<A ID="E11E7" NAME="E11E7">
<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  May 21, 1996 -- New charter schools don&#146;t fit the traditional mold (That&#146;s the point, of course). Half of Texas freshman lack basic skills. Fort Worth group advocates forming black-only school district.</FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>New charter schools don&#146;t fit the traditional mold (That&#146;s the point, of course</B></H4>
<P>The State Board of Education has approved 20 Open Enrollment charter schools.  Under the new legislation, 20 such schools are allowed to open their doors in Texas.  All 20 openings have now been filled.  There were at least 14 schools competing for the final four slots. </P>
<P>Charter schools are public schools which are allowed to be managed at the campus level.  Charter schools can be authorized by the local school district (local charters) or by the state (Open Enrollment). </P>
<P>Here&#146;s some information about some of these new schools.  These are by no means traditional &quot;one size fits all&quot; campuses.</P>
<P>George I. Sanchez Charter School -Houston.  Will serve 300 students in grades 9-12 in an area where 80 percent of the students are eligible for free or reduced lunch, and where 50 percent of ninth graders drop out before graduating. </P>
<P>&#149; Raul Yzaquirre&#146;s School for Success - Houston. Students in grades 7 and 8 will be taught in one classroom rather than changing classes several times each day.  A minimum of 90 minutes each day will be spent on reading, language arts and grammar.  Community members will serve as mentors for students.</P>
<P>&#149; One-Stop Multi-service Charter School - Mission.  The school is for children in grades 7-12  who will be referred to the school through the local juvenile probation system.</P>
<P>&#149; Academy of Transitional Studies - Corpus Christi.  Students will include high school students who are discipline problems and are behind academically.</P>
<P>&#149; Girls and Boys Prep School - Houston.  Boys and girls will be taught in separate classrooms and there will be no competitive sports with outside campuses.  Academic courses will allow for competition in debate, journalism, dance, theater and arts.</P>
<P>&#149; Genesis Charter High School - Dallas. In addition to their studies, students will have to complete 100 hours of community service.</P>
<H4><B>Half of Texas freshman lack basic skills</B></H4>
<P>Almost 50 percent of college freshmen in state schools failed the Texas Academic Skills Program test last year.  The test, which measures basic academic skills, was administered to 132,000 students in state universities and community colleges in Texas.  The passing rate of 51.6 percent for the 1994-95 school year compares to a passing rate of 65.1 percent in the prior year. Because of the poor results, the Texas Higher Education Commission has postponed making the test more difficult. The TASP test was mandated by the Texas Legislature after a study showed that one in four college freshmen lacked the skills necessary to take college courses. The Texas Higher Education Commission is considering releasing the names of school districts whose graduates are failing the TASP in large numbers.</P>
<H4><B>Fort Worth group advocates forming black-only school district </B></H4>
<P>Frustrated with the performance of black students in Fort Worth schools, a group working under the name of Operation Home School Rule wants to form a separate school district. The move is possible under a new state law if 10 percent registered voters approve the split and a special election okays the plan.  Only 32 percent of African-American school children in Fort Worth passed all sections of the TAAS in 1995. Disappointed with these results, the organizers vow to seek an alternative. </P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, Children's Education Fund
