<A ID="E11E6" NAME="E11E6">
<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  May 15, 1996 -- Today Foundation recognizes innovative public schools </FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>Today Foundation recognizes innovative public schools</B></H4>
<P>The Today Foundation (the parent organization of the Children&#146;s Education Fund) has chosen  five winners for its Innovative Public School Award.  This award is designed to recognized those campuses, districts and communities that have found solutions at the local level to their own particular problems.  The winners will receive a certificate and a cash award of $1,000.  </P>
<P>The winners are presented below:  </P>
<P>1.  Allison Elementary School - Austin ISD A group of teachers organized the Early Bird Reading Club to address the problem of students arriving early while improving reading skills.  Often, these working parents had no choice but to drop their kids off at school before the doors opened. The school has in effect added a half hour to an hour to the school day, and students have become hooked on reading as well.   </P>
<P>2.  Lazbuddie High School - Lazbuddie ISD Although academics should be the number one priority at every school, all too often athletics come first.   Lazbuddie High School started an organization called CLASS to recognize high achieving students in academics. More than a program, CLASS is school wide effort to make scholastics a priorty. As a result of CLASS, the school became the Regional Literary Champion, and by 1993 Lazbuddie was the Runner-Up State Champion.  The school has had the State Champion Accounting Team and Computer Team for the last three years. Prior to CLASS, the school entered only four students in UIL competitions. In the last two years, students have earned more than $165,000 in scholarships and this year they have already earned $127,000.  And this is for a graduating class of 28. </P>
<P>3.  Pearsall Summer Youth Program - Pearsall ISD A major problem in the city was increasing gang membership and influx of drugs from nearby Mexico.  The problem was exacerbated in the summer months when young people were left unsupervised.  To address these problems, a cross section of the community including ministers, school officials, probation officers and police created the Pearsall Summer Youth Program. The program takes advantage of resources already existing in the community, such as the library, churches and schools, and serves students from 8 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. 6 days a week. The summer program provides a variety of activities, including classroom instruction.  Last summer participation was high, crime was down and attention to academics was up. </P>
<P>4.  Coyote Club, Carl Schurz Elementary - New Braunfels ISD One school  teacher began coaching kids who could not afford to participate in Little League baseball.  But Craig soon discovered these boys needed to learn more than how to swing a bat.  He began &#147;coaching&#148; them in academics after school as well.   Eventually Craig and his wife Vicky began to regularly help a group of boys in grades 4-8 with homework.  They provided them with equipment to play sports as well.  This shoe string program has grown to the extent that the local Chamber of Commerce is taking over the program four days each week. </P>
<P>5.  Puppy P.A.W.S. Child Development Center - Bosqueville ISD (Waco) This program is the brainchild of a Home Economics teacher who saw the need for more child care facilities and the need for more opportunities in vocational education.  The result is pre-school open to the community that also serves as a lab for students who want to pursue a career in early childhood development. </P>
<P>The Center provides a preschool program for all students regardless of income or disability from 8 to noon.  The Center also provides an enrichment program from noon to 3:30 and extended day care to 5:30.  Parents pay a fee for extended services. </P>
<P>The opening of the Center coincided with student training in the area of Early Childhood Professions.  It was offered as an elective to juniors and seniors in high school.  Students who receive credit in the class can continue the program at the local college. Plans are for the Center to serve 60 kids in the fall of 1996.  </P>
<P>The Center provides a preschool program for all students regardless of income or disability from 8 to noon.  The Center also provides an enrichment program from noon to 3:30 and extended day care to 5:30.  Parents pay a fee for extended services.</P>
<P>The opening of the Center coincided with student training in the area of Early Childhood Professions.  It was offered as an elective to juniors and seniors in high school.  Students who receive credit in the class can continue the program at the local college.</P>
<P>Plans are for the Center to serve 60 kids in the fall of 1996.</P>
