<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  May 6, 1996 -- Huge gap exists between administrative and teacher salaries. Arizona group receives newspaper award </FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>Huge gap exists between administrative and teacher salaries  </B></H4>
<P>The average central office administrator in Texas major urban school districts makes 96 percent more than those on the front lines of education.  This information is from the publication of school district profiles produced by the Texas Education Association which covers the 1994-95 school year.   In that edition, the average salary of urban central office administrators was $61,221 vs. $31,095 for teachers.  Average salaries of teachers were also below those of professional support staff.  In Dallas, central office administrators recently received a pay hike averaging 9 percent compared to a 4 percent raise approved for other school employees.  Some administrators recently received raises of as much as 20 percent.  These raises put the salaries of top DISD administrators well above $80,000 annually.  Meanwhile, average hourly earnings for all Americans rose 3 percent in the first quarter from a year earlier.   </P>
<P>Central office positions and salaries include the following:  </P>
