<A ID="E11E4" NAME="E11E4">
<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  April 29, 1996 -- Catholic school district manages to avoid bureaucracy </FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>Catholic school district manages to avoid bureaucracy</B></H4>
<P>Schools in the Dallas Diocese teach approximately 14,000 student, more than many school districts in Texas.  Because individual Catholic campuses operate with significant autonomy, there is no need for large centralized management.  In fact, only five full-time central office administrators are required to oversee the education of 14,000 students.  Additional central office help includes 3 consultants and three secretaries (one of them part time).  The Dallas School District has approximately 10 times as many students as the Catholic Diocese.  However, there are about 175 central office professionals in the D.I.S.D., or 22 times as many central office professionals.   In other words, including consultants, there are 0.57 central office professionals per 1,000 Catholic students in the Dallas Diocese.  In the D.I.S.D. there are about 1.2 central office professionals per 1,000 D.I.S.D. students. </P>
<P>Perhaps because principals at Catholic campuses, not central administrators, make most campus decisions, it costs less to educate a child attending a Dallas Diocese school.  For example, it costs $2,000 to $2,500 to educate a student at a Dallas Catholic school.  (This is actual cost, not tuition, which is generally set below the actual cost.)  The total operating cost at D.I.S.D., however, is $4,659 per student.  </P>
<P> </P>
