<A ID="E11E3" NAME="E11E3">
<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  March 28, 1996 -- Teachers&#146; being overruled. From the bookshelf. U.S. News investigates low education standards</FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>Teachers&#146; being overruled </B></H4>
<P>A survey by a Texas teachers group reveals that school administrators continue to &#147;socially promote&#148; students that teachers have failed.  Almost 40 percent of the 2,132 teachers who responded to the survey reported such promotions.   The teachers group, the Texas Federation of Teachers, estimates that 130,000 Texas public school students were sent to the next grade level despite failing grades.</P>
<H4><B>From the bookshelf</B></H4>
<P>&#147;Dumbing Down Our Kids&#148; by Charles J. Sykes explains why American children feel good about themselves but can&#146;t read or write.  The book documents the collapse of standards in American schools, details the consequences of educational fads and tracks the &#147;dumbing down&#148; of curriculum during a period of expanding school budgets.  But &#147;Dumbing Down&#148; is not an indictment of American education, or a condemnation of teachers.  The book explains the educational philosophies which have led American students down a path of limited learning.  The author also praises schools that work and discusses</P>
<P>the coming (and on-going) revolution in education.</P>
<P>Facts from &#147;Dumbing Down Our Kids&#148;:</P>
<P>&#149; One-third of American 17-year-olds are not required to do homework on a daily basis.</P>
<P>&#149; Only one in five 9-year-olds can perform basic mathematical computations.</P>
<P>&#149; Fifteen percent of college faculty say their students are adequately prepared for their math courses.</P>
<P>&#149; American businesses spend $30 billion a year on worker training.</P>
<P>&#149; American productivity and test scores have declined almost simultaneously. The author also claims that Goals 2000, which was signed into law in 1994, creates new layers of bureaucracy, including the National Education Standards and Improvement Council, the National Skills Standards Board, the National Occupational Information Coordination Committee, and the National Education Dissemination System.  In addition, many of the goals are non-academic, including new national standards for spending levels, teacher salaries and other mandates or &#147;in-puts.&#148;  </P>
<P>Sykes claims schools that work have a campus-wide concern about reading skills, use reading specialists, emphasize a phonics-based curriculum, pay close attention to individual student reading interests, and carefully evaluate progress of their pupils.</P>
<H4><B>U.S. News investigates low education standards</B></H4>
<P>In the April 1 edition of U.S. News and World Report, the magazine takes a look at education and standards.  The recent interest in higher standards comes from widespread conviction that students can do better.  Only one-third of high school seniors mastered the NAEP reading test in 1994. Only 11 percent had a good grasp of history.  Albert Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teachers, says students are performing far below their capabilities.  Three quarters of respondents to a U.S. News poll said standards should be raised.  The unresolved question is how.  National standards are fraught with political agendas and watering down of curriculum.  State standards have given us an unhealthy focus on the TAAS test.</P>
<P>Other U.S. News findings:</P>
<P>&#149; High school students in Japan, France and Germany spend twice as many hours</P>
<P>&#149; studying math, history and science as U.S. kids.</P>
<P>&#149; 78% of high school seniors spend less than 5 hours per week on homework.</P>
<P>&#149; Only one-third of Japanese students spend so little time studying.</P>
