<A ID="E11E2" NAME="E11E2">
<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  March 20, 1996 -- News on charter schools </FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>News on charter schools </B></H4>
<P>Data gathered from charter schools in Michigan indicates that these new kinds of schools are expanding educational opportunities for minority children.  Thirty-one percent of recently opened charter schools in the state were started by African-Americans.   Blacks represent almost 40 percent of students in charter schools,  versus 16 percent of public school enrollment.</P>
<P>One example of these locally managed charters is Sankofa Shule in Lansing. The school was founded by a former public school teacher who acts as the new school&#146;s principal, language arts teacher, and janitor.   The school has 132 students.  One of the many unique features about the school is the way they</P>
<P>handle discipline problems.  Instead of sending students home, they &#147;suspend&#148; parents from work.  When the student misbehaves, the parent must spend an entire day with their child at school. It is estimated that there are about 400 private, religious and charter schools created by African-Americans.</P>
<P>Study reveals privately funded choice succeeding in Indiana The Educational Choice Charitable Trust in Indiannapolis was the first privately funded scholarship program in the nation.  The program was founded</P>
<P>in 1991 and served as the inspiration for similar programs, including the CEF.  The Hudson Institute has performed research on students particpating in the ECCT program, and has also gathered information on students who applied for ECCT assistance but remained on waiting lists due to funding restraints.</P>
<P>Among the findings: </P>
<P>&#149; Ninety percent of parents who chose to move their children to a private school with help from ECCT reported they were satisfied or very satisfied.</P>
<P>&#149; Parents ranked safety as the most important factor in moving their child to a new school.</P>
<P>&#149; As in all privatley funded scholarship plans, there are instances where families drop out of the program for financial reasons.  However, the Hudson study revealed that families in the lowest income bracket are no more likely to leave the program than other families.  (Our own interpretation of this data is that the real heroes in America are these determined parents struggling to help their children get a better education.) </P>
<P>&#149;  It also appears single mothers are no more likely to leave the program than two-parent families.</P>
<P>&#149; Although families with the lowest incomes are no more likely to leave the Inidanappolis scholarship program, financial pressure is by far the most common reason for any parent to remove their child from the program.</P>
<P>&#149; An analysis of test scores from Indinapolis public schools and children who had taken advantage of the ECCT program revealed that the choice students in the critical grades 6-8 did not experience the severe drop in test scores as did public school students (including those who had applied for ECCT assitance, but remained on waiting lists). </P>
<P>We conclude that the ECCT program, like the CEF, is making a difference in children&#146;s lives today.</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, Children's Education Fund
<BR>P.O. Box 225748
<BR>Dallas, Texas 75222-5748</ADDRESS>
