<A ID="E11E1" NAME="E11E1">
<H3><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR="#FF0000">
<BR>
<IMG SRC="apple3.gif" WIDTH = 14 HEIGHT = 15>  March 7, 1996 -- Beware of an insider subversion of charter schools. Study reveals Dallas children skipping school</FONT></A></H3></A>
<H4><B>Beware of an insider subversion of charter schools</B></H4>
<P>It has been revealed to the CEF that some Austin bureaucrats may attempt to thwart the establishment of charter schools by claiming such schools violate federal desegregation orders.  Under the letter of the federally imposed law, minorities may not represent more than 65 percent of the student body</P>
<P>of any school in Texas.  We expect a large number of charter school applications to come from inner-city minority communities.  The innovators from these communities know what it takes for their own children to succeed.  Yet, it is possible that the charter schools trying to create opportunities for minority children will be labeled in violation of the desegregation order.</P>
<H4><B>Study reveals Dallas children skipping school</B></H4>
<P>A report by the League of Women Voters of Dallas argues that not enough is being done to discourage children from skipping school.  The study notes that juvenile crime in Dallas has trended upward for years.  It also points out that half of youths who complete juvenile programs re-offend within 18</P>
<P>months.  According to the study, the current system is failing because:</P>
<P>&#149; Truants have discovered how to fool school officials.</P>
<P>&#149; School officials do not always follow up on truancy cases.</P>
<P>&#149; Parents refuse to take responsibility for their children.</P>
<P>&#149; Justice of the peace courts do not accept filings for truancy.</P>
<P>&#149; The juvenile department does not pursue truancy cases.</P>
<P>&#149; School officials don&#146;t file cases.</P>
<P>The study concludes, &#147;clearly something is wrong.&#148;  After years of neglect, however, school and juvenile policies toward truancy seem to be improving. For example, the district has assigned 18 truancy officers to file cases instead of the one representing the district previously.</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, Children's Education Fund
<BR>P.O. Box 225748
<BR>Dallas, Texas 75222-5748</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:CEF@schoolreport.com">e-mail (CEF@schoolreport.com)</A></P>
