</DOCHDR>
<html>
  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN News"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P>

<P>
BEFORE THE PUBLIC DISCLOSURE COMMISSION
<P>
OF THE STATE OF WASHINGTON<BR>
<BR>

<P>
IN RE COMPLIANCE)PDC CASE NO: 96-420
<P>
WITH RCW 42.17 BY)Partial Report of
<P>
)Investigation
<P>
Washington Education)
<P>
Association and WEA-PAC)
<P>
)
<P>
C.T. Purdom, WEA President)
<P>
and WEA-PAC Chairman )
<P>
)
<P>
Respondent.)
<P>
______________________________)<BR>
<BR>

<P>
I.
<P>
BACKGROUND<BR>
<BR>

<P>
STRUCTURE<BR>

<P>
The Washington Education Association (WEA)is a union of education
employees
<P>
in Washington State with approximately 65,000 members.<BR>

<P>
The WEA is a state affiliate of the National Education Association
(NEA).<BR>

<P>
The WEA structure includes 22 UniServ Councils and 330 local education
<P>
associations. A UniServ Council is a regional affiliate of the
WEA. A
<P>
local education association is an affiliate of the WEA and NEA.
The
<P>
UniServ Council provides services to the local association.<BR>

<P>
An education employee cannot be a member of the NEA without paying
dues to
<P>
the NEA, the WEA, the local association and the UniServ Council.
Dues for
<P>
WEA membership are based on a percentage of the average classroom
teacher=ED=
<P>
s
<P>
salary as defined by the WEA constitution and Bylaws.<BR>

<P>
Educational employees who do not wish to be members of the organizations
<P>
can pay Agency Shop Fees.<BR>

<P>
Agency Fee Payers pay a percentage of the National, State, UniServ
and
<P>
Local dues. Political action contributions (NEA-PAC/WEA-PAC) and
Community
<P>
Outreach dues are not deducted from Agency Fee Payers wages.<BR>

<P>
The WEA employs 140 full-time staff and is headquartered at 33434
8th
<P>
Avenue South in Federal Way, Washington. The WEA also has offices
in
<P>
Olympia and Spokane, Washington.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
POLITICAL ACTION<BR>

<P>
The Washington Education Association Political Action Committee
(WEA-PAC)
<P>
is the registered political action arm of the WEA.<BR>

<P>
The National Education Association Political Action Committee
(NEA-PAC) is
<P>
the federally registered political action arm of the NEA.<BR>

<P>
WEA-PAC was created by the WEA and became effective September
1, 1994.<BR>

<P>
Prior to September 1, 1994 the political action arm of the WEA
was
<P>
Political Unity Leaders in State Education (PULSE). PULSE dues
were $13.00
<P>
annually and were in addition to the dues paid to the WEA, the
NEA, the
<P>
local and the UniServ councils.<BR>

<P>
School district payroll offices collected the PULSE dues which
were
<P>
then distributed to the WEA.<BR>

<P>
The PULSE dues were collected automatically unless a WEA member
requested
<P>
that the money not be taken from their salary or wages.<BR>

<P>
The automatic withholding of wages for PULSE was considered a
=ECreverse=EE
<P>
check-off system.<BR>

<P>
In November of 1992 the voters of Washington State passed Initiative
134
<P>
which, in part, eliminated the =ECreverse=EE check-off option
and required a=
<P>
n
<P>
affirmative annual authorization by WEA members to collect funds
for
<P>
contributions to political committees or for use as political
<P>
contributions.<BR>

<P>
In December of 1992 a task force entitled =ECLife After Initiative
134=EE wa=
<P>
s
<P>
created by the WEA to examine the new law and assess WEA political
action
<P>
options in light of the new regulations.
<P>
CITIZEN COMPLAINTS<BR>

<P>
On February 1, 1996 a formal complaint against the WEA and WEA-PAC
was
<P>
received by the staff of the Public Disclosure Commission.<BR>

<P>
The complaint alleged a violation of RCW 42.17.680 after the WEA
loaned
<P>
WEA-PAC $162,255.00 and began repaying the loan with a new dues
assessment.<BR>

<P>
On February 6, 1996 a second complaint was received also alleging
a
<P>
violation of RCW 42.17.680 claiming that compulsory union dues
were used
<P>
for campaign activity conducted by WEA-PAC. This complaint also
refers to
<P>
the loan and the repayment with the new dues assessment.<BR>

<P>
On March 1, 1996 the staff received a complaint against the WEA
and WEA-PAC
<P>
alleging a violation of RCW 42.17.080 and RCW 42.17.090. This
complaint
<P>
alleged that WEA-PAC, the WEA and Blue Cross of Washington and
Alaska were
<P>
in collusion to circumvent disclosure reporting requirements.
<BR>

<P>
On May 22, 1996 the staff of the PDC received a complaint against
the
<P>
Sedro-Woolley School District and every other school district
in the state
<P>
for an alleged violation of RCW 42.17.680 when they began withholding
$1.00
<P>
per month per WEA member for the WEA Community Outreach Program
without
<P>
annual employee authorization.<BR>

<P>
On August 23, 1996 the staff received a complaint alleging the
WEA violated
<P>
RCW 42.17.680, RCW 42.17.080 and RCW 42.17.090. This complaint
was a
<P>
reiteration of complaints filed previously.<BR>

<P>
PUBLIC DISCLOSURE COMMISSION ACTION<BR>
<BR>

<P>
In 1995 WEA-PAC was scheduled for an audit by the staff of the
PDC.<BR>

<P>
The audit was assigned to Senior Political Finance Specialist
Joe Beck who
<P>
opened the audit on April 15, 1995.<BR>

<P>
Mr. Beck left the employment of the PDC prior to completion of
the audit.<BR>

<P>
The WEA-PAC audit was held until current staff finished their
assigned work
<P>
schedules.<BR>

<P>
Political Finance Specialist for the PDC Mike Moran was assigned
the
<P>
WEA-PAC audit in January of 1996. At that time the scope of the
audit was
<P>
narrowed to include only a review of bank records and invoices
to determine
<P>
accuracy and timeliness of disclosure filings.<BR>

<P>
On March 1, 1996 a letter was sent to Mr. C.T. Purdom requesting
a response
<P>
to a complaint against the WEA alleging that the WEA was trying
to subvert
<P>
campaign finance reform laws by loans made prior to the implementation
of
<P>
Initiative 134.<BR>

<P>
The letter stated that his response would =ECdetermine what further
action
<P>
the commission would pursue=EE.<BR>

<P>
On March 14, 1996 a response to the Purdom letter was received
from Ms.
<P>
Harriet Strasberg indicating the loans were made to reimburse
PULSE for
<P>
administrative and operating overhead. See exhibit #1.<BR>

<P>
Ms. Strasberg wrote that =ECIt was subsequently decided that WEA-PAC
funds
<P>
would not be used to repay the loans. Rather, WEA used internal
funds from
<P>
its community organizing account to repay the WEA general account.=EE
<BR>

<P>
A determination was made by Assistant Director Susan Harris to
not include
<P>
a review of citizens allegations of statutory violations contained
in
<P>
complaints against the WEA and WEA-PAC as part of the audit examination.
<BR>

<P>
At no time did the audit involve the activities of WEA or PULSE.
<BR>

<P>
An exit interview was held on April 5, 1996 in the offices of
the PDC and
<P>
Mr. Moran submitted his report of examination on April 15, 1996.
<BR>
