III.
<P>
ISSUE<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Statutory Citations<BR>
<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.680 Limitations on employers or labor organizations.
<BR>

<P>
No employer or other person or entity responsible for the disbursement
of
<P>
funds in payment of wages or salaries may withhold or divert a
portion of
<P>
an employee=EDs wages or salaries for contributions to political
committees
<P>
or for use as political contributions except upon the written
request of
<P>
the employee. The request must be made on a form prescribed by
the
<P>
commission informing the employee of the prohibition against employer
and
<P>
labor organization discrimination described in subsection (2)
of this
<P>
section. The request is valid for no more than twelve months from
the date
<P>
it is made by the employee.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.080<BR>

<P>
At the following intervals each treasurer shall file with the
commission
<P>
and the county auditor or elections officer of the county in which
the
<P>
candidate resides, or in the case of a political committee, the
county in
<P>
which the committee maintains its office or headquarters, and
if there is
<P>
no office headquarters then in the county in which the treasurer
resides,
<P>
report containing the information required by RCW 42.17.090.<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.090 reads in part:<BR>

<P>
Each report required under RCW 42.17.080 (1) and (2) shall disclose
the
<P>
following:<BR>

<P>
The name and address of each person who has made one or more contributions
<P>
during the period, together with the money value and date of such
<P>
contributions and the aggregate value of contributions received
from each
<P>
such person during the campaign or in the case of a continuing
political
<P>
committee, the current calendar year:<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.630 (b)(vi) and (vii)*<BR>

<P>
Subject to further definition by the commission, =ECcontribution=EE
does not
<P>
include the following:
<P>
An expenditure by a political committee for its own internal organization
<P>
or fund raising without direct association with individual candidates;
<P>
An internal political communication primarily limited to the contributors
<P>
to a political party organization or political action committee,
or the
<P>
officers, management staff, and stockholders of a corporation
or similar
<P>
enterprise, or the members of a labor organization or other membership
<P>
organization;<BR>

<P>
*This section was eliminated with the implementation of ESSB 5684
on July
<P>
1, 1995. Subsection (vi) was incorporated into RCW 42.17.640.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.020(14)(a)(i) and (14)(b)(v)<BR>

<P>
(a) =ECContribution=EE includes:
<P>
A loan, gift, deposit, subscription, forgiveness of indebtedness,
donation,
<P>
advance, pledge, payment, transfer of funds between political
committees,
<P>
or anything of value, including personal and professional services
for less
<P>
than full consideration;<BR>

<P>
=ECContribution=EE does not include:
<P>
An internal political communication primarily limited to the members
of or
<P>
contributors to a political party organization or political committee,
or
<P>
to the officers, management staff, or stockholders of a corporation
or
<P>
similar enterprise, or to the members of a labor organization
or other
<P>
membership organization;<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.020 (19)<BR>

<P>
=ECExpenditure=EE includes a payment, contribution subscription,
distributio=
<P>
n,
<P>
loan, advance, deposit, or gift of money or anything of value,
and includes
<P>
a contract, promise, or agreement, whether or not legally enforceable,
to
<P>
make an expenditure. The term =ECexpenditure=EE also includes
a promise to
<P>
pay, a payment, or transfer of anything of value in exchange for
goods,
<P>
services, property, facilities, or anything of value for the purpose
of
<P>
assisting, benefiting, or honoring any public official or candidate,
or
<P>
assisting in furthering or opposing any election campaign. For
the
<P>
purposes of this chapter, agreements to make expenditures, contracts,
and
<P>
promises to pay may be reported as estimated obligations until
actual
<P>
payment is made. The term =ECexpenditure=EE shall not include
the partial o=
<P>
r
<P>
complete repayment by a candidate or political committee of the
principal
<P>
of a loan, the receipt of which loan has been properly reported.
<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.020 (33)<BR>

<P>
=ECPolitical committee=EE means any person (except a candidate
or an individ=
<P>
ual
<P>
dealing with his or her own funds or property) having the expectation
of
<P>
receiving contributions or making expenditures in support of,
or opposition
<P>
to, any candidate or any ballot proposition.<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.040 states in part:<BR>

<P>
Every political committee, within two weeks after its organization
or,
<P>
within two weeks after the date when it first has the expectation
of
<P>
receiving contributions or making expenditures in any election
campaign,
<P>
whichever is earlier, shall file a statement of organization with
the
<P>
commission and with the county auditor or elections officer of
the county
<P>
in which the candidate resides, or in the case of any other political
<P>
committee, the county in which the treasurer resides.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.200 Grass roots lobbying campaigns.<BR>

<P>
Any person who has made expenditures, not reported by a registered
lobbyist
<P>
under RCW 421.17.170 or by a candidate or political committee
under RCW
<P>
42.17.065 or 42.17.080, exceeding five hundred dollars in the
aggregate
<P>
within any three-month period or exceeding two hundred dollars
in the
<P>
aggregate within any one-month period in presenting a program
addressed to
<P>
the public, a substantial portion of which is intended, designed,
or
<P>
calculated primarily to influence legislation shall be required
to register
<P>
and report, as provided in subsection (2) of this section, as
a sponsor of
<P>
a grass roots lobbying campaign.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.170Reporting by lobbyists.<BR>

<P>
Any lobbyist registered under RCW 42.17.150 and any person who
lobbies
<P>
shall file with the commission periodic reports of his or her
activities
<P>
signed by the lobbyist. The reports shall be made in the form
and manner
<P>
prescribed by the commission. They shall be due monthly and shall
be filed
<P>
within fifteen days after the last day of the calendar month covered
by the
<P>
report.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.180 Reports by employers of registered lobbyists, other
persons.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
The total expenditures made by the person reporting for lobbying
purposes,
<P>
whether through or on behalf of a registered lobbyist or otherwise.
<BR>

<P>
All contributions made to a political committee supporting or
opposing a
<P>
candidate for state office, or to a political committee supporting
or
<P>
opposing a state-wide ballot proposition.<BR>

<P>
The identifying proposition number and a brief description of
any
<P>
state-wide ballot proposition supported or opposed by expenditures
not
<P>
reported under (d) of this subsection and the amount of each such
<P>
expenditure.<BR>

<P>
CENTRAL ISSUES<BR>
<BR>

<P>
The allegations from the complainants center around two central
points of
<P>
public disclosure law.<BR>

<P>
=46irst, the complainants question the use of a mandatory WEA
dues
<P>
assessments (Community Outreach Funds) without gaining annual
authorization
<P>
by the individual union members.<BR>

<P>
The allegations state that one of the primary purposes of the
new Community
<P>
Outreach assessment was to further the political activity of WEA
and
<P>
WEA-PAC.<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.680 would prohibit mandatory assessments to a political
committee
<P>
or for political contributions without an annual authorization
from
<P>
individual members.<BR>

<P>
The second point is the lack of public disclosure of reportable
political
<P>
expenditures by the WEA and WEA-PAC. The allegations question
the
<P>
expenditure of WEA funds to support political committee activity
and that
<P>
such activity has not been disclosed to the public.<BR>

<P>
RCW 42.17.040, RCW 42.17.080 and RCW 42.17.090 requires that political
<P>
committees register and report contributions and expenditures
in a timely
<P>
manner to the Public Disclosure Commission and the appropriate
county
<P>
auditor.<BR>

<P>
Additionally, the issue of potential reportable expenditures in
the area of
<P>
grassroots lobbying and related lobbying activities that would
require
<P>
public disclosure under RCW 42.17.200, RCW 42.17.170 and RCW 42.17.180
was
<P>
explored.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
IV.
<P>
=46ACTS<BR>

<P>
Life After 134 Task Force<BR>
<BR>

<P>
CREATION<BR>

<P>
Carla Nuxoll, immediate past president of the WEA, created the
=ECLife After
<P>
134 Task Force=EE in 1992 to examine WEA political options in
light of the
<P>
passage of Initiative 134.<BR>

<P>
Nuxoll stated in her interview under oath (NIO) that the WEA was
interested
<P>
in analyzing the initiative to find out what it meant and wanted
to make
<P>
sure that whatever direction they took would be in line with that
law.<BR>

<P>
I do know this that when we were talking about what we were going
to do
<P>
with 134, we wanted to make sure that what we did was the right
thing.
<P>
That was a primary purpose of that committee, was to analyze it
so we knew
<P>
precisely what we could use money for and what we couldn=EDt uh
out of what
<P>
pots if you will and collection methods we could use money and
what we
<P>
couldn=EDt. (NIO P 10-11)<BR>

<P>
James Seibert, Executive Director of the WEA, stated in an interview
under
<P>
oath (SIO) that the task force was set up to begin assessing how
the WEA
<P>
could continue to be involved in political action and continue
to raise
<P>
political action funds. (SIO P 6)<BR>

<P>
Seibert said that the Life After 134 Task Force was designed to
provide a
<P>
forum for a broad discussion of the way they were doing business.
<BR>

<P>
...Right at the very beginning, that this was an opportunity to
reexamine
<P>
everything that we had been doing organizationally and try to
come up with
<P>
something that was in compliance with what 134 had required, but
at the
<P>
same time trying to reinvigorate at least a feeling of our members
at the
<P>
local level that there was value in the WEA being active in the
political
<P>
process. (SIO P 10)<BR>

<P>
Purdom, President of the WEA, said in an interview under oath
(PIO) that in
<P>
his opinion Initiative 134 was an all out attack on the WEA.<BR>

<P>
Purdom stated that the task force was created to look at changes
occurring
<P>
due to the initiative.<BR>

<P>
Well, the Life After 134 Task Force was appointed to help us come
to grips
<P>
and to understand how Initiative 134 impacted us as an organization,
to
<P>
identify the kinds of changes that we needed to make to be in
compliance
<P>
with that law. (PIO P 5)<BR>

<P>
And<BR>

<P>
One of the functions of the task force was to look at how we might
do
<P>
business in the future, how we might do a better job of, what
process we
<P>
might use in terms of recruiting members. =EBCause it was very
clear that w=
<P>
e
<P>
would need to do an annual sign-up. (PIO P 8)<BR>

<P>
Purdom said that the Life After 134 Task Force looked at the short
and long
<P>
term problems.<BR>

<P>
The Life After 134 Task Force really had two, two chunks of time
they
<P>
looked at. One was the immediate to get us into line and make
sure we
<P>
weren=EDt violating the new law and start getting a handle on
it to try and
<P>
consolidate as much money as we could, and then the second phase
was then
<P>
to look at the long term, how we were going to configure ourselves
for the
<P>
future, both in terms of structure and in terms of how we were
going to go
<P>
about raising funds. (PIO P 32-33)<BR>
<BR>

<P>
=46UNDING SOURCES<BR>

<P>
The first meeting of the Life After 134 Task Force was on February
17, 1993
<P>
with the initial goal to replace PULSE dues with a contingency
assessment
<P>
for =ECcommunity education=EE. See exhibit #1a.<BR>

<P>
The emphasis according to NEA Advisor John Chase was to not lose
revenue
<P>
and to =ECmaintain our continuous structure=EE.<BR>

<P>
Seibert said the task force looked at alternatives to a change
in the dues
<P>
check-off system.<BR>

<P>
Well, one of the major factors, one of the major requirements
of Initiative
<P>
134 was the fact that there was a change from the ability of the
WEA to
<P>
have a reverse dues check-off system for political action activities
to one
<P>
in which we had to sign-up the members every year. And so we talked
about
<P>
a vast array of alternatives on how to do that. (SIO P 8)<BR>

<P>
Robert Maier, Lobbyist for the WEA, said in an interview under
oath (MIO)
<P>
that they were not talking about getting around contribution limits
just
<P>
how to remain politically viable in the face of the Initiative.
(MIO P 15)<BR>

<P>
Maier said that one of the concerns of the Life After 134 Task
Force was
<P>
how to raise money.<BR>

<P>
Well, what we had to deal with was, primarily how to raise money
to
<P>
continue to function as an organization active in the political
world.
<P>
Because the law specifically took away our right to collect dues
by reverse
<P>
dues check-off. (MIO P 4)<BR>

<P>
Don Maekawa, Former Controller/Treasurer of the WEA, said in an
interview
<P>
under oath (MAEIO) that requiring members to sign annual authorizations
was
<P>
a concern of the Life After 134 Task Force.<BR>

<P>
I think there=EDs some charges the committee, or task force were
given
<P>
written charges as to what to do, but essentially, it was to take
a look at
<P>
the impact of Initiative 134 and come up with some recommendations
on how
<P>
we could get past this and continue business as usual without
having a,
<P>
=EBcause potentially it could have really cut down the collection
of our
<P>
PULSE dues. (MAEIO P 9)<BR>

<P>
Discussion at the February 8, 1994 meeting of the Life After I-134
Task
<P>
=46orce, as reflected in the minutes, centered around issues that
were raise=
<P>
d
<P>
by UniServ Councils.<BR>

<P>
The following comments and concerns were voiced:<BR>

<P>
Not willing to have a dues increase.
<P>
$13 too high, should be $10 or $12. It wouldn=EDt look like we
were rolling
<P>
it over.
<P>
Do not like the idea of an annual drive.
<P>
We need a systematic way of generating money.
<P>
It is really only a dues increase for those people who have opted
out of
<P>
PULSE in the past.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
AFFILIATION<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Throughout the minutes of the Life After 134 Task Force there
is a concern
<P>
about exceeding the contribution limits to Legislative and Statewide
<P>
Executive candidates.<BR>

<P>
The April 1993 meeting of the Life After 134 Task Force began
to discuss
<P>
the issue of affiliation.<BR>

<P>
The penalties for failing to comply with the initiative are severe,
we
<P>
suspect. Limitations are interlocking, including all state PACs
and we
<P>
have asked for a formal legal opinion.<BR>

<P>
The concept of the councils closing their existing PAC checking
accounts
<P>
and the WEA doing all the reporting was discussed at the April
meeting.<BR>

<P>
Minutes of the June 21, 1993 meeting of the 134 task force stated
that as
<P>
of a certain date all contributions will be distributed by PULSE.
<BR>

<P>
After November 15, 1993, PULSE will house the hard money and will
<P>
distribute contributions as requested by Council PAC=EDs. Though
PAC=EDs wi=
<P>
ll
<P>
not have to be registered with the PDC, they will continue to
function as
<P>
committees charged with carrying out traditional PAC activities.
<BR>

<P>
Recommendations from the June meeting addressed the affiliation
question.<BR>

<P>
UniServ PAC=EDs will no longer have to report expenditures to
the Public
<P>
Disclosure Commission. WEA=EDs legal Division has determined Initiative
134
<P>
=ECprohibits any contributions from PULSE and from the UPAC=EDs,
which, in t=
<P>
he
<P>
aggregate, would exceed the limits placed on contributions by
Part III,
<P>
Section 4 of I-134.=EE<BR>

<P>
As such, we recommend that councils close their existing PAC checking
<P>
accounts and EITHER add it to their council budget as a soft money
line
<P>
item described earlier OR return the money to PULSE and have it
credited to
<P>
the council=EDs hard money account for 1994.<BR>

<P>
Seibert said that WEA decided they would take on the responsibility
of all
<P>
the reporting because they didn=EDt want to make any mistakes.
<BR>

<P>
But, prior to 134, UniServ Councils had some reporting responsibilities.
<P>
They didn=EDt after 134, because PDC determined that we had to
be a single
<P>
PAC statewide, and so we decided that we would take on the responsibility
<P>
of all the reporting because it was easier for us to make sure
they didn=EDt
<P>
make mistakes, or that they didn=EDt fail to report, that we would
be
<P>
responsible since we were determined to be a single PAC after
134. (SIO P
<P>
13)<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Robert Fisher, former Assistant Executive Director for Governmental
<P>
Relations and Political Affairs, said in an interview under oath
(FIO) that
<P>
his biggest concern was both PULSE and local PAC=EDs would contribute
to
<P>
candidates they would go over the limits imposed by Initiative
134. (FIO
<P>
P4)<BR>

<P>
Maier said that they asked the UniServ Councils to disband their
PAC=EDs.<BR>

<P>
I just stated that we wanted to have so that we could make recommendations
<P>
to a system and sort of maintain a statewide, well, not control,
but
<P>
influence or opportunity to talk about how this money should be
used. And
<P>
in the process of that, we asked them to disband their PAC=EDs,
we were real
<P>
concerned about the reporting issues and the financial consequences
of
<P>
that. (MIO P 17)<BR>
