<P>
RECOMMENDATIONS<BR>
<BR>

<P>
On March 6, 1993 the PULSE General Membership voted to approve
the initial
<P>
recommendations of the Life After Initiative 134 Task Force and
requested
<P>
that a full report and recommendations for action be presented
at the 1994
<P>
PULSE General Membership meeting. See exhibit # 2.<BR>

<P>
The recommendations included:<BR>

<P>
Accelerated dues collection.
<P>
Create a designated fund for political contributions.
<P>
Request a loan from WEA to cover operational costs.
<P>
Redraft guidelines for LEAF funds to preserve as much =EChard
money=EE as po=
<P>
ssible.
<P>
Assign the Task Force to complete their charges in time for action
by the
<P>
1994 Representative Assembly.<BR>

<P>
In April of 1994 the Life After 134 Task Force recommended a restructuring
<P>
of the political action program to the WEA Representative Assembly.
<BR>

<P>
The recommendations included Constitution and Bylaws amendments
that set up
<P>
the new structure of WEA-PAC and Community Outreach and funded
the program
<P>
with an additional $12 from WEA members.<BR>

<P>
The new structure eliminated the PULSE Board and designated the
WEA Board
<P>
of Directors as the managers of WEA-PAC.<BR>

<P>
The changes were said to be designed to put more decision making
power at
<P>
the council level and gave one half of the increase in dues ($6)
back to
<P>
the UniServ Councils to be used for local political programs.
<BR>

<P>
The minutes of Life After I-134 Task Force meeting on March 8,
1994 shows
<P>
that there was an open discussion on the dues increase/exchange.
<BR>

<P>
If we don=EDt have a dues increase/exchange, we would have to
sign up member=
<P>
s
<P>
each year. We would not have enough money.
<P>
Members need to understand it is a dues exchange, not an increase.
<P>
Change the name of PULSE and continue payroll deductions at $13
for soft mon=
<P>
ey.<BR>
