<P>
Hard and Soft Money<BR>

<P>
The first reference to =EChard=EE and =ECsoft=EE money was reflected
in the =
<P>
minutes
<P>
of the February meeting of the Life After 134 Task Force.<BR>

<P>
We need to save as much hard money as we can and make sure hard
money is in
<P>
supply to meet the needs of the organization.<BR>

<P>
Under the heading Suggestions to RA in the February 1993 minutes
is a
<P>
discussion of =EChard=EE and =ECsoft=EE money.<BR>

<P>
Define how we will use the fund. =ECThose activities deemed to
be consisten=
<P>
t
<P>
with I-134 previously done by PULSE.=EE Part will be used for
communicating
<P>
with the community on quality education. Use the fund for purposes
not
<P>
considered political contributions under I-134. Save existing
PULSE money
<P>
for direct contributions (Hard money). Everything else will come
out of
<P>
the new general fund (Soft money).<BR>

<P>
Seibert said the terms hard and soft money became very common
in the Life
<P>
After 134 Task Force meetings.<BR>

<P>
It was a term that became very common in the conversation in the
Life After
<P>
134 Task Force. It probably took on its, you know, that=EDs when
it really
<P>
became a term used inside the WEA. I think prior to 134 it would
be safe
<P>
to say that 99 percent of our leaders and 100 percent of our members
had no
<P>
idea about any distinction between these. And it clearly grew
out of
<P>
making a distinction after 134. (SIO P 23)<BR>
