<P>
NEA MODEL<BR>
<BR>

<P>
It appears that the concept of =EChard=EE and =ECsoft=EE money
was modeled a=
<P>
fter
<P>
the Federal Election Commission and NEA examples.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Nuxoll said that the term soft money was a NEA term.<BR>

<P>
It was words that sort of connected with the way NEA talked about
funds
<P>
that they used in dealing with the national and sort of it was
not exact
<P>
but sort of analogous to what we were going to have to deal with.
So I
<P>
think that is kind of how we started to use it. I do know this,
hard money
<P>
meant the money we could give to candidates. Soft money was more
amorphous
<P>
I guess. (NIO P 10)<BR>

<P>
Nuxoll said that with soft money there were no hard and fast rules
and
<P>
there were a multitude of uses and a multitude of situations and
things
<P>
associated with it.<BR>

<P>
Seibert said his understanding of hard and soft money grows out
of the FEC
<P>
regulations.<BR>

<P>
I mean, generally, it=EDs similar to, the term in my experience,
grows out o=
<P>
f
<P>
the FEC and how NEA-PAC money has been treated over the years,
in terms of
<P>
what can be treated as hard money and soft money. (SIO P 21-22)
<BR>

<P>
Maier said that there was discussion among members of the Life
After 134
<P>
Task Force about the distinction at the Federal level about hard
and soft
<P>
money and how the political parties could separate the two types
of funds.<BR>

<P>
I don=EDt know that we predicated our decision to do that based
on the
<P>
parties. I just shared with them that when we contributed to parties
that
<P>
we used two different funds. Uh, and that it was consistent with
what we
<P>
were talking about and consistent with what I read in the initiative,
and
<P>
consistent with what we had told our members, and I had been told
even when
<P>
I came into this job that we used to use hard money for everything,
because
<P>
we had unlimited resources. Now that we didn=EDt we had to comply
by the
<P>
law, but that there were things that we could do that would not
require PAC
<P>
money. (MIO P13)<BR>

<P>
NEA Advisor John Chase suggested at the April 20, 1993 meeting
of the task
<P>
force as reflected in the minutes that a number of ideas should
