<P>
USE OF FUNDS<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Maier said that in his reading of the law it is clear that contributions
to
<P>
candidates is one thing, and everything else can be considered
soft money.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Maier stated that his understanding of hard and soft money centered
around
<P>
candidate contributions.<BR>

<P>
The distinction that I made, and that I actually had conversations
with
<P>
some of your staff about, was that hard money was contributions
to
<P>
candidates, and everything else was soft money. (MIO P 6)<BR>

<P>
Maekawa said that his understanding is that hard money would be
essentially
<P>
moneys that go to political candidates and that soft money was
overhead and
<P>
things that are not for contributions to help candidates into
public
<P>
office. (MAEIO P 32)<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Maier said that he believed that funds expended on ballot measures
and
<P>
initiatives were considered soft money.<BR>

<P>
That in the strictest sense of the law, we thought was soft money,
<P>
although, we had, for a time internally, advocated using hard
money for
<P>
that, because we wanted people to use that as a way of raising
WEA-PAC
<P>
dollars. But we always were clear with them that it was not prohibited
by
<P>
law as far as we were concerned. (MIO P 6)<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Purdom said that his understanding was that expenditures for ballot
<P>
measures and referendum were not hard money activities and excluded
under
<P>
Initiative 134. He said he believed that support for ballot measures
and
<P>
referendums would be considered soft money expenditures. (PIO
P 45)<BR>
<BR>

<P>
The ballot measures and local races and at the county level, and
the city,
<P>
and those kind of things are not addressed as being restrictive
in any way.
<P>
I mean, that=EDs how we got into calling it hard and soft money.
(PIO P 49)<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Rod Regan, WEA staff member, said in an interview under oath (RIO)
that his
<P>
understanding was that soft money could not be used in contributions
<P>
directly to candidate campaigns, legislative candidate campaigns
and that
<P>
administrative costs, initiatives and ballot measures could be
funded with
<P>
soft money. (RIO P 10-11)<BR>
<BR>

