indicate
<P>
that the concept of =EChard=EE and =ECsoft=EE money was initially
brought up=
<P>
by Mr.
<P>
Maier.<BR>

<P>
Soft money can be used for items listed in Initiative 134 under
PART
<P>
II-Definitions, Section 3-5(b) (Attached). Discussion on these
items
<P>
followed. It was agreed that a copy of this list will be sent
to UniServ
<P>
Councils. PULSE hard money is strictly for contributions.<BR>

<P>
A memorandum sent by Mr. Maier in the summer of 1994 to all interested
<P>
parties discussed =ECSoft=EE money uses. See exhibit # 3.<BR>

<P>
The memorandum states in part:<BR>

<P>
What we know for sure is that anything that is NOT a DIRECT or
IN-KIND
<P>
contribution to a candidate at the local, legislative, or state
level CAN
<P>
be paid for with soft money.<BR>

<P>
The memorandum also outlined a list of soft money uses. That list
included
<P>
fundraising for WEA and NEA PAC and for individual for candidates,
GOTV
<P>
mailings, support of state level initiatives and referenda, and
issues
<P>
campaigns with registered voters.<BR>

<P>
Maier said that the WEA distinction about using hard money for
issues
<P>
campaigns was an internal ploy to raise more WEA-PAC money.<BR>

<P>
I mean, it was an internal ploy to raise more WEA-PAC money. But
we never
<P>
said, and it was never told to us, and I=EDm sure I asked the
question about
<P>
whether we had to use PAC money for initiatives and school levies,
and no
<P>
one ever told me I had to. And I was always in the assumption
that we
<P>
could just go ahead and do that, and if we did that, in terms
of a soft
<P>
money contribution, we were to report it, but it wouldn=EDt have
to be PAC
<P>
dollars. (MIO P 9)<BR>
