<P>
POLITICAL ACTION<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Political Unity Leaders in State Education (PULSE) was the political
action
<P>
arm of the WEA until September 1, 1994 when WEA-PAC became the
official
<P>
political committee of WEA.<BR>

<P>
The functions of PULSE were divided between WEA-PAC and a new
Community
<P>
Outreach Program.<BR>

<P>
In the March 1994 issues of WEA Action, Mr. Purdom stated that
one of the
<P>
major decisions to be made is how to fund the new political action
program.
<P>
See exhibit # 4.<BR>

<P>
He said the money spent on political activities is classified
into two
<P>
types of funds known as =ECsoft=EE and =EChard=EE money.<BR>

<P>
To fund a new political action program, the task force is recommending
two
<P>
sources of funding based on the need to maintain two separate
types of
<P>
financial support.<BR>

<P>
He stated that =EChard=EE money would be raised through a voluntary
system o=
<P>
f
<P>
membership in the new WEA-PAC organization and =ECsoft=EE money
would be rai=
<P>
sed
<P>
through a =ECcontribution/dues exchange=EE.<BR>

<P>
The $13 per year PULSE contribution will be eliminated and $12
would be
<P>
added to the WEA dues. Those PULSE members now paying $13 would
pay only
<P>
$12 next year. These monies would be divided equally between the
state and
<P>
council/locals.<BR>

<P>
The =ECcontribution/dues exchange=EE mentioned was a mandatory
membership du=
<P>
es
<P>
increase to fund the Community Outreach Program within the WEA.
<BR>

<P>
Seibert stated in =ECSetting the Record Straight=EE that the Representative
<P>
Assembly created WEA-PAC and the funding for the Community Outreach
<P>
Program. See exhibit #4a.<BR>

<P>
In April 1994, following extensive debate, the WEA Representative
Assembly
<P>
overwhelmingly approved the creation of WEA-PAC to replace PULSE
and also
<P>
created a special new dues category of $12 per year to fund a
Community
<P>
Outreach Program. Half of the dues ($6) were to be rebated directly
to
<P>
UniServ Councils.<BR>

<P>
Two of the purposes of the Community Outreach Program - clearly
explained
<P>
to RA delegates - were to generate funds for UniServ Councils
to carry on
<P>
politically-related activities in local communities and to cover
WEA=EDs sof=
<P>
t
<P>
money costs in order to preserve hard money for political contributions.
<BR>

<P>
The May 1994 issue of WEA Action outlined the changes in the WEA
political
<P>
action program.<BR>

<P>
WEA Vice President Lee Ann Prielipp and Governmental Relations
Field
<P>
Representative Bob Maier gave delegates the recommendations of
the =ECLife
<P>
After 134=EE Task Force and fielded questions from members about
the purpose
<P>
and uses of the proposed $12 dues increase to offset the effects
of
<P>
Initiative 134=EDs restrictions.<BR>

<P>
And<BR>

<P>
At all levels, state-council-local, the $12 will be considered
=ECsoft
<P>
money=EE, meaning that it cannot be used for direct or indirect
campaign
<P>
contributions. It can be used for such activities as: coalition
building;
<P>
community organizing; member awareness; training; candidate recruitment;
<P>
political technology; our member lobby program; the endorsement
convention;
<P>
initiative and ballot measures; and community communications.
<BR>

<P>
In April of 1994 the WEA Representative Assembly voted to create
the
<P>
special new dues category of $12.00 per year to fund a Community
Outreach
<P>
Program.<BR>

<P>
The new WEA-PAC was to be funded by a voluntary payroll deduction
of $12
<P>
which was to be authorized by each member on an annual basis.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Regan said that one of the changes resulting from the Life After
134 Task
<P>
=46orce was to disband PULSE, create WEA-PAC and create the Community
<P>
Outreach funds. (RIO P 6)<BR>

<P>
=46isher said that PULSE was disbanded and that the Community
Outreach
<P>
Program did some of the activities that used to be conducted under
PULSE.
<P>
(FIO P 17)<BR>

<P>
=46isher said that the WEA was doing the type of things WEA-PAC
and the
<P>
Community Outreach Program began doing after Initiative 134.<BR>

<P>
So we have been doing that kind of activity for some time and
really what
<P>
it was a way of encouraging our local folks to be more active
in areas
<P>
other than just putting money in campaigns. So it was an encouragement
to
<P>
them to get themselves going on some other coalition and those
type of
<P>
activities. (FIO P 19)<BR>

<P>
PULSE REDUCTIONS<BR>

<P>
One concern voiced by Purdom, Seibert, Maier and Regan was the
drop in
<P>
participation in the WEA political action committee once the reverse
<P>
check-off provisions under payroll deductions were eliminated.
<BR>

<P>
Prior to 134 passing, we had approximately 42 to 43 thousand PULSE
members.
<P>
PULSE dues were $13.00 a year, so it was slightly more than a
dollar a
<P>
month that was collected. (SIO P 11)<BR>

<P>
Seibert said that the impact of Initiative 134 resulted in an
80 percent
<P>
drop in contributions.<BR>

<P>
It dropped almost immediately to eight, right in that area, and
it=EDs begun
<P>
to go up. It=EDs between eleven and twelve, I think now. (SIO
P 19)<BR>

