<P>
DUES COLLECTION<BR>

<P>
The Community Outreach dues were segregated both in the collection
at the
<P>
local school district and in the accounting within WEA.<BR>

<P>
A copy of the North Thurston School District APA Dues &amp; Contribution
<P>
Billing from the WEA show separate withholding for NEA dues, WEA
dues,
<P>
Community Outreach Funds, UniServ Council dues, Local Education
Association
<P>
dues, NEA-PAC contributions and WEA-PAC contributions. See exhibit
# 5.<BR>

<P>
Purdom said that the Community Outreach Program funding is kept
in a
<P>
separate account of the budget and is collected at the same time
as general
<P>
dues. (PIO P 40)<BR>

<P>
A memorandum sent to School District Payroll Officers on July
20, 1995 from
<P>
=46ern Buffington, WEA Director of Membership Systems, shows that
the
<P>
Community Outreach Dues are separate from the WEA Dues and are
to be
<P>
deducted from all Active members regardless of FTE status. The
memorandum
<P>
goes on to state that Agency Shop Fee Payers are exempt from the
Outreach
<P>
Dues. See exhibit # 6.<BR>

<P>
A similar memorandum sent to School District Payroll Officers
shows that
<P>
CPEA Membership Dues include a separate $12 per month for Community
<P>
Outreach. See exhibit # 7.<BR>

<P>
Purdom also said that Agency Fee Payers were excluded from the
assessment
<P>
so they don=EDt have to spend additional time arguing with agency
fee payers=
<P>
.<BR>

<P>
The Community Outreach dues increase appears to have generated
$643,847.00
<P>
between September 1, 1994 and August 31, 1995. Expenditures for
the
<P>
Community Outreach Program for that same period were $672,432.28.
A
<P>
difference of $28,585.28.<BR>

<P>
Between September 1, 1995 and August 31, 1996 it appears that
the Community
<P>
Outreach dues increase generated $597,058.00. Expenditures for
the
<P>
Community Outreach Program for that same period were $671,719.21.
A
<P>
difference of $74,661.21.<BR>

<P>
It is not known where the additional funds originated.<BR>

<P>
PDC INQUIRY<BR>

<P>
On March 23, 1994 Mr. Fisher wrote a letter to PDC Acting Director
David
<P>
Clark requesting information concerning changes in PULSE. See
exhibit # 8.<BR>

<P>
Mr. Fisher wrote the following:<BR>

<P>
If the purpose of PULSE changes from a political action committee
to a
<P>
committee that does not make campaign contributions, but, uses
the funds
<P>
for purposes such as:<BR>

<P>
1.Community communication on education issues;
<P>
2.Underwriting the cost of endorsement conventions;
<P>
3.Support of member lobbying;
<P>
4.Coalition building;
<P>
5.Community and member issue awareness;
<P>
6.Underwriting the membership drive for WEA-PAC, a newly created
political
<P>
action committee;
<P>
7.General member training for political involvement;
<P>
8.Political technology such as computers, software, etc.; and,
<P>
9.issue polling.<BR>

<P>
Can PULSE continue to collect contributions by payroll deduction
without
<P>
annually obtaining deduction authorization?<BR>

<P>
To ensure a clear separation between the activities identified
above and
<P>
political campaign contributions, WEA is forming a new political
action
<P>
committee, WEA-PAC.<BR>

<P>
In response to the inquiry by Mr. Fisher, Vicki Rippie, Assistant
Director
<P>
for Public Information and Policy Development, stated in a letter
that some
<P>
of the activities the new PULSE would undertake would be considered
<P>
contributions and that the new PULSE may meet the definition of
a political
<P>
committee and be subject to the annual withholding authorization.
See
<P>
exhibit # 9.<BR>

<P>
PDC staff cannot state unequivocally that new PULSE would not
meet the
<P>
definition of a political committee and thus have its contributors
subject
<P>
to the annual withholding authorization. It depends on what PULSE
actually
<P>
does,..<BR>

<P>
Rippie=EDs letter clearly outline what would constitute an in-kind
<P>
contribution from WEA to WEA-PAC.<BR>

<P>
In addition, the new PULSE would underwrite the costs of: 1) WEA=EDs
<P>
candidate endorsement conventions; 2) WEA-PAC=EDs membership drive;
3)
<P>
political involvement training for WEA members; and 4) providing
computer
<P>
and software technology to WEA-PAC. WEA understands that these
latter
<P>
three PULSE activities, and perhaps others, would constitute in-kind
<P>
contributions to WEA-PAC.<BR>

<P>
The letter goes on to say =EC(In addition, as we discussed, PULSE=EDs
lobbyi=
<P>
ng
<P>
activity will doubtless qualify is as a lobbyist employer and
all of its
<P>
direct expenditures to influence legislation - including grassroots
<P>
lobbying expenses - will be reportable.)=EE.<BR>

<P>
=46isher said that he would have forwarded Ms. Rippie=EDs response
to Mr. Se=
<P>
ibert.<BR>

<P>
What I would have done with any response I got to a question like
this I
<P>
would have forwarded it up to Seibert. I mean that is where the
decisions
<P>
are made, so this would have gone up to Federal Way. (FIO P 9)
