17-18)<BR>

<P>
Seibert said that the recommendation for a loan came out of the
Initiative
<P>
134 task force.<BR>

<P>
Since we believed at that point that we could pay overhead out
of, out of
<P>
general dues money and expenditures, we decided to make a loan
to
<P>
WEA-PAC/PULSE to do that. So we would be preserving as much of
the hard
<P>
money as possible.. (SIO P 27)<BR>

<P>
On March 6, 1993 the PULSE general membership approved the Life
After 134
<P>
Task Force recommendation to request a loan for WEA to cover operational
<P>
costs and costs identified as PULSE activities which are non-political
<P>
contributions, i.e. =ECsoft money=EE activities. The loan was
to be paid ba=
<P>
ck,
<P>
with interest, not later than September of 1994 with the collection
of the
<P>
1994-95 PULSE dues. See exhibit # 2.<BR>

<P>
On August 31, 1994 the WEA authorized an initial loan to PULSE
for
<P>
$117,115.00. See exhibit # 10.<BR>

<P>
This loan was to cover the =ECsoft money=EE costs incurred by
PULSE from
<P>
January 1, 1994 to July 31, 1994.<BR>

<P>
Shirley Kurrus, former Records Recorder and Accounting Assistant
for the
<P>
WEA and PULSE/WEA-PAC, said in an interview under oath (KIO) that
the
<P>
purpose of the loan was to pay for PULSE=EDs overhead expenditures
for the
<P>
prior year.<BR>

<P>
The administrative and overhead costs for PULSE, the old PULSE,
prior to
<P>
134, were reimbursed to the new WEA-PAC. (KIO P 27)<BR>

