<P>
Partial Report of Investigation
<P>
Washington Education Association and WEA-PAC
<P>
Page - PAGE 23-<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Rec'd from PDC 11/18/96<BR>

<P>
SUPPLEMENT TO REPORT OF INVESTIGATION<BR>

<P>
Introduction
<P>
PDC staff has conducted an investigation of the WEA and WEA-PAC
for
<P>
possible violations of RCW Chapter 42.17.<BR>

<P>
As part of this investigation, staff examined RCW 42.17.680, enacted
as
<P>
part of Initiative 134, which requires the annual reauthorization
of
<P>
payroll deductions for contributions to political committees or
for
<P>
political contributions. In analyzing the application of .680
to the facts
<P>
present in this case, staff discovered that, because of the way
.680(3) was
<P>
drafted, culpable conduct will not always fall within the statute=EDs
<P>
proscription. Staff believes that the voters=ED intent in enacting
.680
<P>
cannot be fulfilled as the statute now reads, and requests authorization
<P>
from the Commission to bring to the attention of the legislature
the
<P>
problem with enforcing this provision of law.<BR>

<P>
Investigative Findings
<P>
During the course of its investigation, staff learned that the
WEA is
<P>
receiving money, in the form of a special assessment levied on
union
<P>
members through payroll deduction, that goes to WEA=EDs Community
Outreach
<P>
Program (COP). Money is automatically deducted from members=ED
paychecks,
<P>
but not from agency fee payers. Members cannot =ECopt out=EE from
the COP
<P>
assessment. A portion of the COP money was used to support WEA-PAC.
<P>
RCW 42.17.680
<P>
In applying the Public Disclosure Law to the pertinent facts,
staff
<P>
examined Subsection (3) of RCW 42.17.680, which states:
<P>
No employer or other person or entity responsible for the disbursement
of
<P>
funds in payment of wages or salaries may withhold or divert a
portion of
<P>
an employee=EDs wages or salaries for contributions to political
committees
<P>
or for use as political contributions except upon the written
request of
<P>
the employee. The request must be made on a form prescribed by
the
<P>
commission informing the employee of the prohibition against employer
and
<P>
labor organization discrimination described in subsection (2)
of this
<P>
section. The request is valid for no more than twelve months from
the date
<P>
it is made by the employee.<BR>

<P>
Application of RCW 42.17.680
<P>
In this instance, assessments were automatically deducted from
WEA members=
<P>
=ED
<P>
paychecks for the COP, which in turn made payments on behalf of
WEA-PAC.
<P>
Members could not decline to pay the COP assessment.<BR>

<P>
In examining RCW 42.17.680 and whether salaries or wages had been
diverted
<P>
for contributions to a political committee or for use as political
<P>
contributions, the issue of who is subject to the statue=EDs prohibition
<P>
arose.<BR>

<P>
The prohibition of RCW 42.17.680 against withholding or diverting
wages for
<P>
political contributions is directed towards the employer or =ECother
person
<P>
or entity responsible for the disbursement of funds in payment
of wages or
<P>
salaries.=EE Clearly, the WEA is not the employer of the members
whose wage=
<P>
s
<P>
are being payroll-deducted. Furthermore, the WEA is not an entity
who is
<P>
=ECresponsible for the disbursement of funds in payment of wages
or
<P>
salaries.=EE If the quoted phrase had ended with the word =ECfunds,=EE
then=
<P>
it
<P>
would certainly be arguable that the WEA was responsible for the
<P>
=ECdisbursement of funds=EE by using the assessment for purposes
of the
<P>
Community Outreach Program. However, the phrase does not end there--it
<P>
goes on to qualify =ECdisbursement of funds=EE with the words
=ECin payment =
<P>
of
<P>
wages or salaries.=EE The WEA does not disburse funds in payment
of its
<P>
members=ED wages or salaries.<BR>

<P>
In trying to interpret whether .680(3) applies to labor organizations
using
<P>
deducted moneys for political purposes, staff was also guided
by comparing
<P>
the language of subsections (1) and (2) of .680 to subsection
(3).
<P>
Subsections (1) and (2) specifically apply to any =ECemployer
or labor
<P>
organization=EE while subsection (3) does not.<BR>

<P>
Staff=EDs conclusion was that the prohibition of RCW 42.17.680(3)
cannot be
<P>
applied to labor organizations under facts such as are present
in this
<P>
case.<BR>

<P>
School districts do fall within the scope of RCW 42.17.680(3)=EDs
prohibitio=
<P>
n
<P>
since they are the employer disbursing funds in payment of wages.
However,
<P>
school districts who payroll-deduct under facts such as these
do not seem
<P>
culpable. While it might be appropriate to charge an employer
directly
<P>
forwarding payroll-deducted moneys to a clearly-identified PAC,
it is a
<P>
different matter where dues are being payroll-deducted for a labor
<P>
organization and then used by the labor organization to make contributions.
<P>
The employer has no authority to control use of the dues money,
and
<P>
furthermore, it is staff=EDs understanding that federal labor
law prohibits
<P>
the employer from asking what the dues will be used for.<BR>

<P>
Thus the dilemma in this case: they party that controls the use
of the
<P>
withheld funds does not fall within the terms of the prohibition;
the party
<P>
that does fall within the prohibition cannot control or ask about
the use
<P>
of the funds being withheld so as to avoid violating the law.
<BR>

<P>
Recommendation<BR>

<P>
Staff believes that the inability in this case (and possibly future
cases)
<P>
to hold the culpable party responsible for using payroll deductions
that
<P>
have not been annually authorized for political contributions
frustrates
<P>
the intent of the voters in passing I-134, and requests the Commission's
<P>
approval to take this problem with enforcing .680 to the legislature
for
<P>
consideration. Even if the Commission does not agree that in this
instance
<P>
deductions were used as political contributions, staff would still
<P>
recommend seeking legislative change since the .680 enforcement
problem may
<P>
well come up again.<BR>

<P>
There was a complaint filed against one school district in this
matter.
<P>
However, there is no reason to believe that all school districts
in the
<P>
state were not acting in the same manner.<BR>

<P>
###<BR>
<BR>

<P>
received from the PDC 11/18/96<BR>

<P>
IN THE MATTER OF ENFORCEMENT)
<P>
ACTION AGAINST)PDC CASE NO. 96-420
<P>
)
<P>
WASHINGTON EDUCATION )STAFF'S BRIEF IN
<P>
ASSOCIATION AND WEA-PAC)SUPPORT OF REFERRAL
<P>
)TO ATTORNEY GENERAL'S
<P>
)OFFICE
<P>
RESPONDENTS.)
<P>
______________________________)<BR>

<P>
I. INTRODUCTION
<P>
Staff is conducting an investigation of the Washington Education
<P>
Association (WEA) and WEA-PAC. To date, this investigation has
<P>
revealed
<P>
three violations of RCW 42.17. First, the WEA and WEA-PAC failed
<P>
to
<P>
properly disclose a $162,255 donation from the WEA to WEA-PAC.
<P>
Secondly,
<P>
the WEA and WEA-PAC failed to disclose approximately $170,000
in
<P>
contributions from the WEA to WEA-PAC. Finally, the investigation
<P>
found
<P>
that the WEA has formed a second political committee, the Community
<P>
Outreach Program (COP), and that COP has not filed as a political
<P>
committee.<BR>

<P>
The investigation of the first two charges is complete. Investigation
of
<P>
the third charge is still in progress, but staff believes that
further
<P>
investigation of that charge will provide only provide additional
evidence
<P>
to support our allegation that COP is a political committee.
<P>
Staff believes that, based on the magnitude of the alleged violations
found
<P>
to date, a $2,500 penalty is not sufficient. Staff recommends
that this
<P>
matter be referred to the Attorney General's Office (AGO) for
<P>
prosecution
<P>
pursuant to RCW 42.17.360(5) and .395(3). At the same time, staff
will
<P>
continue its investigation of the third charge pursuant to RCW
<P>
42.17.370(6).<BR>

<P>
Staff is recommending referral to the AGO at this time because
of the
<P>
possibility that a law suit may be filed by Citizens for Fair
Campaign
<P>
=46inancing (CFCF) before we have an opportunity to present a
<P>
complete
<P>
investigation to you. On September 26, 1996, CFCF notified the
AGO
<P>
that
<P>
CFCF would file a law suit against the WEA if the AGO did not
act
<P>
within
<P>
forty-five days. Pursuant to RCW 42.17.400(4), CFCF must provide
<P>
the AGO
<P>
with a second ten day notice before CFCF may file a law suit against
the
<P>
WEA for the violations discussed in this brief.<BR>

<P>
II. FACTS AND ARGUMENT
<P>
The WEA is a labor organization representing approximately 65,000
<P>
public
<P>
school employees and is the state affiliate of the parent National
<P>
Education Association. Within the WEA there are
<P>
22 Uniserv Councils and 330 Local Education Associations.<BR>

<P>
A.The WEA's Political Operations Prior To Initiative 134.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Prior to January, 1994, the WEA directed school districts to
<P>
automatically
<P>
deduct one dollar per month from all members for placement in
its
<P>
political
<P>
committee, Political Unity of Leaders in State Education (PULSE).
<P>
Members
<P>
could opt out of this deduction, but a majority did not. Approximately
<P>
48,000 members gave one dollar per month to PULSE during 1993.
<BR>

<P>
Pulse spent this money on a variety of activities including support
of
<P>
candidates, ballot measures and local levy elections. WEA billed
PULSE
<P>
for
<P>
its share of overhead and administrative costs. In addition, PULSE
<P>
rebated
<P>
forty (40) percent of its money to the Uniserv Councils who then
spent
<P>
this
<P>
money in support of candidates, ballot measures and local levy
elections.
<P>
Both PULSE and most of the 22 Uniserv Councils filed with the
PDC as
<P>
political committees.<BR>

<P>
B. The WEA's Political Operations After The Adoption of Initiative
134.<BR>

<P>
Initiative 134 was adopted by a 72 percent vote in November, 1992.
In
<P>
addition to contribution limits, Initiative 134 contains RCW
<P>
42.17.680(3).
<P>
That section provides, in relevant part:
<P>
No employer or other person or entity responsible for the disbursement
<P>
of
<P>
funds in payment of wages or salaries may withhold or divert a
portion of
<P>
an employee's wages or salaries for contributions to political
committees
<P>
or for use as political
<P>
contributions except upon written request of the employee.<BR>

<P>
This statute meant that the WEA could no longer have one dollar
per
<P>
month
<P>
automatically deducted for PULSE. Members would have to
<P>
affirmatively
<P>
authorize this deduction each year. WEA leadership expected that
RCW
<P>
42.17.680(3) would cause a huge decrease in money available to
its
<P>
political committee, and that is exactly what happened. The number
of
<P>
members who gave one dollar per month dropped from approximately
<P>
48,000 in
<P>
1993, to approximately 8,000 in 1994. In response to this anticipated
<P>
shortage of political money and the limits contained in Initiative
134, the
<P>
WEA formed a =ECLife After 134 Task Force=EE. The purpose of the
<P>
group was =
<P>
to
<P>
review the new law and to decide how they could continue to
<P>
=ECconduct
<P>
business as usual=EE, knowing that their funds would be radically
<P>
reduced.
<P>
Acting on the recommendations of the &quot;Life After 134 Task
Force,&quot;
<P>
WEA took
<P>
several actions which led to this investigation.<BR>

<P>
1.The WEA Changed The Structure Of Its Political Operations.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
In April 1994, the WEA eliminated PULSE and replaced it with
<P>
WEA-PAC and
<P>
the Community Outreach Program (COP). WEA-PAC was formed to
<P>
continue many
<P>
of the political activities formerly conducted by PULSE including
<P>
contributions to candidates and ballot measures. Due to a concern
that
<P>
contributions needed to be centralized to avoid exceeding the
limits
<P>
contained in Initiative 134, the Uniserv Councils=ED WEA-PAC
<P>
rebates are
<P>
being held by WEA-PAC. The Uniservs were told to stop filing as
<P>
political
<P>
committees, and upon request to WEA-PAC, contributions on behalf
of
<P>
the
<P>
Uniserv Councils would be made and reported by WEA-PAC.
<P>
WEA-PAC is funded
<P>
by voluntary one dollar per month member contributions. Members
must
<P>
affirmatively authorize this deduction on an annual basis.<BR>

<P>
COP's purposes, as stated by the WEA's Executive Director, were
to
<P>
cover
<P>
WEA-PAC's &quot;soft&quot; money expenses in order to preserve
WEA-PAC's
<P>
&quot;hard&quot; money
<P>
for contributions to state and legislative candidates and to generate
funds
<P>
for Uniserv Councils to carry on politically-related activities
in local
<P>
communities.<BR>

<P>
COP is funded by a mandatory one dollar per month dues increase
<P>
which was
<P>
passed at the WEA Representative Assembly in April, 1994. Members
<P>
may not
<P>
opt out of this dues increase, but agency fee payers are not charged
<P>
COP
<P>
dues. COP money is collected separately from annual dues and is
<P>
segregated
<P>
and accounted for separately at the WEA. One-half of the money
which
<P>
comes
<P>
into COP is rebated directly to the Uniserv Councils based on
number of
<P>
members, while one-half of COP's money stays at the state level.
<BR>

<P>
In addition to the moneys spent by WEA-PAC and COP for political
<P>
purposes,
<P>
the WEA has used general dues to make contributions to ballot
<P>
measures.
<P>
=46or example, the WEA made $700,000 in contributions to the No
on
<P>
173 and
<P>
177 Committee.<BR>

<P>
2.The WEA Accelerated Collection Of Political Dues For The Year
<P>
1993-1994.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
In January, 1993, the PDC ruled that the new voluntary
<P>
system of dues collection contained in RCW 42.17.680(3) would
<P>
become
<P>
effective on January 1, 1994. The WEA's 1993-94 fiscal year ran
from
<P>
September 1, 1993, through August 31, 1994. In anticipation of
a sharp
<P>
decline in funds available for its political committee, the WEA
<P>
accelerated
<P>
collection of its political dues for the 1993-94 fiscal year.
That is, in
<P>
December, 1993, the WEA collected PULSE dues through August,
<P>
1994. Staff
<P>
does not allege that this action violated Initiative 134.<BR>

<P>
3.The WEA, Through The COP, Made $162,255 In Donations To
<P>
WEA-PAC Which
<P>
WEA-PAC Reported As Loans From The WEA.<BR>

<P>
In September, 1994, WEA-PAC reported to the PDC that it had
<P>
received a
<P>
$117,115 loan from the WEA. In January, 1995, WEA-PAC reported
<P>
that it had
<P>
received an additional $45,140 loan from the WEA. These amounts
<P>
were
<P>
calculated to repay WEA-PAC for overhead and other administrative
<P>
expenses
<P>
incurred by PULSE from January, 1994, through August, 1994. In
<P>
February,
<P>
1995, WEA-PAC reported that these loans had been forgiven.<BR>

<P>
Staff's investigation revealed that these &quot;loans&quot; were
made from the
<P>
WEA's
<P>
general dues account, and were never intended to be repaid by
<P>
WEA-PAC.
<P>
Instead, WEA used (as was always intended) COP money to repay
the
<P>
WEA's
<P>
general dues account. WEA-PAC should have reported these deposits
<P>
as
<P>
donations from the WEA, not as loans. In addition, the WEA or
COP,
<P>
failed
<P>
to report these donations to WEA-PAC, nor did WEA-PAC report
<P>
these as
<P>
in-kind contributions.<BR>

<P>
4.WEA-PAC And The WEA Or COP Failed To Report Contributions
<P>
From COP To
<P>
WEA-PAC Totaling Approximately $173,517.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
=46rom September, 1994, through August, 1996, money collected
<P>
through the CO=
<P>
P
<P>
was used to pay WEA-PAC's overhead and other administrative
<P>
expenses.
<P>
These expenditures by COP constituted contributions to WEA-PAC,
<P>
yet they
<P>
were not reported by WEA-PAC, the WEA or COP. Approximately
<P>
$173,517 in
<P>
contributions were not reported. This is a conservative calculation
of the
<P>
amount of contributions not reported for the period September,
1994
<P>
through
<P>
August, 1996; the WEA itself calculated the $162,255 =ECloan=EE
<P>
based on the
<P>
administrative expenses of PULSE for an eight month period.<BR>

<P>
The WEA believes that money which is used for direct contributions
to
<P>
candidates is hard money, and that such contributions are reportable
to
<P>
the
<P>
PDC. The WEA believes that money which is used to pay the overhead
<P>
of
<P>
WEA-PAC is soft money, and that WEA-PAC is not required to report
<P>
such
<P>
expenditures or contributions. These concepts are found in Initiative
134,
<P>
but only apply to bona-fide political parties in regards to contribution
<P>
limits. The WEA may have come to its erroneous understanding based
<P>
on the
<P>
WEA's understanding of federal election law.<BR>

<P>
5.COP Is A Political Committee Subject To The Reporting
<P>
Requirements Of RCW
<P>
42.17.080-090.<BR>

<P>
=46rom September, 1994, through August, 1996, one of COP's
<P>
primary purposes
<P>
was to influence governmental decision making
<P>
by paying the administrative costs of WEA-PAC and re-paying the
loan,
<P>
allowing WEA-PAC to preserve its funds to make contributions or
<P>
independent
<P>
expenditures supporting or opposing candidates. To this end, COP
<P>
made
<P>
approximately $300,000 in contributions to WEA-PAC. COP (both
the
<P>
state
<P>
portion and Uniserv portions) also made direct contributions to
ballot
<P>
measures and other political committees. These activities made
COP a
<P>
political committee, yet COP did not register and report as a
political
<P>
committee.<BR>

<P>
6.There May Be Other Political Committees That Have Failed To
<P>
Report With
<P>
The PDC.<BR>

<P>
One-half of the money received by COP was rebated directly to
the 22
<P>
Uniserv Councils. The COP was merely a pass through for this money.
<P>
However, upon the instructions of the WEA, the Uniservs (with
few
<P>
exceptions) ceased reporting their political activities to PDC.
Due to the
<P>
time constraints of this investigation and the large number of
Uniserv
<P>
Councils, it is not clear at this time what all of the Uniservs
did with
<P>
the money they received from COP or if they should be reporting
to
<P>
PDC.
<P>
The Uniservs were told that they could use COP money for any activity
<P>
except the direct support of candidates. However, some Uniserv
<P>
Councils
<P>
spent their rebate exclusively on community organizing. Others
used the
<P>
money on reportable political activities such as contributions
to local
<P>
candidates and local levy elections. The question of what the
<P>
Uniserv Councils did with their COP rebates, and whether certain
<P>
Uniserv Councils should be reporting as political committees needs
to be
<P>
investigated.<BR>

<P>
In addition, as noted above, the WEA has made several large
<P>
contributions to ballot measures out of general dues, including
$700,000
<P>
in
<P>
contributions to the No on 173 and 177 Committee.
<P>
The question of whether the WEA itself constitutes a political
<P>
committee needs further investigation.<BR>

<P>
7. Staff's Findings of a 1994 Audit of WEA-PAC Does not Excuse
the
<P>
Alleged Violations.<BR>

<P>
Staff conducted an audit of WEA-PAC for the 1994 election cycle.
This
<P>
audit was concluded in April, 1996. The audit, in general, concluded
that
<P>
the WEA was in substantial compliance with RCW 42.17 for the period
<P>
August
<P>
1, 1994 through December 31, 1994. In April, 1996, a meeting was
<P>
held with
<P>
the WEA regarding the audit. At that time, the first two complaints
had
<P>
been filed against WEA and WEA-PAC. There was no discussion of
the
<P>
complaints filed with the PDC at that April, 1996 meeting. The
WEA
<P>
argues
<P>
that the findings of the 1994 audit preclude the PDC from being
able to
<P>
take action against the WEA for the improper reporting of the
&quot;loan&quot;.
<P>
PDC
<P>
staff does not agree with that assertion.<BR>

<P>
=46irst, the two complaints on file with the PDC prior to the
April, 1996
<P>
meeting focused on RCW 42.17.680 and the use of compulsory union
<P>
dues for
<P>
campaign activities. The February 6, 1996 complaint does state
that
<P>
=ECIt
<P>
was the intent of the union to repay itself, it is clearly the
intent of
<P>
the law to prohibit such activities.=EE However, this is the only
portion
<P>
o=
<P>
f
<P>
either complaint which alleges that WEA-PAC never intended to
repay
<P>
the
<P>
loan. The complaints alleged a violation of RCW 42.17.680, not
a
<P>
reporting
<P>
violation. Regardless, a letter from WEA=EDs attorney, Harriet
<P>
Strasberg,
<P>
dated March 13, 1996, written to staff in response to the complaints,
<P>
states:<BR>

<P>
WEA made two loans to PULSE in the amounts of $117,115 on August
<P>
31, 1994
<P>
and $45,140 on December 21, 1994. The purpose of these loans was
to
<P>
reimburse PULSE for expenses incurred for the administration and
<P>
overhead
<P>
(equipment, rent, supplies, postage, etc.) necessary for the support
of
<P>
WEA=EDs political action committee. Those funds were neither
<P>
intended for
<P>
nor were they used for, contributions to candidates or for initiative
<P>
campaigns.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
It was subsequently decided that WEA-PAC funds would not be used
<P>
to repay
<P>
the loans.<BR>

<P>
Therefore, at the time of the April, 1996 meeting, staff had no
reason to
<P>
believe that the =ECloan=EE was actually a donation.<BR>

<P>
Secondly, the complaints were not discussed at the April, 1996
meeting.
<P>
It
<P>
was not reasonable for the WEA to assume staff=EDs silence meant
the
<P>
complaints had been dismissed.<BR>

<P>
The WEA also argues that the PDC had notice of WEA-PAC=EDs
<P>
failure to repor=
<P>
t
<P>
contributions from COP at the time of the audit because PULSE
had
<P>
reported
<P>
administrative expenses in the past, and WEA-PAC no longer reported
<P>
administrative expenses. This argument is misplaced.<BR>

<P>
The audit did not review PULSE=EDs reports. It was limited to
a review
<P>
of
<P>
WEA-PAC=EDs reports. The first section of the audit makes this
clear.
<P>
An audit has been conducted of the records and reports of the
<P>
Washington
<P>
Education Assn. PAC (herein referred to as =ECWEA-PAC=EE) from
<P>
August 1, 199=
<P>
4
<P>
through December 31, 1994.<BR>

<P>
The audit did not compare reports filed by PULSE with reports
filed by
<P>
WEA-PAC. It was not reasonable for the WEA to assume or expect
<P>
staff to
<P>
have uncovered WEA-PAC=EDs contributions from COP.<BR>

<P>
III. CONCLUSION<BR>

<P>
Based on the evidence we have discovered in our investigation,
we
<P>
believe
<P>
the WEA and WEA-PAC either failed to disclose, or failed to properly
<P>
disclose, approximately $300,000 in contributions from the WEA
to
<P>
WEA-PAC.
<P>
In staff=EDs opinion, these alleged violations alone warrant a
penalty
<P>
greater than $2,500. In addition, based on the investigation to
date, we
<P>
believe the WEA has formed a second political committee, COP,
which
<P>
has not
<P>
filed as a political committee, and there may be other entities
which have
<P>
failed to file as political committees. Staff recommends that
this matter
<P>
be referred to the Attorney General's Office for prosecution and
<P>
pursuant
<P>
to RCW 42.17.360 and .395. Staff will assist this effort by continuing
its
<P>
investigation pursuant to RCW 42.17.370(6). As noted above, staff
<P>
makes
<P>
this recommendation now because of the possibility that a law
suit may
<P>
be
<P>
filed by CFCF before we can return to you with a completed
<P>
investigation.<BR>

<P>
___________________________
<P>
Susan Harris
<P>
Assistant Director
<P>
Compliance and Enforcement<BR>
<BR>

<P>
Dated:_____________________
<P>
These contributions also appear to violate the spirit of RCW
<P>
42.17.680(3). However, that statute only applies to the school
districts
<P>
and the school districts do not appear to be culpable in this
matter. This
<P>
issue is discussed in detail in the Supplement to Report of Investigation.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
STAFF'S BRIEF IN SUPPORT
<P>
OF REFERRAL TO ATTORNEY
<P>
GENERAL'S OFFICE - PAGE1<BR>
