<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN News"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P>These two articles outline the events of the last few days.  We hope that the Attorney General will prosecute the WEA vigorously so that they change their behavior in the future.  This will be a real test for the AG, who received teacher union support in the last election.  Stay tuned.<p><br>The Seattle Post-Intelligencer, Saturday, November 16, 1996, p. A-8<p>Union may face court action<p>By Scott Sunde, P-I Reporter<p>OLYMPIA -- The state's campaign watchdog believes it has found the Washington Education Association in such serious violation of election-finance laws that it is urging the state Attorney General's Office to take the teachers union to court.<p>The WEA said the Public Disclosure Commission's interpretation of the law is wrong, and complained that the union is a victim of a political conspiracy.<p>In a report released yesterday, the PDC staff concluded that the teachers union, which with 65,000 members is one of the state's most powerful political forces, failed to properly report more than $300,000 in campaign spending and ran afoul of the law by not registering as a political action committee.<p>The PDC can levy a fine of no more than $2,500.  But the attorney general could take the WEA to court, seek a fine of $10,000 for each violation, and, in special cases, ask a judge to triple the fine.<p>"The staff didn't feel that $2,500 was sufficient," said Melissa Warheit, the PDC's executive director.  "There as, we feel, a lot of money that wasn't reported as it should have been."<p>As Warheit and her staffers talked with reporters in the PDC's lobby yesterday, teachers union officials and their opponents listened.  They debated with the PDC, talked with reporters and continued to argue in an elevator on their way out of the office building.<p>"We think their interpretation is wrong," said Trevor Neilson, a WEA spokesman.  "We think we do follow the rules.  We will go to court to challenge each of their allegations."<p>Warheit will turn the report over to the five-member Public Disclosure Commission on Tuesday.  The commissioners will have the final say on whether to turn the matter over the attorney general.<p>"This is the largest violation in PDC history," said Bob Williams, president of the Evergreen Freedom Foundation, a conservative Olympia think tank that filed a PDC complaint against the teachers union in August.  "There is so much more that has to be done.  They've just scratched the surface."<p>Neilson called the report "an orchestrated effort on the part of Bob Williams and extremely conservative political operatives to weaken WEA's influence in the political arena.  What happens politically in Washington is tied intrinsically to education.  And that's an arena we need to be in."<p>The WEA is one of the state's biggest players when it comes to political contributions.<p>For example, the WEA dipped into members' union dues this year to provide at least $700,000 to the campaign that opposed referendums that would have created a school voucher system and charter schools, PDC officials said yesterday.<p>Voters rejected both measures by large margins earlier this month.<p>The PDC investigation comes four years after voters approved a new campaign finance law.  That law, which Republicans heavily backed, has made it harder for unions such as the WEA to collect money from the rank and file for political contributions.<p>Complaints about the WEA's fund raising and contributions started coming in to the PDC in February.  But wasn't until September that the agency investigated them, Warheit said.  Before September, the commission had its hands full with, among other things, a major investigation of state House Majority Leader Dale Foreman.<p>Foreman, a Wenatchee Republican who was ultimately cleared, failed to win his party's nomination for governor in the September primary.<p>The PDC staff investigation of the WEA concludes:<p>     The WEA loaned $162,255 to its political action committee from September 1994 to January 1995.  The union forgave the loan.  The PDC staff said the loan was "never intended to be repaid" by the committee and should have been reported as contributions.<p>     The WEA paid the political action committee's overhead from September 1994 through August 1996, spending $173,517.  That money, too, should have been reported as a contribution but wasn't, the PDC staff said.<p>     The union's community outreach program is a political action committee, but has never registered as one.<p>According to the report, the Community Outreach Program was designed to cover the WEA's political action committee expenses in order to preserve money for political campaigns.  The program was funded by a mandatory $1-a-month member dues increase.<p>The outreach program made contributions to the WEA's political action committees and other similar groups and made direct contributions to [the political committee formed to oppose the charter schools and scholarship voucher] ballot measures, the PDC concluded.<p>"The activities made COP (the outreach program) a political action committee, yet the COP did not register and report as a political action committee," the PDC report concludes.<p>Neilson, the WEA spokesman, denied that the outreach program is a political committee.  Harriet Strasberg, a WEA lawyer, said the PDC contention that the teachers union failed to report more than $300,000 in spending was a record-keeping matter that the agency could have solved by simply asking the union to file amended reports.<p>Neilson said the PDC audited the WEA and in April found the union in compliance with finance laws.  PDC staffers said that audit did not cover the matters included in the report released yesterday.<p>The PDC has become zealous and is responding to pressure, Neilson said.  He pointed to criticism of the PDC from Foreman.  At the same time, Williams' Evergreen Freedom Foundation has been highly critical of the PDC and the teachers union, Neilson said.<p>Moreover, in late September, lawyers from the Seattle firm of Davis Wright Tremaine wrote Attorney General Christine Gregoire and others saying they would sue the union if no action was taken against it.  The lawyers said they represented the group that persuaded voters four years ago to change campaign finance laws.<p>"We think the WEA is being made an example of," Neilson said.<p>Williams said he will urge Gregoire to seek triple damages against the union.<p>He said he will also seek to have the union's contributions of $700,000 from member dues to the anti-initiative campaign investigated.<p>In its report, the PDC staff said the contribution does need further investigation.<p>--end of article--<p>The Seattle Times, November 19, 1996, p. B-4.  <br>(Top of the Editorial Column)<p>WEA should clean house in wake of PDC findings<p>(unsigned editorial of The Seattle Times Editorial Board)<p>In a Sept. 3 Seattle Times op-ed, Washington Education Association executive director James Seibert claimed "Meticulous records track every hour and every dollar that WEA spends doing anything even remotely political."  He also assured the public that WEA is following the law.<p>Wrong on both counts.  A staff report of the state Public Disclosure Commission released last week shows that the union failed to properly  disclose more than $300,000 in campaign finances over the past two years.  According to the PDC staff, this may be among the most serious campaign-spending violations in state history.  The report recommends three specific violations be referred to the Attorney General for prosecution:<p>     ILLEGAL TRANSFERS OF MONEY.  The staff found WEA failed to properly disclose a $162,255 donation to its political action committee.  The WEA repeatedly claimed that the loan was legal and was being paid back with interest.  The PDC concluded otherwise:  "The loan was never intended to be repaid."<p>     UNDISCLOSED POLITICAL EXPENDITURES.  For the past two years, WEA has covered its PAC's full overhead costs totaling $173,517.  These administrative expenses never appeared in PDC reports, a violation of Initiative 134, which [also] requires written consent from union members for all political expenditures.<p>     FORMATION OF AN UNREGISTERED POLITICAL ACTION COMMITTEE.  Prior to passage of I-134, the WEA automatically deducted $1 per month from all members for placement in its political action committee.  After approval of the initiative, which required paycheck deductions for political activity to be voluntary and renewed annually, PAC contributions dropped from 80 percent to 20 percent.  To make up the loss, the union imposed a mandatory $12 annual fee to fund a "Community Outreach Program."  WEA officials insisted the program did not make direct contributions to political causes, but the PDC disagreed, concluding that it was a political action committee subject to state registration and reporting requirements.<p>The questions don't end there.  The PDC staff also confirmed that the WEA -- not its PAC -- spent more than $700,000 in unreported campaign contributions to defeat the charter-school and school-voucher initiatives (I-177 and I-173).  Due to the range of suspect activities, the PDC staff recommended further investigation into whether the WEA itself constitutes a political committee.<p>WEA leaders are trying to obfuscate the PDC staff findings by attacking the Evergreen Freedom Foundation, a conservative think tank based in Olympia whose research galvanized the PDC investigation.  But the demand for good government , ethical leadership and public accountability is nonpartisan and non-ideological.  Union spokesmen suggest only minor procedural matters are at issue.  But it appears that the WEA played unfair and broke the law.<p>Voters, and especially rank-and-file teachers, deserve apologies -- not lame excuses and conspiracy theories.  Public school students, their parents and teachers whose overriding interest is what goes on in classrooms across the state would be well served by a swift housecleaning in WEA headquarters.<p>--end of editorial--
