<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN News"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P>Milt Chappell from National Right to Work sent us this update on his activities in Southern California.<p><br>Teacher Takes Union To Court Over<br>Union Dues <p>By DAN GALLAGHER <br>Daily Transcript Staff Writer <p>Nov. 14, 1996 <p>A Kearny High School teacher is taking the San Diego Teachers Association (SDTA) into federal<br>court, charging the teachers' union with illegally using her union dues for political and other<br>"non-bargaining" activities, as well as forcing teachers to maintain their union membership against<br>their will. <p>Jean Apple filed a class-action lawsuit in the U.S. District Court in San Diego last week against<br>SDTA, the California Teachers Association (CTA), the National Education Association and the<br>San Diego Unified School District. Apple contends that the SDTA violated her First, Fifth and<br>14th Amendment rights by not allowing her to resign and not refunding the money which the union<br>uses to contribute to political and ideological campaigns, which are unrelated to the union's<br>bargaining activities. <p>"What this case is about is the right of teachers to leave the union," said Milton Chappell of the<br>National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation, who is representing Apple in this case. "We<br>believe it is a violation of her constitutional rights." <p>The written agreement between the district and the association allows union members to revoke<br>their membership during the month of July in the year that the contract with the district expires.<br>Since the contract doesn't expire until the end of June 1998, teachers wishing to leave the union<br>may not resign until July 1998, according to Article 16, Section 16.8 of the contract. <p>The association draws authority for such a code from California Government Code 3540.1, which<br>allows public school employee organizations to require employees to maintain their membership in<br>the unions as a condition of their employment for the duration of the contract. Chappell claims he<br>knows of other teachers who have tried to resign from the union and have been blocked, which is<br>why he initiated the lawsuit as a class action. He hopes the federal court will rule the code<br>unconstitutional. <p>"We don't think this will withstand the test of the Constitution," Chappell added. <p>Apple, who has taught severely mentally handicapped students at Kearny High for the past nine<br>years, originally joined the union because she needed the liability insurance offered through the<br>association for her class, which often traveled throughout the community. She said she decided that<br>she wanted to leave the union about seven or eight years ago because the views espoused by the<br>union were in conflict with her own. <p>"I don't want to be associated with an organization that holds the views that they do," Apple said. <p>She would not comment on what specific views or issues she disagreed with the union on. <p>Apple wrote several letters this year to various association officials requesting resignations or<br>demanding it. Marc Knapp, president of SDTA, wrote a reply on Sept. 9 denying her request and<br>quoting the section of the contract. However, Knapp said in the letter that he sympathized with<br>Apple's concerns, and said "there are areas where I personally part company with SDTA." <p>After July 1998, the association will allow teachers to become "agency fee payers." The members<br>will reap the benefits of the collective bargaining which the union undertakes, but between 10 and<br>20 percent of their membership dues will be refunded, amounting to approximately $200. Agency<br>fee payers will not vote in SDTA elections or receive legal or economic benefits through SDTA,<br>CTA or the National Education Association. <p>SDTA officials confirmed that a teacher may not move into the agency fee payer status until July<br>1998 when the contract expires. The only exceptions made, according to Association Vice<br>President Maryann McDonald, are for "religious objectors." Objectors must pay what would be<br>their dues to one of three charities who work with children. <p>"It's interesting that this lawsuit was filed by the National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation,<br>because they are an anti-union organization," McDonald said. "I find that a little disturbing." <p>Chappell said he hopes the case will overturn the provisions in the California code which allow the<br>union to require membership during the contract time. Although they will ask for past dues spent<br>on political activities, Apple said she does not care if she gets any money back. She said she just<br>doesn't want to pay any more in the future. <p>gallagher@sddt.com <p><p>
<br>
