  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN News"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P>Dear Colleague,<p>The following information is being provided so that you know your rights and options regarding union membership and action being taken to protect those rights. If you would like more information, please contact me.  Feel free to distribute this information among your colleagues according to the policies established for your work setting.<p>Cindy Omlin, Speech-Language Pathologist, CCC-SP.<p>P.S.  For more information you may also access the website at<br>www.schoolreport.com/weacn/<p>-----------------------------------------------------------------<p>STATEWIDE CLASS ACTION LAWSUIT FILED AGAINST WASHINGTON EDUCATION<br>ASSOCIATION, NATIONAL EDUCATION ASSOCIATION AND LOCAL EDUCATION ASSOCIATIONS FOR THE UNAUTHORIZED USE OF UNION DUES:  YOU ARE INVITED TO JOIN THE LAWSUIT.  <p><B>WASHINGTON EDUCATION ASSOCIATION KILLS BILL TO INFORM MEMBERS OF THEIR RIGHTS</B><br> <br>In order to keep education employees in submission to the unions mandatory dues arrangement, the WEA killed House Bill 1738.  This bill stated:<br> <br>NEW SECTION.  Sec. 1.  The legislature believes that all public employees covered by collective bargaining agreements should be notified of their First Amendment rights under the United States Constitution.  Because the First Amendment enumerates rights that are fundamental to our freedom, notice of these rights, as determined by the United States Supreme Court, must be conspicuously and routinely provided to a person whose employment is covered by a collective bargaining agreement.  The legislature finds that it should be the responsibility of the public employer and the collective bargaining representative to provide such notice.  The purpose of this act is to protect First Amendment rights, consistent with the belief that to compel a<br>man to furnish contributions of money for the propagation of opinions which he disbelieves, is sinful and tyrannical.<br> <br><B>YOUR RIGHTS</B><br> <br>Education employees are not required to join the union, but non-union employees must pay an agency shop fee or their fair share of the unions representation in collective bargaining, grievance resolution and contract maintenance (chargeable activity).  Those joining the lawsuit are willing to pay this "fair share,"  but they believe that political and ideological<br>activity on which a diverse membership disagrees should not be funded by mandatory dues.<br> <br>The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that educators and other workers have the First Amendment right to withhold that portion of their union dues which is spent on non-chargeable activity, such as political activity and other non-essential services.  Employees also have the right to challenge the amount that the union claims it spends on chargeable activity.  Non-members who do not challenge the unions calculation continue to pay 100% of the union dues.<br> <br>Because the union deceptively categorizes its political spending, its calculation of the "fair share" is disproportionately high.  Therefore, this lawsuit is to challenge the unions calculation.  The WEA claims that 85% of the dues are used for collective bargaining and other chargeable activity. The Spokane Education Association President recently admitted to a news reporter, however, that 70-80% of the SEA dues is NOT used for member<br>representation.<br> <br>The union is legally required to represent agency shop fee payers<br>(non-members) the same as union members and provide the same benefits, rights, and services of the bargained contract.  Non-members cannot participate in union governance, receive strike benefits, or receive WEA liability insurance.   (Liability insurance is easily obtained from independent education associations.)<p>The union has repeatedly failed in its obligation to inform employees of their rights.  When asked, union officials usually give no information, or they give inaccurate or obscure information.   WEA shows greater regard for maximizing their collection of dues than in upholding employee rights.<br> <br><B>THE LAWSUIT</B><br> <br>A class action lawsuit was filed in federal court on October 10, 1995. National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation staff attorney, Milton Chappell, will provide most of  the legal work at no cost.  Local attorney services provided by Steven T. OBan of Ellis, Li & McKinstry, PLLC, administrative services and communication expenses will be covered by a fee<br>of $150 for each union challenger which is expected to sustain expenses up until the point of trial (in 12-18 months).  Another fee of $150 may be assessed if the suit goes to trial.  Total fees for the entire action have been capped by the attorney at $300 per challenger. If the judge does not certify the class, only those who have joined this suit will benefit from the courts decision.  If the class is certified, all non-members will benefit from the court's decision.<br> <br>Our attorneys intend to audit the WEAs books and disclose and challenge their expenditures in court. (Teachers who challenged the WEA in 1994 received an out of court settlement for a 50% reduction in dues for two years ($200-300 per year).  That settlement has expired.)<br> <br><B>JOINING THE SUIT: STANDING TOGETHER FOR PRINCIPLE</B><br> <br>Those joining this lawsuit are NOT anti-union.  We SUPPORT union<br>expenditures on legitimate union activities for collective bargaining,contract maintenance and improvement of working conditions.  We believe, however, that union expenditures for political and ideological activity should be funded only by voluntary contributions to WEA-PAC.  We believe that the unions disproportionate focus on political activity is reducing its effectiveness and focus on the protection of employee rights and workplace issues.  Kathy OToole, General Counsel for the WEA, has characterized employees who believe the union should focus on representing its members as "dinosaurs."<br> <br>Those wishing to receive information about their rights and the forms for resigning from the union and joining this statewide challenge must call 1(800) 336-3600 and request the packet for the WEA Class Action Lawsuit. Once the forms and fee (or downpayment) are received, our attorneys will shepherd the challengers through the legal process and take care of all<br>communications with the WEA.  You are very important as the eyes and ears of our attorneys.  It is very important that you send documentation of questionable activities and spending by the union to them.<br> <br>This is your chance to make a difference and redirect the union to its legitimate purpose.  Over 150 education employees from all over the state have already joined this suit. You can too!<br> <p>
<br>
