</DOCHDR>
<html>
  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN News"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P>From The Seattle Post-Intelligencer<br>Thursday, October 10, 1996, p. B-1<p>Teachers to sue union over use of dues<br>Action comes during probe of WEA political donations<p>by Scott Sunde, P-I reporter<p>A group of 20 teachers will sue the Washington Education Association in federal court today, joining a growing number of voices that are accusing the state's largest teachers union of illegally using dues to back political candidates and causes.<br>The lawsuit, which also is expected to name the National Education Association as a defendant, comes during a major investigation by the state's Public Disclosure Commission of the WEA's sources of political contributions.  The investigation is the commission's "No. 1 priority" said Melissa Warheit, PDC Executive Director.<br>The WEA expects the Public Disclosure Commission to find no problems.<br>"We're very confident we're using  . . . our members' dues legally," said Teresa Moore, a WEA spokeswoman.<br>The WEA and its 65,000 teacher members are central players in the campaign against two initiatives on the November ballot:  173, which would set up a voucher program allowing parents to use tax money to send their children to public or private schools; and 177, which would set up so-called charter schools.<br>By August, the Washington Education Association had financed about 65 percent of the budget of the campaign set up to defeat both initiatives.<br>PDC reports show about $210,00 in contributions through September, Warheit said.  That money did not come from WEA's political action committee, and the PDC is trying to determine the source of the money, Warheit said.<br>Supporters of the initiatives fear not only that the association will pour more money into the campaign, but also that it will do so illegally.<br>"They're going to spend all this money [against I-177] illegally, and it won't come out as a crime until after the election," said Jim Spady, who with his wife sponsored the drive to get the charter school initiative on the ballot.<br>Indeed, the size of the investigation and other work means the PDC is unlikely to finish its investigation until after the election Nov. 5, Warheit said.  She said her staff wants to be done by Nov. 12.  That would allow commission members to discuss violations and charges -- if any are alleged -- at their meeting Nov. 19.<br>The lawsuit expected to filed today in Seattle focuses on agency fee payers, teachers who are not union members.  Federal law says that the union must represent these nonmembers, but it also says that the union can charge them only for the cost of representing them.  That charge is their agency fee.<br>The WEA has about 2,700 agency fee payers.<br>The teachers involved in the lawsuit believe the WEA is charging them more than the cost of representing them, said Steven O'Ban, a Seattle attorney who is representing the teachers.<br>O'Ban said the lawsuit will contend that some of the extra money the WEA charges these teachers ends up being used for political purposes.<br>Moore, the WEA spokeswoman, said the association is confident that is charging the fee payers a correct amount.  "None of their money is used for political purposes," she said.<br>The Public Disclosure Commission is looking at a larger question of whether the WEA is circumventing a 1992 law that made it harder for unions to use dues for political purposes.<br>Before voters passed the 1992 law, the WEA asked members if they would agree to pay $12 a year for political purposes.  About 80 percent of union members agreed to the charge, and that amount was automatically deducted from their paychecks unless they stopped it.<br>The 1992 law said union members would have to agree each year to the contribution.  Today, only 20 percent of WEA members make the contribution to a political action committee.<br>But opponents of the union contend that hasn't stopped the union from using regular dues for political purposes.<br>Some teachers complained to the PDC last spring.  And in August, the Evergreen Freedom Foundation, a conservative think tank based in Olympia, filed a second complaint.<br>One question concerns the WEA's community outreach campaign.  Members are charged $1 a month in regular dues to support the campaign.  The money goes to voter education, member education, organizing parents and other purposes, Moore said.<br>WEA critics say the outreach campaign is simply the old checkoff system under a new name.<br>But Moore said the WEA is using the outreach money legally and that it is not going to candidates for office.  She could not offer specifics about where the money has gone or whether any has gone to the campaign against the initiatives.<br>Warheit said the PDC is considering whether the outreach program has circumvented the law.
<br>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:WEAChallenger@schoolreport.com">e-mail (WEAChallenger@schoolreport.com)</A></P><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Newss"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P><center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/imagemaps/mainmap.map"><img src="http://www.schoolreport.com/gifs/mainmap.gif" ISMAP border=0></A></center></body></html>
