<html>
  <head>
    <title></title>
  </head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN News"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P><CENTER> <B>For Immediate Release<br>August 28, 1996<br></B> </CENTER><p>Contact: (360) 956-3482                      <br>Peggy Jackson<br>Bob Williams<br>Lynn Harsh<p><CENTER> <B>EFF CHARGES WEA WITH LARGEST ONGOING CAMPAIGN<br>VIOLATIONS IN PDC HISTORY</CENTER></B><p>On August 26, Bob Williams, President of the Evergreen Freedom Foundation presented<br>the Public Disclosure Commission with evidence detailing the biggest campaign<br>violations in PDC history: the Washington Education Association's illegal taking and<br>spending of $4 million just in the last two years.<p>EFF also issued strongly-worded criticism to the Public Disclosure Commission staff for<br>their failure to properly investigate the systematic skimming and illegal spending of rank-<br>and-file teacher money.<p>Williams stated, "The WEA's illegal political machine is today operating in high gear<br>to heavily influence November elections.  The machine is fueled by the rank-and-file<br>teachers' dues which are supposed to be used for non-political, traditional collective<br>bargaining purposes.  Sadly, the WEA has received an implicit green light from the PDC<br>to continue illegal campaign expenditures."<p>For example:<p>1.  $1.3 million has been extracted from the teachers' paychecks during the past two<br>years and has been illegally spent on undisclosed political activities without teachers'<br>consent.<p>2.  Illegal transfers of money from the WEA to its PAC (WEA-PAC) have been made: <br>a $162,255.00 "loan" made from the "Community Outreach Program" (essentially a<br>WEA money-laundering entity), to the PAC was "forgiven".<p>3.  The WEA-Pac is housed in the WEA building and has no record paying its own<br>sizable administrative expenses, including rent (totaling est. $120,000.00 per year.)   <p>It has been two years since the first Whistle-blowers--a handful of courageous teachers--<br>hired a law firm to take on their case against the WEA for its illegal procurement and<br>political use of their dues.  Teachers have filed numerous complaints with the PDC<br>against the WEA since January. <p>Frustrated by the PDC's lack of initiative, the teachers encouraged EFF to conduct their<br>own investigation.  The serious systematic violations uncovered by EFF are<br>meticulously documented and available to the PDC.  EFF also discovered the<br>existence of an embarrassingly insufficient PDC audit which failed to address teachers' <br>allegations against the WEA (recorded in the PDC's own files).  The PDC staff's has issued<br>conflicting statements regarding future investigations of WEA.<p>Meanwhile, two lawsuits brought against the Union by the teachers have already been<br>successfully settled out of court, suggesting the depth of the violations.  Additional teachers,<br>emboldened by the Union's ongoing violations, have brought a new suit.  Yet, however<br>successful the teachers' lawsuits may be, action on the part of the PDC is urgently required: <br>any settlement loss sustained by the WEA's political machine is peanuts compared to what its<br>illegally-funded political agenda stands to lose if forced to comply with the law.  Forced<br>compliance with the law, simply stated, would very likely bankrupt the WEA-PAC before the<br>all-important November elections.<p>All of this should have lit a fire under the PDC months ago.  <br>It didn't.  Meanwhile the largest PAC represented at the Democratic Convention in Chicago this<br>week is the Teachers Union;  700 Union delegates (or spouses of), paid to attend by the Union,<br>are all primed to push forward their agenda.<p>Meanwhile back at home, the WEA bosses illegally make ready a multi-million dollar<br>political campaign targeted against candidates, and initiatives:  $1.4 million is budgeted<br>through August alone just to defeat Initiatives 177 and 173.<p>On August 26 the Evergreen Freedom Foundation brought two requests before the PDC for their<br>immediate attention:<p>1.  Place an immediate injunction on all political spending by the WEA and its affiliates<br>until an audit which actually attends to the evidence the PDC has access to, can be<br>completed.<p>2.  Direct the PDC staff to make this audit a priority, hiring outside staff if necessary, for<br>a timely completion.<p>The WEA will doubtless continue to claim that very few of the dollars collected from teacher's<br>pay checks are spent on political activity.  However a review of their books resoundingly<br>contradicts their public statements.<p>"A society is only as free as its elections are fair:  hence the important role of The Public<br>Disclosure Commission as the watchdog of campaign finance regulations," Williams stated.<p>The EFF has offered to sit down with the PDC to review the extensive evidence.<p>Included is a copy of EFF's summary material presented to the PDC regarding the WEA<br>violations and cover-up.   <p>                           <CENTER># # # # # </CENTER>                      <p>August 26, 1996<p>Susan Harris<br>Public Disclosure Commission<br>PO Box 40908<br>Olympia, WA 98504-0908<p>Dear Susan,<p>     Numerous teachers have contacted us over the past few years upset about how<br>their union, the Washington Education Association, (WEA) is misspending teacher<br>collective bargaining dollars.  As a citizen advocate and government watchdog group,<br>our Foundation is keenly interested in such matters.<p>     Our subsequent investigation of the WEA has uncovered an unfortunate pattern<br>of illegal expenditures and activities.  In fact, we estimate the Washington Education<br>Association (WEA) and its affiliate organizations have illegally spent nearly $4<br>million for political purposes during the past two years alone.<br>     This letter details the three principal charges we are leveling against WEA and<br>their affiliates.<p>     1.  WEA has illegally taken $1.3 million from teachers' salaries during the<br>past two years and has violated the law by spending all or most of the $1.3 million<br>on political activities. <p>     2.  Illegal transfers of money were made from WEA to PULSE (now called<br>WEA-PAC) amounting to $162,255 to be used for political purposes.<p>     3.  Illegal administrative expenditures were made by WEA on behalf of<br>WEA-PAC totaling an estimated $120,000 per year.<br>      The WEA clearly intends to make similar, or greater financial expenditures in the<br>upcoming fall elections.  In a Seattle Times interview on April 9, 1996, Robert Maier,<br>lobbyist for WEA, discussed how WEA gets around expenditure limits.  Maier says<br>money spent by independent expenditure groups in 1996 "will be amazing" because of<br>the "higher stakes."<p>     James Seibert, WEA Executive Director, said in the association's June newsletter,<br>"Between now and election day, the education community--including WEA--must set<br>aside many of our routine and traditional activities and focus our energies and resources<br>on electing officials who share our vision for public education.  We also must defeat<br>those candidates and initiatives that ultimately could destroy the institution of public<br>education."  Activity by WEA such as Seibert calls for is illegal.<p>     Because of the seriousness of these charges, and because of the impending<br>elections, we ask that, by September 20th, the PDC complete an investigation of the<br>longstanding charges against WEA contained in this letter.  <br>     <br>     We also ask that an injunction be placed on all WEA-PAC expenditures until these<br>issues are resolved.<p>     For your information, the key pieces of evidence used in this document are: IRS 990<br>reports, independent audit reports and WEA-PAC and PULSE PDC records all from years 1992,<br>1993 and 1994 (PDC includes 1995).  Also used are testimony and exhibits from the April 1996<br>arbitration hearing, the WEA Action newsletters and Jim Seibert's letter to teachers statewide<br>titled "Setting the Record Straight."<p>                      <CENTER><B>WEA Charges Detailed<br></B></CENTER><br><B>1. Details of the $2.6 million Community Outreach Fees Violation </B><br>     WEA is spending a lot of money for political purposes that is not being reported.  One<br>of the major violations is occurring using what is called the Community Outreach Program Fees-<br>-a mandatory program assessment of $12 per teacher per year.  This $12 per year, per teacher<br>alone adds up to approximately $1.3 million in income for WEA over the last two years.  James<br>Seibert, WEA's Executive Director, acknowledges that the Community Outreach Program<br>money will be spent to "carry on politically-related activities in local communities and to cover<br>WEA's soft money costs in order to preserve hard money for political contributions."<p>     But current law under Initiative 134 requires an annual written authorization by<br>employees for employers to withhold wages for political contributions (RCW 42.17.650). <p>     When Initiative 134 was passed by the voters, WEA stated it didn't apply to their<br>members because they are not public employees.  But an AG opinion from Roselyn Marcus<br>dated December 14, 1992 determined that the Initiative does apply to teachers and that annual<br>written authorization for PAC contributions must be obtained.<p>     After WEA-PAC contributions became voluntary under I-134, the number of teachers<br>giving to the political organization (PULSE, and now WEA-PAC) plummeted.  The Community<br>Outreach Program, with its $12 mandatory fee--identical to the amount previously mandated by<br>the PAC--is a direct attempt to recoup this loss.<p>     But WEA has not reported contributions or expenditures from these "politically-related<br>activities" to the PDC.  This  violates existing state law.<p>     When pressed for details, the WEA told teachers that funds from this new fee would be<br>used to begin repaying loans previously made from WEA to WEA-PAC--also a violation of state<br>law.  In other words, WEA cannot even legally collect the money much less spend it.  <p>     To support this point, it should be noted that WEA does not require this $12 from<br>agency-fee payers because it is not viewed as a legitimate bargaining expense.<p>     Most, if not all of these expenditures are political and as such (1) violate the state law<br>that forbids automatic dues checkoff, and (2) must be reported to the PDC.  <p><B>2. Details of Illegal Transfers of $162,255 (Attachments #1 and #4)</B><p>     PDC records show WEA loaned $117,115 to PULSE (now called WEA-PAC) on August<br>31, 1994.  A second loan of $45,140 was made on December 21, 1994 bringing the total of<br>teacher funds loaned to the political action committee by WEA to $162,255.<p>     On January 3, 1995, WEA forgave the $162,255 loans.  In other words, WEA loaned<br>mandatory collective bargaining dues to a political action committee. <p>     In December 1995, a teacher contacted EFF regarding these loans.  He questioned<br>"forgiving" the loans since that meant teacher union dues and agency fees would have been used<br>for direct, "hard-money" contributions to candidates and ballot measures.  Several teachers filed<br>a PDC complaint in this regard on February 6, 1996.<p>     But a different version of intent was given by Mr. Maekawa, the WEA Treasurer.  He<br>stated, "The loan to PULSE was from WEA funds..." and that "...the loan is being repaid from<br>the Community Outreach Fund."  Upon further questioning by the teachers, Maekawa explained<br>that the fund has repaid $65,000 so far, another $65,000 is budgeted this year, and after that,<br>the balance "may be forgiven" altogether.   <p>     Mr. Seibert furnished two different answers regarding the loans and the mandatory fee<br>assessed to each WEA member.  In his January 26th letter, Seibert states WEA began repaying<br>the loan from the Community Outreach dues and that the 1995-96 Association budget includes<br>a second loan payment of $65,000 to be transferred from Community Outreach funds to the<br>WEA general fund.  Seibert said WEA will make its third and final payment for the balance of<br>the loan plus accrued interest in 1996-97.  <br>     Seibert's second version came several months later in his sworn testimony to the<br>Arbitration panel (April 24, 1996) when he said the loans would not be repaid.<p>     Seibert also says that both the 1994-95 Association budget and annual independent audit,<br>along with the 1995-96 Association budget, clearly show repayment of the loan.  But in fact,<br>they do not. The actual expenditure report WEA passed out at the arbitration hearing shows<br>no funds have been repaid on the loan (See attachment #2). <p>     The IRS reports submitted by WEA do not mention a loan.  The independent audit does<br>not reveal a loan (See attachments #3 and #4) .<p>     Any way they want to tell the story, what WEA is doing is illegal.<p>     <B>In order to fully investigate this matter, the following questions must be answered:</B><p>1. When were the loans approved by the WEA Board?<br>     If it was a loan, and the independent audit says it was not, the dates must be obtained<br>     from WEA Board minutes.<p>2. What were the terms of the loans?<br>     Records turned in to the PDC indicate the "loans" were promissory notes with 6.5%<br>     interest.  The WEA Board minutes would indicate the rest of the terms.<p>3. When were loan checks written from WEA to PULSE?<br>     (Copies of canceled checks can be obtained.)<p>4. When were the loans reported to the PDC?<br>     PDC records reflect the first loan for $117,115 was issued on 8\8\95 and reported to<br>     PDC on 8\31\94.  The second loan for $45,140 was made on 12\12\94 and reported to<br>     PDC on 12\21\94.<p>5. When were the loans forgiven and who authorized it?<br>     PDC records show that the loans were forgiven on Jan 3, 1995.  Did the WEA Board<br>     meet between December 21, 1994 and January 3, 1995?  If so, a copy of the Board<br>     minutes authorizing the write-off should be procured.  <p>     Transcripts of a 1996 arbitration hearing indicate WEA never intended the<br>     $162,255 to be a loan. (See attachment #)  This being the case it was an illegal<br>     contribution.  If it was intended to be a loan write-off, WEA should have reported<br>     an in-kind donation to PULSE for the amount of the loan written off.  This was<br>     not done making either tactic a violation.<p>6. Why did the amount of the forgiven loans not include any interest that was due? <br>     According to PDC records the loans were a 6.75% interest-bearing promissory note.<p><B>3. Details of Illegal Administrative Expenditures </B><p>     Until the 1994 "loans," WEA-PAC (PULSE) had a long history of paying for administra-<br>tive and overhead costs associated with the day-to-day operation of WEA-PAC.  But in  1995<br>and 1996, WEA-PAC has reported no administrative costs to the PDC.  Yet the WEA-PAC<br>office is a physical place, located in the WEA headquarters in Federal Way, still presumably<br>requiring routine office expenses; i.e. rent, employee wages, benefits, state and federal tax<br>withholdings, telephone, utilities, postage, copy machines, office supplies, computers, etc.<p>     In fact, WEA is picking up the administrative costs for WEA-PAC.  Their 1995<br>independent audit report states, "The Association is affiliated with the Washington Education<br>Association--Political Action Committee (WEA-PAC) whose primary purpose is to advance the<br>political needs of employees in public education....Effective September 1, 1994, the Association<br>pays all WEA-PAC administrative costs."  <p>     The independent audit report for 1993 and 1994 states the following: "The Association<br>[WEA] provides PULSE with office and staffing requirements under an advance and<br>reimbursement policy."  This audit shows that WEA paid $117,115 in PULSE administrative<br>expenses in 1994.  <br>     In addition, the audit report confirms that WEA paid WEA-PAC administrative expenses<br>totaling $162,255.  However, these expenditures were not reported to the PDC by either WEA<br>or WEA-PAC.<p>     Interestingly, in 1994 PULSE paid WEA $6,503.50 monthly for what they categorize as<br>salary, rent and data.  That alone totals $78,040 and doesn't include the costs of any special<br>PAC mailings.  <p>     We estimate WEA-PAC's administrative costs to be at least $120,000 per year.<p>     Due to the seriousness of these charges I am requesting that the PDC:<br>     1. Issue an injunction on all WEA-PAC expenditures until these issues are resolved. <br>The amount of apparent illegal activity by WEA-PAC exceeds the cash balance.<br>     2. Require WEA to repay all teachers (from April 1994 to the current time) for<br>whom they do not have signed authorizations for the $12 per year. !! # of teachers!!<br>     3. Require the WEA-PAC to repay the loan to WEA and fine WEA for willful<br>campaign violations.<br>     4. Require WEA to report all political expenditures as required by our public<br>disclosure law.  All contributions in excess of campaign limits should be refunded to WEA<br>by WEA-PAC.<br>     5. Audit all income and expenditures in the Community Outreach Program for 1994<br>to present.<p>     Three sections of RCW 42.17.010 stand out regarding these apparent violations.  "It is<br>hereby declared by the sovereign people to be the public policy of the state of Washington:<br>     (1)"That political campaign and lobbying contributions and expenditures be fully<br>disclosed to the public and that secrecy is to be avoided...."<br>     (10)"That the public's right to know of the financing of political campaigns and lobbying<br>and the financial affairs of elected officials and candidates far outweighs any right that these<br>matters remain secret and private...."<br>     (11)..."The provisions of this chapter shall be liberally construed to promote complete<br>disclosure of all information respecting the financing of political campaigns and lobbying."<p>     Susan, I am a former governmental auditor and CPA.  I want to assure you that I do<br>have documentation for all the charges contained in this letter.  If you need any additional<br>information, please contact me.<br>                              Cordially,<p><br>                              Bob Williams<p><p>                         <CENTER>  # # # # #  </CENTER>                      <p><br>Please refer to the following letters: Barbara Amidon and Cindy Omlin (2/6/96), John<br>Wright (5/17/96), Jeff Leer (undated), Bob Williams (7/9/96 and 7/23/96) <p><p>               <B><CENTER>Timelines and Conflicting Stories</CENTER></B><br>  <br>     Serious discrepancies arise when reviewing the timeline of money loaned, forgiven,<br>transferred, etc.<br>  <br>April 1994     Community Outreach Program is approved and each WEA member is<br>               assessed $12 in program dues effective in the fall of 1994.<br>  <br>Aug. 31, 1994  WEA loaned PULSE $117,115.<br>  <br>Sept. 13, 1994 PULSE reported loan to PDC.<br>  <br>Sept. 14, 1994 PDC received PULSE's report (PDC# 2584-EZ).<br>  <br>Nov. 4, 1994   The WEA Audit Report for 1993 and 1994 states, "On August 31, 1994,<br>               the Association paid $117,115 to an affiliated organization [PULSE] for<br>               reimbursement of the affiliate organization's administrative expenses<br>               for the period January 1, 1994, through July 31, 1994.  Revenue from a<br>               dues increase will be used to offset this expenditure."  <br> <br>               Note: the auditors do not call these expenditures a loan.  <br> <br>               The auditor goes on to state "Subsequent to August 31, 1994, the Board<br>               of Directors approved reimbursement of additional expenses totaling<br>               approximately $45,000." <br> <br>               The auditor says the $162,255 is for additional expenses and not a loan. <br>               If this is the case, these apparent in-kind expenditures by WEA were not<br>               reported to the PDC as required by law.<br> <br>     Note the discrepancies.  The auditor does not state that the $162,255 are loans.  In fact,<br>he states they are reimbursements for the affiliate organization's administrative expenses. <br>Auditors are precise as to timing.  Note he says the expenses are for the period of January 1,<br>1994 to July 31, 1994.  This conflicts with Seibert's comments in "Setting the Record Straight<br>on WEA's Loan to PULSE" in which Seibert says $100,000 was for calendar year 1993.<br> <br>Dec. 21, 1994  WEA loaned $45,140 to PULSE which brought total of loan to $162,255. <br>               This is the same $45,000 referred to by the above auditor's report.  Since<br>               the auditor's report was dated November 4, 1994 and it clearly<br>               indicated that this was not a loan, how could PULSE report it to the<br>               PDC as a loan on December 21, 1994?  Thus, PULSE incorrectly<br>               reported it to the PDC as a loan and delayed reported the expenditures<br>               until after the election.<br> <br>     Observation: On January 1, 1995, PULSE shows a balance of $408,716.40 after<br>receiving the second loan in December of $45,140.  One wonders why a "loan" was necessary.<p>Jan. 3, 1995   WEA loan to WEA-PAC was forgiven.<br> <br>Jan. 5, 1995   WEA-PAC reported the $45,140 loan to PULSE to PDC.  Note this was<br>               reported after the loan was allegedly forgiven.<br> <br>Jan. 6, 1995   PDC received WEA-PAC report (PDC# 0065-6EZ)<br> <br>Feb. 9, 1995   WEA-PAC reported that the loan had been forgiven on January 3, 1995.<p>Feb. 13, 1995  PDC received WEA-PAC report (PDC #0445-4EZ).<br> <br>Mar. 15, 1995  PULSE reported to the PDC by FAX that the loan was still outstanding. <br> <br>Mar. 16, 1995  PDC received PULSE report(PDC # 0765-2EZ). <p>Nov. 2, 1995   1995 WEA audit report reports, "During the fiscal year ended August 31,<br>               1995, the Association reimbursed WEA-PAC for pre-September 1, 1994<br>               administrative expenses totalling $45,140 ($117,115 -1994)"  Note: these<br>               expenditures were not reported by WEA-PAC to the PDC.  <br> <br>Jan. 26, 1996  Letter from Seibert to Local Association Presidents, UniServ Presidents,<br>               UniServ staff/office copy "Setting the Record Straight on WEA's Loan to<br>               PULSE" <p>Apr. 24, 1996  At the Arbitration Hearing, Mr. Seibert confirmed WEA would not repay<br>               the loan.  Mr. Seibert stated that "...the loan is not being paid back from<br>               WEA-PAC in order to preserve the funds in WEA-PAC."  <p> <CENTER>  # # # # #  </CENTER>     <br>end.
<br>
