<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#804000" ALINK="#FF8000"><P><A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/news.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/toc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Newss"> </A> <A HREF="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/index.htm"><IMG SRC="http://www.schoolreport.com/weacn/news/home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="WEACN Home"></A></P>Friends:<p>The Seattle Post-Intelligencer was one of several Washington papers to carry the Associated Press's coverage of the WEA's campaign finance violations with the Public Disclosures Commission.  Bob Williams and Lynn Harsh of the Evergreen Freedom Foundation have done a fantastic job bringing these violations to the attention of the PDC.<p><br>Seattle Post-Intelligencer<br>August 29, 1996, Page B-1<p>PDC asked to probe teachers union spending<p>by:  The Associated Press<p>OLYMPIA -- The largest teachers union in Washington state has illegally collected and spent $4 million in the past two years, a conservative group contended in a complaint filed with the Public Disclosure Commission this week.<p>The Evergreen Freedom Foundation, an Olympia-based conservative think tank, has accused the Washington Education Association of illegally taking money from teachers' salaries and spending it on political activities.  The foundation says the practice is banned by citizen Initiative 134, passed by voters in 1992.  The initiative overhauled campaign finance laws.<p>The foundation's president, Bob Williams, a Republican who lost the 1988 governor's race, asked the PDC to stop the teachers union from all political spending until the case is resolved.<p>Union spokeswoman Teresa Moore dismissed Williams' claims as politically motivated.<p>"As a former Republican candidate for governor and an outspoken critic of public education, Bob Williams is following the Dole campaign's lead in attacking teachers and their unions," Moore said in a statement.  "We are confident that we have followed all PDC rules and guidelines."<p>The foundation's claim was accompanied by a news release that criticized the PDC for not investigating the allegations earlier this year after a handful of teachers filed complaints.<p>Melissa Warheit, executive director of the PDC, said the case was put on hold while the commission's staff struggled with a heavy workload of cases, including one involving Republican gubernatorial candidate Dale Foreman that is subject of hearings this week.<p>Now that many of those cases have been resolved, she said the foundation's claims against the WEA "will be the No. 1 priority."<p><CENTER>######</CENTER><p>end of article.<br>
<br>
