<A HREF="../index.htm"><IMG SRC="grahome.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="See File"></A>
</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>SIZING UP SCHOOL CHOICE</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>The Blum Center for Parental Freedom in Education</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>David W. Kirkpatrick On School Choice, No. 5, December 1995</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>One of the challenges by opponents of school choice is &quot;Where is the research proof?&quot;  Aside from the fact that there is such proof, and ample practical experience, this might carry more weight if they would first apply this standard to the present system.</P>
<P>Where, for example, is research justifying building a box, called a school, which is filled with smaller boxes, called classrooms, in which rows of students face the front of the room, before a teacher who typically talks 70-80% of the time, that is, three to four times as much as all of the students combined?</P>
<P>Few activities in schools, government or independent, are based upon research, and the older they are the less evidence there is that they are justified. Worse yet, much schooling directly contradicts research findings.  Some large schools have a long history.  Santa Monica, California high school was reported to have 8,000 students as far back as 1961. </P>
<P>Generally, consolidation of schools, and school districts, has taken place in the past 40 years, since the appearance in 1959 of James B. Conant's <B>The American High School </B><B>Today</B>, in which he said schools should be bigger.  He didn't specify how big, but he suggested high schools have graduating classes of about 100.  Assuming a four-year school, and a modest dropout rate, that translates into high schools of about 400-500.</P>
<P>Roger Barker and Paul Gump's <B>Big School, Small School</B> (1964) cited hundreds of studies stressing the advantage of small schools.  As they said, &quot;a school should be sufficiently small that all of its students are needed for the enterprises.  A school should be small enough that students are not redundant.&quot;</P>
<P>This was ignored by superintendents and school boards with an &quot;edifice complex.&quot;  By the mid-1980s, said Walter Karp, 63% of all high school students were in schools of 5,000 or more.</P>
<P>A Minnesota study a generation ago concluded that the most economical high schools were those with 38-175 seniors which, again, averages out to about 400 students in a four year school.</P>
<P>Herbert Kiesling found the relation between school size and student performance to be negative over a size range from average daily attendance of fewer than 200 to almost 4,000. That is, as school size increased student performance decreased.</P>
<P>Neil Postman and Charles Weingartner in 1973 cited studies that concluded that the maximum size for what they termed &quot;a humanized school&quot; is about 250. </P>
<P>A decade ago Joe Nathan noted that small schools, whether in a city or small town, tended to have higher achievement rates, less violence, and greater student participation in school activities.  He also reminded us that almost all American presidents have been the products of small towns and small schools.  </P>
<P>Government schools average approximately 500 students - 85,000 schools for 43 million students.  This average would be larger except for the thousands of rural schools where 500 students are not possible.  Even into the 1990s 40% of rural elementary schools had less than 200 students, and 75% of secondary schools fewer than 400.</P>
<P>The average independent school averages only about 200 students - 25,000 schools for about five million students.  This would be smaller except that many urban parochial schools mimic their public neighbors. Having winning sports teams has also played a role in decisions on school size.</P>
<P>Where is the centralized school that was ever built because of a demand by teachers, students, parents or taxpayers?   Overwhelmingly these groups oppose such projects, the closing of a small school often meaning the loss of local neighborhood or community identity, in addition to being contrary to sound educational policy.  Even the claimed economies of scale tend to be rhetorical rather than reality, when factors such as additional bureaucracy and transportation are taken into consideration.   </P>
<P>Research findings about school districts are similar.  Deborah Verstegen, in the <B>Journal of Educational Finance</B>, fall 1990, noted &quot;...data from New Jersey ...found, in 'all cases, larger district enrollments are associated with lower test scores.'&quot;  <I>In all cases</I>.</P>
<P>Such findings have been regularly reported in the general press as well as educational and research journals - and just as regularly ignored.</P>
<P>Thomas Toch, in <B>The Washington Post</B>, October 20, 1991, commented on the closer relationships between students and teachers in smaller schools, which have consequences beyond just the academic, although related.  He cited a 1987 study that found student dropout rates in schools with more than 2,000 students are twice those in schools with fewer than 667.  A 1988 review reported there is more class cutting, absenteeism and classroom disorders in the larger schools.  More recently, similar conclusions regarding attendance, dropping out, violence, vandalism, student involvement in activities, and school climate being negatively affected by school size were drawn by Diana Oxley in the <B>PHI DELTA KAPPAN</B> of March 1994.</P>
<P>Even schools of 400-500 may be too large.</P>
<P>Dennis Dunn, in <B>Every Child Is Our Child</B>, 1992, argued that the maximum size for any school should be 200-215, and that Ted Sizer, former Dean of the Harvard Graduate School of Education, now at Brown University and the leader of the Coalition of Essential Schools, believes 200 is best.</P>
<P>The story of the growing success over the past 20 years in the East Harlem section of New York City has been told many times, but bears repeating.  Ranking last among the city's 32 subdistricts, the decision was made to seek greater staff involvement and decision-making.  While school choice and size were not part of an original master plan, since no such plan was established, these emerged as two main elements in raising the district from dead last to the middle ranks, although its students are disadvantaged.</P>
<P>In a system where schools had been as large as 2,300 students, all of the modified schools are small, some with only a few dozen students and none with more than a few hundred and about a dozen teachers.</P>
<P>Equally dramatic results occurred in NYC's nearly 70-year-old Julia Richman High School, only 37% of whose 1,800 students graduated and more than 75% of whom were absent on typical day.  In 1993, in collaboration with a local affiliate of Sizer's Coalition of Essential Schools, six smaller high schools were opened.  Attendance and test scores have gone up, dropout rates down, and the schools are safer.</P>
<P>In <B>Education Week</B>, March 22, 1995, Ann Bradley again confirmed that &quot;small schools are much more hospitable places for both students and teachers...&quot;</P>
<P>The charter school movement indicates the value of this approach.  While these are autonomous public schools, they lack the power to tax or compel attendance.  With a few exceptions, such as the Vaughn school in Los Angeles which was a large public school that was granted charter status, they are small, and all are schools of choice.   Some, such as the St. Paul Academy, began with 15 or 20 students, an enrollment which many public school educators maintain makes impossible an effective program.  So much for conventional thinking.</P>
<P>Small schools and schools of choice have many nonacademic advantages as well.  As already mentioned, centralized schools leave many neighborhoods or communities without a school of their own.  Parental involvement, already difficult for disadvantaged families who may feel looked down upon by, or otherwise uncomfortable in, the typical school environment, is further limited when a school is so large that many students live miles away.</P>
<P>Transportation, nonexistent with the dispersion of small neighborhood schools, may become a major cost.  Bureaucracy increases.  A study by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) found that, of the nations reviewed, the United States is the only one in which fewer than half of school employees are teachers.  </P>
<P>Resistance to innovation increases; with more staff, students and parents there are more interests whose approval, or at least acquiescence, must be obtained.  This alone is a major argument for school choice. This entire struggle to reform schools would be avoided if each school was an autonomous school of choice.  Political approval would not be needed.</P>
<P>Finally, beginning more or less where we started, as now Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan said in 1969, &quot;the education establishment is resistant to research findings...and will probably remain so...&quot;  So when members of that establishment argue for research evidence, as they almost invariably do when opposing virtually every proposed reform, they should be required to first provide the research base for what they are presently doing.</P>
<P>With few exceptions, they can't do it. Not just because they aren't familiar with the research, which they aren't, but because it rarely exists.</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
