<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>WILL &quot;MORE&quot; EVER BE ENOUGH?</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>The Blum Center for Parental Freedom in Education</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>David W. Kirkpatrick On School Choice, No. 4, November 1995</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>It is impossible to educate students without spending money.  There are also schools, both government and independent, that have minimal funds to do their job.</P>
<P>Having said that, the never-ending appeal by the educational establishment for more money faces at least two major problems.</P>
<P>The first, and most fundamental, is that more money will simply not be forthcoming, at least not in the amounts that educators request.  With the many demands on the public dollar, and growing public resistance to any major spending increases, government schools will do well to receive increases even marginally ahead of inflation.  As the title of a <I>Denver Post</I> article by Al Knight said a few years ago, &quot;If Money's the Solution, That's the Problem.&quot;</P>
<P>Even if money were available in relatively abundant measure, where is the evidence that it would lead to significant improvements?  Per-pupil funding in constant dollars has significantly increased in the past three decades.  Whether one accepts the thesis that results have deteriorated, or that the alleged decline of the schools is a myth, there can be no arguing the fact that gains have not doubled or tripled to keep pace with the expenditure of dollars.</P>
<P>There are school districts where the expenditures are only a few thousand dollars per pupil per year. There are others, in New York and Texas, for example, that spend in excess of $20,000.  Yet where is the district that thinks it is spending enough?</P>
<P>As an aside, it should be noted that the most &quot;elite&quot; K-12 schools in the nation are not the private ones to which this description is usually applied but the high spending suburban districts.   It is the private ones that seek to attract students without regard to geography and that provide financial assistance to those who could not otherwise afford to attend.  Where is the wealthy suburban district that does the same?  They not only do not seek such variety, or offer such assistance, in many instances they have hired security people to check on their students to make sure they are all residents.  No urban, poor, minority or other nonresidents need apply.  </P>
<P>The failure of money to improve results is indicated by two federal reports - 1983's <I>A Nation at Risk</I>, and 1994's <I>Goals </I><I>2000: Educate America Act</I>. </P>
<P>Contrary to those who see some sinister plot to destroy the government schools, neither of these reports was issued by reformers or those who belong to this alleged conspiracy.  The eighteen members of the National Commission on Excellence in Education, who issued <I>A Nation at Risk</I>, included public school administrators, the 1981-82 National Teacher of the Year, the President of Yale University, a Nobel Laureate, a former Governor, and the retired chairman of Bell Labs, among others.   <I>Goals 2000</I> is an act of Congress, which is hardly a hotbed of education reform or radical thought.</P>
<P>And what did these reports say?</P>
<P>The former included one of the most famous remarks ever made about education:</P>
<P><I> </I><I>&quot;If an unfriendly foreign power had attempted to impose on </I><I>America the mediocre educational performance that exists </I><I>today, we might well have viewed it as an act of war.  As it </I><I>stands, we have allowed this to happen to ourselves...We </I><I>have, in effect, been committing an act of unthinking, </I><I>unilateral educational disarmament.&quot;</I></P>
<P><I> </I></P>
<P>And they provided specifics:</P>
<P>&quot;International comparisons of student achievement, completed a decade ago, reveal that on 19 academic tests American students were never first or second and, in comparison with other industrialized nations, were last seven times. </P>
<P>&quot;Some 23 million American adults are functionally illiterate by the simplest tests of everyday reading, writing, and comprehension...</P>
<P>&quot;Average achievement of high school students on most standardized tests is now lower than 26 years ago when Sputnik was launched...</P>
<P>&quot;The College Board's Scholastic Aptitude Tests (SAT) demonstrate a virtually unbroken decline from 1963 to 1980...</P>
<P>&quot;Both the number and proportion of students demonstrating superior achievement on the SATs (i.e., those with scores of 650 or higher) have also dramatically declined.</P>
<P>&quot;Many 17-year-olds do not possess the 'higher order' intellectual skills we should expect of them.  Nearly 40 percent cannot draw inferences from written material; only one-fifth can write a persuasive essay; and only one-third can solve a mathematics problem requiring several steps.&quot;</P>
<P>Eleven years later, after innumerable reform efforts, the expenditure of more than two trillion dollars, and more words about reform than any society should  have to tolerate, what did Congress say in the <I>Goals 2000: </I><I>Educate America Act</I>?</P>
<P>&quot;The Congress finds that...</P>
<P>&quot;the reforms in education from 1977 through 1992 ...often have been limited to a few schools or to a single part of the educational system.&quot; (p. 35)</P>
<P>&quot;A majority of public schools in the United States are failing to prepare students to achieve the National Education Goals.&quot; (p. 91)</P>
<P>&quot;(A) The current achievement levels of students in the United States are far below those that might indicate competency in challenging subject matter in core content areas.</P>
<P>&quot;(B) During the last 20 years, relatively little changed in how students were taught.  Despite much research suggesting better alternatives, classrooms continue to be dominated by textbooks, teacher lectures, short-answer activity sheets, and unequal patterns of student attention.</P>
<P>&quot;(C)...the differences in performance between Caucasian students and their minority counterparts remain unacceptably large...the gender gap in mathematics...still remains at higher levels of problem solving.  Too little progress has been made in reducing gender performance gaps favoring males in science and females in writing.' (p. 112)</P>
<P>&quot;(A) The rate of decline in our urban schools is escalating at a rapid pace.  Student performance in most inner city schools grows worse each year. At least half of all students entering ninth grade fail to graduate 4 years later and many more students from high-poverty backgrounds leave school with skills that are inadequate for today's workplace.  Student</P>
<P>performance in many inner city neighborhoods grows worse each year...</P>
<P>&quot;(D) An educational emergency exists in those urban and rural areas where there are large concentrations of children who live in poverty.&quot; p. 115</P>
<P>&quot;Many elementary and secondary schools in the United States--</P>
<P> (i) are structured according to models that are ineffective and rely on notions of management and governance that may be outdated or insufficient for the challenges of the next century; and</P>
<P> (ii) are unsuccessful in equipping all students with the knowledge and skills needed to succeed as citizens and in the working world.&quot; p. 119</P>
<P>&quot;(A)...Disappointing student performance on achievement tests and licensure examinations, declining rates of postsecondary education persistence and completion among minorities, and other troubling trends in the quality of postsecondary education...&quot;</P>
<P>&quot;(C) The more than 1,000,000 men and women incarcerated in the prisons and jails in the United States are among the most severely educationally disadvantaged in the United States, with high rates of functional illiteracy and extremely low levels of educational attainment.&quot; p. 121</P>
<P>&quot;(A) education research...is not having the impact on the schools...that such research should;</P>
<P>&quot;(B) relevant education research and resulting solutions are not being adequately disseminated to and used by the teachers...</P>
<P>&quot;(C) there are insufficient linkages...to ensure that research on effective practice is disseminated and technical assistance provided to all teachers...</P>
<P>&quot;(F) teachers have little control over what inservice education teachers will be offered.&quot; pp 140-141</P>
<P>This is progress?  Note that a span of eleven years is almost an entire educational cycle.  Virtually all of the students in 1983 were gone by 1994, too many of whom (a majority?) have lost their educational opportunity forever.</P>
<P>How many more trillions must be spent, and millions of citizens destined to live at the margins of society, before it is realized that this system must be opened up, that, for too many, the benefits of schooling as usual are minimal, if not disastrous?</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
