<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selected Writings by David W. Kirkpatrick 950530cc.htm</TITLE>
<LINK REL="ToC" HREF="httoc.htm">
<LINK REL="Next" HREF="950510cc.htm">
<LINK REL="Previous" HREF="9511blum.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#8000FF" BACKGROUND="yelgrain.gif">
<P><A HREF="9511blum.htm"><IMG SRC="grappage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Previous Page"></A>
<A HREF="httoc.htm"><IMG SRC="gratoc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="TOC"></A>
<A HREF="950510cc.htm"><IMG SRC="granpage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="../index.htm"><IMG SRC="grahome.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="See File"></A>
</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><!--<B>No Changes above</B>--><!--<B>Start below</B>--><B>SCHOOL CHOICE: THE VIEW FROM MILWAUKEE</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>Vol. 4, No. 11, May 30, 1995</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>Most readers of this newsletter know that in 1990-91 Wisconsin approved a proposal by Rep. Annette &quot;Polly&quot; Williams for the Milwaukee Public School District's 97,000 students, and to the number of eligible nonpublic schools that could participate, the program has been growing slowly each year.  About 750 students received government-funded tuition vouchers in 1993-94 to attend any one of a dozen non-religious private schools in that city.</P>
<P>Less well-known is a privately funded school-choice program begun in 1992 by PAVE, Partners Advancing Values in Education.  PAVE scholarships may be used at any private school in Milwaukee, including religious schools.  Contrary to those who argue modest grants will not help low-income people, PAVE, like most private programs, is for such parents and provides maximum grants of $1000 at the elementary and middle-school level and $1,500 for high-school students.  Eligibility is limited to families with incomes less than 185% of the poverty level.</P>
<P>PAVE funded 2,370 students in 1993-94 - up from 2,089 the year before, 1992-93 - who attended 102 private schools. One such parent was Valerie Barrett who, with her two children, took part in REACH conferences of December 1993 and May 1994.  In 1993-94 PAVE received an additional 2,200 applications. </P>
<P>Even Williams' Milwaukee Parental Choice Program turns away students every year because of the lack of capacity due to the limited number of eligible schools.</P>
<P>Another significant factor is that the PAVE program is reportedly the largest private program in the nation and also the only one to operate alongside a government-supported school choice program.</P>
<P>Critics who like to say the Milwaukee Parental Choice Program program isn't successful are not in Milwaukee, rarely quote Milwaukee sources, and ignore the much larger, inclusive private PAVE program.</P>
<P>A Wisconsin Policy Research Report gives the results of a random sample of 1,000 adult, black/African-American Milwaukee residents conducted in January.  They paint quite a different picture than some would have you believe is the case.</P>
<P><B>Q:</B><B> </B><B>Should Parents have the Right to Choose their local school?</B></P>
<P><B>A:</B> 95.2% said yes; </P>
<P>  3.4% said no; </P>
<P>  1.4% didn't know/didn't respond</P>
<P><B>Q:</B><B> </B><B>Which Schools Provide the Better Education?</B>  </P>
<P><B>A:</B> 69.6% said Private/ Parochial</P>
<P> 16.3% Milwaukee Public</P>
<P> 14.1% DK/DR.  </P>
<P>Given the margin of error this is essentially the same as a 1990 survey that found 72% believed the private schools are better.</P>
<P><B>Q:</B><B> </B><B>Have Milwaukee Schools Improved in 5 Years?</B>  </P>
<P><B>A:</B> 21% said yes</P>
<P> 22.3% felt they stayed the same</P>
<P> 47% thought they have gotten worse </P>
<P>  9.7% didn't know/didn't respond.</P>
<P><B>Q:</B><B> </B><B>Suppose that you had a child in the local Milwaukee public school, and that the government gave you a voucher worth $3,500 which </B><B>you could use to enroll your child in any school--public, private, or church-related. Would you use that voucher to enroll your child in a </B><B>different public school from your local school, in a private school, in a church-related school, or would you keep your child in the same </B><B>public school he or she would be in right now?</B></P>
<P><B>A:</B> 41.5% said they would use a private school </P>
<P> 28.5% would remain with their present public school </P>
<P> 18.5% would utilize a church-related school</P>
<P>  5.4%  would transfer to a different public school</P>
<P>  5.7%  didn't know or didn't respond.</P>
<P><B>Q:</B><B> </B><B>Is Today's Education Better Than Your Own?</B> </P>
<P><B>A:</B> 48.1% said it is worse</P>
<P> 40.3% said it is better</P>
<P>  7.9% viewed it as the same</P>
<P>  3.7% didn't know or didn't respond.</P>
<P>Then the following question was asked about the state program:</P>
<P><B>Q:</B><B> </B><B>A choice plan is currently being offered to low income parents in Milwaukee.  Under this plan some parents can choose to send their </B><B>children to a local public or private school, but not to a parochial school.  Would you favor or oppose expanding this choice program to </B><B>include parochial schools?</B></P>
<P><B>A:</B> 70.5% favor including parochial schools (more than three times those opposed)</P>
<P> 21.7% opposed</P>
<P>  7.8% didn't know/didn't respond.</P>
<P>This is interesting given the other response that fewer than 19% would themselves use a voucher at a parochial school.</P>
<P>Milwaukeeans clearly know where they stand on this issue, despite claims made by school choice opponents, few of whom have ever been near the city. </P>
<P>On a different topic, when asked about placing the <B>Educational Emphasis on Basics vs. Building Confidence</B></P>
<P><B>A:</B> 60% favored the basics</P>
<P> 33.2% building confidence and self-esteem</P>
<P>  6.8% didn't know/didn't respond.</P>
<P>Rep. Williams has herself often said that minorities are more interested in education than integration.  The survey tested sentiment on this issue as well, asking:</P>
<P><B>Q:</B><B> </B><B>If the Milwaukee Public Schools had the opportunity to increase learning among all students by reducing the degree of integration, </B><B>would you approve or disapprove of this?</B></P>
<P><B>A:</B> 55.3% approved, indicating their belief that, given the choice, education is of primary importance</P>
<P> 36.8% said they disapproved of this tradeoff</P>
<P>  7.9% didn't know/didn't respond.</P>
<P>Generally speaking, older people are more satisfied with the public schools, or have more reservations about major reforms such as school choice.  This has been the result in other surveys as well.  This may be because of the Good Old Days Syndrome, and because schools years ago didn't face some of the serious problems of today.  Also, in earlier times fewer students remained through high school graduation so those who did graduate were more accepting of the school environment.  </P>
<P>There was one exception to this in Milwaukee, however.  Those 55 to 64 thought schools have improved a bit but those 65 and over were quite critical of today's school system.</P>
<P>The number of those who would use private or parochial schools is up 5% from the 1990 survey  and is now five times the number of those who actually use such schools today.</P>
<P>Although the 28.5% who would use the same public school is low, it is still higher than the overall negative view of the Milwaukee public schools in general.  As is often the case, with education, with Congress, etc., the public's general view is more critical than is the specific view of their own school, Congressman, etc.</P>
<P>Most significantly of all, though, is the 95.2% that agreed parents should have the right to select the school their child(ren) attend.  It is almost unheard of for polls to find 95% of the public agreeing on anything.  You could almost ask if they think the sun will come up in the east in the morning and 4.8% might be expected to say no, or not answer. </P>
<P>Janet R. Beales and Maureen Wahl of the Reason Foundation have also issued a report on the PAVE program which found that students therein, who have the much wider choice of schools to attend, outperform both Milwaukee Parental Choice Program and Milwaukee Parental Public School students on standard tests.</P>
<P>Parents said educational quality was the most important reason they chose a particular school.  Ninety-six percent were satisfied with what their child was learning.  This would seem to have a bearing on why nonpublic schools of all types tend to have fewer problems with discipline than the public schools, not to mention violence.  Regardless of age, when we have more control over our lives and are where we want to be, we are less likely to have or cause problems.</P>
<P>Remember, despite other claims of school choice opponents, these are not handpicked students.  They are from low-income families, 57% headed by a single parent. Participating private schools may not screen applicants.  Acceptance or rejection is based on capacity.  If more apply than can be accepted, a random lottery is used.  </P>
<P>Although this year's survey found many who thought the Milwaukee Public Schools have improved in the last five years, the Reason Foundation study notes that 79% of the students graduated from high school in 1971; by 1993 just 44% did.  Today's graduates have a 2.18 grade point average, on a four-point grading scale.  This despite the fact that per pupil spending has increased 21% from 1973 to 1993, from $5,820 to $7,030, in 1993 constant dollars.</P>
<P>Consistent with this finding is a statement by Rep. Williams that 60% of Milwaukee Public School students drop out of high school.  More disturbing, she said that one-quarter of the remainder, 10% of the original group, graduate with minimal academic skills.</P>
<P>Those who claim school choice will leave the poorest students behind are describing many public school districts, and not just Milwaukee.</P>
<P>In Harrisburg, PA, where this is being written, 75% of the students live below the poverty level; 60% are from single parent homes; 70+% are black; and about 15% are Hispanic.  </P>
<P>Who has been left behind?  The poor.  Those who can flee have already done so, by moving out, or by sending their own children to a nonpublic school.  Not least among these &quot;escaping&quot; (remember, that National Education Association President Keith Geiger has said we can't allow students to escape - which would indicate they are prisoners) are the teachers in these public systems.</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
