<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selected Writings by David W. Kirkpatrick 950510cc.htm</TITLE>
<LINK REL="ToC" HREF="httoc.htm">
<LINK REL="Next" HREF="950215cc.htm">
<LINK REL="Previous" HREF="950530cc.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#8000FF" BACKGROUND="yelgrain.gif">
<P><A HREF="950530cc.htm"><IMG SRC="grappage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Previous Page"></A>
<A HREF="httoc.htm"><IMG SRC="gratoc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="TOC"></A>
<A HREF="950215cc.htm"><IMG SRC="granpage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="../index.htm"><IMG SRC="grahome.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="See File"></A>
</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><!--<B>Start below</B>--><B>How Much &quot;Progress&quot; Can We Stand?</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 4, No. 9, May 10, 1995 </FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>O1</P>
<P>ne of the most famous government reports ever issued was 1983&quot;s <I>A Nation At Risk</I>, which concluded that the nation's public schools were engulfed in &quot;a rising tide of mediocrity&quot;, and that if any other nation did to us what we are doing to ourselves we would consider it an act of war.</P>
<P>It might be well to recall that the report spoke of public schools as a system, not as isolated situations here and there, or just in inner-city schools, or whatever.  They were speaking of the suburban schools as well, where parents and the public are all to willing to believe that their schools are good schools, regardless of any evidence to the contrary, or without making any effort to determine whether this is true or not.</P>
<P>To a large degree parents, taxpayers and the general public are content as long as schools are open (no strikes), are quiet (no violence), the students seem to be achieving (report cards have good grades, even if they happen to be inflated ones), and the students don't complain (which they rarely do as long as they aren't hassled too much and their report cards keep mom and dad satisfied).</P>
<P>If you live in such a district, it isn't necessary to conduct an investigation, with which the system probably will not cooperate.</P>
<P>Try a few simple tests of your own. To be fair, you might do this even if your youngster attends a nonpublic school.  After all, you should be concerned with your child's educational attainments, regardless of the school he or she attends.</P>
<P>Obtain an outline map of the United States and hand it to your son or daughter and ask them to identify the states.  As a teacher who did this several times each year with 11th graders, I found that few could get more than 10 or 15 right the first time, and many couldn't even identify Pennsylvania.  By repeating this periodically through the year, however, most of them could eventually identify most states.</P>
<P>This is not a trivial matter.  Those who cannot picture in their minds where the states are will have little understanding of such references.</P>
<P>Or, the next time you stop at the bank ask for a check register.  They are free.  Fill in a page or two with some expenses, deposits, check fees, and bank interest, such as appear in your own regular statement.  But don't do any of the computation.  See if your favorite student can accurately balance the figures, a matter of simple addition and subtraction.  The National Assessment of Education Progress (NAEP) tests indicate that most 17-year-olds cannot do this.</P>
<P>Find some relatively easy crossword puzzles for them to complete.  These test both knowledge, even if it is sometimes trivia, and the ability to spell words correctly.</P>
<P>You may be surprised by the outcome of such simple home tests.</P>
<P>I2</P>
<P>n any event, by 1994, eleven years after <I>A Nation at Risk</I>, innumerable attempts to reform the public schools, and the expenditure of more than $2,000,000,000,000 (that's two trillion dollars, no misprint), what has been achieved?</P>
<P>According to Congress, not much.</P>
<P>Last year the Congress adopted the <I>GOALS 2000: EDUCATE AMERICA ACT</I>.  Ignoring the merits or demerits of that 231 page measure, which are still being debated and may or may not be modified or repealed by the current session of Congress, consider the findings which were used to justify its enactment and specific provisions.</P>
<P>&quot;The Congress finds that-</P>
<P>&quot;...the reforms in education from 1977 through 1992 have achieved some good results, but such reform efforts to often have been limited to a few schools or to a single part of the educational system&quot; (p. 34)</P>
<P>&quot;A majority of public schools in the United States are failing to prepare students to achieve the national education goals.&quot; (p. 91)  </P>
<P>Yes.  A majority.  Again.</P>
<P>  </P>
<P>&quot;(A) The current achievement levels of students in the United States are far below those that might indicate competency in challenging subject matter in core content areas.</P>
<P>&quot;(B) During the last 20 years, relatively little changed in how students were taught.  Despite much research suggesting better alternatives, classrooms continue to be dominated by textbooks, teacher lectures, short-answer activity sheets and unequal patterns of student attention.</P>
<P>&quot;(C) Despite progress in narrowing the gaps, the differences in performance between Caucasian students and their minority counterparts, remain unacceptably large. While progress has been made in reducing the gender gap in mathematics, such gap still remains at higher levels of problem solving.  Too little progress has been made in reducing gender performance gaps favoring males in science and females in writing.&quot; (p. 112)</P>
<P>&quot;(A) The rate of decline in our urban schools is escalating at a rapid pace.  Student performance in most inner city schools grows worse each year.  At least half of all students entering ninth grade fail to graduate 4 years later and many more students from high-poverty backgrounds leave school with skills that are inadequate for today's workplace.  Student performance in many inner city neighborhoods grows worse each year.  At least half of all students entering ninth grade fail to graduate in four years...</P>
<P>&quot;(B) Rural schools enroll a disproportionately large share of the poor and at-risk students of the United States and yet often lack the means to address effectively the needs of these children...</P>
<P>&quot;(D) An educational emergency exists in those urban and rural areas where there are large concentrations of children who live in poverty.&quot; (p. 116)</P>
<P>&quot;(A) Many elementary and secondary schools in the United States--</P>
<P>  (i) are structured according to models that are ineffective and rely on notions of management and governance that may be outdated or insufficient for the challenges of the next century; and</P>
<P>  (ii) are unsuccessful in equipping all students with the knowledge and skills needed to succeed as citizens and in the working world.&quot; (p. 119)</P>
<P>&quot;Disappointing student performance in achievement tests and licensure examinations, declining rates of postsecondary education persistence and completion among minorities, and other troubling trends in the quality of postsecondary education should be addressed by the United States as part of its overall drive to improve American education...</P>
<P>&quot;The more than 1,000,000 men and women incarcerated in the prisons and jails in the United States are among the most severely educationally disadvantaged in the United States, with high rates of functional illiteracy and extremely low levels of educational attainment...an estimated 90 percent of these individuals are expected to be released by the end of the decade...&quot; (p. 121)</P>
<P>&quot;(A) education research, including research funded by the Office, is not having the impact on the schools of the United States that such research should;</P>
<P> (B) relevant education research and resulting solutions are not being adequately disseminated to and used by the teachers that need such research and solutions. &quot; p. 140</P>
<P>&quot;(C) there are insufficient linkages...to ensure that research on effective practice is disseminated and technical assistance provided to all teachers...</P>
<P> (F) teachers have little control over what inservice education teachers will be offered.&quot; (p. 141)</P>
<P>Is this progress???</P>
<P>This is the &quot;achievement&quot; resulting from eleven years, 2+ trillion public</P>
<P>dollars, and the best efforts of the federal government, fifty state governments and 15,000+ local school districts?</P>
<P>Imagine, if you will, if current trends continue, what we can look forward at the conclusion of the eleven years from 1994-2005, during which 3-4 trillion more dollars will be spent.</P>
<P>For those who tag any discouraging word about schooling as &quot;school bashing,&quot; remember &quot;The Congress finds that&quot; these conditions exist.</P>
<P>As in 1983, these findings are not merely anecdotal or or isolated situations.</P>
<P>&quot;A majority of public schools in the United States are failing...The rate of decline in our urban schools is escalating at a rapid pace.  Student performance in most inner city schools grows worse each year...An educational emergency exists in those urban and rural areas..(Many schools) are structured according to models that are ineffective...(and) are unsuccessful in equipping all students with the knowledge and skills needed to succeed...relevant education research and resulting solutions are not being adequately disseminated to and used by the teachers...&quot;</P>
<P>Pardon the repetition but the message seems not to be getting through.</P>
<P>Should we not stop talking about reforming or &quot;restructuring&quot; the system, placing the student first, etc., etc.,  and begin actually doing it?</P>
<P>Is it acceptable to have a public school where the police were called in more than 200 times from September 1994 to March of 1995, an average of nearly twice each school day?  (This is not fiction.  It is a real school.)</P>
<P>What more needs to be said?</P>
<P>How much worse must it become?</P>
<P>How much longer can this be tolerated?</P>
<P>Does anybody care?</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
