<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><!--<B>Start below</B>--><B>LOW-INCOME STUDENTS BENEFIT FROM CHOICE</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 3, No. 3, February 15, 1995</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<H5>
<FONT SIZE=3><B><I>Privately Funded Choice Plans</I></B></FONT></H5>
<P>More than a dozen private school choice programs in cities around the nation operate very successfully.</P>
<P>When the Bradley Foundation joined with others to fund scholarships for low-income students in Milwaukee in 1992 all 4,500 applications were picked up the morning after the scholarships were announced.</P>
<P>PAVE's first year report noted immediate gains, with astounding levels of parental involvement.  &quot;Ninety-six per cent of the parents surveyed attended parent-teacher conferences and 67% attended parent-teacher organization meetings.&quot;</P>
<P>More than 90% of the parents said they were &quot;satisfied&quot; or &quot;Very Satisfied&quot; with teacher performance, discipline, textbooks learning achievement, involvement opportunities and school location.</P>
<P><I>Given the Choice: A Study of the PAVE Program and School Choice in Milwaukee</I>, a recent study from The Reason Foundation, says the program's success is ongoing and low-income students demonstrate higher academic performance in private schools than in public schools. </P>
<P>With state and local officials across the country, including Pennsylvania, Arizona, Connecticut, Kansas, Texas, New Jersey, Ohio, Texas, and Wisconsin considering adopting or expanding school-choice programs &quot;careful study of existing choice programs is an imperative,&quot; says Janet R. Beales, coauthor of the study.</P>
<P>Ms. Beales, policy analyst with the Reason Foundation, and coauthor Maureen Wahl, director of research for the Milwaukee-based Family Service America, analyzed PAVE's school-choice program, and one implemented by the state, assessing performance gains, demographics, parental satisfaction, and attrition.</P>
<P>The government-run program, the Milwaukee Parental Choice Program (MPCP), authored by state Rep. Annette &quot;Polly&quot; Williams, began in 1990-91.  It granted roughly 750 tuition vouchers to students in 1993-94 which enabled them to attend any one</P>
<P>of a dozen non-religious private schools in Milwaukee.</P>
<P>Unlike the MPCP, PAVE scholarships may be used at any Milwaukee private school, including religious ones.  In its second year of operation, 1993-1994, PAVE served roughly 2,370 students in 102 different private schools.  Both programs target low-income students, are heavily oversubscribed, and report high levels of parental satisfaction.  Contrary to charges of some opponents, among the top reasons why parents choose a school for their child is education quality and school discipline.</P>
<P>Beales notes that the PAVE program serves over three times as many low-income students as the MPCP but for most of the students it serves the MPCP has been successful. A state-sponsored evaluation found that, while MPCP students were at the bottom of their public school class, they have shown modest academic achievement gains in the choice program.</P>
<P>The Reason Foundation's findings show that PAVE students outperform (MPS) students on standardized tests of academic achievement.  A higher fraction of PAVE students scored at or above the National Percentile Rank (NPR) than other comparison groups.</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="mg1.gif" WIDTH = 668 HEIGHT = 211 ALT="Undisplayed Graphic"></P>
<P> Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge</P>
<P> Inaugural Address, January 17, 1995</P>
<P><I>                             &quot;We will offer Pennsylvania's parents and children quality educational </I></P>
<P><I>                             choices: public; private; and religious.  We will be guided by the only </I></P>
<P><I>                             special interest that really matters -- our children.&quot;</I></P>
<P>The state-funded voucher system has worked so well that Governor Tommy Thompson is proposing its expansion in his 1995-1997 state budget.</P>
<P>If adopted, vouchers worth $3,300 per child, or the actual tuition, whichever is lower, would be provided for Milwaukee students, grades K-12, to attend any school of their choice, whether religious or non-sectarian, with the cost capped at $11.5 million.  In 1997-98, 5,500 students would be eligible and the voucher would be adjusted for inflation.  After that there would be no limit other than the available openings in private schools.</P>
<P>Milwaukee Mayor John Norquist, who first had doubts about the Williams proposal, is now an active supporter of its expansion.  He has said that, what has been termed &quot;The GI Bill for Kids will hurt public schools in the same way the original GI Bill hurt public universities: it will help make them the best in the world.&quot;</P>
<P>When PAVE students who attended public schools are compared to those who had only attended private school significant differences in achievement appear.  Public school transfers are consistently lower in math, reading, and composite scores, than those who had only attended private schools.</P>
<P>Based on demographics, the two groups have almost identical economic and family backgrounds.  &quot;This evidence suggests that differences in test scores may be due to prolonged enrollment in private schools of choice,&quot; says Beales. &quot;In other words, the type of school the student attends, public or private, may greatly influence academic performance.&quot;</P>
<P>Beales said, &quot;Our findings suggest that the earlier parents are given the choice of schools, the better their children will perform.  Likewise, the fewer regulatory restrictions placed on choice, the more students will have the opportunity to choose a school that meets their needs.&quot;</P>
<P>While the education establishment opposes such programs, it apparently only does so when they are beyond its control.  Since 1986-87 Milwaukee's school board, in addition to operating its own alternative high schools for at-risk students, has been authorized to contract with outside groups to educate up to 30% of such pupils.  But, of course, the district decides which students it wishes to move out.</P>
<P>Two years ago the state of Wisconsin authorized all school districts to contract for educational services for up to 200 of those at-risk.   They are defined as those in grades 5-12 who are one or more years behind in high school credits or two or more years behind in basic skills.  The students must also be either a dropout a habitual truant, a parent of an adjudicated delinquent.</P>
<P>In 1993-94 the Milwaukee schools had 1,200 such students being educated at 22 sites, and they were paying more than $5,000 for each student.</P>
<P>Milwaukee's public educators have no doubts about the value of school choice, at least for themselves.  It has been reported that 62% of them do not send their own children to the city's public schools.  That indicates their judgment about the quality of the schools within which they work.</P>
<P>This is not unknown in the rest of the nation as well, not only with public educators but with opponents of school choice generally.  As David Boldt of <I>The Philadelphia Inquirer</I> has noted, these opponents have no problem with school choice for themselves.  They are generally suburbanites who wouldn't dream of sending their own children to the schools to which they so readily consign the children of the poor.</P>
<P>(The Reason Foundation, is a national public-policy research organization. Founded in 1978 its address is 3415 S. Sepulveda Blvd, Suite 400, Los Angeles, CA 90034.  <I> Given The Choice: A Study of the PAVE Program and School Choice in Milwaukee</I> is its latest report on education and school choice.  Other studies include <I>School Voucher Programs in the United States</I> and <I>Doing More With Less: Competitive </I><I>Contracting for School-Support Services.</I> For copies, write or call the Foundation at (310) 391-2245.</P>
<P> </P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
