<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><!--<B>No Changes above</B>--><B>COMPARING APPLES AND ORANGES </B><B>-</B><B> A REAL LEMON</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>Vol. 3, No. 29, December 30 1994</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>By David W. Kirkpatrick</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<P>Some opponents of school choice are citing an October 1994 <I>Money</I> magazine article as evidence that public schools are as good as private schools.  Aside from the fact that such comparisons, whether made by public or private advocates, are irrelevant to the school choice debate, it is important to note what the article said.</P>
<P>One is reminded of Karl Marx's comment that he was not a Marxist.  What is said is often not what is interpreted by others. Thus the point here is not to criticize the article, but the distortions that some make of it.</P>
<P>One of the article's conclusions is that &quot;Students who attend the best public schools outperform most private school students.&quot;  Of course.  The best in one category are compared with the average in the other.  It is equally true that students in the best private schools outperform most public school students.  Neither finding requires any study.</P>
<P>It is also reported that &quot;The average public school teacher has stronger academic qualifications than the average private school teacher.&quot;  True, and irrelevant.  Study after study has concluded that qualifications such as advanced degrees, years of teaching experience, and certification have no correlation with either teacher effectiveness or student achievement.</P>
<P>Even Arthur Wise, president of the National Council for the Accreditation of Teacher Education,said in, of all places, the April 1991 issue of the National Education Association's <I>NEA Today</I>, that &quot;Right now, teacher certification procedures are a joke!&quot;</P>
<P>It was also said that &quot;The best public schools offer a more challenging curriculum than most private schools.&quot;  Again, the best of the public schools are compared with all of the private ones, and the statement could be reversed with equal validity.</P>
<P>According to the article, &quot;Catholic schools beat average publics on student success measures, but not by much&quot;; &quot;in many tough inner cities, Catholic schools often provide the only oasis of educational opportunity&quot;; and, &quot;there is no denying that, overall, the Catholic schools in our sample outperformed the average and disadvantaged public schools on students achievement measures.&quot;  In many instances the majority of the students are non-Catholics as well. </P>
<P>Although it was not reported here, these schools typically spend only one-half to one-third as much as public schools.  While salaries are a part of the reason, &quot;Catholic schools had the largest classes, averaging between 20 to 30 students each.&quot;  </P>
<P>The study also &quot;found the most luxurious buildings in average public school districts.&quot;  Many public school boards and superintendents have an &quot;edifice complex.&quot;</P>
<P>Furthermore, &quot;a fifth of both private and public schools have student bodies that are 50% or more minority,&quot; while &quot;The most racially segregated institutions in our sample are the advantaged public schools.&quot;</P>
<P>There are about 25,000 nonpublic and 85,000 public schools in the nation. Some 20,000 of the latter are high schools.  The <I>Money</I> report &quot;examined 70 public and private schools.&quot;  Of these, they visited 22 and interviewed the other 48 principals by telephone.</P>
<P>Based on this .064 of 1% sample, it is claimed &quot;about 10% of all public schools--about 2,000 nationwide--are as outstanding academically as the nation's 1,500 most prestigious and selective private schools.&quot;  </P>
<P>Besides, can it be seriously maintained that elite suburban schools are &quot;free&quot; of cost?  While reference is made to the cost of private schools none is given for the elite public ones which often spend more per pupil than private schools.  That cost is mostly paid from local sources, primarily the property tax which is deductible from the federal income tax, giving these wealthy citizens a free ride on at least part of the educational support they provide for their children.</P>
<P>That the magazine's readers have incomes above the norm is shown by the suggestion that parents seeking a good public school &quot;move to an affluent district with a top-ranked public school system.&quot;</P>
<P>Aside from the fact that everyone can't move to one of the favored suburban districts, there would be no room for them if they did.  Then there is the impossible barrier of cost.</P>
<P>How much?  Far too much.</P>
<P>&quot;In the most desirable suburbs whose schools we examined, median prices for single-family homes ranged from $156,000 in Birmingham, Mich., a Detroit suburb, to more than $500,000 in Beverly Hills and Kenilworth, Ill., which sends its kids to nearby New Trier High.&quot;  </P>
<P>I t will no doubt be a consolation to Detroit's poor inner-city students and parents to learn that they can improve their educational opportunities by buying a $156,000 home in the suburban community of Birmingham.</P>
<P>Those in Illinois have even a better option.  New Trier High school has been recognized as one of the finest such schools in the nation for years, public or private.  And it is a school available to all who can meet the modest requirement of being able to purchase a $500,000 home.</P>
<P>With average income in this nation being less than $30,000 a year, you see how practical this suggestion is, not only for the poor, disadvantaged and minorities but for the typical American family as well.</P>
<P>The truth is that highly rated suburban schools, which may spend $25,000 or more per pupil per year, an amount spent by few if any elite private schools, are private schools in public school disguise.</P>
<P>They are elite schools for the most affluent Americans, private enclaves excluding 99% of their fellow Americans and virtually 100% of the disadvantaged and minorities.</P>
<P>As indicated at the beginning, the entire article is irrelevant to the school choice debate, a topic which is not part of the article.</P>
<P>No one seriously argues that all private schools are better than all public, or the reverse.</P>
<P>When a high school graduate elects to go to college &quot;A&quot; rather than college &quot;B&quot;, does anyone make odious comparisons between the two institutions?</P>
<P>Of course not.</P>
<P>The same should be true of K-12 education.</P>
<P>Even if, to quote a former Pennsylvania Secretary of Education, &quot;every school a good school&quot; were the norm, individuals would still select one rather than another.</P>
<P>More than that, as the U.S. Supreme Court unanimously decided in 1925, everyone has a constitutional right to school choice, a right that those with means can exercise, either by paying tuition at a nonpublic school or living in &quot;an affluent district with a top-ranked public school system.&quot;</P>
<P>Those without means are in effect denied their constitutional right.</P>
<P>That is the heart of the matter.</P>
<P>School choice is not about comparing schools; it is about individual rights.</P>
<P> ~ ~ ~</P>
<H5>
<FONT SIZE=3><B><I>A &quot;Choice&quot; Publication</I></B></FONT></H5>
<P>William Bentley Ball, who was a presenter at the first REACH Alliance School Choice conference in December of 1993,  is perhaps the premier lawyer in the nation on what he regards as two essential educational principles: parental rights in education and the freedom of private education from government domination. </P>
<P>He has been the attorney for cases on religious freedom in education in 22 states and argued ten such cases before the U.S. Supreme Court, including defending the Amish in the <I>Yoder</I> case and arguing for religious educational rights in <I>Lemon v. Kurtzman</I>, which he regards as a decision based on extreme anti-religious bigotry.  Just last year he successfully argued for the right of a deaf student to have a publicly funded sign-language interpreter on Catholic school premises in the <I>Zobrest</I> case, </P>
<P>Bill is the author of a new book, <I>Creatures of the State</I>, the title of which is taken from the 1925 unanimous U.S. Supreme Court ruling that school choice is a constitutional right.  It is written for the general reader and is a guidebook to where we stand under current decisions of the Supreme Court and includes his concern, increasingly shared by others, that government control of education has very negative effects.</P>
<P>Among those praising the book are former U.S. Secretary of Education William J. Bennett and Mary Ann Glendon, Learned Hand Professor of Law at Harvard University.</P>
<P>If you would like to give yourself, or others, a thoughtful and provocative present this holiday season, <I>Mere Creatures of the State</I>, may be ordered for $15.95 ($13.95 plus $2.00 shipping) from CRISIS Books, Box 1006, Notre Dame, IN 46556</P>
<P> ~ ~ ~</P>
