<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>QUESTIONS,  QUESTIONS,  QUESTIONS</B><B>... and the answer is </B><B>SCHOOL CHOICE</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>Vol. 3, No. 26, November 15, 1994</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P><B>WHY</B> do opponents of school choice claim it will lead to segregated schools when that is what currently exists in the public school system?</P>
<P>When <I>Brown v. Board of Education</I> was handed down by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1954, 19 of the 20 largest school districts included minority populations but were predominantly white. </P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, if segregation is a concern to defenders of the public school status quo, is it true that in 1994, forty years later, student enrollments in all of the twenty-five largest school districts in the nation are predominantly minority?  Even within these largest districts, segregation exists because of population distribution.  Schools with nearly all-white enrollment and schools with nearly all African-American or all Hispanic within the same district are accepted as normal.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it commonly the case that nonpublic schools in large urban districts have a better racial or economic mix of students than the local public schools?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do some groups claiming to represent minority populations, such as the NAACP, oppose school choice, and even join lawsuits opposing parental choice for those they claim to represent when public opinion polls show that minority citizens now favor school choice by a larger margin than does the general public.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it possible for a poll in Philadelphia by Temple University earlier this year to find that 82% of African-American and Hispanics say they would use a voucher if it were worth $1500, and 90% would do so if it were $3,000, yet the Black Caucus in the Pennsylvania General Assembly opposes making this possible.  Who are they representing?  And for how long will this be possible?</P>
<P>1</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> does the public school establishment say it takes all students when most districts refuse to accept home-schooled students for classes and extracurricular events in which they wish to participate?  These students, after all, do live within the school district's boundaries.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do school districts argue that accepting home schoolers on a part-time basis will cost them money, when it costs them less than if home schooled students attend the school on a fulltime basis. (it may cost about one-twelfth as much to home-school a student, paid for by the parents, as it does to educate them in a public school).  Their parents are taxpayers who actually save the schools money.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, as another argument for treating home schoolers as aliens in the district, is their part-time participation opposed on the grounds of legal liability when, again, if the students decide to attend the district's schools on a regular basis, neither cost nor legalities are raised in an attempt to keep them from doing so.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do the public schools say they take all students when they only take those who live within their district? Many public school districts across the nation, especially in suburban areas, hire investigators to make sure that students from outside their district boundaries do not attend their schools. </P>
<P><B>WHY</B> isn't it recognized that it is the nonpublic schools that accept students without regard to their home address.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do the public schools emphasize that they take all students but rarely talk about how many they retain?  Across the nation 25-30% of public school students drop out - or are, in effect, pushed out, whereas nonpublic schools not only accept almost all of the students who apply but have a very high retention rate as well.  And this applies to nonpublic, and the new charter, schools that are specifically interested in problem students.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do defenders of the status quo charge that student and parental choice is sometimes determined on the basis of geography when the public schools are almost totally established on this basis, that is, students at assigned to each public school on the basis of some arbitrarily drawn attendance line, and those who live within this geographic area must attend that school and no other, not even another similar school in the same district.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do the public schools insist on treating each student as their personal property - they can't be allowed to &quot;escape,&quot; in the words of National Education Association President Keith Geiger - at the same time they complain that they don't have enough money to educate, or even house, the students they already have?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> isn't it recognized that if resources exceed responsibilities, whether in business and industry, personal finances, or schooling, there are essentially two options: 1. increase the resources, or 2. decrease the responsibilities.  With funding an ever-growing problem for the public schools, and no likelihood of &quot;adequate&quot; funding, which is rarely ever defined in specific terms, the public schools would be better able to function if they at least had the same amount of funds with fewer students - per-pupil funds would increase.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> aren't more high school students with the ability to do so permitted and encouraged to attend college prior to the usual graduation from high school?  Twenty years ago a Carnegie Commission on Higher Education report noted that there is so much duplication between the last two years of high school and the first two years of college that one or two of those years could be eliminated, at least for many students.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> don't more states follow the lead of Minnesota  which, for nearly a decade now, has had a law which permits state funds, currently in excess of $4,000 per year, to be applied toward college tuition for the years the student would otherwise have been in high school.  This is money that the state will be spending anyway, and it is more efficient and effective, and saves the student a year or more of schooling seat time, to support those students who can benefit from early admission.  In the decade of experience with this postsecondary enrollment option thousands of students have taken advantage of its provisions, as a group they have performed better in college</P>
<P>than those who graduated in the normal sequence, and within the first few years of the law's existence Minnesota high schools quadrupled the number of Advanced Placement courses they offered - college level courses presented in the high schools -in an obvious attempt to keep the students in their schools and keep the state funds flowing their way.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, in Pennsylvania has there been so little use of a regulation on the books for more than twenty years that permits a public school district to grant a regular high school diploma to any student who satisfactorily completes a year of college.  One district did so with a student who went to college after her sophomore year of high school.  Not only that, the district allowed her to wait two years and then participate in the graduation exercises with her class.</P>
<P>At a minimum, probably at least 15% of today's high school students could do the same, for at least one of the years they would otherwise be in high school.  As well as saving money directly, and permitting the students to move earlier into their career years, it might save further sums of money if enough students took advantage of it to alleviate the need for school expansion or construction.</P>
<P>In Pennsylvania, for example, with 100,000+ high school graduates annually, 15,000 or more students taking advantage of this option would save huge amounts of money, making some of those dollars available for other budgetary purposes.  Projected nationally that could be several hundred thousand students - if school districts were more flexible, reasonable, and less concerned with holding onto every student they can.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> isn't it recognized that hundreds of colleges and universities do not require a high school diploma for admission?  Thus, the above suggestion is not merely theoretical. It can be done right now by those districts who place the student first, rather than the system.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, if the teacher unions know what should be done to make schools more effective, don't they  fund a school and show us by example.  The California Teachers Association raised some $16 million last year to oppose a voucher initiative.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> don't they raise another $16 million and establish a school in south central Los Angeles, the WATTS area.  That could provide $16,000 per pupil for 2 500 pupil schools.  If that still isn't enough, they could have $32,000 per pupil for one school of 500.  No district in the nation, or college either, spends that kind of money.  With 400 pupils they could spend $40,000 each.  </P>
<P>In fact, they wouldn't even need a special assessment.  Myron Lieberman notes that the combined local, state and national income of both unions is probably in excess of $1 billion.  The NEA even has a national foundation that could fund a school if it didn't spend its funds in smaller grants.</P>
<P>Somewhere between $16,000-$40,000 surely should do it.  And even that is more than public funding can ever provide for 40+ million students.</P>
<P>But they won't do it.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>?  Because they really have no answers and by claiming that more money will solve public schooling's ills, without saying how much is enough, they always have the excuse that failure could be avoided if only there were more funds available.</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
