<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selected Writings by David W. Kirkpatrick 941030cc.htm</TITLE>
<LINK REL="ToC" HREF="httoc.htm">
<LINK REL="Next" HREF="941010cc.htm">
<LINK REL="Previous" HREF="941115cc.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#8000FF" BACKGROUND="yelgrain.gif">
<P><A HREF="941115cc.htm"><IMG SRC="grappage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Previous Page"></A>
<A HREF="httoc.htm"><IMG SRC="gratoc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="TOC"></A>
<A HREF="941010cc.htm"><IMG SRC="granpage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="../index.htm"><IMG SRC="grahome.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="See File"></A>
</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><!--<B>No Changes above</B>--><B>DOES GOVERNMENT FUNDING = GOVERNMENT CONTROL ?</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>Vol. 3, No. 25, October 30, 1994</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>One argument against public funding of school choice is the view that &quot;who pays the piper calls the tune.&quot;  This is sometimes even stated by some who would otherwise support choice.</P>
<P>Admittedly this is a possibility, as is the argument that all students might want to attend the same school.  A possibility, however, may be far different from reality, as higher education attendance attests.</P>
<P><B>$</B>ome are so anti-government, and so convinced that this would happen that there is no reasoning with them to the contrary.</P>
<P>As Al Smith used to say, &quot;Let's look at the record.&quot;</P>
<P>A commonly cited basis for this concern is <I>Grove City College v. Bell</I>, a 1984 U.S. Supreme Court decision which held that student assistance under the federal Basic Educational Opportunity Grants (BEOG) program subjected the college to the provisions of Title IX, barring sex discrimination by institutions receiving &quot;federal financial assistance.&quot;  </P>
<P>Perhaps the leading legal expert on this subject is Attorney William Bentley Ball, who has represented ten cases before the U.S. Supreme Court, including the June 1993 <I>Zobrest</I> decision.  He addressed this topic at the REACH Alliance conference in December, 1993, a summary of which appeared in the December 30, 1993 issue of <I>Choice Comments</I>.</P>
<P>For those who missed it, his basic point held that &quot;It is true that the Court held the BEOGs constitute such assistance to Grove City.  But it so held because Congress, in enacting the BEOG program, had expressly declared that a specific purpose of the BEOGs was in fact to 'provide assistance to <U>institutions</U> of higher education.' Further, the Court said that Congress had specifically intended Title IX requirements to be closely tied to the BEOG statute.&quot;</P>
<P>That is, the Court did not hold that government-funded student aid necessarily justifies government regulations, but that this particular form of aid was meant for institutions.</P>
<P>Thus, while <I>Grove City</I> is accepted by many as sufficient proof of the danger of government funding, the basis for that decision is ignored, as are the further facts that out of more than 3,000 schools in higher education, only two show such concern, and that higher education is much less regulated than are the public schools.</P>
<P>Pennsylvania owns 14 universities.  There is no constitutional or other restriction preventing it from doing anything it wishes with them - expanding them, merging them, abolishing them, or whatever.</P>
<P>Yet look at how they actually operate.</P>
<P>Their curriculum is not mandated.  </P>
<P>Their faculty need not be certified.</P>
<P>A 180-day school year is not law. </P>
<P>Or a five hour instructional day.  </P>
<P>Or any of the other endless mandates and restrictions on the public schools. </P>
<P>Ohio Governor George Voinovich said in his state-of-the-state message this year that Ohio's public school superintendents are responsible for filling out some 1200 forms and reports annually, a figure that probably has some applicability to public school superintendents in the rest of the nation.</P>
<P>Every state owns institutions of higher education.  If public funding means public regulation, why don't they establish mandates at this level similar to those in basic education?  </P>
<P>The answer can only be that it isn't necessary because higher education operates on the basis of choice.  There are some fourteen million fulltime college and university students, and millions more of part-timers, yet not one of them is assigned to the school they attend, or required to remain there.  Therefore, stifling government controls are not needed or used.</P>
<P>Would this not be true in basic education as well?  Is it not true for the millions of students who are in nonpublic schools or homeschooled?</P>
<P>Is it not true in other nations?  </P>
<P>Indeed it is.</P>
<P>The Organization for Economic  Cooperation and Development, the OECD, did a study of developed nations to determine the degree of local autonomy or flexibility possessed by the public schools.  All of the nations, except the U.S., have some form of school choice, yet the U.S. was ranked dead last on this basis.</P>
<P>Does this not at least suggest that lack of school choice results in excessive government regulation, and that its presence will reduce mandates?</P>
<P>After all, when a state such as Pennsylvania spends more than <B>$</B>14 billion on K-12 schooling, and the general public can't control it or escape from its clutches, must not the state try to establish controls of its own, even though they don't work?</P>
<P>Would it need to have all these mandates if parents could send their children to a school of their choice and thus be able to withdraw them from any school that was failing them?  Is this not the accountability that is sought but which at present does not exist?</P>
<P><B>$</B>ome who fear government controls say that the idea they can be avoided or minimized is naive.  They argue that we should have school choice but it can only come about when the present system is abolished, and there is complete separation of school and state (sometimes termed SOSAS), with absolutely no public funding at all.  </P>
<P>They visualize a system, if that's the word, whereby all of the fifty million school age youngsters in this nation attend a school of their choice with funding provided by parents, churches, and other altruistic sources.</P>
<P>Talk about being naive.</P>
<P>Let's look at that record.</P>
<P>Where in the world is there a nation in which the government has absolutely no involvement in the education of children?   </P>
<P>Where is there a society in which all of the money needed to educate the young comes from private sources?</P>
<P>Where is there a system in which, whatever the level of funding from public versus private sources, there is absolutely no government regulations, mandates or oversights? </P>
<P>What is the likelihood of that which exists nowhere in the world becoming a reality in this nation?</P>
<P>Even the 1925 <I>Pierce</I> decision, in which the U. S. Supreme Court said &quot;the child is not the creature of the state&quot;, and unanimously ruled that no child in this nation can constitutionally be compelled to attend a public school, said that the government could establish reasonable conditions under which education could be conducted. </P>
<P>Is it possible, or desirable, that the government or citizenry would permit anyone to do whatever they wish regarding their children's education?</P>
<P>If the thought that the education of fifty million children can be totally supported by individual resources and voluntary organizations has any validity, why don't those advocating it try to put it into practice?</P>
<P>After all, even under the present system there is no prohibition preventing totally private funding from being established.  If everyone with incomes sufficient to pay for their children's education is joined by churches, foundations, and whatever other sources that may be willing, decides to provide the money necessary to educate all children, including most especially the children of the poor and disadvantaged, they can start phasing in that program now.</P>
<P>As more and more children are so provided for, public school enrollments will drop, government funding at all levels will become less and less necessary, and eventually all taxes to support public education can be eliminated because there will no longer be any public school students.</P>
<P><B>$</B>pecifically suggesting it, and saying let it start now, rather than to propose it as some ideal world of the future, is to expose it for the dream it is.</P>
<P>It has never happened.  It is not happening now.  And it will not happen in the future.</P>
<P>In short, there is no way to fund the education of huge numbers of children without it being to a large degree a collective effort.  Total separation of school and state is a fantasy.</P>
<P>A greater separation than now exists is not.  That requires an objective judgment of what form of government funding will involve the least amount of government control.  That form is clearly individual student vouchers, or scholarships - a GI Bill for Kids - in which the producers are directly accountable to those they serve, the only accountability that will work.</P>
<P>Finally, those who do not wish to participate in a publicly funded school choice program need not do so.  But they should not use their view to prevent its creation because without it no one has that option.  And that's all it is - an option.  By its very definition school choice is voluntary.</P>
<P>Those who fear the government, like the public school establishment that opposes parental choice because they fear loss of control, can only succeed with a viable alternative.</P>
<P>Totally private funding is not it.   </P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
