<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selected Writings by David W. Kirkpatrick 941010cc.htm</TITLE>
<LINK REL="ToC" HREF="httoc.htm">
<LINK REL="Next" HREF="940830cc.htm">
<LINK REL="Previous" HREF="941030cc.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#8000FF" BACKGROUND="yelgrain.gif">
<P><A HREF="941030cc.htm"><IMG SRC="grappage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Previous Page"></A>
<A HREF="httoc.htm"><IMG SRC="gratoc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="TOC"></A>
<A HREF="940830cc.htm"><IMG SRC="granpage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Next Page"></A>
<A HREF="../index.htm"><IMG SRC="grahome.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="See File"></A>
</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>DO YOU EVER WONDER...</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 3, No. 23, October 10, 1994 </FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B><!--<B><I>Start below</I></B>-->
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P><B>WHY </B>the public school establish-ment, which claims to &quot;teach critical thinking and problem solving&quot;, is unable to think critically and solve its own problems?</P>
<P><B>WHY </B>are those who want to change the educational process known as conservatives while those defending the status quo claim to be reformers?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it claimed school choice will &quot;cream&quot; the best students when public magnet schools have been doing that  for years, and elite public schools, such as Central High in Philadelphia and Stuyvesant High in New York City have done so for generations?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it that significant reform is opposed with the claim that research is needed (aside from the question as to why these same sources so often also oppose research projects) when much of the present system not only lacks a research base but is in direct contradiction to research findings.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, for example, do we educate students by building a box called a school, inside of which are little boxes called classrooms, occupied by students in rows facing the front of the room, where an adult talks 75-80% of the time; that is, the adult talks three to four times as much as all of the students combined?  </P>
<P><B>WHY</B> does secondary schooling use arbitrary time blocks after each of which students move to another room for a separate subject of instruction?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it said that each student is &quot;taken from where he or she is to where they need to go&quot; when, in fact, they move in groups, from class to class or grade to grade, based essentially upon age with little regard to where each is or needs to go.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> are school districts so large?  Studies indicate a direct relation between a district's size and the cost per student; and an inverse relationship between district size and student achievement.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, in contradiction to many studies, are public schools built for thousands of students?  Schools for a few hundred, at most, are more effective at educating students and developing their potential.  For example, see Roger Barker and Paul Gump's book <I>Big School, Small </I><I>School</I>, published in 1964.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, when youngsters from violent and dysfunctional neighborhoods or families, who lack order and self-discipline in their lives, are in high schools of 2,000 or more students, with many from similar circum-stances, are we surprised that those schools are violent and dysfunctional?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, if large schools are economical and effective, are nonpublic schools smaller?  In Pennsylvania the average public school has about 600 students, with suggestions for further school consolidation, while the average nonpublic school has about 150. </P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it that rarely, if ever, is a consolidated school called for, or supported, by students, parents, the general public, or teachers?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, in short, if the research, the community, and most educators agree that small schools are better, do superintendents and school boards have an &quot;edifice complex?&quot; </P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is there an increasing trend, and continual efforts, to increase the state share of education funding when studies indicate that higher state funding is related to higher per pupil costs and lower student achievement?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it only in education that those who are public employees feel the need to attack and denigrate those who are privately employed?  Do doctors and nurses in public hospitals or departments of health regard those in private practice as enemies?  Do lawyers in district attorneys' offices or departments of justice regard lawyers in private practice as unqualified or unprofessional?  Do the police, who are public employees and unionized, oppose or try to restrict private security forces?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> are public school teachers referred to as professionals when they are told where, when, what, sometimes even how, to teach, with whom to teach, and otherwise treated like the public employees they are.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do so many public school teachers, who almost unanimously object to the above conditions, resist reforms, such as school choice, which would enable them to eliminate most of these restrictions and work directly on a mutually acceptable basis with their students, as do doctors with patients, lawyers with clients, and  other professionals?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, if the process is valid, is certification required for those who teach in the public schools but not for those who prepare those who teach in the public schools?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> does schooling require more certification credentials than any other profession - to teach at the elementary level, to teach at the secondary level, to be an elementary school principal, to be a secondary school principal, to be a superintendent, ad infinitum?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do so many educators complain about excessive government regulation (and they are right) but oppose any attempts to enact meaningful deregulation of the system?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do so many businessmen, who say they believe in free enterprise, competition, and minimal government interference, support a monopolistic school system in which individual enterprise is a no-no, competition is nonexistent, and government interference is virtually absolute?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> should school administrators be former teachers?  Are court administrators lawyers?  Are hospital administrators doctors?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it assumed that an adminis-trator who was once a teacher is qualified to evaluate all teachers regardless of specialty?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B>, when a disadvantaged student from a lower socioeconomic status doesn't do well, is the student blamed; but when those from advantaged back-grounds do well the school claims the credit?   The school may even be viewed as a good school rather than one with good students.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> would anyone be proud of the fact that they compel students to attend an unsafe school?  The National Education Association is.  </P>
<P><B>WHY</B> did NEA TODAY, Sept. 1994, page 6, boast that the &quot;NEA and its allies succeeded in defeating two negative amendments to the Elementary and Secondary Education Act (ESEA).  By close votes, the Senate defeated an amendment that would have provided federal funds for private school tuition vouchers to students in schools deemed unsafe...&quot;  </P>
<P><B>WHY</B> have they no shame?  Are they so afraid of vouchers that danger to students is of no concern?  In case of doubt, the item's headline is, &quot;Best Win For Education Employees.&quot;</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> isn't NEA President Keith Geiger, quoted in <B>USA TODAY</B>, October 20, 1993, as saying that inner-city schools &quot;are absolutely terrible--they ought to be blown up,&quot;  willing to let the students leave first?</P>
<P> </P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do so many educators bemoan parental apathy when parental involvement is often welcomed only on the school's terms.  Join the PTA, the Booster Club, help raise money, or help spread the word about our good school but don't think parental involvement means you can have your child assigned to another school, or another teacher, or otherwise have any choice over your child's school environment.  Apathetic parents may have much to be apathetic about.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> does the U.S. Secretary of Education advocate &quot;parental involvement&quot; when he says he is totally opposed to parental choice, which would give them power.  </P>
<P>Involvement - power = manipulation.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do both opponents and propo-nents of school choice argue over how good or bad the &quot;system&quot; is when that is essentially irrelevant?  Even the strongest defender of the status quo will admit that not all public school students succeed, and even the most adamant &quot;school basher&quot; will have to concede that some public school students do very well.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> should the argument for school choice rest on how many public schools succeed or fail?  With 15,000 school districts, millions of staff and 42,000,000 students, almost anything that can be said is true someplace.</P>
<P>Even if only 10% fail - and no one argues the figure is that low, - that's more than 4,000,000 students.  It is no satisfaction to them, or anyone else, if others succeed.  Similarly, the number that don't succeed is irrelevant for those who do.</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> does the American Civil Liberties Union oppose school choice, when a unanimous U.S. Supreme Court said in 1925 it is a civil liberty?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> don't we talk about students, which is what school choice is all about.  As the U.S. Supreme Court said in 1925, &quot;the child is not the creature of the state.&quot;</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> do those claiming full school choice is unconstitutional object to such laws being passed and tested in the courts?  Don't they believe what they say?</P>
<P><B>WHY</B> is it that when the establishment tries something different, such as Outcome-Based-Education (OBE) they say it will take years to evaluate, but when they object to a reform, such as school choice in Milwaukee or privatization in Baltimore they attack it if it doesn't show immediate gains?</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
