</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>THERE ARE FEWER FINGERS IN THE DIKE</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 3, No. 19, August 30, 1994</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B><!--<B><I>Start below</I></B>-->
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>1</P>
<P>Recently the Senate of Pennsylvania created a Select Committee to Study the Structure and Financing of Public Education in the Commonwealth.  The committee held four hearings across the state from August 9-12.</P>
<P>The main impetus behind the resolution was teacher strikes and the suggestion for a statewide teacher contract.  By far, most of those who testified opposed a statewide contract.  There was also concern over state and federal mandates.</P>
<P>But many went well beyond these points, with some imagining the unimaginable and questioning the existence of the present system.</P>
<P>At each hearing several persons, including school board members, called for, or predicted, school choice.</P>
<P>Thus the title above.</P>
<P>Here are some edited comments:</P>
<P>&quot;The problem is whether or not public education will continue as we have known it or will be replaced by a system described by some as school choice. This may sound dramatic but I assure you that public education as an institution is not in good shape to meet the challenges of the future.  Indeed, some consider it to be in a terminal state before its death is recognized.&quot; <I>- Dr. Norman F. Ness, Vice </I><I>President, Concerned Citizens-Kennett Consolidated School District, Kennett Square.</I></P>
<P>&quot;It is my personal opinion that the best means of reforming our schools is to make the schools responsive to parents by introducing school choice. Wealthy individuals have school choice now, either by living in a good school district or by having the resources to send their children to independent schools.&quot; <I>- Jeff Hellrung, President, Chester County Tax Action Group</I>.</P>
<P>&quot;It should be made easier to experiment, not more difficult.  We should stop gasping in horror every time someone mentions merit pay, or vouchers, or school choice.  All of these things deserve serious scrutiny.  The current system doesn't work.&quot; <I>- Eugene W. Hickok, Carlisle </I><I>School Board member, and college professor</I>.</P>
<P>2</P>
<P>If a statewide contract is introduced: &quot;the long-term effect will be further deterioration of the quality of public education as more disgruntled parents look to school vouchers, charters or other solutions to their educational problems.&quot; - <I>Dr. Earl Barnhart, Carlisle School Board </I><I>Member</I>.</P>
<P>&quot;I would suggest looking at proposals which will strengthen local and parental control such as school choice.&quot; <I>- John C. O'Neal, Member, </I><I>Montoursville Area School Board</I>.</P>
<P>&quot;I believe that every child is part of the public and is entitled to equal funding for educational purposes.  Public and private schools, nonpublic schools, and home schooling comprise the total educational package in Pennsylvania.  Where a child receives the education is entirely up to the parents.  You should provide equity in funding education regardless of where the education takes place.  Provide a minimum of $4,777 for each student in the state.  This money would go to the school district or the school facility or the parents who provide the education.&quot; <I>- Robert E. Roush, Jr., Member, Big Spring School Board</I>.</P>
<P> (The California Supreme Court said it would accept vouchers as an equitable means of funding, <I>Serrano v. Priest, Dec. 30, 1976, - Serrano II- </I><I>Editor)</I>.</P>
<P>&quot;It is almost a year to the day that I became involved with the convoluted practices in public education.  Time, and information have radically revised my ideas about public education.  It is too expensive to save and not worth the effort.  The answer to every problem in public education can be addressed more intelligently if the General Assembly has the courage and foresight to vote into law schools of choice.  Just as there is separation of church and state, there should be separation of state and education.  Government should not be educating or dictating what our children are taught.  Free enterprise would allow the State to get out of the school business, provide the taxpayers financial relief, allow parents a choice, and give children excellent and individualized educations.&quot; <I>- Carolyn J. Rapaport, Co-Chairman, </I><I>Pennsylvania Taxpayers for Quality Education. </I></P>
<P>(For more on this concept, see Stephen Arons, <I>Compelling Belief</I>, NY: McGraw-Hill Book Co., 1983. - Editor).</P>
<P> ~~~~~</P>
