<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>SCHOOL CHOICE IS SUPPORTED BY 90%</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 3, No. 16, July 30, 1994 </FONT></CENTER></H3>
<P>By David W. Kirkpatrick</P>
<P><!--Start below--></P>
<P><B><I>PHILADELPHIA</I></B></P>
<P>According to a Temple University survey directed by Prof. Paul Seidenstat 90% of African-American and Hispanic parents support full school choice.  Similar conclusions have been drawn by other polls for some time, although with smaller percentages.  This raises the question as to how long those who claim to represent minority citizens can continue to maintain that fiction while strongly opposing school choice.</P>
<P>The Temple survey reported general backing as well, by margins proportional to the amount of the voucher/scholarship.  With a $1,500 grant, 72% of the parents said they would elect a transfer; 80% would do so if the grant were raised to $3,000.</P>
<P>Given the growing financial as well as educational crisis in the Philadelphia school district - the deficit may exceed $400 million within three or four years - and this overwhelming support of school choice in the city, its implementation there is inevitable, and sooner than many may imagine.</P>
<P><B><I> </I></B><B><I>VERMONT</I></B></P>
<P>2</P>
<P>has permitted school choice from the beginning of the public school movement in the 19th century.  Local communities may operate secondary schools or pay tuition for students to attend a public or private school of their choice, with no geographic restrictions.  Students go to schools in several other states and Canada; at least one recently went to a school in Paris, France, the tuition paid by the local government back home.  </P>
<P>About one-third of Vermont's towns have no public secondary school, so 25% of these students exercise choice, three-quarters of whom attend other public schools.  Just as parents elsewhere move into a community so their children can attend the local school, some in Vermont move where there is no secondary school so their children can exercise choice.</P>
<P>In 1961 the Vermont Supreme Court ruled that religious schools could not be included in the choice program a decision that reportedly was not implemented.  It is now moot because the Court has unanimously reversed itself, rejecting a First Amendment challenge to the state's payment of tuition in religiously affiliated schools, saying &quot;jurisprudence has evolved greatly since 1961.&quot;</P>
<P><B><I> </I></B><B><I>NEW YORK</I></B></P>
<P>The U.S. Supreme Court surprised perhaps no one but the defendants with its June ruling that the Kiryas Joel Village School District, whose boundaries contain only students of the Satmar Hasidim religion, is unconstitutional.  Even so, the decision was not unanimous and five justices indicated that the Court's 1985 <I>Aguilar</I> decision should be reconsidered.  At that time the Court prohibited public remedial education teachers from providing services on the premises of religiously affiliated schools.  It appears that a majority of the present Court might hold such religiously neutral assistance to students to be constitutional.</P>
<P>3</P>
<P><B><I> </I></B><B><I>NEW YORK </I></B><B><I>CITY</I></B></P>
<P>The Manhattan Institute's Center for Educational Innovation has chosen Community School Districts 5 and 7 as the first two New York City school districts in the Gilder Initiative for School Choice Throughout New York City.  With a one million dollar challenge grant from Institute Trustee Richard Gilder, the Initiative provides seed money and expert support to create theme-based alternative schools, help restructure failing schools and implement district-wide school choice.</P>
<P>The Center participates in demonstra-tion programs in Manhattan, the Bronx, and Brooklyn, in addition to Baltimore, Philadelphia and East Orange, New Jersey.  Recently it has been asked to join restructuring projects in Buffalo, Atlanta and Newark.  The Center's personnel include several former New York City district level superintendents, including Seymour Fliegel (East Harlem District 4, noted for its successful school choice program).</P>
<P>Further information can be obtained from John Elwell, Director, Center for Educational Innovation, 52 Vanderbilt Avenue, New York, NY 10017 - Telephone (212) 599-7000, FAX (212) 599-3494.</P>
<P>4</P>
<P><B><I> </I></B><B><I>CALIFORNIA</I></B></P>
<P>Parents for Educational Choice has been succeeded by the Coalition Advocating Reform in Education (CARE), which has set the March 1996 Presidential primary as their target date for a second statewide initiative on school choice.</P>
<P>Much has been made of the defeat of the first initiative last fall although many predicted this in advance.  In addition to the political strength and financial resources of the opponents, there are those who feel success is more likely through legislation, which, unlike initiatives, can be amended.  California's Proposition 13 in 1978, which capped property taxes, was Howard Jarvis' fourth try.</P>
<P>A properly drafted school choice initiative will ultimately triumph as well, and it won't take four attempts.</P>
<P>In an attempt to avoid full school choice, much of the public school establishment in California now favors public school choice such as is being implemented in Los Angeles.  So much for the claim that competition will not lead to school reform.</P>
<P>Their support of public school choice may speed the establishment of full school choice, once awareness develops of the changes which result from even this limited step.  The campaigning for students by individual public schools in Los Angeles is attracting national attention, and will make it difficult to continue the claim that parents aren't interested in, or capable of, deciding where their children should go to school.</P>
<P>CARE's address: 645 14th Ave. San Francisco, CA 94118; Tel. (415) 752-7333; FAX (415) 752-5851. Rabbi Pinchas Lipner, Chairman.</P>
<P><B><I> </I></B><B><I>MINNESOTA</I></B></P>
<P>Various &quot;second chance&quot; options are available.  Generally, eligible students are at least one year behind grade level; two years behind in performance; pregnant or a parent; chemically dependent; or absent from school for three weeks straight.  </P>
<P>The need is demonstrated by the fact that about 28,000 students participate each year.  This in a state that already leads the nation in the percentage of students who graduate from high school, over 91%.</P>
<P>5</P>
<P>A school choice proposal in Connecticut failed by a 71-71 vote at the end the legislative session earlier this year.  Supporters are confident that support has continued to grow and that they now have the votes necessary to pass an enabling act when the legislature next convenes.</P>
<P>According to a recent statewide poll, 62% of New Jersey's citizens favor the introduction of full school choice, 69% in Jersey City where Mayor Bret Schundler is seeking to introduce this option.  Backed by Governor Christie Whitman, leaders in the State House and Senate, and others, the Mayor's proposal, &quot;The Jersey City 'Schoolchildren First' Education Act,&quot; is expected to receive major legislative attention this fall.</P>
<P>As with any full school choice program, the Mayor's proposal would not just empower students and their parents but educators as well.  Teachers and administrators will be eligible to receive waivers from the State Commissioner of Education enabling them to create a wide variety of programs tailor made to children's different needs.  This will include the ability of parents and teachers to establish charter schools, public schools largely free from the usual bureaucratic interference.  Speaking of</P>
<P><B><I> </I></B><B><I>CHARTER SCHOOLS</I></B></P>
<P>there are claims that, like school choice in general, they will &quot;cream&quot; the better students.  Experience is disproving this smokescreen.  Five of fifteen charter schools scheduled to open next year in Massachusetts, will serve disadvantaged and at-risk students, as will three of nine approved charters in Colorado and a majority of the 50+ in California.</P>
<P><B><I> </I></B><B><I>PRIVATE </I></B><B><I>PROGRAMS</I></B></P>
<P>About 7,000 disadvantaged children now receive grants to attend 500 schools in more than a dozen states.  Typically, these programs provide half-tuition, parents the rest, proving that even parents with limited financial resources will make extraordinary efforts to help their kids. </P>
<P> ~ ~ ~ ~ ~</P>
