<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>SCHOOL CHOICE: WHAT RESEARCH REVEALS</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 3, No. 13, June 30, 1994</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>Some time ago this newsletter reviewed what research had to say about school choice, especially work by Professor Mary Anne Raywid of Hofstra University. This is an update.</P>
<P>Opponents of school choice like to say there is no adequate research on its effects, while they claim the results will be negative.  Aside from asking how they know its impact when they are unaware of the research, they are wrong on both counts. </P>
<P>Professor Raywid, as long ago as 1982, had studied some 1200 choice programs.  Ironically, in her report published that year she thanked the National Education Association (NEA) for its cooperation in allowing its research staff to do computer runs and otherwise assist her in tabulating the results of her study.</P>
<P>Raywid has continued her research since then, and in a more recent publication by the Manhattan Institute, she still concludes that study after study favors the practice of students choosing the school they will attend; that choice has a positive effect on student achievement; that, of the main restructuring strategies, school-based management and choice, &quot;choice wins, hands down&quot;; and that it generates teacher leadership.</P>
<P>Contrary to claims that choice will lead to increased segregation, Raywid says it promotes integration better than do mandatory assignment plans.</P>
<P>As for the charge that students won't make good choices, undoubtedly true in some cases, Raywid finds &quot;no reason to assume that a poorly chosen school could be any more injurious to a particular youngster than many assigned schools are now--and in a choice system, unlike an assignment system, the student caught in such circumstances has the advantage of being able to transfer.&quot;</P>
<P>An unusual finding is that school choice reduces the number of special education students.  There are &quot;large numbers of cases where kids who have appeared to be slow, learning disabled, or emotionally troubled are simply transformed in a different school environment, and the special services are no longer needed.&quot;</P>
<P>She thinks that schools of choice improve because teachers are able to be creative, develop programs they believe in, and thus work better with kids.  These &quot;more positive circum-stances evoke greater commitment, greater effort, and greater efficacy.&quot;</P>
<P>In this win-win situation where teachers can develop their own school, and students are more likely to be where they can succeed, teachers, students, and parents all experience higher satisfaction rates.</P>
<P>One reason for this is that schools of choice are often much smaller than public schools designed by those who neither teach nor study in them.  As &quot;schools-within-schools or schools with limited enrollments--it is a smaller, cozier environment and the staff are more likely to know one another.  Moreover, they are far more likely to work fairly closely with one another than in a traditional school.&quot;</P>
<P>The average nonpublic school in Pennsylvania has about 160 students, compared to more than 400 for the average public school - and the public average would be even higher if rural schools, many of which are necessarily small, were factored out.  That is not a minor item in Pennsylvania, which has the largest rural population of any state in the nation.</P>
<P>Nationally, the average nonpublic school has about 200 students, and the average public school about 500, a figure also distorted because of millions of rural students.</P>
<P>Given the hundreds of studies that find problems with the present public school structure, operation and results, Raywid thinks the demand for schools to improve is legitimate, but the demand for better schools must be accompanied by alternatives on how to do it.  Of those alternatives, she says becoming &quot;a school of choice...is the best way in my judgment.&quot;</P>
<P>Time has borne out her view two years ago that the choice movement was just beginning since the public demand for educational progress and meaningful accountability seems to be here to stay, and a large majority favor it.  She believes that choice &quot;is one of the most non-invasive forms of accountability we'll find, and one of the least injurious to education.&quot;</P>
<P>She favors choice because: &quot;First...I think choice is the best route we know to school improvement, the best lever or catalyst we have for reform.  Second, I think parents have a right to more say in their children's education than traditional schools allow them.  Choice seems to me the most appropriate way to empower them.&quot;</P>
<P>Although perhaps the one who has most thoroughly studied choice for the longest period of time, Raywid is not the only researcher in the field noting positive results.</P>
<P>John F. Witte of the Robert M. Lafollette Institute of Public Affairs is studying Milwaukee's state mandated voucher program.  Contrary to another claim of opponents, Witte, like Raywid, finds that &quot;rather than skimming off the best students, this program seems to provide an alternative educational environment for students who are not doing particularly well in the public school system.&quot;</P>
<P>Since that time Witte has publicly stated that, in looking at Milwaukee's 97,000 students as a group, at the 60,000-some students who are eligible for the Rep. Polly Williams sponsored program, and the fewer than 1,000 who can actually take part, the first year the participants were the poorest of the three categories and, in the second year, they were poorer still.</P>
<P>In short, there has been no &quot;creaming,&quot; the students given a chance for a meaningful alternative were exactly those intended.</P>
<P>This should make sense to those who are not fearful, or determined to use scare tactics to oppose choice.  Better students, by definition, are those who are the ones most successful in a given school.  They would therefore seem to be the ones least likely to make a change.  It is precisely those who are doing least well, or who are most unhappy, that will want a different educational environment, and who should be permitted to choose one.</P>
<P>Another researcher, Prof. Robert L. Crain of Columbia University Teachers College, has issued a report on school choice in which he said, &quot;Among the big cities, this is the most egalitarian program I know and probably the most exciting...&quot;</P>
<P>He reported that students in New York choice schools increased their reading skills nearly twice as fast, on the average, as children attending neighborhood schools and they earned 25% more credits toward graduation.</P>
<P>These results reinforce research elsewhere which show that pupils do better and parents participate more in schools they choose.  Furthermore, teachers are prouder and perform better in schools of choice.</P>
<P>John A. Murphy, for seven years superintendent of Prince George's County public schools in Maryland, a largely minority system, and now heading the Charlotte-Mecklenburg schools in North Carolina, has said he found &quot;a choice system brings much more harmony between the home and school.  Rather than forced busing for integration, which antagonizes many people, there is voluntary busing to get to a school of choice.&quot;</P>
<P>Other supporters include Arizona Governor Fife Symington who said, &quot;I just can't believe in modern-day America...anybody would deny a parent the right to choose a school that's best for their child.&quot;</P>
<P>Since the earlier newsletter, the first charter schools in the nation have begun operation, beginning with Minnesota.  Time after time, contrary to the &quot;creaming&quot; charge, these schools are small and geared to students with problems who are most in need for working options.</P>
<P>Privately funded choice programs are appearing across the nation, beginning a few years ago in Indianapolis and now in operation is such cities as San Antonio, Atlanta, Detroit and Milwaukee (Where parent Valerie Barrett lives.  She has told two REACH conferences what a difference school choice has made in the lives of herself and her two children).</P>
<P>Despite the usual glitches with new and growing efforts, school choice programs work, are saving children, and serve as encouragement for others toiling to achieve them in their own communities or state.  </P>
<P>School choice is spreading; its success has been clearly demonstrated; it has a long history in the developed democratic nations around the world; it has been introduced and is being expanded in former Iron Curtain nations; and the opponents have no workable alternatives or even arguments other than, as Ted Kolderie has noted,  &quot;saying what if, what if, spreading fear and doubt.&quot;</P>
<P> ~ ~ ~</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
