<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>SCHOOL CHOICE, PUBLIC SCHOOL &quot;BASHING&quot;, AND &quot;THE FAR RIGHT&quot;</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 3, No. 12, June 20, 1994 </FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B><!--<B><I>Start below</I></B>--><B><I> </I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<H5>
<FONT SIZE=3><B><I>SCHOOL BASHING</I></B></FONT></H5>
<P>Many in the public school establishment, especially those speaking for the two teacher unions, repeatedly make two accusations against school choice advocates.</P>
<P>The first is that we indulge in &quot;bashing&quot; the public schools.  That charge, in itself, is a form of &quot;bashing&quot; - a resort to name-calling rather than dealing with the real issue.</P>
<P>Are we critical of much that occurs in government schools?  You bet.  And some of us have spent enough time as staff members to know whereof we speak.  But we have also said that a system with 15,000 districts, 85,000 schools, millions of staff members, and some 45,000,000 students is so varied that almost anything you say is true somewhere.</P>
<P>No one seriously claims that good things don't occur in public schools.  To the contrary, we have repeatedly said that with full school choice most students will stay where they are.  It is the defenders of the status quo who fear there will be a flight from the public schools if students can do so.</P>
<P>When we are critical, the criticism is based on facts, facts usually drawn from the government, research studies and surveys, and media reports.</P>
<P>Probably the best known critique is the 1983 report <I>A Nation at Risk</I>, the federal study by a commission representing the establishment.</P>
<P>How many times have you heard it said that public schools are engulfed by &quot;a rising tide of mediocrity,&quot; and that, if another nation did to us and our children what we are doing to ourselves we would consider it an act of war?  If that is &quot;bashing,&quot; blame the federal report.</P>
<P>Since 1983 this nation has spent over $2,000,000,000,000 (that's two <B>trillion</B> dollars) on the public schools, has increased per pupil spending 30% in constant dollars, and has tried to reform the system.  All of the students who were there in 1983, except for some in kindergarten and first grade, have since graduated or dropped out.</P>
<P>What has been gained from all that time, money and effort? </P>
<P>Not much, according to the latest federal statement, the<B> GOALS 2000: EDUCATE AMERICA ACT</B>.</P>
<P>In it, &quot;Congress finds as follows:&quot;</P>
<P>Page 91, &quot;(1) A majority of public schools in the United States are failing to prepare students to achieve the National Education Goals...&quot;</P>
<P>Page 112, &quot;(A) The current achieve-ment levels of students in the United States are far below those that might indicate competency in challenging subject matter in core content areas.&quot; </P>
<P>Page 115, &quot;(A) The rate of decline in our urban schools is escalating at a rapid pace.  Student performance in most inner city schools grows worse each year.  At least half of all students entering ninth grade fail to graduate 4 years later and many more students from high-poverty backgrounds leave school with skills that are inadequate for today's workplace.  Student performance in many inner city neigh-borhoods grows worse each year... (D) An educational emergency exists in those urban and rural areas where there are large concentrations of children who live in poverty.&quot;</P>
<P>The rate of decline is escalating; student performance grows worse; an educational emergency exists.  Defenders of the status quo need to tell the Congress to stop &quot;bashing&quot; the public school system. </P>
<P>If that isn't severe enough, how about the comment that inner city schools &quot;are absolutely terrible--they ought to be blown up.&quot;  That was said not by the government but by Keith Geiger, President, National Education Assoc-iation, <B>USA TODAY</B>, Oct. 20, 1993.  </P>
<P>Or, in the 1990s, &quot;we're going to be digging even deeper, and the teachers are going to be even dumber.&quot;  Albert Shanker, President, the American Federation of Teachers, <B>NEW YORK TIMES</B>, Nov. 5, 1989.</P>
<P>Neither are noted advocates of school choice for all students.</P>
<H5>
<FONT SIZE=3><B><I>THE FAR RIGHT</I></B></FONT></H5>
<P>The other commonly levelled charge is that school choice is a scheme promoted by the far right, a term that is not defined, referring to groups and individuals generally not named.</P>
<P>1</P>
<P>In February, NEA's Keith Geiger referred to Americans for School Choice as a &quot;hard-core, well-organized elite of right-wing political activists.&quot; Yet the ASC board is a distinguished group which includes many governors.</P>
<P>Historically, reference to the political left and right goes back to the French Revolution when radicals and revolu-tionaries sat on the left in the legisla-ture and their opponents, including monarchists, sat on the right.</P>
<P>With few revolutionaries and fewer monarchists today, the political spectrum is often said to range from communists on the left to fascists on the right.  Some argue it is a circle not a line since both fascism and communism lead to dictatorships.</P>
<P>In any event, the far left can be ignored in this context since no one claims they favor school choice.</P>
<P>As for the far right, in this country that usually refers to such as the American Nazi Party, the Skinheads, or even the Ku Klux Klan.  The Klan which opposes Blacks, Catholics, and Jews, was the inspiration of the Oregon initiative in the early 1920s which directed that all students in that state had to attend public schools.  So the &quot;far right,&quot; like the far left, is not inclined to favor individual choice.</P>
<P>Like &quot;bashing,&quot; &quot;far right,&quot; is a smokescreen, an appeal to emotion that avoids dealing with the right of parents to send their children to schools they choose, which was unanimously affirmed by the (far right?) U.S. Supreme Court in 1925 when it voided the Oregon law.  </P>
<P>Beyond this, however, it might be helpful to note some of the advocates of school choice, and consider how far to the right they might be.</P>
<P>Since REACH is a Pennsylvania organization we'll start with the 28 (of 50) state senators who passed school choice legislation in the previous session, and 89 in the House.</P>
<P>Or REACH Board member Ed Donley, who, in 1993, received the most prestigious award of the Pennsylvania State Education Association, recognizing his contributions to public education.</P>
<P>Consider Wisconsin Democratic Representative &quot;Polly&quot; Williams, sponsor of that state's Milwaukee choice program and Wisconsin chairman of Jesse Jackson's campaigns for president.</P>
<P>Governors include William Weld of Massachusetts; Wisconsin's Tommy Thompson, John Engler of Michigan, Christie Whitman of New Jersey, George Allen of Virginia, Fife Symington of Arizona, and Pete Wilson of California.</P>
<P>In 1976, the California Supreme Court, in <I>Serrano II</I>, said the inequitable funding of California's public education system could be resolved with tuition vouchers.</P>
<P>Polly Broussard, a 20-year public school teacher in Louisiana, is an Americans for School Choice board member, that right-wing elite.</P>
<P>Other public educators include John Taylor Gatto, New York City's public school Teacher of the Year three successive years, and New York State Teacher of the Year in 1991; Kevin Irvine, Colorado's Teacher of the Year in 1991; and Linda Cross, a Wisconsin teacher who was nearly elected Superintendent of Public Instruction.</P>
<P>2</P>
<P>To this list may be added former U.S. Secretary of Education Lamar Alexander, a former Governor of Tennessee and former President of the University of Tennessee; and U.S. Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, who more than twenty years ago introduced a &quot;Baby GI Bill&quot; proposal in Congress to enable more youngsters to choose their school.</P>
<P>Even a majority of public school teachers, in a poll reported in <B>USA TODAY</B> in August of 1990, agreed schools would be better if parents chose those their children attend.  </P>
<P>Are they what is meant by right wing?</P>
<P>3</P>
<P>Finally, to show how things can be distorted, a flyer on the &quot;New Right&quot;, recently distributed in Pennsylvania, had four interesting quotes. They are:</P>
<P>&quot;It is only the ignorant who despise education.&quot; <I>Publius Syrrus</I>, 42 B.C.</P>
<P>Schooling has its critics but who despises education?  We aren't told.</P>
<P>&quot;It is impossible for ideas to compete in the market place if no forum for their presentation is provided or available.&quot; <I>Thomas Mann</I>.  Does the establishment provide such a forum?</P>
<P>&quot;To educate is to open minds to many points of view and many thoughts.  To indoctrinate is to close minds to all but one thought and one point of view.&quot; <I>Stephen Robinson</I>.  Supporters of school choice don't stifle dissent.</P>
<P>Finally, &quot;I fear more from everyone thinking alike than from some people thinking otherwise.&quot; <I>Charles G. Bolte</I>.</P>
<P>So do we friends, so do we.</P>
<P>All four quotes represent beliefs exactly opposite of those demonstrated by the flyer containing them.  This would be humorous if the shallowness of thought it exposes weren't so sad.</P>
<P> ~~~~~</P>
