<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>SCHOOL CHOICE:  A Q &amp; A Primer</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 2, No. 15, August 15, 1993</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>By David W. Kirkpatrick</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<P>Q.  What is school choice? </P>
<P>A.  School choice permits everyone to exercise their constitutional right to select the school their child(ren) attend.  This right existed unchallenged until the 1920s, when a unanimous U.S. Supreme Court, saying &quot;the child is not the creature of the state,&quot; ruled that no child can be legally compelled to attend government schools.</P>
<P>It is also about educational achievement so that a child who, for whatever reason, is not performing satisfactorily, or who is unhappy, in one educational setting can select another where he or she might be successful.</P>
<P>It is not about &quot;bailing out the Catholic (or any other) schools,&quot; since they, like all schools, would have to compete to attract and hold students.  </P>
<P>Where school choice has been introduced it has not been uncommon for government school enrollment to go up (particularly where drop-outs are permitted to return) and even for nonpublic enrollments to go down where the government schools improve and offer a satisfactory education.</P>
<P>Q.  Is it constitutional?</P>
<P>A.  An expert on constitutional law, Harvard Law School Professor Laurence H. Tribe, said in the June 12, 1991 <I>New York Times</I> that &quot;Any objection that anyone would have to a voucher program would have to be policy-based and could not rest on legal doctrine.  One would have to be awfully clumsy to write voucher legislation that could not pass constitutional scrutiny...aid to parents...would be constitutional.&quot;</P>
<P>Q.  What are the major differences between &quot;governmental school choice&quot; and &quot;non-governmental school choice?&quot; Is one better than the other? </P>
<P>A.  Full school choice is better because it would offer more choices in the number and types of schools.  Choice restricted to government schools only, all of which operate under the same basic rules and restrictions, would offer only officially approved options.  </P>
<P>That would be analogous to the perhaps apocryphal story that Henry Ford once said you could have a Ford in any color you wanted, as long as it was black.</P>
<P>Q.  Why is it important that school choice legislation pass?</P>
<P>A.  Government schools have become increasingly expensive without corresponding results.  It is estimated that over 700,000 students drop out annually.  That's more than 4,000 each school day.  Another 700,000 or more graduate who are not functionally literate.</P>
<P>Many districts, especially urban districts such as Philadelphia, Los Angeles and Chicago, face severe financial problems. There isn't the money available that they believe they need to survive so we must try alternatives.</P>
<P>Prof. Mary Anne Raywid of Hofstra University, has studied school choice for years. In the Dec. 1990/Jan. 1991 issue of <I>Educational </I><I>Leadership</I>, She said, &quot;I have been an advocate of choice, as well as a scholar and chronicler of its development, since the early 1970s...three (reasons) underlie my own view...a conviction that public education's future is in real doubt and that schools may not survive; a conviction that all schools, not just the weakest, need present and continuing revitalization; the belief that in public schools, as in other public institutions, power has tended to gravitate to bureaucracies in ways inconsistent with our democratic commitment.&quot;</P>
<P>Q.  Won't school choice cost more money?</P>
<P>A.  It could well cost less.</P>
<P>For example, the Philadelphia School District budget for the coming year, despite severe slashes including eliminating about 1000 staff positions, includes $100 million for capital costs, mostly for site acquisitions.  This is because enrollment in the district is increasing by 5-6,000 students per year.  After the $100 million is spent, hundreds of millions more will be necessary to construct the new schools, and then still further hundreds of millions to staff and operate them.</P>
<P>Would it not be much less expensive to provide students with scholarships and permit them to go elsewhere?</P>
<P>Even a $5,000 scholarship is less than the district currently spends per student and it would make a massive building program unnecessary.  There are more than 200 private schools in Philadelphia, virtually none of which spend $5,000 per pupil.  Most tuition costs are in the $600-3,000 range.  (The school choice legislation before the General Assembly only calls for scholarships up to $700 at the elementary level and $1,000 for high school students.)</P>
<P> </P>
<P>Q.  How will the state pay for school choice?  Or, to state it another way, as some opponents charge, won't this mean a tax increase, or a diversion of funds away from government schools?</P>
<P>A.  The funding can come from the normal increase in state revenues that occur each year.  The Pennsylvania 1993-94 state budget is some $800 million higher than the budget for the 1992-23 fiscal year, yet it did not require a tax increase.</P>
<P>State revenues grow about 5% each year; more in good economic years.  It can reasonably be expected that there will be a further $800 million or more available when next year's budget is adopted.  If this bill passes, it will require less than $80 million each year, or just 10% of the increase, for each of the first three years, after which increases will be significantly reduced, or stabilize. </P>
<P>Therefore, clearly no tax increase is necessary, nor would funds have to be diverted from the government schools.  </P>
<P>It would, of course, involve a determination of the state's funding priorities, but every budget, personal or public, is a statement of priorities.  This is a necessity facing the state every year, since requests for new or increased funding always exceed the amount of money available.</P>
<P>Q.  What effect will the passage of school choice legislation have on public education?  On private education?  On education of our children in general?</P>
<P>A.  We believe it will make possible improvements in all three categories.  And not just because of competition, which is only one factor.  If schools are directly responsible to students and parents, as in higher education, even in state-owned institutions, there will be less need for government officials to continually pass mandates in an effort to make them better, an effort that has obviously failed.</P>
<P>All higher education students are in a school of choice.  Half of them graduate from a college other than the one at which they started.  And, while higher education is not without its problems, it is generally agreed that it functions better than K-12 government schools.</P>
<P>Q.  Competition is given as a major reason for the passage of school choice.  If non-government schools can practice selective admission/retention, while government schools must accept and educate learning disabled and other special needs students, there seems to be a lack of equity.  To be fair, the same demands should be made of the parties competing, which does not seem to be the case.  How do you respond to that?</P>
<P>A.  First, the choice legislation before the Pennsylvania General Assembly would not permit arbitrary discrimination.  A school, public or private - and this legislation does call for public school choice, where five or every six students in Pennsylvania are - would not have to participate.</P>
<P>If, however, it does participate, it must accept all applicants on a space avail-able basis. If more apply than there are spaces, selection must be by lot.</P>
<P>Second, government schools, at the individual school or district level, do not have to accept all students.  They only accept those assigned to that school, or who live in that district.  The advantaged live in their own districts, removed from the problems others may face.</P>
<P>Forty years after <I>Brown v. Board of Education</I>, all 25 of the largest government school districts in the nation have a student body that is primarily minority.</P>
<P>Further, government schools do not have to retain, and they certainly do not educate, all students.  The dropout rate, which is often a force out rate, has already been mentioned.  Nor do government schools have to accept or retain all students with special needs.  </P>
<P>In fact, students with the most severe special needs are not in government schools; they are in private institutions, including some which are out of state.  Nor is this meant to be a criticism.  No standard school, government or otherwise, is equipped to handle students with severe problems and/or needs.</P>
<P>Finally, the equity issue, the &quot;even play field,&quot; argument is valid, but it cuts both ways.</P>
<P>The typical nonpublic school has half, or less, the fiscal resources of a government school.  It is not reasonable to expect a school receiving $700-1,000 per student to accept and serve students who may cost $60,000 or more per year - as do some students with special needs; or to provide all the services to be found in a govern-ment school that spends, as a statewide average in Pennsylvania, more than $7,000 per year per student. (Some school districts in the nation spend more than $15,000 per pupil.)</P>
<P>School choice would be one way to level the field for both groups.  If government schools are accountable directly to students and parents there is much less need for regulations, as in higher and nonpublic education.</P>
<P>If funds are available in reasonable amounts to all students, as they are in Vermont, where they can be used in government and nongovernment schools, in or out of state, and as the California Supreme Court declared in 1976 when it said tuition vouchers would be one way to insure equity in state supported education, the likelihood of students finding a suitable school are dramatically increased.</P>
<P>As Quentin L. Quade, Director of The Blum Center for Parental Freedom In Education, at Marquette University, has written: <I>there is no </I><I>educational downside to educational choice, and no good argument, only smoke screens, against it.  It is not parental freedom that needs </I><I>to justify itself but any policy which limits it.</I></P>
<P> ~ ~ ~ ~ ~</P>
<P>&quot;Currently, we seem to take pride in  teaching all young people in the same way.  We believe that doing so promotes equality.  It does the opposite.  What is fair about creating just one kind of school with one kind of teaching when children's interests, learning styles, and develop-mental levels differ so dramatically? ...Choice celebrates the differences among children and uses those differences to good effect...Choice works for teachers, too.&quot; Charlotte-Mecklenburg, NC School Supt. John Murphy, PHI DELTA KAPPAN, April 1992</P>
<P> ~ ~ ~ ~ ~</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
