<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>&quot;IF MONEY'S THE SOLUTION, THAT'S THE PROBLEM&quot;</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3><!--No Changes above-->Vol. 2, No. 20, October 30, 1993</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B><!--<B><I>Start below</I></B>--><B><I> </I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P><B> </B></P>
<P><B>This was the title of an article by Al Knight in </B><B><I>The Denver Post</I></B><B> some time ago, and it is demonstrably true.</B></P>
<P><B>Knight reported that the Colorado Education Association &quot;scorned a variety of school measures still before the legislature as 'so-called </B><B>reform measures' and said the CEA would testify against every one of them.&quot;</B></P>
<P><B>The CEA seemed prepared to reject anything except more money.  Thus, Knight's conclusion that money as the solution is the problem.</B></P>
<P><B>There is ample evidence that he is right, evidence over a long period of time, and in a variety of circumstances. </B></P>
<P><B>Some were noted in my book, </B><B><I>Choice in Schooling</I></B><B> (Chicago: Loyola University Press, 1990).  For example, the More Effective Schools (MES) </B><B>program that was introduced with much fanfare in New York City in the late 1960s, as a collaborative effort of the Federation of Teachers and </B><B>the school district.  Unable to be done districtwide because of the cost, selected schools received more money for smaller classes, additional </B><B>specialists, and the like; all the things that are supposed to make for more effective schools, thus the title.</B></P>
<P><B>In the mid 1970s the program was quietly dropped.  It proved to be the More Expensive Schools program, which was no longer affordable </B><B>and had not produced the expected results.</B></P>
<P><B>Another instance was reported by John Henry Martin and Charles H. Harrison, in their book </B><B><I>Free to Learn</I></B><B> (Englewood Cliffs, NJ: </B><B>Prentice-Hall, Inc., 1972)</B></P>
<P><B>Martin was the superintendent in a school district that increased its budget 35% (how many can do that today?) to put the touted practices </B><B>in place.</B></P>
<P><B>As my book noted, &quot;Average class size went from over thirty pupils to about twenty.  Specialists of all kinds were hired or increased in </B><B>number: guidance counselors, psychologists, social workers, classroom aides, and remedial teachers.  Two full-time remedial reading </B><B>teachers were assigned to each elementary school in which the average enrollment was six hundred students.&quot;  And more.</B></P>
<P><B>After an evaluation two years later Martin said:</B></P>
<P><B>In the end, the cherished faith died...all that was done to make a difference had made no difference.  The panaceas were, after all, only false </B><B>promises--vain expectations.  All the patented prescrip-tions...had failed. </B></P>
<P><B>While the New York MES program was underway, Former Berkeley, California Supt. Neil Sullivan told how his district also lowered class size, </B><B>provided remedial teachers, etc., and three years later concluded that the inner city children has not only failed to gain from these efforts but </B><B>had actually lost ground. (Syndicated Columnist James J. Kilpatrick, &quot;Accountability in the Schoolhouse,&quot; Allentown, PA: </B><B><I>The Morning </I></B><B><I>Call</I></B><B>, Nov. 23, 1970)</B></P>
<P><B>We have apparently not learned from these, and other attempts. </B></P>
<P><B>A recent program to make the unworkable work, is in Kansas City.</B></P>
<P><B>As reported in the August 28, 1993 issue of </B><B><I>The Economist</I></B><B>, this effort has a long history.  It was clear that Kansas city schools had </B><B>problems.  Nine years of litigation culminated in a 1986 court decision ordering the school system to be drastically revised, even if it took </B><B>huge amounts of money, which it did.</B></P>
<P><B>Many schools were torn down.  Fifty-six &quot;magnet&quot; school were created.  Technology flourished, with one computer for every three pupils at </B><B>Central High School, which was rebuilt at a cost of $32 million.  Nearly a million dollars was budgeted each year to promote the district on </B><B>television to persuade parents keep their children in, or return them to, schools in the district.</B></P>
<P><B>The excess cost has been $1.3 billion beyond the regular school budget, or more than $36,000 for each of the district's 36,000 pupil </B><B>placements.  This, in turn, required significant financial support from the state, support that could only be provided by scrimping on </B><B>what was available for the rest of the state's schools and students.</B></P>
<P><B>The result?  The racial balance is unchanged.  University of Missouri Professor John Alspaugh says there has been no improvement in </B><B>reading and math scores.  Students in elementary schools which did not become magnet schools outperform those in schools that were </B><B>among the chosen.</B></P>
<P><B><I>The Economist</I></B><B> says that, despite the rise in expenditure, &quot;the drop-out rate has risen every year, without fail, since the decree was handed </B><B>down, and now stands at a disgraceful 60%&quot;</B></P>
<P><B>It also reminded its readers that University of Rochester economist Eric Hanushek has cited almost 200 studies that indicate more spending </B><B>on traditional schooling does not translate into improved learning, higher attendance or other desirable goals.</B></P>
<P><B>A Jack Anderson column, &quot;School vouchers proposed in N.J.,&quot; </B><B><I>The Erie Times</I></B><B>, Sept. 23, 1993, tells of the efforts by Jersey City Mayor Bret </B><B>Schundler, who will address the REACH conference in December, to introduce school choice into that district, one that was taken over by </B><B>the state of New Jersey in 1989, because it was ruled a &quot;total educational failure.&quot;  The district is only a bit smaller than Kansas City, 30,000 </B><B>students instead of 36,000. </B></P>
<P><B>What has the state done? </B></P>
<P><B>Mostly, the usual - thrown money at the problem, more than $100 million in four years.  While falling short of the Kansas City monetary </B><B>deluge, that is still a significant amount.</B></P>
<P><B>Yet fewer than half of the district's 9th graders pass the state proficiency exam and more than half the students drop out.  Perhaps </B><B>unknowingly, the district is about to embark on the Kansas City journey by instituting a magnet program, with specialized schools </B><B>emphasizing science and technology, engineering, etc.  It isn't quite clear how they propose to have students </B></P>
<P><B>achieve in such areas when they are not proficient in basic skills. In the meantime, the city's nonpublic schools, which spend far less per </B><B>pupil, about $3,500 per year, graduate 90 percent of their students, a high proportion of whom pursue postsecondary studies. </B></P>
<P><B>There is an old chestnut about the businessman who lost money on every sale but hoped to make it up on volume.</B></P>
<P><B>It has also been said that one form of insanity is to do more of what you have been doing and expect different results.</B></P>
<P><B>Both of these seem to be variations of the process of public schooling.  Of all the professions, (accepting for the moment that education is a </B><B>profession), those in education should be the least likely to follow the same unsuccessful road that others have tread before them.</B></P>
<P><B>Those who claim to teach critical thinking and problem solving should be able to think critically and solve some of their own problems.  </B><B>Instead, they seem unwilling to even discuss alternatives, much less accept them.</B></P>
<P><B>Where are the establishment groups that promote open and full debate of any and</B></P>
<P><B>all educational ideas?  Where are the ones that are willing to support trial efforts of any and all alternative programs to see whether they </B><B>show promise of working better, and being more beneficial to both students and the public interest than what now exists?</B></P>
<P><B>It is this inability of its defenders to establish viable programs that threatens the present system, not the reformers.  As Myron Lieberman </B><B>says in his latest book, </B><B><I>Public Education: An Autopsy</I></B><B>, (Harvard Univ. Press, 1993) &quot;promarket forces have one ineradicable advantage </B><B>...the inherent futility of conventional school reform.  The direction of change in public opinions is not in doubt: the emergence of a </B><B>market system is a question of when, not if.&quot;</B></P>
<P><B> </B><B>~ ~ ~ ~ ~</B></P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
