<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>Bankruptcy Approaching</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>Vol. 2, No. 1, January 15, 1993</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P>From &quot;the more things change the more they stay the same&quot; file: &quot;If it were not for the school systems' monopoly on the education of the poor, the schools would have gone bankrupt long ago.&quot; Allan C. Ornstein, p. 91, &quot;Decentralizing Urban Schools,&quot; <I>Journal of Secondary Education</I>, February 1971</P>
<P>Even with the monopoly, bankruptcy may be approaching. Some of the reasons why were pointed out in 1978 by Ed Steimel, President of the Louisiana Association of Business and Industry:</P>
<P>&quot;Public education (1) cannot be improved from within; (2) will not accept change so long as the bur-eaucracy can resist it; (3) must reach the brink of disaster or per-haps fall to ruin before the bur-eaucracy can be overthrown; (4) is doomed in its present form because it has totally lost the element of competition which is essential to the setting of priorities and the achievement of goals; (5) will probably survive long after it has died; and (6) will probably exper-ience reincarnation in another form of publicly financed education.&quot;  </P>
<P>Here are some signs that &quot;the brink of the disaster&quot; may be near. </P>
<P>Last school year, the Holyoke, Massachusetts schools dismissed more than a third of its faculty.  Seventy students in an auto mechanic class, spoke only Spanish while their teacher spoke only English.</P>
<P>Students at Lawrence High School Had to bring toilet paper to school because the district could not longer afford to buy it.</P>
<P>In Wales, Massachusetts, five of the seven teachers at the elementary school were dismissed, leaving the principal with 58 students in a combined 5th &amp; 6th grade class, one teacher with a class of 52 3rd and 4th graders; and the other teacher has a class of 76, made up of kindergarten through 2nd grade students.  The school also had no custodian or secretary. Despite this, the community voted against raising property taxes to rehire the teachers but did approve raising $20,000 to collect garbage.</P>
<P>California had cut education spending by 12% (after inflation) in three years.  Despite this, in early September the state cut aid to education by $2 billion, and said it would hold basic state per-pupil funding steady over the next two years.  Even that now seems doubtful, with predict-ions the state is facing another deficit, of $7.5 billion.  In the Sonoma Valley Unified School District, administrators and teachers have not had a salary increase in two years, while the San Jose district may have to reduce its budget by 20% in the next three years.</P>
<P>A national survey found 74% of 50 principals had budget cuts, 40% had let teachers go; Nearly half had cut back on music, art and programs for the gifted, and 80% had eliminated field trips.</P>
<P>In Texas 76% of the districts responding to a survey said they had either cut or frozen teacher pay - the Sterling City School District cut starting salaries by $1,282.</P>
<P>Florida's Broward County cut nearly $20 million out of its budget,and eliminated the positions of 35 assistant principals, 109 primary specialists, and 300 high school teachers.</P>
<P>Last June, the St. Louis School District laid off 295 employees, including 80 teachers.  The Board had earlier voted to eliminate a total of 457 positions.  Another 162 were eliminated  by attrition. They also planned to close 10 of their 123 schools.</P>
<P>At the beginning of this school year, there were predictions of a $400 million shortfall in Maryland this year and level state funding next year.  This could bring about funding reductions for the eighth time in two years.</P>
<P>Minnesota school administrators suggested that the state freeze school employees salaries and revoke the teachers' right to strike.</P>
<P>By late November, Los Angeles, the nation's second largest school district, was facing bankruptcy. This is a district where half of the entering kindergarten students do not speak English and half of the nearly 650,000 students live in poverty.  The state, as noted above, is in no position to make up the funding gaps.  Nor is the federal govern-ment, although some educators have high expectations of the incoming administration.  Great increases in federal funding cannot be realized since the national annual deficit is in the hundreds of billions of dollars.  Even with selective cuts in some programs there is no chance of a balanced federal budget in the immediate future so any new or expanded initiatives can only be paid for by borrowed dollars.</P>
<P>Colorado voters in November defeated a proposed sales tax hike, so the public schools there reportedly face at least a 9% drop in per-pupil funding next year. This is compounded in districts where property values have declined because of the adoption of a tax limitation measure.</P>
<P>Even wealthy, and high-spending, states are not exempt.  Connecticut has eliminated all funding of gifted programs, resulting in 36 districts discontinuing such offerings.</P>
<P>New Jersey, which adopted a record tax increase, and revised its school funding formula a year and a half ago, is witnessing the same stress, even in the more affluent suburban areas.  Barbara Horl, who heads a school board in a mostly white-collar suburban area, was quoted in <I>The New York Times</I> on Nov. 29, as saying &quot;Everyone who is part of the public schools is seeing the strain...how long we can continue holding the system together before something snaps is the big question for not only us but school districts everywhere.&quot;</P>
<P>Pennsylvanians know they are part of this mix.  Last year the Sto Rox School District in western Pennsylvania, despite having one of the highest property tax rates, became financially distressed and was taken over by the state,   That's the third district where the state has had to do this in the last 20 years.  The pace may be about to pick up, with predictions that nearly 40 other districts are almost in the same condition.  Some claim that figure could go as high as 100 in the next year or so.</P>
<P>The Philadelphia School District began this school year with overcrowded classes, some at Germantown High School with more than 60 students.  <I>The Inquirer</I> has cited transfers from private and parochial schools as a contributing factor, a trend that has been going on for years, as was pointed out during the debate over school choice funding a year ago.  It would be much more efficient, and educationally effective, to keep students in nonpublic schools, even at a cost of $2-3,000 each - and only $900 was proposed - than for them to transfer to public schools at a cost of $7,000 each.</P>
<P>One teacher facing up to the issue is Jonnie Johns, a San Fernando Valley English teacher:</P>
<P>&quot;The union is jumping up and down for money that the district doesn't have, that the state doesn't have, and that the country doesn't have.  Everybody is putting their head in the sand, bickering over dollars, and they're not facing the truth, that the system is collapsing.  We're out of money, we're out of morality, we're out of everything.&quot;</P>
<P>Teachers are leaving, unfortunately including the best ones, such as the 1988-89 Idaho State Teacher of the Year, and New York State's 1991 Teacher of the Year.</P>
<P>Bob Lemoine, social studies department at Germantown, said  &quot;somebody's got to figure out how we can do it better.&quot;  </P>
<P>Clearly the establishment has no idea what to do except call for more money, money which isn't going to materialize in any significant amounts.</P>
<P>The sad thing is there are ways to do it better, including but not restricted to school choice, but they can't even get a fair hearing, much less be tried.</P>
<P>Generally speaking, the choices are: 1) large increases in funding for the present system, 2) let the system slowly strangle, along with the welfare of millions of youngsters, or, 3) change the system. The first is impossible, the second is undesirable, so the third should be inevitable - and it may be, but apparently not without passing through a period of chaos first.</P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
