<HEAD>
<TITLE>Selected Writings by David W. Kirkpatrick 92090cc.htm</TITLE>
<LINK REL="ToC" HREF="httoc.htm">
<LINK REL="Previous" HREF="930115cc.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#8000FF" BACKGROUND="yelgrain.gif">
<P><A HREF="930115cc.htm"><IMG SRC="grappage.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="Previous Page"></A>
<A HREF="httoc.htm"><IMG SRC="gratoc.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="TOC"></A>
<A HREF="../index.htm"><IMG SRC="grahome.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="See File"></A>
</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="h1logo.gif" WIDTH = 124 HEIGHT = 50></P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#000000"><B>More Money</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<HR ALIGN=CENTER>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Choice Comments</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H3 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=3>Vol. 1, No.  3, September 1992</FONT></CENTER></H3>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>By David W. Kirkpatrick</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<HR WIDTH=60% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<P><B>&quot;There's a saying among teachers: If you think education is expens-ive, try ignorance.  Education is tremendously expensive in the United </B><B>States, but what we are getting for our money is ignor-ance.&quot; p. 51, John Chancellor, </B><B><I>Peril and Promise</I></B><B>, NY: Harper &amp; Row, 1990</B></P>
<P><B>NBC's John Chancellor is right.</B></P>
<P><B>The idea that more money, by itself, will lead to improved education is held by too many.  The representative of one educational group in the </B><B>state, commenting a few months ago at a hearing of the House Education Committee on the Outcome-Based Education proposals being put </B><B>into effect, said they would be difficult to implement &quot;when funding of education is at an all-time low.&quot;  This caused Chairman Ron Cowell </B><B>to say that, while the committee was there to receive comments and not to debate with anyone, it is more accurate to say that funding of </B><B>public education is at an all-time high.  And it is.</B></P>
<P><B>Figures from </B><B><I>The Condition of Education/1992</I></B><B>, the latest annual report from the U.S. Department of Education, prove it.</B></P>
<P><B>Using constant 1991 dollars, total revenues per pupil were $623 in 1930.  By 1990, they were $5,399, nearly nine times as great.  </B></P>
<P><B>They grew from $623 in 1930 to $835 in 1940, up 34%.  By 1950 it was $1,188, a 42% boost.  By 1960 funding grew 59%, to $1,885; and the </B><B>1960s saw a tremendous upsurge in costs, 67%, to $3,144 in 1970, a decade that also saw a great increase in the number of students, from </B><B>35.2 million in 1960 to 45.6 million in 1970, the greatest increase of any single decade.</B></P>
<P><B>By contrast, enrollment declined in the 1970s and 1980s, from 45.6 million in 1970 to 41.6 million in 1980 and to 40.5 million in 1990.</B></P>
<P><B>Still, per pupil revenues rose, up 33% from 1970-1980, reaching $4,188 in 1980; and 29% more in the 1980s, to $5,399 in 1990.</B></P>
<P><B>The 29% rate of increase in the 1980s was the lowest of any of the six decades, but note that the base to which that rate applied was much </B><B>greater.  So, while the rate increase was only 29%, the dollar per pupil growth was $1,211, almost twice as great as the total dollars per pupil </B><B>in 1930.</B></P>
<P><B>Two things should seem to be clear from this history.  First, if money alone could resolve the crisis in public education, it would have </B><B>happened a long time ago.</B></P>
<P><B>Second, it seems unlikely that a similar expansion in per pupil revenues will be possible in the decades ahead.  Projecting the increase of the </B><B>past six decades to the next six gives a per pupil figure of $46,788 in the year 2050.  </B></P>
<P><B>As indicated, these figures are based on constant 1991 dollars.  In dollars of the time, which will vary in value, as well as changes in pupil </B><B>enrollment, the figure 60 years from now would be well in the hundreds of thousands of dollars per student.</B></P>
<P><B>Does anyone really believe this is possible?</B></P>
<P><B>Whatever one's position on public education may be, and attitude toward taxes, there are, in general terms, only three scenarios confronting </B><B>us.</B></P>
<P><B>The first is that we come up with substantial amounts of new dollars to keep the present system afloat.</B></P>
<P><B>And substantial means just that - huge amounts of money, not just a few percent more per year.</B></P>
<P><B>The second is that the present system continues on its slow path of financial strangulation as it struggles to maintain itself without what its </B><B>practitioners regard as sufficient funds.</B></P>
<P><B>The third option is for the system to be changed - really changed.</B></P>
<P><B>Since the first option is not possible, and the second option is not desirable, the third alternative must be inevitable.</B></P>
<P><B>If this outline is correct, the pertinent questions then become: what changes are desirable or necessary?   How are they to be brought about? </B><B>  How desperate must the situation become before it is generally accepted that the present system cannot survive?   And how many </B><B>students must suffer the consequences in the meantime?</B></P>
<P><B>Nor is this just a statistical exercise.  The &quot;more money&quot;' theory has been tried, and in sums not likely to be duplicated.</B></P>
<P><B>&quot;A generation ago John Henry Martin put the platitudes to the test and found them wanting.  The things that are supposed to make public </B><B>schools work were tried: more money; more teachers... smaller classes; more specialists.  And they didn't work.  Martin realized they didn't </B><B>work, wrote that they didn't work...But these same ideas continue to be promoted and believed.</B></P>
<P><B>&quot;Martin was the superintendent of a school district which supported an increase in the budget of thirty-five percent, making possible many </B><B>changes that are supposed to make for efficient schools and efficient education.</B></P>
<P><B>Average class size went from over thirty pupils to about twenty.  Specialists of all kinds were hired or increased in number: guidance </B><B>counselors, psychologists, social workers, classroom aides and remedial teachers.  Two full-time remedial teaching teachers were </B><B>assigned to each elementary school in which the average enrollment was six hundred students.</B></P>
<P><B>&quot;Teachers with advanced degrees were hired, the curriculum was updated, an extensive in-service program for teachers was initiated, a </B><B>teacher council was chosen by secret ballot, and dozens of other reforms were introduced.</B></P>
<P><B>&quot;After two years, outside evaluators were hired to make a thorough and detailed assessment of the results.</B></P>
<P><B>&quot;Students took achievement tests, with the results analyzed by class size, teacher age and experience, and the students' race, sex, and family </B><B>income.</B></P>
<P><B>&quot;Martin reported:</B></P>
<P><B> </B><B>In the end, the cherished faith died...all that was done to make a difference had made no difference.  The panaceas were, after all, only </B><B>false promises--vain expectations. All the patented prescriptions... that made such a grand appearance in the college textbooks and the </B><B>theses of the pedagogues had failed the hard test of reality in the field.  pp 103, John Henry Martin and Charles H. Harrison, </B><B><I>Free To </I></B><B><I>Learn</I></B><B>, Englewood Cliffs, NJ: Prentice-Hall, Inc.&quot;</B></P>
<P><B>(The preceding is from pp 12-13, of my book, </B><B><I>Choice in Schooling</I></B><B>, Chicago: Loyola University Press, 1990)</B></P>
<P><B>A similar program was tried in New York City in the late 1960s. Termed the More Effective Schools (MES) Program, it was a cooperative effort </B><B>by the school district and the New York local of the American Federation of Teachers, then headed by Al Shanker, now the AFT's national </B><B>president.  It was introduced with much fanfare, and did many of the things tried in Martin's district.</B></P>
<P><B>The result was the same,  Much more money was spent (it might more properly have been called the More Expensive Schools program), with </B><B>no significant gains in academic achievement; teacher-pupil ratios were reduced to better than one to twelve; evaluated, it was found </B><B>ineffective, rather than effective; only four of 21 schools had students reading at grade level on the average; and all four had a student </B><B>body consisting mostly of white middle-class students.  </B></P>
<P><B>In the mid-1970s the program was quietly dropped. (pp 13-14, same source)</B></P>
<P><B>In short, those who oppose school choice and/or other proposals to have meaningful change need to come up with alternatives of their own. </B><B> Opposition isn't enough.   Time is running out.</B></P>
<P><B>On a separate note, it might also be noted that, since school choice is criticized by some as &quot;elitist,&quot; that when </B><B><I>Brown vs. Board of </I></B><B><I>Education</I></B><B>, was handed down by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1954, 17 of the 20 largest public school districts in the nation were </B><B>majority white.  Today, The enrollment in all of the 25 largest public school districts is largely  minorities, and disadvantaged minorities at </B><B>that. The same is true for smaller cities.  Harrisburg has more minority and disadvantaged students, than the other 23 districts in </B><B>Cumberland, Dauphin and Perry Counties combined.  And most of its teachers live in other districts.</B></P>
<ADDRESS>Copyright 1996, David W. Kirkpatrick
<BR>2323 Rudy Road, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, 17104-2025
<BR>Phone: (717) 232-2146, Fax: (717) 232-2164
<BR>To excerpt or reprint, please contact the author.</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com">e-mail (Kirkpatrick@SchoolReport.com)</A></P>
