<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PTA Forum with Charlene Haar -- It's Not the Parents Talking</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FF0000" VLINK="#800080" ALINK="#8000FF">


<A HREF="../../index.htm"

><IMG SRC="home.gif" WIDTH = 32 HEIGHT = 32 BORDER = 0 ALT="See File"></A>
</P>
<H1 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER><A ID="I1" NAME="I1">
<FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#000000"><B>PTA - It's Not &quot;Parents Taking Action&quot;</B></FONT></A></CENTER></H1>
<H2 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#070F4B"><B><I>Organizational Trends, Capitol Research Center</I></B></FONT></CENTER></H2>
<H4 ALIGN="CENTER">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><I>Charlene K. Haar</I></B>
<BR></FONT></CENTER></H4>
<P>Despite much lip service to the contrary, teachers and teacher unions frequently view citizen/parent participation in school affairs as a threat to their benefits and their prerogatives.  Although the importance of teacher/parent cooperation is obvious, parent/teacher relations are actually characterized by inherent conflicts of interest.</P>
<P>   For instance, parents want teachers to be available to meet with parents after school or on Saturdays or weekends.  Clearly, such availability is not in the interests of teachers.  They prefer to be duty free as much as possible; typically, they view availability to parents before or after the regular school day as an extra duty which calls for additional compensation.  In saying this, I impute to teachers only the same degree of self interest that characterizes most workers.  At some point, however, we must distinguish employer from employee rights; understandably, teachers, like employees generally, draw the line more in their favor than their employers would.  </P>
<P> Of course, parents are not the legal employers of public school teachers.  Nevertheless, teacher employment responsibilities are important to parents in ways that go far beyond the ordinary citizen's stake in public education.  A critical point is that these ways involve conflicts of interest that are typically resolved in collective bargaining between teacher unions and school boards.  For example:</P>
<P> 1.  Teachers prefer to work the fewest possible days; parents often prefer a longer school year.</P>
<P> 2.  Parents want a convenient and expeditious complaint procedure vis-a-vis' complaints against teachers.  In contrast, teacher unions typically bargain for a wide variety of procedural requirements, such as insistence that parental complaints be in writing; a teacher right to have a union representative present when parents complain; and brief time limits for submitting parental complaints.</P>
<P> 3.  Teachers want complete control over pupil grades; parents want an appeal procedure to challenge grades they perceive as unfair.</P>
<P> The situation can be summarized as follows:  Parent/teacher cooperation is conducive to pupil achievement.  Such cooperation, however, has significant implications for teacher terms and conditions of employment.  Conflicts inevitably arise over these employment issues.  In the overwhelming majority of school districts, the teacher union positions render it more difficult for parents to articulate or defend their needs, interests, preferences, and/or complaints.</P>
<P> On teacher availability for parental conferences, we can envisage the following:</P>
<P>  School District A.   </P>
<P>  Teachers shall be available:</P>
<P> 1.  Without additional compensation any day after school by appointment.</P>
<P> 2.  One evening a month during the school year.</P>
<P> 3.  One Saturday morning a month during the school year.</P>
<P> 4.  Also at other times paid for by the district at an agreed upon hourly rate.</P>
<P>  School District B.  </P>
<P>  Teachers shall be available:</P>
<P> 1.  One day a week after school, from 3:00 to 4:00 p.m.</P>
<P> 2.  Two evenings each semester at PTA meetings.</P>
<P> 3.  No weekend or other availability except as agreed to by the teachers.</P>
<P>  School District C.</P>
<P>  Teachers shall be available:</P>
<P> 1.  One evening each semester.</P>
<P> 2.  One entire day, teacher time paid by the school district, pupils dismissed for          the day.</P>
<P> Leaving in abeyance the issue of fairness to teachers, and considering teacher availability from a parental perspective, many parents have jobs which preclude after school conferences with teachers, or would require a substantial loss of pay. Saturdays would be most convenient and most economical for many parents.  Parents who can meet with teachers after school on some days cannot on others, hence rigid limits on availability is virtually certain to render teachers unavailable to many parents.</P>
<P> The variations in parental home and employment obligations require considerable flexibility in teacher availability if all parents who wish to confer in person with a teacher are to be able to do so without a significant financial sacrifice.  To summarize briefly, both parents and teachers have legitimate but conflicting interests on teacher availability.  Hours of employment, however, are a mandatory subject of bargaining.  That is, both the teacher union and the school board must bargain on the issue if requested to do so by the other party.  Consequently, in most school districts, the issue is resolved by collective bargaining.  The bargaining is not between parents (or parental organizations) and teacher unions; it is between representatives of the school board and of the teacher union.  The adequacy of teacher representation is indisputable.  Most teachers are represented by, or have available at bargaining tables, full-time experienced union representatives with impressive backup support.  These union representatives know the provisions relating to teacher availability in every school district.  The school board negotiator who proposes four evening meetings a year will have to explain why nearby districts require two, one or even none, except at the option of the teacher.</P>
<P> The union will agree to parent meetings during the regular school day, but if and only if the school board agrees to delete a day of instruction.  Such negotiated decisions become a part of the union contract, which has the force of law for its duration.  And so goes the real world of parent/teacher cooperation, as unremitting in teacher interests as in any other aspect of bargaining.</P>
<P> Parents and/or parental organizations do not bargain on behalf of parental interests; that is a school board responsibility.  Ideally, the board negotiations take into account all the interest groups with a stake in an issue: parents, taxpayers, employers, teachers, support staff, and so on.  These interest groups rarely have their own representatives present during teacher bargaining; as a practical matter, the school boards decide how much or how little weight to accord to parental interests.</P>
<P> In practice, school boards accord minimal weight to parental interests.  One reason is that the PTA, which supposedly represents parent interests, does not take sides on school district collective bargaining issues.  Incredible as it may seem, the PTA opted for neutrality in 1968 and reaffirmed this position in 1987.  Because of the far-reaching implications of the PTA policy with respect to collective bargaining, let me spell out in full its resolution on the subject. </P>
<P>          P O S I T I O N   S T A T E M E N T</P>
<P>TEACHER NEGOTIATIONS, SANCTIONS, AND STRIKES, (1968)</P>
<P> Teacher negotiations, sanctions, and strikes are very much a part of the reality of operating public schools.  While there are great variations throughout the country in the intensity of teacher militancy, no school system can escape the necessity of responding to the growing voice in educational decision-making.  Not only do school boards and school administrators have to reckon with teacher militancy, but PTA becomes involved.</P>
<P> The PTA, because of its strategic position, has become involved in activities related to negotiations and may find itself on the horns of several dilemmas.</P>
<P> 1.  If the PTA provides volunteers to man the classrooms during a work stoppage, in the interest of protecting the immediate safety and welfare of children, it is branded as a strike breaker.</P>
<P> 2.  If the PTA does not take sides in issue[s] being negotiated, it is accused of not being interested.</P>
<P> 3.  If it supports the positions of the board of education, which is the representative of the public in negotiations, the teacher members of the PTA have threatened to withdraw membership and boycott the local PTA activities.</P>
<P> As a result, PTA leadership in local units, councils, and states has expressed an urgent need for guidance in this difficult situation.</P>
<P><U>Guide to State Congresses</U></P>
<P> The best efforts of state PTAs in regard to teacher negotiations, sanctions, and strikes start with alertness before a situation arises.</P>
<P> 1.  Study state laws regarding negotiations, sanctions, and strikes so as to act within the law, and so that counsel to local units will be consistent with the law.</P>
<P> 2.  Seek to bring together in conference meetings the state leadership of all groups concerned for the purpose of mutual understanding.</P>
<P> 3.  Encourage state legislation which will improve the procedures for negotiations and resolution of impasse.</P>
<P> 4.  Help local units understand particular state issues involved.</P>
<P> 5.  Urge school boards and teachers to establish frequent and regular lines of communication about educational concerns.</P>
<P><U>Guidelines for Councils and Local Units</U></P>
<P> Because situations locally vary so widely, both across the country and even within states, guidelines cannot be highly specific.  A great deal of discretion in action is left to the council and the local unit.  These are suggested measures for action organized appropriately to three phases:  the pre-strike period, during the strike, and after the strike.  These guidelines, plus counsel from the state PTA and the basic good judgement of the people, should enable the council and the local PtAs to minimize the dilemmas and to contribute constructively to community understanding, teacher satisfactions, renewal of cordial parent-teacher dialogue,and improved educational climate for children.</P>
<P><U>Pre-strike period</U></P>
<P> 1.  Continue to work for quality education.  Efforts in this regard reassure teachers that parents are helping to achieve their goals of greater job satisfactions and improvement of substandard salaries.</P>
<P> 2.  Be alert to early symptoms of teacher dissatisfaction:</P>
<P> a.  Abnormal turnover in teaching staff and administrators.</P>
<P> b.  Teacher-supported legislation defeated by state legislature.</P>
<P> c.  Growing dissatisfaction of teachers as evidenced by complaints. </P>
<P> 3.  Seek action that corrects the basic causes of dissatisfaction -- salaries, student conduct, teaching conditions, lack of participation in decision-making.</P>
<P> 4.  Inform the officers of teachers' organizations, the school boards, and administrators of the appropriate role PTA might play in the event of a work stoppage, and be advised as to provisions for the welfare and safety of children during work stoppage. </P>
<P> 5.  Urge school boards and local teachers' organizations to consider the advisability of developing written agreements on negotiation procedures, including grievance procedures.  Because work stoppages and negotiations are ofttimes conducted in a way that tends to create dissension and low morale that are harmful to children, the PTA should do all it can to prevent such situations from developing.  The advance planning and the orderly procedures embodied in written agreements may avert strikes.</P>
<P> 6.  Learn from the school board and the teachers' organizations what issues are being negotiated.</P>
<P> 7.  Provide full public airing of the issues.  The purpose of these discussions is to dispel confusion and develop intelligent, informed public opinion.  If a strong majority opinion develops regarding an issue that affects children, the PTA has a responsibility to bring this to the attention of the negotiation parties.  PTAs should be keenly aware that the decisions made in negotiations ofttimes have much more of an impact upon the welfare of children than to temporary closing of the school and other disruptive action.</P>
<P> 8.  Reexamine the role of teacher members in the local unit.  Teachers as well as parents should join and participate by individual choice.  Their motivation to participate should spring from a professional awareness of the unique contributions which they may render and the value of teacher rapport with parents and the community.  The teacher continues as a willing partner in the PTA when participation is free of unwarranted expectations.</P>
<P><U>During the Strike</U></P>
<P> 1.  Urge immediate and continuous negotiations and if necessary mediation to get schools open as soon as possible.  If negotiation is delayed, the PTA should seek to bring the school board representatives and teachers' organization representatives together.</P>
<P> 2.  Serve as an open forum to inform the public on the points of disagreements and the progress of negotiations.</P>
<P> 3.  PTA should not man the classrooms, except possibly for a day in the absence of advance notice of a strike.  No only is manning of classrooms inconsistent with PTA efforts to obtain a qualified teacher in every classroom, but personal liability may be incurred.  If the school administration intends to keep the schools open during a teacher walkout, it should develop a corps of volunteers outside the PTA structure.</P>
<P> 4.  Suggest and urge appropriate action by parents, community agencies, and volunteer groups that will protect children during the period the school is closed.</P>
<P> 5.  Encourage the full and continuous participation of teacher members in PTA activities.</P>
<P><U>After the Strike</U></P>
<P> 1.  Plan activities that will restore harmony, promote teacher morale, and renew parent-teacher dialogue.</P>
<P> 2.  Through informed public opinion see that the negotiated agreements which settled the strike are faithfully implemented.</P>
<P> 3.  Work for community understanding and support of school needs.</P>
<P> </P>
<P> Clearly, the aforesaid PTA policy is a colossal victory for the teacher unions; it neutralizes the one interest group most likely to oppose teacher union positions from participation in the bargaining process.  If the organization representing parents does not complain about excessive tenure protections, teacher unavailability to meet with parents, and complaint procedures geared to teacher protections instead of parental rights, it is very unlikely that any other organization will do so.  Deplorably but understandably,  </P>
<P>school boards accord minimal weight to parental interests.   Consider also the fact that many school board members are elected as the result of teacher union support.  Thus, while the parents have taken themselves out of the process, the teachers and their unions are active at every stage of it, usually to the detriment of the parents.  As the PTA resolution explicitly recognizes, the intimidation factor also plays a role at the school and teacher levels.  Many parents are afraid of teacher retaliation if they aggressively advocate parental over teacher interests.  The prevailing thought is that parents must be in a supportive role, no matter what the issue. </P>
<P> In view of PTA neutrality and union opposition to proposals contrary to teacher interests, it is virtually impossible for school boards to negotiate pro-parent positions on collective bargaining issues.  To do so would require that parents challenge teachers at PTA meetings in which the teachers themselves are present and well prepared to crush any movement in this direction.  Under these circumstances, the PTA's neutrality in bargaining is a tremendous advantage for teacher unions.  When school boards do not receive bargaining proposals that protect parental interests, and subsequently sacrifice parental to teacher interests, as often happens, the PTA cannot object; neutrality comes to the fore.</P>
<P><B>Who then will advocate for parents?</B></P>
<P> Because they are subservient to teacher unions, the PTAs cannot provide parents with a useful role in educational policymaking.  PTA programs are designed to diminish, not to increase dissatisfaction with school performance.  Instead of hearings to expose academic deficiencies, PTAs sponsor events where the best work of students is presented.  Significant time and effort are involved in teacher support services, such as trip chaperoning, and fund raising for school activities.  PTA parents are supposed to be supporters, not critics of schools and teachers.  After nearly 100 years, the PTA can not offer even the pretense of affecting basic educational decisions.  </P>
<P> Interestingly enough, in its early years the PTA did not include teachers qua teachers.  Nor should it be assumed that its transformation from an organization representing parents to an organization which has abandoned its initial raison d'&#234;tre occurred without any internal turmoil and loss of membership.  As a result of criticism of teacher unions by some state and local PTA's, teacher union members threatened to or actually withdrew their membership and boycotted PTA activities.  More than 12 million teachers, administrators, and parents were members of the National PTA in 1966 when PTA power peaked.  Its financial status at that time made other citizen groups drool with envy, but by 1974 neither the <U>PTA </U><U>Magazine</U> nor the association could make ends meet.  The National PTA lost over six million members from 1966 to 1982, precisely the years in which collective bargaining by teacher unions increased to unprecedented levels.  Indisputably, teacher opposition to the PTA played a significant role in the decline of parent membership as well.</P>
<P> Nevertheless, the facade of cooperation was carried on among the national leadership during these years of overt teacher/parent conflicts.  In fact, the 1970 National PTA program included David Selden, President of the American Federation of Teachers (AFT), as a panel participant on &quot;Parent Involvement in the Schools.&quot;  Meanwhile, the National Education Association (NEA), was distributing literature in the PTA convention exhibit area.  By this time, PTA membership had dropped by about three million, whereas the NEA gained 85,880 members in 1970.</P>
<P> By 1970 both the NEA and AFT were vigorously lobbying for state legislation to legitimize and regulate collective bargaining negotiations by unions of school district employees.  Wisconsin had been the first state to do so in 1962, followed in 1965 by California, Connecticut, Michigan, Massachusetts, Oregon, and Washington.  By April 1972, 29 states had passed legislation requiring school boards to bargain with teacher unions.  Although bargaining rights were enacted partly because legislative approaches to teacher terms and conditions of employment were deemed ineffective, the paradoxical result of the bargaining laws was to strengthen the teacher unions politically. </P>
<P>  At its 1972 convention, the NEA established its Political Action Committee (NEA-PAC).  As a result, the NEA became even more effective as a special interest group.  At first, the PTA tried to emulate this development.  At its 1972 convention, the PTA dropped its policy that the PTA &quot;will not interfere with administration of schools and shall not seek to control their policies.&quot;   The organization's new goal was to &quot;seek to participate in the decision-making process establishing school policy&quot; instead of sitting passively on the sidelines.   However, the teacher unions, had decided that the most effective way to advance teacher welfare and security was to characterize these objectives as benefitting parents and children.  Consequently, and as a result of their much greater resources, the teacher unions largely upstaged the PTA as the advocate for parents and children.</P>
<P> At the same time, teachers were again reassured of their dominant position within the PTA.  With specific reference to the controversial 1968 Resolution, the 1972 National PTA President said &quot;In the role of teacher strikes and the PTA role, I hope all of you will read the PTA guidelines carefully.  Teachers, administrators and school board members were consulted in their legal and professional capacities.  The importance to teachers will be obvious to any reader.&quot;</P>
<P> In defiance of the 1968 PTA Resolution, many American parents abandoned the national PTA policies on teacher bargaining and teacher strikes.  For example, most parents in Hortonville, Wisconsin, sided with their school board, not with their PTA counterparts, during a strike in that district.  Even though Wisconsin law prohibited strikes by public employees, Hortonville teachers struck on March 18, 1974.  The Hortonville school board unexpectedly fired the teachers for engaging in an illegal strike and for violating their individual contracts.  On April 8 school reopened with replacement teachers.  The town veterinarian made appearances at the school's agriculture classes and more than 100 other parents volunteered for door duty and playground supervision.  </P>
<P>  When PTA National President Lillie E. Herndon was asked in 1974 if there were &quot;any teachers left in the PTA?&quot; she acknowledged that in 1970 the National PTA quietly quit keeping track of the occupations and ages of its members.  As a result, a lack of demographic data continues to handicap PTA efforts to assess membership attitudes toward the organization. </P>
<P> At a 1974 joint meeting of NEA, AFT and PTA officials, officers of the NEA and AFT asked PTA leaders:  &quot;Why don't you people just form a parents group and leave the teachers out of it?&quot;  The suggestion went unheeded and extensive press coverage publicized the continuing parent/teacher conflicts.  For example, the state PTA and the Ohio Education Association (OEA) split over three bills in the Ohio legislature.  Two of these bills involved teacher certification, training and dismissal; the third was an association supported negotiations bill that included binding arbitration.  The state PTA actively and successfully opposed several OEA legislative proposals.  Consequently, at its 1976 state convention, OEA adopted a resolution asking its 85,000 teachers to drop out of the PTA, to boycott all PTA activities, and to encourage parents to form new parent-teacher organizations not affiliated with the PTA.  Understandably, the 1976 Ohio PTA President said, &quot;For years we did everything the teacher association wanted and we never disagreed about anything.  Now that we're beginning to deal with real issues, they (the union) have a different opinion about us.&quot;  </P>
<P> Elsewhere, teachers and parents continued to fight over legislative issues.  In 1977, the Indiana PTA voted not to support the teacher union proposals for limits on class size, teacher preparation time and provisions which would allow the union to collect service fees from all teachers regardless of union membership.  Two years later, PTA President Grace Baisinger, played a prominent role in organizing the National Coalition to Save Public Education.  Coalition members and the PTA vehemently opposed (and still oppose) tuition tax credits (or vouchers) to enable parents to enroll their children in public and/or private elementary and secondary schools of choice.  Despite the absence of statistics on the issue, it is likely that many private school parents dropped out of the PTA as a protest against PTA's policies on these issues.  Parents of students, and teachers in nonpublic schools were fighting for their own convictions.  </P>
<P> In an effort to increase PTA's lagging membership, the PTA launched an allout attack on rival parent-teacher organizations (PTOs) and parent advisory councils.  Parent advisory councils were mandated by federal law and were often required to focus on specific groups of children, such as the bilingual or the gifted or disadvantaged.  In 1977, Congress dealt the PTA a severe blow by requiring schools and school districts to set up new councils to meet the law, rather than use the existing councils in which PTA had been represented.  California, Florida and Illinois have required citizen involvement in some state funded school improvement programs for several years, as have other states.  </P>
<P> Similar requirements for parent involvement are included in the Goals 2000 legislation which was passed by the 103rd Congress, March 31, 1994.  With its membership now stabilized at just over six million, the PTA is urging its members to become the parent representatives on these federally funded councils, possibly shutting out representation from other parent groups.  Insofar as this happens, the teacher</P>
<P>unions will be assured of support from council members purporting to represent parents.</P>
<P> Although much more remains to be said about PTA subservience to teacher unions, let me conclude with a few comments about the possibilities for parent empowerment on educational matters.  In thinking about how to represent parental interests more effectively, NEA history is instructive.  Prior to teacher bargaining, the NEA included both teachers and administrators at the local, state, and national levels.  Local associations were almost invariably ineffectual defenders of teacher interests.  It was practically impossible to propose an action or policy critical of school administrators when the latter were members of the association, especially if active in its governance.   Similarly, the PTA's futility results from its all-inclusive membership policies.  Unless the teachers leave as they began to do in 1967, or are expelled, the PTAs will continue to be an exercise in futility.</P>
<P> The only other feasible solution is to establish a new parental organization which does not include teachers in its governance structure.  This would be extremely difficult to do since many teachers would presumably still have the right to join and participate as parents.  However, as public resentment against skyrocketing costs, dismal educational results, and questionable educational reforms increases, parents are more likely to demand a stronger presence in educational policymaking.  Increasingly, citizen participation in educational affairs will highlight the differences between noneducators and teachers who are employed in the schools.  Consequently, parents are seeking organizations and procedures through which they, the primary consumers, can make the government education monopolies more responsive.   As this struggle intensifies, the teacher unions will undoubtedly do their utmost to preserve the six million member PTA in its present form.  The unions may well be successful in this effort, but their success may also convince many parents that school choice and competition is the only way to empower parents to control the education of their children.</P>
<P>   </P>
<P>    </P>
<P> The resolution's sponsor made an impassioned plea for support of her position.  She compared its importance to eliminating cigarette smoking by minors, a continuing effort by the PTA, first begun in 1926.</P>
<P> Brief discussion followed; an amendment was defeated, and the resolution was passed within the limited minute debate period.  Delegates to the 1994 state convention of the California Congress of Parents, Teachers and Students had passed their only resolution: &quot;That the California State PTA seek participation in coalitions to study the effects of electro-magnetic fields.&quot;  Delegates further directed the PTA leadership to inform its districts, councils and units about the EMF issue.</P>
<P> At that same convention, the audience broke into thunderous applause when a speaker asserted that the California PTA had defeated the voucher bill known as Proposition 174 in November 1993.  &quot;You were the voice of the California children!&quot; she shouted.</P>
<P> Thirty-six days later, PTA delegates from 53 states and territories meeting in Las Vegas were considering resolutions dealing with violence in video games, inhalant abuse, the quality of indoor air in portable classrooms, and the sale, resale, and destruction of confiscated firearms.  Generally known as the PTA, this is the National Congress of Parents and Teachers at work in 1994.</P>
<P><B>National Congress of Mothers</B></P>
<P> In 1885 Alice McClellan Birney, a former journalist, wife of a prominent Washington lawyer and mother, envisioned an organization &quot;uniting in holiest purpose&quot; to educate all the mothers of the country about the supreme importance of the child.  Mrs. Birney was fortunate that hot summer at Chautauqua, New York, where the first adult education center in the United States was holding its annual summer school.</P>
<P> Ten thousand men and women were at the conference.  Two prominent kindergarten teachers who were holding a series of mothers' meetings were among them.  In their local communities, kindergarten teachers often invited visits from parents, and occasionally formed child study circles from these visits.  At the Chautauqua meeting, however, the idea of a national effort to educate parents in child care excited the audience.</P>
<P> At the meeting, several ministers requested Mrs. Birney to speak to their congregations on &quot;Better Trained Mothers.&quot;  To organize the mothers' group, Mrs. Birney enlisted the financial support of Phoebe Apperson Hearst, the 53 year old widow of California Senator George Hearst, and the mother of the future newspaper publisher, William Randolph Hearst.  Hoping to encourage at least 50 women to come to Washington to support her vision, Mrs. Birney sent a four-page invitation to attend the First National Congress of Mothers, February 17-19, 1887.  The invitation, which was sent to all the leading women's clubs in America, stated in part:</P>
<P> &quot;It is universally admitted that feminine influence has been a mighty factor for good in all ages, and, therefore, incalculable benefit may be expected from the assembling of many women for the interchange of views, and the study of home problems which can be solved by woman alone.&quot; </P>
<P> The National Congress of Mothers became a socially acceptable activity for women who had leisure time to spend outside their homes.  The welfare of children and the &quot;elevation of mankind&quot; were causes with more universal appeal than those of the American Association of University Women which had been organized in 1882, and the General Federation of Women's Clubs, or the Daughters of the American Revolution, organized in 1890.</P>
<P> The National Congress of Mothers enlisted women from the upper social strata from the beginning; the wife of the vice-president of the United States and the wives of several cabinet members were present at its formation and reception at the White House.  These women feared that the country's children were at risk and that as a consequence, the country was at risk.  If the next generation was to assume a constructive role in society, parents needed to understand the importance of their role and to develop the skills required to raise their children.  </P>
<P> In order to effectuate the &quot;kindergarten principles from cradle to college,&quot; Mrs. Birney encouraged the formation of mothers' clubs to serve as a means of communication between those who wanted information and those who could supply it.   Although resolutions expressing the mothers' concerns were drafted and occasionally petitions presented to the U.S. Congress, these clubs were not pressure groups.  For example, one such petition in 1899 called for the creation of a National Health Bureau.  Locally, the clubs encouraged such projects as campaigns for better school sanitation, public playgrounds, and vacation schools.</P>
<P><B>National Congress of Parents and Teachers</B></P>
<P> At the fifth national annual convention in Columbus, Ohio, in 1901, the New York State Superintendent of Public Instruction called for the cooperation between home and school as he presided over a conference attended by parents and teachers.  Nevertheless, the idea of including teachers in the National Congress of Mothers was not generally accepted until eleven years after the organization was founded and six years after the resignation of Alice McLellan Birney.  In 1908 the name was changed to The National Congress of Mothers and Parent-Teacher Associations, but did not become the National Congress of Parents and Teachers until 1924.  As early as 1920, however, the national office was in the National Education Association (NEA) building in Washington, D.C.  In 1954, the national office moved to Chicago where it currently rents space in the IBM building on the near North side. </P>
<P> By 1927, the influence of the teachers in the PTA was evident.  The program for the PTA's 1927 convention &quot;was built around the seven cardinal objectives of education as adopted by the National Education Association (NEA).&quot;  National PTA membership exceeded 1 million and plans were underway to publish <U>Parents &amp; Teachers</U>, the first PTA textbook. </P>
<P> PTA work was and is carried out through committees and volunteers. Early committees included:  Education, Finance, Health, Kindergarten, Literature, Legislation, Press, Printing, Program,  Transportation, and Domestic Science.  Present day committees vary according to need and resources, but resemble those established in the 1920s.  The earliest Education Committee was established for the education of mothers and has evolved into a committee dedicated to influencing educational policies and practices.</P>
<P> Membership began to rise after the depression, continued through the Second World War, and nearly doubled from 1945 to 1950, exceeding 6 million by 1950.  As membership increased, so did PTA activity with respect to legislation.  In cooperation with the teacher organizations and such organizations as the League of Women Voters, the 1947 National PTA called for &quot;active support&quot; for increased school aid funds, reorganization of school districts into larger units, various welfare measures, and opposition to limitation on property tax rates.</P>
<P> In the PTA's formative years, parents had exercised considerable control in their neighborhood or rural one-room schools; however, consolidation of school districts tended to reduce the parental role in school district decisionmaking.  With increasing frequency, the school administrator was a professional who was often insulated from local parents.  And as state laws standardized educational practices and curriculum, parents had fewer means of influencing what happened in the schools attended by their children.</P>
<P> Ironically, in order to better serve its members, the 1953 California PTA Board of Managers reorganized its larger districts into smaller areas to improve its communication and volunteer efforts.  &quot;No area of child welfare service was ignored by our 1,316,048 members,&quot; reported the California PTA President the year after the reorganization was implemented.</P>
<P><B> </B></P>
<P><B>Not to decide is to decide</B></P>
<P> As the mid-1960s approached, PTA members at the grass roots became involved in more volatile controversies.  Teacher strikes illustrate this point: 2 in 1965; 30 in 1966; and 80 in 1967.  </P>
