<h3 align="center">Outsourcing Defense?</h3>
<h4 align="center">Investor's Business Daily - Guest Editorial (01/17/96)</h4>
<h4 align="center">By Loren B. Thompson</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Defense Department is about to begin a major change in its management philosophy. One
result could be a huge opportunity for private entrepreneurs. 

<p>In February, the Pentagon will disclose its first selections of military support functions suitable for
outsourcing.

<p>Though private industry has been systematically outsourcing for years, this is a near-revolution for
the armed forces.

<p>About half of the defense budget consists of support functions such as maintenance, supply, health
care, data processing, administrative services, facilities management, transportation and so on. In
1995, these defense functions cost over $100 billion.

<p>The use of outside contractors is not unusual in the Pentagon. But the military has traditionally
held that any activity necessary to waging war should be under the control of the armed services,
meaning that it should be performed internally.

<p>Defense planners recognize that most support functions do not fall within the core competencies
of the military. But they have been reluctant to rely on the market for services that could make the
difference between life and death in wartime.

<p>Now budget pressures and the impressive performance of the private sector are forcing planners
to rethink that premise.

<p>World-class firms such as Boeing and General Dynamics commonly achieve 20% to 30% savings
when they outsource noncore functions.

<p>Similar savings on even half of the services now internal to Defense could save over $10 billion.
That's enough to offset current shortfalls in funding for weapons modernization.

<p>If the private-sector record is any indicator, privatization should also IMPROVE the efficiency
and responsiveness of the defense infrastructure.

<p>Some Pentagon organizations, such as the Defense Logistics Agency, have greatly improved their
management practices. But it is a rare government agency that can match the performance of free
enterprise. Even when the public sector achieves comparable performance in some key measure,
such as delivery time or data throughput, costs are usually much higher.

<p>Thus, defense privatization could save a great deal of money while actually bolstering the
effectiveness of the armed forces.

<p>That at least is the conclusion of senior Clinton administration officials who have spent much of
the past three years trying to make the Pentagon a more market- driven organization.

<p>Privatization - outsourcing to the private sector - is just the latest in a series of Clinton efforts to
wipe out the barriers between the defense-acquisition system and the commercial economy.

<p>Some uniformed personnel grumble that these initiatives will compromise military access to vital
services in wartime.

<p>Senior political appointees think this shows a lack of awareness about how capable private-sector
companies have become. Reliable private-sector sources of logistics, information services,
maintenance and the like may once have been hard to come by, they say, but those days are long
gone. Today it is the military that tends to lag behind.

<p>The Pentagon privatization initiatives could create sizable new business opportunities over the
next several years.

<p>Private firms will be able to compete for the right to provide a vast array of support functions.
And more contractors will be needed to manage the resulting arrangements.

<p>Past experience suggests that private- sector experts would manage outsource contracts better
than Pentagon bureaucrats. Outsiders tend to have more relevant skills and background and are
much easier to ''incentivize'' than civil-service contract managers.

<p>The only thing that could derail these common-sense improvements is Congress. Legislators
sometimes rush to defend even the most redundant or superfluous facilities, preventing Pentagon
policy-makers from rationalizing their unwieldy infrastructure. That's why a special law and
commission were needed to close obsolete military bases.

<p>With market-oriented Republicans controlling Congress, it seems reasonable to expect less
tolerance of government waste and more faith in the private sector's ability to provide flexible,
efficient support to the military.

<p>With support in Congress, privatization could be the most important defense management
initiative of the post-Cold War period.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Loren B. Thompson is a senior fellow at the Alexis de Tocqueville Institution.  
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
