<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">Election Analysis of Congressional Candidates</h3>
<h3 align="center">Supported by the Teacher Unions</h3>
<h4 align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center">AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 139</h4>
<h4 align="center">November 6, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong><hr>

<p></strong>America's major teacher unions -- the National Education Association (NEA) and the American
Federation of Teachers (AFT) -- have spent millions of dollars this election season in an attempt
to elect a new Congress.  Analysis of the recipients and targets of their PAC money suggests that
much of the unions' efforts did not bear fruit.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In the races in which they funded challengers, the unions were only able to win 20 percent of the
races in the Senate (one out of five) and 17.5 percent in the House (18 of 103).  In the
all-important open seats, teacher union-backed candidates won 38.5 percent of Senate seats (five
of 13) and 48.7 percent of House seats (19 of 39).  The incumbents they backed in each chamber
did very well.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The NEA also used independent expenditures to try to defeat nine targeted House members.  In
those contests, which were chosen in part because polls suggested they could be won, the NEA
nonetheless only won four of nine seats, despite spending hundreds of thousands of dollars in
several of the races.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The three tables below present all the election data.

