<html>
<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">Do Unions Represent Teachers?</h3>
<h3 align="center">Leaders Back Liberal Agenda; Many Members Don't</h3>
<h4 align="center">By Carl F. Horowitz</h4>
<h4 align="center">Investor's Business Daily - National Issue - September 17, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>As kids head back to school, their teachers have landed in the middle of the presidential race. And
GOP presidential candidate Bob Dole put them there.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In his acceptance speech to the Republican convention, Dole called on the public to support
school teachers but oppose their unions.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''I say this not to the teachers,'' he said, ''but to their unions: If education were a war, you would
be losing it. . . . When I am president, I will disregard your political power, for the sake of the
parents, the children, the schools and the nation.''

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>At first glance, it seems a contradiction to speak out for teachers but attack their unions.

<p>Yet there's a logic to it - the leaders of the teachers' unions are Democratic Party activists; many
teachers are not. Union leaders, commanding huge sums of cash, back strong liberal positions,
despite the views of many of their members.

<p>The 2.2 million-member National Education Association and the American Federation of
Teachers, with about 900,000 members, have sent huge contingents of delegates to every
Democratic Party convention since 1976. About 10% of the delegates in '92 were NEA members.

<p>It was much the same this August in Chicago. Of the 4,320 regular delegates, 480, or 11%, were
from the NEA (363) or AFT (117). Each union also accounted for several dozen of the 605
alternates, the Democratic National Committee said.

<p>The unions have a lot of money to throw around, too. NEA and AFT take in a combined $1.3
billion a year, mainly from dues, says Charlene Haar, president of the Education Policy Institute, a
Washington-based think tank. This money goes to a wide range of member services, including
information and seminars, as well as political field organizing. Haar co-wrote the '94 book, ''The
NEA and AFT: Teacher Unions in Power and Politics.''

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>John Berthoud, vice president of the Arlington, Va.-based Alexis de Tocqueville Institution,
estimates NEA now spends $39 million a year on some 1,500 political field organizers throughout
the U.S.

<p>These funds do not include those of the union's political action committee or other offshoot
groups.

<p>Federal Election Commission data for the 1993-94 election cycle show the NEA contributed $2.2
million to Democratic candidates, but only $25,800 to Republican candidates.

<p>These sums do not include the national NEA's ''soft-money'' donations to national and state party
organizations. Nor do they include state and local chapter donations to parties and candidates,
virtually all Democrat.

<p>Given their size, it's not surprising NEA and AFT members form a large pool of unpaid
volunteers, assisting with phone banks, canvassing and polling.

<p>The NEA has endorsed more than 250 candidates for Congress this year -not one a Republican.
Both the NEA and AFT have endorsed President Clinton's re-election.

<p>But there's another side to the story: the teachers themselves. Many of them resist becoming
adjuncts to the Democratic Party. Besides that, far from all teachers even belong to a union.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Almost 40% of the National Education Association's members call themselves Republicans,
according to the NEA's own polls.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In November, the Washington-based polling firm, Peter D. Hart Research Associates, asked AFT
members how they would vote in the next congressional race. About 40% planned to support the
Democratic candidate, 16% the GOP candidate, and another 22% weren't sure.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>At the Republican convention in San Diego, 34 delegates were NEA members.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>EPI's Haar says teachers are split one-third each Democrats, Republicans and independents.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>About 25% to 30% of all public school teachers do not belong to a union, while almost no private
school teachers belong, Haar said. Many teachers are nonunion out of personal conviction, as well
as for financial reasons.

<p>Why would so many teachers belong to unions that back politicians and causes they may actually
oppose?

<p>One explanation is that labor law allows NEA and AFT to act as gatekeepers, much as it does
other unions. In states with collective bargaining laws for teachers, unions can make teachers join,
or pay ''agency fees'' in lieu of joining, as a condition of employment. In those states, teachers with
different political views must still pay the union or not get a job.

<p>Combined national, state and local annual dues for NEA and AFT members, willing or not, range
from around $300 to $700.

<p>For teachers who do back their unions, there's a good reason for it. Unions overwhelmingly
represent teachers in public schools. And public employees' unions have a distinct agenda, argues
Rutgers University economist Leo Troy, one of Haar's co-authors.

<p>Old- style unionism focused on working conditions and job security. Today's newer kind, found
mainly in the public sector, pursues income redistribution, he observed in his own book, ''The
New Unionism in the New Society.''

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''The New Unionism has yet to see a tax it doesn't like,'' he wrote.

<p>Teachers' unions thus have an interest in forming cadres for the party of income redistribution -
the Democrats.

<p>Berthoud of the De Tocqueville Institution did some calculation early this year. If Congress were
to pass NEA's legislative program, he said, federal spending would go up $702 billion a year. And
almost all of it would go to health care and Social Security.

<p>NEA officials insist they place education above party politics.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''I think we have a long history of making the schools better,'' said NEA Government Relations
Director Mary Teasley.

<p>Rank and file don't have a problem with that goal. The Hart poll for AFT revealed 58% of
teachers see improving education as one of the two top nationwide election issues.

<p>Mark Mellman, president of a Washington consulting firm that has done confidential polls on
teacher attitudes and that has numerous Democrat clients, says union leaders take their cue from
the members.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''Teachers' unions reflect attitudes of their members,'' he said.

<p>In fact, the NEA's board recently voted to affirm a commitment to bipartisanship. Union heads
themselves can sound like today's Republicans.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''Time is running out on public education. . . . The dissatisfaction that people feel is very basic,''
noted AFT President Albert Shanker.

<p>Yet the unions seem in conflict with the GOP on two key education issues: giving certain eligible
parents vouchers to use as they see fit, which backers say means transferring kids to private
schools; and contracting out public school services to private firms.

<p>Candidate Dole has proposed vouchers of $1,000 for grades K-8 and $1,500 for grades 9-12 to
eligible parents for a private-school education. Funding for each voucher would be divided
between Washington and the states.

<p>The unions vigorously oppose such a measure.

<p>Private contracting enjoys support among free- market advocates. School districts typically
underestimate the true costs of services, argues Reason Foundation education specialist Janet
Beales.

<p>But contracting doesn't sit well with teachers' unions.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''NEA and AFT leadership are vehemently opposed to contracting out,'' Haar said. ''Opening up
competition in service delivery runs the risk of fewer union members and fee payers.''

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>It also might explain why teachers' unions organize workers tangential to teaching. For years
NEA and AFT have organized bus drivers, cafeteria workers and other school employees.

<p>In the 1993-94 school year, about a fourth of NEA's rolls were not full-time teachers. They
included support staff, retired teachers, ''life members,'' agency-fee payers and students.

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
