<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">"E Pluribus Union"</h3>
<h4 align="center">The Detroit News - Editorial</h4>
<h4 align="center">Sunday, September 1, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On the eve of Labor Day, teachers unions find themselves caught in the national political
spotlight. Their powerful presence at the Democratic National Convention has been highlighted
by pundits, and a national audience watched Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole dress
them down. Union apologists now hope to deflect public scrutiny by hiding behind Americans'
respect for local teachers.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But the politicization of our schools as a result of union politics is a legitimate issue. Both the
National Education Association (NEA), America's largest union, and the American Federation of
Teachers (AFT), an AFL-CIO affiliate, contribute overwhelmingly to Democratic candidates.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>So far in the 1995-1996 election cycle, 99.1 percent of NEA political action committee (PAC)
contributions and 98.6 percent of AFT PAC monies have gone to Democrats, according to a
recent analysis by a non-profit Washington think tank, the Alexis de Tocqueville Institution. The
teachers unions' partisanship is so pronounced they make the much-vilified Tobacco Institute and
the National Rifle Association - which have given 78.3 percent and 80.1 percent of their PAC
funds, respectively, to Republican candidates - look wildly bipartisan.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The unions' spending contrasts with their members' attitudes. Forty percent of NEA members
reportedly are Democrats, but roughly 30 percent are Republicans and 30 percent independents. 
In an internal AFT poll, 54 percent of the members surveyed said they would support
congressional candidates favorable to the Clinton administration, but 26 percent said they would
support candidates who opposed it.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The NEA's strong-arm political lobbying led Forbes magazine to dub it the "National Extortion
Association" and prompted a U.S. News and World Report columnist to charge that "the NEA,
the giant dinosaur of educational policy, is the largest single reason why the public-school system
seems almost impervious to real reform. Its clear goal is power over a monopolistic system...."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Bob Dole stressed in his acceptance speech that in attacking the unions, he wasn't attacking
teachers. It's a fair distinction. There is plenty of evidence that unions place their own interests
ahead of the interests of classroom teachers and the kids they instruct. The unions' resistance to
merit pay hardly serves their best teachers, for instance, but it does help keep the pressure on for
higher salaries and more education spending.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Here in Michigan, the power of the teachers unions has been restrained by new laws forbidding
strikes and levying automatic fines in case of walkouts. That's a big reason schools are opening
this year with little of the trouble that has characterized opening day in the past.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Legislature should also consider laws giving teachers the freedom to choose whether they
want to pay the union to bargain for them in the first place (all teachers in most districts must
render the union a fee to cover the cost of "representing" them). Freeing teachers from this
coercion would constitute a giant step toward meaningful academic freedom in the classroom. It
would also force unions to compete more vigorously for the affections of teachers if they want to
stay in business.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The unions don't fairly represent the attitudes of the rank-and-file. And if the unions claim
otherwise, then they shouldn't have any qualms about giving teachers a say in whether teachers
want union bargaining services - much less spend a chunk of teacher paychecks on political causes
in which they may have little interest.
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
