<html>
<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><em><strong>"The NEA's Fiscal Agenda - Bad News for Kids"</strong></em></h3>
<h4 align="center"><strong>Remarks of John Berthoud</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong><u>July 1, 1996</u></strong></h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>1. Introduction</strong>

<p>One would be hard-pressed to find a legislative and political agenda more damaging to the
interests of America's children than that of the National Education Association.  This is the clear
conclusion of three Tocqueville Institution studies of the NEA.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>We have conducted a detailed fiscal review of the NEA's <em>Legislative Program for the
104<sup>th</sup>Congress</em> and this morning, I'd like to outline the <em>Legislative Program's</em> impact on 1) deficits
and 2) entitlements -- two obvious areas of concern for children.  We have also done two fiscal
profiles of the Members of Congress that NEA-PAC is supporting and opposing and I'll provide a
summary of these findings.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>II. Deficits</strong>

<p>In our analysis of the <em>NEA Legislative Program</em>, we matched the proposals in their wish list to
CBO cost estimates of corresponding bills and came to several stunning conclusions.  Most
significantly, we found that if every item was enacted, federal spending would increase by at least
$702 billion per year.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>I should stress that we believe this figure is a conservative estimate.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>If not funded by deficits, the NEA agenda would translate into an annual tax increase of
$10,554 on a family of four.  The tax increase would be 13 times the size of that in the 1993
budget package.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>While the NEA claims they'd like to lower the federal deficit, given the magnitude of the funds
required, we believe that the much more likely result of adoption of the NEA Agenda would be
a) a large tax increase <em>and</em> b) a substantial increase in the federal deficit.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>III. Entitlements</strong>

<p>The NEA of course tries to claim that it is more than a mere union -- they argue that much of its
agenda is driven by the best interests of children.  This contention however, is completely
contradicted by analyzing their entitlements agenda.  On issues like Social Security and Medicare,
their <em>Legislative Program</em> again is diametrically opposed to the interests of America's kids.  Let
me give you several examples:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>All told, the NEA would expand Social Security benefits for today's retirees by $126.8 billion
per year.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>For each dollar in new spending on children and education that the NEA proposes (over $24
billion annually), it advocates $5.24 in new spending on Social Security.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>While the debate in Washington is (correctly, I'd argue) about how much and how fast to raise
the Social Security retirement age, NEA is advocating lowering the retirement age.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>For Medicare, they oppose many common-sense reforms such as means-testing.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p>In sum, our major entitlement programs face grave fiscal imbalances in the coming years which
will require big sacrifices by today's children and the NEA not only is doing nothing to correct
these problems but is seriously adding to them.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>IV. PAC Contributions</strong>

<p>The NEA backs up their advocacy of big government with their campaign contributions.  The
Tocqueville Institution has done two analyses on this issue -- one which we just released last
week.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In our new study, we have looked at NEA-PAC contributions to 1996 House and Senate
candidates.  From January 1995 through the end of April 1996, the NEA's Political Action
Committee has contributed $643,030 to Congressional candidates.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Analyzing the Members running in 1996 who have served in the 104<sup>th</sup> Congress, it is clear that the
NEA is financing candidates who have voted to expand government, while opposing those who
have voted to cut it.  NEA-backed Senate and the House candidates on average voted during the
first session of the 104<sup>th</sup> Congress to increase annual federal spending by $30.4 billion and $28.9
billion respectively.  The Senate and House candidates that the NEA is opposing voted to cut
government by $31.8 billion and $32.4 billion respectively.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Clearly, despite the NEA's rhetoric that their fiscal agenda is just to stop draconian cuts in
government, in reality the net cuts made by the Members they are working to defeat have been
modest -- about 2 percent of total federal spending.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While NEA-backed Members have voted for increases about as big as the cuts voted for by
NEA-opposed Members, there is more to the story.  Of course, many NEA-supported Members
did not have an opportunity to vote for the spending increase legislation they are espousing.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>We can get a better idea of the real agendas of NEA-backed Members by looking at their
legislative wish lists -- the bills these Members are sponsoring and cosponsoring.  We have done
that in an earlier study of NEA-PAC contributions to House Members running for re-election in
1994 and found that the average NEA-backed Member had an agenda to increase federal
spending by $302 billion per year.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Thus, the NEA is spending hundreds of thousands of dollars in PAC money to a) defeat Members
who have voted for modest cuts in the size of government, and b) support Members who have
voted for modest increases, but who if given control of the legislative agenda would radically
expand government -- by about 20 percent.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>V. Conclusion</strong>

<p>This portrait of the NEA is not pretty, but this is what the numbers tell us.  The political and
legislative agenda of the NEA would a) increase taxes, b) increase deficits, and c) greatly add to
the coming crises of our major entitlement programs.  The net result is devastation for America's
children.
</body>
</html>
