<html>
<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>A Fiscal Analysis of NEA and AFL-CIO Contributions to</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>1996 Congressional Races</strong></h3>
<h4 align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center">AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 126</h4>
<h4 align="center">June 25, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Executive Summary</strong>

<p>While the two most prominent labor organizations in American politics -- the AFL-CIO and the
National Education Association -- claim that their fiscal agenda is simply to stop "draconian"
cutting of government, analysis of their PAC contributions for the 1996 election cycle and voting
records of the 104th Congress reveals a very different story.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>The Members of Congress that they are opposing have voted to cut government, but only by
rather modest amounts -- about two percent of federal spending.</li>
  <li>The Members that these two labor groups are backing, however, have not supported the status
quo, but rather have been voting to increase the size and scope of the federal government.</li>
  <li>The size of the net cuts voted for by labor-opposed Members roughly equals the size of the net
increases voted for by labor-backed Members.  Thus, if the cutters have been "radical," the
labor-backed Members have been just as radical in their record of support for larger
government.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>A Fiscal Analysis of NEA and AFL-CIO Contributions to</strong>

<p align="center"><strong>1996 Congressional Races</strong>

<p align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President

<p align="center"><strong>I. Introduction</strong>

<p>The two most prominent labor organizations in American politics, the AFL-CIO and the National
Education Association, are again poised to take a major role in American national  elections. 
While arguably unions have had a diminished voice in recent elections, labor leaders are
determined to have a substantial impact on the 1996 results.  Gerald W. McEntee, president of the
American Federation of State, County &amp; Municipal Employees (an AFL-CIO affiliate), has called
the 1996 election "Armageddon."<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Through the end of April 1996 -- half a year before the election -- the two labor groups combined
had already contributed in excess of <em>$850,000</em> to 1996 congressional candidates.  More campaign
contributions will follow, as will independent expenditures -- the AFL-CIO for example is
planning on spending $21 million on ads and $14 million on grassroots organizing.  Members of
the NEA and AFL-CIO as well as political observers should be very interested in knowing where
all this money is going.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>II. The NEA's and AFL-CIO's Stated Views on the Size of Government</strong>

<p>The battle over the size and scope of the federal government has been the preeminent topic of the
104th Congress.  Both the NEA and the AFL-CIO have sought to portray the budget-cutting
efforts in the 104th Congress as draconian.  These supposedly drastic cuts are the reason why
both labor organizations have fought many proposed changes in spending and are now seeking to
defeat the Members of Congress who voted for these changes.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The NEA claims that Members of Congress supporting cuts have undertaken a "budget blitz that
aims to decimate federal funding for America's classrooms and schoolchildren."<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a> The Congress's
efforts to cut education and training have been termed an "assault on all fronts" and "an
ideologically-driven amputation."<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a> The NEA has also asked, "How can we tell children we are
cutting the budget to protect their future when the result will be to destroy the present."<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The AFL-CIO similarly has tried to portray the efforts of Members of the 104th Congress as
radical.  The group doesn't claim advocacy of big government but rather simply opposition to
budget changes that would "force long-term cuts in education, Medicare, Medicaid and other
programs that serve working families - while they award massive tax breaks to the rich."<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a> They
have been opposing "deep" spending cuts and "slashes" in programs because "working people,
seniors, students and others would be hit hard."<a href="#N_6_"><sup>(6)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While opposing radical cuts and "slashing," the labor groups have tried to portray themselves as
supporting reasonable cuts in federal spending.  Keith Geiger, President of the NEA, suggested
that the 104th Congress adopt the following as a guideline: "Congress intends to relentlessly cut
wasteful spending and to eliminate unnecessary functions of government.  At the same time,
because we believe in expanding opportunity for <em>all </em>Americans, we pledge to accomplish what
previous Congresses conspicuously failed to do: Fully funding Head Start and Title I, and
expanding college grants and loans so that no qualified American is denied a higher education."<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a>
In the aggregate, it seems that Geiger is advocating a policy of budget neutrality -- more spending
in some areas, but less in others.  While perhaps not advocating a net cut in federal spending,
there is certainly no hint of support for expansion in net federal spending.  The NEA seems to be
claiming a position of keeping total federal spending as is, while shifting money from "wasteful"
areas to higher priorities.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In sum, both groups are portraying themselves as opponents of radical cuts, but neither wants to
appear to be advocating an increase in the size of government.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This paper seeks to analyze these groups' portrayal of their own agendas through an examination
of the records of Members they are supporting and opposing in 1996.  To do this, this paper looks
at all NEA and AFL-CIO congressional campaign contributions for the 1996 election cycle and
matches these up with figures on how supported and opposed Members voted to change the
budget in the first session of the 104th Congress.  The campaign contribution figures come from
these groups' Federal Election Commission reports, covering all contributions made from January
1995 through the end of April 1996.  Over this entire period, the NEA's Political Action
Committee (PAC) has contributed $643,030 to Congressional candidates.  The AFL-CIO's PAC
has contributed $209,880.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The tool used for analysis of these Members' votes was the VoteTally database of  the nonpartisan
National Taxpayers Union Foundation.  VoteTally tracks every vote by Members  to increase or
decrease the size of government (using mostly Congressional Budget Office cost estimates). 
VoteTally's most recent release, which was used for this report, covers the entire first session of
the 104th Congress.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>All Members of the 104th Congress who are running for election in 1996 are included in this
analysis.<a href="#N_8_"><sup>(8)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>III. NEA Contribution Patterns</strong>

<p>Tables 1 and 2 present an outline of the spending patterns of 1996 candidates that the NEA is
either supporting or opposing through its contributions.
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<table border cellpadding=5 width="84%">
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="50%">
<p align="center">Table 1. Spending of Members and NEA Contributions</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top" width="49%">Net Annual Increase or Decrease in
Government Spending Voted for in
the First Session of the 104th
Congress</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-supported Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top">+$30.4 billion</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-supported House candidates</td>
<td valign="top">+$28.9 billion</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-opposed Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top">-$31.8 billion</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-opposed House candidates</td>
<td valign="top">-$32.4 billion</td></tr></table>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The NEA is financing candidates who have voted to expand government, while opposing those
who have voted to cut it.  The candidates for the Senate and the House that the NEA is
supporting voted on average to increase annual federal spending by $30.4 billion and $28.9 billion
respectively.  The Senate and House candidates that the NEA is opposing voted to cut
government by $31.8 billion and $32.4 billion respectively.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Nine of the eleven Senate candidates receiving NEA donations voted to increase government. 
Only 12 out of 33 House and Senate Members running for the Senate in 1996 voted for bigger
government.  The NEA has thus contributed to almost all the Members running for the Senate
who want to increase government.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<table border cellpadding=5 width="64%">
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="70%">
<p align="center">Table 2. Percent of Candidates With A Net Voting Record

<p align="center">To Cut the Size of Government</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-supported Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top" width="29%">18.2%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-supported House candidates</td>
<td valign="top">13.4%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-opposed Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top">100.0%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">NEA-opposed House candidates</td>
<td valign="top">100.0%</td></tr></table>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>All of the candidates that the NEA has contributed money against voted to cut the size of
government.  But these Members have only voted for modest cuts -- about two percent of federal
spending.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While this study concludes that Members that the NEA is supporting have voted to slightly
increase the size of government, a previous AdTI analysis of their legislative wish lists -- the bills
they are sponsoring and cosponsoring -- suggests much more expansive visions for government. 
That study<a href="#N_9_"><sup>(9)</sup></a> showed that the average House candidate supported by the NEA during the 1994
election cycle had an agenda to increase federal spending by $302.2 billion per year.  While of
course the list of Members opposed by NEA in 1994 and in 1996 will include some different
individuals, it is still probably reasonable to view the two groups as being similar politically.<a href="#N_10_"><sup>(10)</sup></a>
Accepting the fundamental comparability of the two groups, this huge discrepancy between what
the 1994 group was sponsoring and what the 1996 group was voting for (a net increase of $28.9
billion) shows the power of control over the legislative agenda.  Presumably, many of the bills that
NEA-supported Members wished to pass never got  a vote during the 104th Congress.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This conclusion about the importance of agenda-setting is furthered by the relative similarity of
the legislative agendas of the group of Members that the NEA opposed in 1994 and the votes
taken by the group of Members that the NEA is opposing in 1996.  The candidates that NEA
opposed in 1994 had legislative agendas (as reflected in their sponsorship of bills) that would on
average have cut federal spending by $22.6 billion per year.  The closeness of this figure to the
average of the votes of the group being opposed this year (a net cut of $32.4 billion) suggests that
these Members had a greater ability to set the agenda.  We can conclude that the group of
Members opposed by the NEA in 1996 have voted in a manner consistent with what the 1994
group "promised" through their sponsorship of legislation.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>IV. AFL-CIO Contribution Patterns</strong>

<p>Tables 3 and 4 present the same data for the candidates that the AFL-CIO is supporting and
opposing.
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<table border cellpadding=5 width="84%">
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="50%">
<p align="center">Table 3. Spending of Members and AFL-CIO Contributions</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top" width="49%">Net Annual Increase or Decrease in
Government Spending Voted for in
the First Session of the 104th
Congress</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-supported Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top">+$33.7 billion</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-supported House candidates</td>
<td valign="top">+$32.2 billion</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-opposed Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top">-$29.9 billion</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-opposed House  candidates</td>
<td valign="top">-$33.6 billion</td></tr></table>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The profiles of Members that the AFL-CIO is supporting and opposing closely resemble the
profiles of Members that the NEA is supporting and opposing.  AFL-CIO-backed Members have
voted to increase government by about the same amount that the AFL-CIO-opposed Members
have voted to cut it.  The candidates it is backing for the Senate and the House voted on average
to increase annual federal spending by $33.7 billion and $32.2 billion respectively.  Members that
it is opposing who are running for election to the Senate and the House voted to cut government
by $29.9 billion and $33.6 billion respectively.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<table border cellpadding=5 width="64%">
<tr>
<td colspan="2" valign="top" width="70%">
<p align="center">Table 4. Percent of Candidates With A Net Voting Record

<p align="center">To Cut the Size of Government</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-supported Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top" width="29%">12.5%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-supported House candidates</td>
<td valign="top">8.0%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-opposed Senate candidates</td>
<td valign="top">100.0%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">AFL-CIO-opposed House candidates</td>
<td valign="top">100.0%</td></tr></table>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>As was the case with the NEA, all Members that the AFL-CIO is working to defeat have voted to
cut the size of government.  And again, they were on average only voting to cut it modestly -- by
about two percent.  87 percent of AFL-CIO-backed Senate candidates and 92 percent of
AFL-CIO-backed House candidates voted for bigger government.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>V. Conclusion</strong>

<p>While the Members of Congress that these labor groups oppose are not supporting draconian cuts
in government, each of these organizations has made a clear choice in their PAC contributions. 
They are opposing candidates who have voted to trim government and instead they are supporting
Members who have voted to expand it.  "Following the money" has shown that (contrary to their
statements) <em>these groups: a) support bigger government, and b) are opposed to even limited
efforts to cut government.</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>An interesting finding of this paper is that the cuts voted for by labor-opposed Members are
roughly equal in size to the increases voted for by labor-backed Members.  If the Members these
groups are targeting for defeat have been voting for "radical" cuts, that same term must be applied
to the expansive agendas of their supporters.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Endnotes</strong>
<a name="N_1_">
<p>1. </a> Labor organizations began their renewed efforts in electoral politics earlier this year in the
special election to fill the seat of Senator Bob Packwood.  AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said
after that election that, "The Oregon race provides a vital first chapter in a new textbook on
politics we're going to write this year, as we build the core of a powerful new grassroots
movement." ("Democrat Wyden Wins Packwood's Seat in Senate in Mail-Ballot Election," <em>BNA
Daily Labor Report</em>, February 1, 1996, Page A11.)
<a name="N_2_">
<p>2. </a> Keith Geiger, "The Other Class War," (NEA advertisement), <em>The Washington Post</em>, October
24, 1995, Page C4.
<a name="N_3_">
<p>3. </a> Ibid.
<a name="N_4_">
