<html>
<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>Judging an Interest Group by the Politicians It Keeps:</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>An Analysis of NEA-PAC Contributions to House Races</strong></h3>
<h4 align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President, Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 120</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>May 1, 1996</strong></h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong><hr>
</strong>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Executive Summary</strong>

<p>It is said that you can judge individuals by the company they keep.  The same principle can be
applied to interest groups.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A review of contributions by the Political Action Committee of the National Education
Association reveals that the Congress that NEA is seeking to elect would radically change the
direction of American government.  Most significantly, NEA's ideal Congress would vastly
expand federal spending and taxation.  The average House candidate supported by the NEA
during the last election cycle had an agenda to increase federal spending by $302.2 billion per
year.  On the other hand, the candidates that NEA opposed had a net agenda to cut federal
spending by $22.6 billion per year.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Despite NEA's pledge of support for America's children, if NEA could have the Congress it
wanted, it would mean either hundreds of billions of dollars in new taxes on America's families or
hundreds of billions of dollars in deficits for future generations.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But regardless of the impact that an NEA Congress might have on America's kids, NEA members
can rest assured.  Despite a very big tax-and-spend agenda, NEA's ideal Congress would still
maintain NEA's special Washington, DC property tax exemption.  The ideal NEA Congress
would also be strongly opposed to educational choice and vouchers for low-income children.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Judging an Interest Group by the Politicians It Keeps:</strong>

<p align="center"><strong>An Analysis of 1993-94 NEA-PAC Contributions to House Races</strong>

<p align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President, Alexis de Tocqueville Institution

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>I. Introduction</strong>

<p>The National Education Association (NEA) has become one of the most powerful constituencies
in American politics.  NEA and its state affiliates are a major participant in the legislative process
in Washington and in the 50 state capitals.  The national and state organizations also contribute
millions of dollars to political campaigns at all levels.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The amounts that NEA spends to achieve influence in the policy process and elections are
staggering.  They annually spend $39 million on 1,500 field organizers around the
country.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a>During the 1994 election cycle, the NEA-PAC spent $2 million on House campaigns,
and was the fifth largest PAC contributor in the United States.<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a> And beyond legislative and
executive branch battles in Washington and the states, NEA is actively involved in numerous
court battles as well.  It is no wonder that many view the NEA as the nation's most powerful and
influential union.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Given this clout, it is important for both the NEA's members as well as the public at large to see
what kind of Congress the NEA is seeking to create.  Who are the candidates for Congress that
the NEA is supporting through campaign contributions and who are they opposing?

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This paper assesses three key measures of significance to voters and/or the NEA to get such an
understanding.  First, the paper examines the aggregate spending agendas of candidates supported
or opposed by the NEA.  This analysis gives a good overall view of the political ideology that we
would see in NEA's ideal Congress.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The paper then looks at two votes that have been of central concern to the NEA during the 104th
Congress: the NEA's District of Columbia property tax exemption and educational vouchers for
low-income Washington, D.C. children.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In all three cases, we cross-index contributions by NEA for and against members with their
records.  AdTI analyzed contributions to House races instead of Senate races since the patterns
for 435 House seats are more distinctive than for the 35 Senate seats up in 1994.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>II. Spending Agendas of Candidates</strong>

<p>NEA-PAC, the political action committee of the National Education Association, contributed
money to 306 House races in the 1994 cycle.<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a> In 259 of those races, there were incumbents
running who thus had a legislative record in the 103rd Congress.  We can analyze the legislative
agendas established by those 259 members during the 103rd Congress to get a good idea of the
kind of Congress that NEA wants.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>To achieve an understanding of the agenda of these members, AdTI used BillTally, a
computerized tracking system developed by the National Taxpayers Union Foundation (NTUF)
that reports a cost estimate for every legislative proposal in each Congress.  The BillTally data
come from the Congressional Budget Office and similar sources.  Agenda totals for individual
members are developed by cross-indexing each member's sponsorship and cosponsorship records
with the cost estimates for the bills.  For this paper, the data for the 103rd Congress are used.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In 1994, NEA supported 206 candidates who were incumbents and thus had established a
legislative agenda during the 103rd Congress.  Those 206 members had an average agenda in the
103rd Congress to increase federal spending by $302.2 billion per year.  This represents <em>a 20%
increase in the size and scope of the federal government</em>.  NEA opposed 53 incumbents who ran
again.<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a> These members had a strikingly different profile -- they had legislative agendas during the
103rd Congress that would on average have cut federal spending by $22.6 billion per year.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><img src="neapac1.gif" width="504" height="319" align="top" >

<p>We can conclude that if the NEA elected the Congress it wanted, annual federal spending would
radically increase.  This finding corresponds with earlier AdTI research on the NEA legislative
agenda which showed that if every idea that the NEA proposes in their <em>Legislative Program for
the 104th Congress </em>were adopted into law, federal spending would increase by $702 billion per
year.<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a> Clearly, NEA is supporting candidates who will effectuate the large increase in taxing and
spending proposed in their legislative agenda.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>III. Special Tax Break for NEA</strong>

<p>While NEA's ideal Congress would apparently radically increase spending, and either taxes or
deficits (paid for by future generations, i.e., America's children), there was one vote during the
104th Congress where NEA-supported members acted like fiscal conservatives and supported a
tax break.  Unfortunately, that tax break would only benefit NEA members -- it was to continue
their exemption from property taxes in the District of Columbia.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A special federal charter granted by Congress to the NEA (normally this special treatment is
reserved for non-political groups such as the Red Cross and Boy Scouts) allows the group to pay
no tax on its downtown Washington office building.  Recently renovated, the headquarters has an
assessed value of $65 million.<a href="#N_6_"><sup>(6)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This special status was granted to the NEA in 1907, at a time when the group and American
education were entirely different, and it could truly be said that the NEA had simply a benevolent
or public purpose.  89 years later, both the NEA and American education have evolved
tremendously.  The change in the NEA was recognized by the IRS in 1978 when NEA was
reclassified as a labor union, a decision which was affirmed by a federal court a year later.<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Last fall, in an amendment to the Washington, D.C. appropriations bill, the House voted on
whether to maintain this special break for the NEA.  The measure ultimately failed by a narrow
vote of 213-210.<a href="#N_8_"><sup>(8)</sup></a> A vast majority of members who received 1994 NEA financial support (173
out of 176 -- 98%) voted to maintain the NEA's special tax break.<a href="#N_9_"><sup>(9)</sup></a> Most other members
opposed it.  Among those who had 1994 campaigns where neither candidate received NEA-PAC
financing, 97 of 128 (76%) supported ending the special break.  Among members who had
opponents financed by the NEA, 110 of 119 (92%) supported eliminating the exemption.  The
chart below graphically presents the split in Congress.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><img src="neapac2.gif" width="601" height="352" align="top" >

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>It seems clear that the NEA's expenditure of $2 million on House campaigns in 1994 was a good
investment and helped to protect the lucrative tax break which it enjoys every year, valued at $1.6
million according to the Washington, D.C. Department of Finance and Revenue.  Obviously,
NEA's failure to pay its share of property taxes has required city businesses and residents to make
up the difference.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>IV. Vouchers for Low-Income Kids?</strong>

<p>Another issue of central importance to the NEA in the 104th Congress has been the debate over
proposed vouchers for low-income children in the District of Columbia.  Like the NEA tax
exemption, the proposal was also voted on in the House as an amendment to the appropriations
bill for the District of Columbia.<a href="#N_10_"><sup>(10)</sup></a> The vouchers were actually $3,000 scholarships that would be
made available to children of low-income D.C. residents to attend public, private, or parochial
schools anywhere in the greater Washington area.<a href="#N_11_"><sup>(11)</sup></a> The amendment passed the House but
ultimately never became law because of opposition in the Senate and White House.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>There was again great polarization on the vote on this issue between those House members
receiving NEA support and all other members.  162 out of 169 (96%) members who received
NEA contributions supported the NEA's position on vouchers for DC kids.  This contrasts sharply
with the members whose opponents were funded by the NEA -- 117 of 120 (98%) voted for the
vouchers.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Paralleling the NEA tax exemption vote, the most objective members -- those with 1994 races
where NEA contributed to neither candidate --  opposed the NEA and strongly supported school
vouchers.  117 of 129 members (91%) who had no NEA money for or against them in 1994
supported vouchers.  This perhaps suggests that free from the influence of NEA money and left to
their own devices, members might support school vouchers.  But at least in the 104th Congress,
the NEA succeeded in continuing the denial of vouchers to low-income District residents.  <em>Again,
these are the same residents who have to pay more in property taxes because of NEA's special
exemption.</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><img src="neapac3.gif" width="601" height="352" align="top" >

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>V. Conclusion</strong>

<p>The ideal Congress for the NEA would thus be very strongly opposed to choice and vouchers for
low-income children.  This has always been a central issue to the NEA and it is not surprising that
members who were financially backed by the union strongly opposed vouchers.  What is
interesting is our finding of overwhelming support for vouchers among all other members of
Congress.  Again, 91% of members who had no NEA money for or against them in 1994
supported vouchers.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Fiscally, NEA's ideal Congress would radically increase federal spending.  Despite NEA's pledge
of support for America's children, if NEA could have the Congress it wanted, it would mean
either hundreds of billions of dollars in new taxes on America's families or hundreds of billions of
dollars in deficits for future generations.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Finally, regardless of the impact that an NEA Congress might have on America's kids, NEA
members can rest assured.  Despite a very big tax-and-spend agenda, NEA's ideal Congress would
still maintain the NEA's special property tax exemption.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Endnotes</strong><a name="N_1_">

<p>1. </a> "Why Teachers Don't Teach," <em>U.S. News &amp; World Report</em>, February 26, 1996, Page 70. <a name="N_2_">

<p>2. </a> LynNell Hancock and Martha Brant, "Towns to Unions: Drop Dead!" <em>Newsweek</em>, November
27, 1995, Page 81. <a name="N_3_">

<p>3. </a> Besides contributing to one of the nominees in 306 races, NEA also made contributions to
about two dozen candidates who did not end up as the final nominee of their party. <a name="N_4_">

<p>4. </a> While some of the incumbents that NEA supported lost, all of the incumbents opposed by the
NEA nevertheless won. <a name="N_5_">

<p>5. </a> John Berthoud, "The Fiscal Impact of the NEA's Legislative Agenda," Arlington, VA: The
Alexis de Tocqueville Institution, March 1996. <a name="N_6_">

<p>6. </a> Robert Pambianco, "End Special Treatment for the National Education Association,"
<em>Intellectual Ammunition</em> (published by the Heartland Institute), May/June 1995. <a name="N_7_">

<p>7. </a> Ibid. <a name="N_8_">

<p>8. </a> The amendment was sponsored by Representative Henry Bonilla (R-TX). <a name="N_9_">

<p>9. </a> AdTI did not include in any of these totals members who didn't vote. <a name="N_10_">

<p>10. </a> The amendment was sponsored by Representative Steve Gunderson (R-WI). <a name="N_11_">

<p>11. </a> See John Berthoud, "Like Clinton's Daughter, Other Kids Deserve School Choice, Too," <em>The
Hartford Courant</em>, November 23, 1995.
</body>
