<html>
<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">The Fiscal Impact of</h3>
<h3 align="center">The NEA's Legislative Agenda</h3>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><h4 align="center">John E. Berthoud, Ph.D.</h4>
<h4 align="center">Vice President</h4>
<h4 align="center">The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center">March 4, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">Foreword by U. S. Representative Joe Scarborough

<p>George Orwell once said, "We have sunk to a depth at which the restatement of the obvious is the
first duty of intelligent men."  That is the grand and dignified service that the Alexis de
Tocqueville Institution has rendered with this report.  It puts in concrete numbers that which
those of us who have worked on education issues in the Congress have long thought.  Namely,
that the National Education Association has an agenda that is quite extravagant, that does not
have much to do with education, and that is, like so many wish lists unconstrained by reality,
expensive.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>If the Department of Education has become the mechanism by which local education dollars are
squandered, it is the National Education Association that has become the most prolific source of
ideas for squandering them.  Hence, the NEA's laundry list of legislative proposals ranging from
"Constitutional, Civil, and Human Rights Protection," to "Voting Reform," to what it terms the
"Preservation and Advancement of Good Public Policy."  Such subjects may be, at a time when
high schools are producing graduates who cannot read, distant from the concerns of the
educational community, but the NEA seems not to have noticed.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Not noticing reality, however, is something that the NEA appears to have developed into a high
art, and this is where the AdTI report is most revealing.  According to the report, if the NEA's
proposals were adopted into law, federal spending would increase by $702 billion per year,
resulting in a new tax burden of $10,554 per year for a family of four.  Leave aside the deleterious
effects such spending and tax increases would have on the nation's economy and on the budget of
the average family, the point is that the public rendered its judgment on the size and scope of the
government it wants in the historic 1994 elections and there is no indication that it will be
changing its mind soon.  It seems that for the NEA, time stopped in 1965, or perhaps 1933, and
has not moved since.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>These facts would almost be funny were it not for this: the NEA claims to represent 2.2 million
teachers across the United States.  That is over two million individuals charged with the
responsibility of educating and of helping to shape the character of the nation's future voters.  To
the extent that the NEA's agenda fails to represent those teachers, it is marching under borrowed
banners.  To the extent that the NEA actually is representing its members' views, it is a measure of
the yawning chasm that has developed between the culture of the country and the culture of the
education establishment.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"The philosophy of the schoolroom in one generation will be the philosophy of the government in
the next,"  Lincoln said.  That is undoubtedly true and it is the reason why Dr. Berthoud's report
on the cost of the NEA's policy agenda is so important.  It has been well said that Americans need
to be summoned to an honest reckoning of the cost of our spending appetites.  The Alexis de
Tocqueville Institution deserves great credit for revealing just how expensive such an appetite can
be. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Joe Scarborough represents the 1st Congressional District in Florida and is a lead sponsor of
the Back to Basics Education Reform Act</em>.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>The Fiscal Impact of</strong>

<p align="center"><strong>The NEA's Legislative Agenda</strong>

<p align="center">John E. Berthoud, Ph.D.

<p align="center">Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>"The issue simply put is whether you want to pay now or pay later" -- Keith Geiger, NEA
President</em><a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>I. Introduction</strong>

<p>The National Education Association (NEA) has long billed itself as an advocacy group for
education and not a union.  The NEA claims to be dedicated to the interests of children and
America's future.  However, a review of its <em>Legislative Program for the 104th Congress</em> reveals
that NEA's public policy agenda would be extremely costly for America's children.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>II. The NEA Agenda</strong>

<p>The NEA <em>Legislative Program</em>, while representing the group's 2.2 million members,<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a> is actually
established by the NEA's Legislative Committee and then adopted by the annual Representative
Assembly.<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a> The program is broken into three tiers, divided according to the level and intensity of
NEA activity on the issue.<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution has examined the NEA spending agenda, item by item, and
where possible ascribed a cost to each proposal.<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a> The primary tool used for this analysis has been
BillTally, a computerized tracking system developed by the National Taxpayers Union Foundation
(NTUF) that reports a cost estimate for every legislative proposal in each Congress.  The BillTally
data come from the Congressional Budget Office and similar sources.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For some items in the NEA agenda, no cost estimate was available, so they could not be included
in this report.  Hence, the numbers in this report <em>understate</em> the total cost of the NEA agenda.  All
cost estimates have been annualized, that is, they are expressed in terms of the average change in
spending in a single year.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>All told, if every idea that the NEA proposes were adopted into law, <em>federal spending would
increase by $702 billion per year</em>.  Table 1 summarizes its agenda.  The appendix to this paper
provides the detailed analysis used to arrive at the $702 billion total.<a href="#N_6_"><sup>(6)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>If this spending is financed by taxes, it would translate into an added burden of $10,554 per year
for a family of four.<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a> However, as will be argued below, the most likely outcome is that much of
this new spending will be financed by bigger federal deficits.  This would be ironic given NEA's
statements against deficits during the Reagan administration -- throughout those eight years, the
NEA made numerous pronouncements about the importance of deficit reduction and complained
that "record budget deficits" were responsible for squeezing critical programs.<a href="#N_8_"><sup>(8)</sup></a>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">

<table border cellpadding=5 width="99%">
