<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>III. A Generational Perspective</strong>

<p>One of the most ironic aspects of the NEA agenda is the huge fiscal burden it imposes on future
generations.<a href="#N_9_"><sup>(9)</sup></a> Despite NEA's claims to be an organization concerned first and foremost with
children, their legislative wish list has a strong bias in favor of today's retirees.  Perhaps this is not
surprising given that over 110,000 members of the NEA are retired.<a href="#N_10_"><sup>(10)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Beyond the massive taxes and/or deficits that its agenda would bequeath to future generations,
NEA makes no effort at long-term entitlement reform.  In fact, the NEA agenda would exacerbate
the problem posed by entitlements for future generations by actually <em>increasing spending</em> on
today's beneficiaries.  Given the coming financing crisis for programs such as Social Security and
Medicare, these types of policies will clearly harm America's children.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For Medicare and Medicaid, NEA supports a system with "protected benefits" and opposes any
shift of costs to beneficiaries or "any new barrier to eligibility for benefits under Medicare."  It
also opposes "any means test for Medicare" which would limit benefits for the wealthiest
retirees.<a href="#N_11_"><sup>(11)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For Social Security, NEA opposes reforms that many see as common sense, such as
means-testing.  Not only does NEA oppose increases in the age when benefits begin, but it
actually supports "reductions in the Social Security retirement age."  To put this position in
perspective, the Social Security retirement age is currently 65 and will slowly rise to 67 by the
year 2027.  By any demographic standard, even 67 is far too low.  If the retirement age had kept
pace with changes in life expectancy since the 1930s when Social Security was created, it would
be 76 today.<a href="#N_12_"><sup>(12)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But the devastating impact of the NEA Social Security agenda becomes clear only when we total
the cost: the NEA would expand federal spending on Social Security by <em>$126.8 billion per year</em>. 
While this is a stunning figure, it is important to note that there are other items NEA supports for
which cost estimates could not be obtained that would otherwise have added tens of billions of
dollars annually to the cost of its Social Security agenda.  For example, NEA also supports
"improved Social Security benefits for participants, especially low-income workers, dependents
and survivors."  Thus, the $126.8 billion is a very conservative figure.
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">

<p>Table 3 presents one point of comparison.  For each dollar in new spending for children and
education that NEA proposes (over $24 billion annually -- not an insubstantial amount), it
advocates $5.24 in new spending on Social Security.
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">

<table border cellpadding=5 width="99%">
<tr>
<td colspan="3" valign="top" width="6%">
