<tr>
<td valign="top">13</td>
<td valign="top">Social Security</td>
<td valign="top">$126.76 billion</td></tr></table>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>NEA writes of its political clout, "NEA, with an average of nearly 5,000 members in each of the
nation's 435 congressional districts, is in a unique position to use at-home lobbying efforts to
advance the cause of public education and improve the status of security of Association
members."<a href="#N_13_"><sup>(13)</sup></a> It would appear that the latter concerns about the status of Association members far
outweigh concerns for the cause of public education.<a href="#N_14_"><sup>(14)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>IV. More Federal Educational Dollars: Good Money After Bad?</strong>

<p>While the total amount of new spending that NEA proposes for children pales in comparison to
what it would like to spend on Social Security and other programs for the elderly, education
funding would still increase substantially.  99 percent ($24 billion) of the money listed under
"Children &amp; Education" in Table 3 is for increased federal education spending.  NEA is thus
advocating spending yet more federal dollars on education rather than enacting fundamental
reforms to solve the problems with America's schools.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Federal education spending in FY 1995 was $32.9 billion, which was 165 percent more than what
was spent in 1979 (29 percent more in real terms).<a href="#N_15_"><sup>(15)</sup></a> NEA would expand that by <em>73 percent</em>,
thereby furthering the federal role in education which has expanded markedly since the
Department of Education was created in October 1979.<a href="#N_16_"><sup>(16)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>NEA would also thereby further increase spending per pupil, and while the United States has been
sinking in recent years in international comparison of educational outputs, inputs (spending) have
been on the rise and already tower over those in most other nations.  With the exception of
Switzerland, the United States spends more on education per student than any other country in
the world -- almost 50 percent more than Germany and 85 percent more than Japan.<a href="#N_17_"><sup>(17)</sup></a> K-12 per
pupil spending, in inflation-adjusted terms, increased by 36.7% in the 1980's.<a href="#N_18_"><sup>(18)</sup></a> The NEA agenda
would thus continue a trend of more spending and more Washington involvement in education,
thus obscuring the importance of the real reforms that are needed for America's schools.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>V. Funding the NEA Agenda: Taxes or Deficits?</strong>

<p>NEA's agenda would vastly expand the size and scope of American government.  As indicated
above, if NEA paid for its agenda today, it would cost the average family of four over $10,000
per year.  NEA states that it supports a tax system which will not only pay for this massive agenda
but which will also collect enough revenues to actually start paying down the national debt.  While
discussing the deficit and its budget policies, NEA notes that while it is not the only priority,
"reducing the federal budget deficit is a priority for the country."<a href="#N_19_"><sup>(19)</sup></a> But realistically, the likely
outcome of the NEA agenda would be even larger deficits than we have today, which would have
to be paid off by future American families.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>There are several reasons for this conclusion.  First, the NEA specifically rejects many ideas that
would help pay for its agenda.  For example, while NEA has a very expansive health care agenda,
it opposes ending or even limiting the tax exemption of employer-provided health care
benefits.<a href="#N_20_"><sup>(20)</sup></a>And again, it specifically opposes many basic reforms of either the Social Security or
Medicare systems.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The second reason is simply politics.  It just is unrealistic to expect tax hikes of this magnitude to
be enacted.  The 1990 and 1993 budgets each raised taxes by several hundred billion dollars over
five years and both caused a tremendous outcry and voter rebellion in subsequent elections. 
According to the Congressional Budget Office, the 1993 budget package raised $259 billion over
five years.  Over a five year time period, <em>the NEA agenda would require over thirteen times as
much money as was raised in taxes by the 1993 budget package.</em> Beyond the electoral
consequences of such a tax hike, the damage to the nation's economy would be overwhelming. 
The political impossibility is clear.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><img src="neaage.gif" width="432" height="337" align="top" >

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Furthering this doubt that the NEA would actively champion and get enacted the trillions of
dollars in taxes needed to balance a budget reflecting NEA spending policies is its position that:
"NEA opposes any constitutional amendment imposing limitations on taxes or the federal
budget."<a href="#N_21_"><sup>(21)</sup></a> This statement reflects a long history of NEA opposition to a federal Balanced Budget
Amendment (BBA).  NEA, in fact, has been a leading opponent of the BBA.<a href="#N_22_"><sup>(22)</sup></a> When the BBA
was debated in the House of Representatives in January 1995, the NEA claimed that a BBA,
"would have forced deep, across-the-board cuts to domestic programs leading to the elimination
of education."<a href="#N_23_"><sup>(23)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The conclusion seems obvious.  Above and beyond an increase in taxation, enacting the NEA
legislative agenda would lead to massive deficits in America's future.  The NEA argues that
current efforts to balance the budget would be "cutting off our children's future."<a href="#N_24_"><sup>(24)</sup></a> An
examination of the <em>NEA Legislative Program for the 104th Congress</em> indicates that the charge
more accurately applies to its vision for America.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Appendix: Detailed Analysis of The NEA Legislative Agenda</strong>

<p>NEA's<em> Legislative Program for the 104th Congress</em> can be broken down into 22 discrete
categories.<a href="#N_25_"><sup>(25)</sup></a> Cost estimates for proposals in each of these categories were obtained from
BillTally, a computerized tracking system developed by the National Taxpayers Union Foundation
(NTUF) that reports a cost estimate for every bill in each Congress.  The NEA proposals were
matched to bills with an equivalent purpose.  The BillTally cost figures come from the
Congressional Budget Office and similar sources.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>All cost estimates represent the annual change in federal spending for each proposal.  Thus, the
figures for each of the 22 sections represent not the total spending that NEA wants for that areas,
but the annual incremental change.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Care was taken to eliminate double counting, that is, where the NEA agenda repeated itself, these
costs were not counted twice.  Also, every effort was made not to use a bill whose purposes
duplicated those of another bill used elsewhere in this study or use a bill which had some section
later enacted into law.  It is important to note that the cost of many ideas has never been
estimated, and in those cases the particular items are not listed.  Because of the magnitude of the
probable cost of items not included, even if all double-counting was not completely eliminated,
the total cost figures of this paper are conservative.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>1. Increased Federal Funding for Education</strong>

<p>NEA supports two types of added funding for Elementary-Secondary Education.  First, NEA
supports a program of general aid to state and local educational agencies.  Second, NEA supports
categorical assistance to local education agencies for special programs.  The total cost for both
parts of this section of the NEA agenda is conservatively estimated at $5,640 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>Aid for the disadvantaged</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $1,645 Million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 4323, The Neighborhood Schools Improvement Act, 102nd Congress.  Cost:
$700 million.  The bill provides disadvantaged students with early intervention
programs and scholarships.</li>
      <li>HR 4076, 102nd Congress.  Cost: $695 million.  The bill assures a quality
education for all children.</li>
      <li>S 2758, 102nd Congress, Sec. 5. ($250 million -- program in all 50 states during
the summer months to meet the educational needs of deprived children).</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
