Diet.  According to CBO, the cost is $1,104 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>Mental health and pupil services</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $420 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1524, 102nd Congress, Student Counseling and Assistance Network Act. 
The cost is $180 million.</li>
      <li>HR 1197, 102nd Congress, Children's and Communities Mental Health Systems
Improvement Act.  Cost: $240 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>Technological improvements</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $505 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 89, 103rd Congress, Authorizing a program of grants to the states and
establishing a technology agency within the Department of Education to improve
the use of technology in elementary and secondary schools.  Cost: $505 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>School construction, renovation, and repair; and aid for school libraries</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $822 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 92, 103rd Congress, The Neighborhood Schools Improvement Act.  Cost:
$822 million.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p align="center"><strong>2. Collective Bargaining</strong>

<p>NEA supports a "federal statute that would guarantee meaningful collective bargaining rights to
the employees of public schools, colleges, universities, and other postsecondary institutions." 
While such legislation would undoubtedly have an impact on federal spending, the cost is too
speculative to be included in this analysis.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>3. Children and Youth</strong>

<p>Under this category, NEA has legislative objectives that cost a total of $4,340 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>Federal assistance for early childhood education programs, including Head Start.</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $4,300 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 3842, 103rd Congress, The Head Start Act Amendments of 1994.  The
estimated cost of this bill is $4,300 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>Establishment and funding of programs and standards to protect children from physical, sexual,
or emotional abuse and/or neglect.</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $40 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 2573, 103rd Congress, A Bill to protect children from violence, sexual abuse,
neglect.  Cost in text is $40 million. </li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p align="center"><strong>4. Health Care Policy</strong>

<p>Of the many variants of overall health care reform, NEA supports the most expensive -- a 
national single-payer system.<a href="#N_26_"><sup>(26)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A single-payer scheme creates a system of total government control over health care.  As in
Canada, the federal government would collect the funds for health care and pay all the bills (hence
the name "single-payer").  The federal government would decide the total amount that could be
spent on health care.  States would administer plans, but under tight constraints from Washington. 
Medicare and Medicaid would be combined into the new system and private sector insurance
would  be virtually eliminated.  The estimated cost for a single-payer health care system is
$534,600 million.<a href="#N_27_"><sup>(27)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In addition to a single-payer system, NEA supports other programs with substantial costs.

<ol>
  <li>NEA also supports "strengthened occupational health and safety standards and programs with
diligent enforcement."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $90 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1280, 103rd Congress, The Comprehensive Occupational Safety and Health
Reform Act.  Estimated cost: $90 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>NEA also supports "a major federal commitment to HIV research to develop a preventive
agent, effective treatments, and a cure."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $715 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1538, 103rd Congress, The Comprehensive AIDS Prevention Act, $715
million annually.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>NEA supports, "Coverage for full men's and women's reproduction health care."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $560 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 26, 103rd Congress, The Reproductive Health Equity Act.  Cost estimate:
$560 million annually.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p>Total cost for this section: $535,965,000,000.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>A. Medicare and Medicaid</strong>

<p>NEA states that it supports strong Medicare and Medicaid systems with protected benefits.  A
policy of refusing to contemplate some benefit reductions today to save the Medicare system from
impending bankruptcy<a href="#N_28_"><sup>(28)</sup></a> places NEA in opposition to current reform efforts put forward by both
President Clinton and the Republican Congress.  Still, the NEA's positions will not mean any
additional spending -- only the prevention of reduction in costs.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While under the accounting guidelines of this paper, we can't count the savings that NEA opposes
here, it should be pointed out that they are substantial.  NEA, for example, opposes any
means-testing of Medicare.  Pete Peterson believes that comprehensive means-testing of all
entitlement benefits could save $71 billion per year by the year 2000.<a href="#N_29_"><sup>(29)</sup></a> As Peterson writes, "We
can either ask the affluent among our peers to make the sacrifice or we can ask our kids.  To insist
on doing the latter is to forget Thomas Jefferson's moral injunction to hold the future
harmless."<a href="#N_30_"><sup>(30)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>5. Constitutional, Civil, and Human Rights Protection</strong>

<p>A conservative estimate of the cost of this section of NEA's agenda is $295 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>NEA supports "federal legislation to combat violence against women, children and the elderly."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $295 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1133, 103rd Congress, "The Violence Against Women Act."  According to
the text of the bill, the cost is $295 million.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

