  </ol>
</ol>

<p align="center"><strong>13. Social Security</strong>

<p>As with Medicare and Medicaid, NEA again does not advocate any reductions in Social Security
spending, despite the fact that most current retirees are receiving benefits two to five times greater
than the actuarial value of what they and their employers put in.<a href="#N_32_"><sup>(32)</sup></a> Rather than trimming benefits,
the NEA advocates <em>increasing</em> spending on Social Security.  There can hardly be any action more
damaging to the nation's children than adding this type of fiscal burden to America's future
generations.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>By way of background, the spending growth in Social Security has truly been phenomenal over
the past 45 years.  In 1950, Social Security represented about one percent of the federal budget. 
Today, it represents about 25 percent.  And were it not for Social Security, federal outlays as a
percent of GNP would today just about equal what they were in 1950.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Combined with other programs, Social Security has meant a tremendous diversion in resources
towards elderly Americans.  Per capita federal spending on the elderly in FY 1990 amounted to
$11,466 compared to a scant $1,020 for those under age eighteen -- including education.<a href="#N_33_"><sup>(33)</sup></a> The
United States spends five times as much per capita on social welfare spending for the elderly as
we do for the non-elderly.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Contrary to popular belief, individuals don't have a special Social Security account containing the
money that they paid in.  Instead, Social Security has always operated on a "pay-as-you-go"
system whereby benefits paid out today come from today's workers and families.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>According to projections by the Social Security Board of Trustees, just to maintain the current
level of benefits, the Social Security and Medicare combined payroll taxes will have to jump from
16.5% to an astonishing 30.5% in 2025, under intermediate projections, and to 43.0% under
high-cost projections.  Keep in mind that recent trends have placed the U.S. economy closer to
the Trustees' more pessimistic high-cost assumptions than their intermediate assumptions.

<p>Total new spending proposed by the NEA in this section comes to $126,760 million.  The
specifics include:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>NEA supports a complete repeal of the so-called "Social Security Notch Adjustment."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $100,000 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>Social Security Administration.</li>
    </ol>
    <li>Notes:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>The notch adjustment ended a windfall for retirees born between 1917 - 1926
who received double, and in some cases triple, inflation adjustments to their base
Social Security payments.  In the 1970s, Congress shut off the spigot, indexing
benefits to the rate all other Social Security recipients received.  Consequently,
retirees in this cohort revolted under what they perceived as an unfair "reduction"
in benefits, even though their Social Security checks grew as fast as inflation! 
Roy Ferguson, an actuary who works in the Office of the Actuary at the Social
Security Administration, estimates total repeal of the "notch" at an astonishing $1
trillion over the next ten years, or $100 billion a year.</li>
      <li>Like other current recipients of Social Security, even without the adjustment
repeal, the "notch babies"  are still getting far more in benefits than what they
paid into the system.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>NEA supports "repeal of the spousal offset under Social Security."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $640 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1674, 103rd Congress.  According to the Social Security Administration, the
cost is $640 per year.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>NEA opposes "limitations on post-retirement earnings for Social Security recipients."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $1,520 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>CBO.</li>
    </ol>
    <li>Notes:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>This is the estimate for repeal of the earnings test, the point where working
beneficiaries over sixty-five give up one dollar in Social Security benefits for
every three dollars they earn from other sources. Social Security is a retirement
benefit, not a welfare program for those who chose to continue working past the
retirement age.  Since the inception  of the Social Security program, the earnings
test has been an integral part in maintaining the retirement characteristic of Social
Security.  The benefit is not, nor was it ever intended to be, a wage supplement.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>NEA supports "reductions in the Social Security retirement age."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $24,600 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>This figure is derived by using the inverse of the budgetary <em>savings</em> that have
been calculated to accrue from speeding up the currently scheduled increase in
the retirement age to 67.<a href="#N_34_"><sup>(34)</sup></a> The savings figure is the budgetary impact in the
ninth outyear which is not the full impact and thus is conservative (by the 11th
year, when the change is nearly fully implemented, the savings exceed $35
billion).  Given the ambiguous nature of NEA's statement, we opted for a
conservative estimate of the budgetary impact.  The actual impact could be much
larger.</li>
      <ol>
        <li>This is also a conservative estimate since deaths of potential recipients
between the ages of 63 and 67 would mean that lowering the retirement
age would add more beneficiaries than raising it would eliminate.</li>
      </ol>
    </ol>
    <li>Notes:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>While it certainly sounds nice, as most Americans would like to retire early, such
a policy would lay a heavy burden on future generations.  The Social Security
retirement age is currently 65 and will slowly rise to 67 by the year 2027.  In fact,
by any demographic standard, today's retirement age is far too low, not too high. 
If retirement age had kept pace with changes in life expectancy since the 1930s
when Social Security was created, it would be 76 today.<a href="#N_35_"><sup>(35)</sup></a></li>
      <li>While most other western industrialized nations have moved to <em>raise</em> the
retirement age as their populations live longer, the NEA would have the U.S. go
the other direction.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p>It is important to note that there are several items on the NEA Social Security agenda which also
cost substantial amounts of money but for which there are no cost estimates.  These items include:

<ol>
  <li>NEA supports "improved Social Security benefits for participants, especially low-income
workers, dependents and survivors."</li>
  <li>NEA supports "meaningful survivor/disability benefits for minor surviving children under the
care of parents, grandparents, or other custodial adults."</li>
  <li>NEA supports "Social Security benefit equity for men and women through earnings sharing
and/or benefit changes."</li>
  <li>NEA supports "restoration of the dependents' education allowance under Social Security."</li>
</ol>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>NEA also opposes modest reforms that have been proposed by very responsible organizations. 
The proposals, which could save billions of dollars, include:

<ol>
  <li>Means-testing Social Security.  NEA supports "Social Security as social insurance, not welfare
or a 'means-tested' program."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Savings: $45.7 billion to $222.1 billion</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>CBO estimate.</li>
    </ol>
    <li>Notes:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>Means-testing Social Security -- reducing benefits to upper-income retirees --
would achieve significant budgetary savings and help ensure the actuarial
soundness of the program.  Interestingly,  the NEA states it supports, "protection
of the solvency of the Social Security system through an actuarially sound tax
base that maintains the integrity of the Social Security trust fund and through use
of general revenues, if necessary."  </li>
      <li>What the NEA supports is the continuation of what has become a windfall for all
retirees, but particularly upper-income beneficiaries.</li>
      <li>Over 20% of Social Security benefits go to people with incomes over $50,000. 
This group of well-off Americans collected $115 billion from the federal
government in 1992.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>NEA opposes "any reductions in Social Security benefits, including limits on annual COLA
adjustments."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Savings: Limiting Social Security COLA's to 2/3's of CPI would save $11.24 billion
annually.</li>
    <li>Notes:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>This is a very moderate reform that has been proposed by many analysts as one
way to limit the tremendous growth in Social Security.  The modesty of this
proposal can be seen by virtue of the fact that private pension plans offset only
about 30 percent of the effects of inflation.<a href="#N_36_"><sup>(36)</sup></a></li>
      <li>Reducing COLA adjustments even by very slight amounts can save billions of
dollars.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p align="center"><strong>14. Substance Abuse/Dependency</strong>

<p>The total cost for NEA's agenda in this section is $432 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>"Improved and expanded drug treatment and rehabilitation programs that assure access to all
who need these services."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $446 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1677, 103rd Congress, Grants to states for education to at-risk youth. 
According to the text of the bill, the cost is $72 million.</li>
      <li>HR 3980, 103rd Congress, A bill to support and assist drug courts.  According
to the text of the bill, the cost is $200 million.</li>
      <li>HR 3353, 103rd Congress, A bill to reduce juvenile drug trafficking.  According
to the text of the bill, the cost is $100 million.</li>
      <li>HR 3350, 103rd Congress, A bill to provide for residential substance abuse
treatment in prisons.  According to CBO, the cost is $35 million.</li>
      <li>HR 2958, 103rd Congress, A bill to provide for demonstration projects for
victims of substance abuse and domestic violence.  According to the text of the
bill, the cost is $10 million.</li>
      <li>HR 3569, 103rd Congress, The Women and Alcohol Research Equity Act. 
According to the text of the bill, the cost is $9 million.</li>
      <li>HR 3783, 103rd Congress, Comprehensive Fetal Alcohol Prevention Act. 
According to Representative Richardson, the cost is $20 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>"Repeal of agriculture subsidies for tobacco."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $-14 million </li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1482, Rep. Inglis, 103rd Congress, A bill to eliminate the tobacco price
support program.  Savings: $14 million.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p align="center"><strong>15. Taxation</strong>

<p>Since this paper analyzes the cost of the spending agenda of the NEA, adding in its taxation
agenda would be double-counting, because its tax agenda is, in a sense, the mirror image of its
spending agenda.  Thus, no tax changes are thus included in the aggregate figures of this paper. 
Still, there are several interesting aspects to the way in which the NEA advocates raising the
revenue to pay for its spending agenda.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>NEA supports a whole host of new exemptions and deductions for taxpayers.  Most significantly,
NEA champions exclusion from federal taxation of state and local sales taxes.<a href="#N_37_"><sup>(37)</sup></a> Providing
exemptions of state and local taxes makes those taxes less burdensome and makes it easier for
other levels of governments to raise them.  Simply put, the exclusion helps advocates of bigger
government at the state and local level further their agendas.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Other new tax breaks that NEA supports include various tax exemptions for education
expenditures, expansion of home office deduction provisions, and expansion of employee benefit
tax deductions.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>NEA does, however, favor ending some tax breaks, which could save money.  NEA supports
eliminating tax benefits to organizations that promote hatred.  Although constitutionally dubious,
the vague nature of the proposal precludes estimating how much revenue this would raise.  NEA
also supports eliminating "unfair tax loopholes or giveaways such as tax abatement and foreign
trade zones that reduce revenues and shelter corporations and high-income individuals from
paying taxes."<a href="#N_38_"><sup>(38)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>It is also worth noting that NEA opposes tuition tax credits at the elementary, secondary, or
postsecondary levels.  Similarly, NEA opposes vouchers or certificates in education.<a href="#N_39_"><sup>(39)</sup></a> Over the
past decade, NEA legislative activity has peaked when fighting these types of public policy
proposals.<a href="#N_40_"><sup>(40)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>No matter what cost or savings come from the creation and elimination of these various tax
provisions, the bottom line of the NEA spending agenda will be hundreds of billions of dollars in
new taxes for Americans.  NEA writes that it supports, "a tax system that provides for education
and other social needs while achieving reduction of the national debt."<a href="#N_41_"><sup>(41)</sup></a> To enact the spending
agenda discussed in other sections of this paper would require in the aggregate an enormous
increase in revenues.  Given the public disapproval of the huge (but by comparison far more
limited) tax increases enacted in 1993, it seems unlikely that the NEA would get its wish for taxes
to be raised enough to pay for its massive new spending agenda.  Thus, the most likely casualty of
NEA's agenda would be federal finances -- besides huge tax increases, further deficits and debt are
almost guaranteed.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Furthering this doubt that the NEA would actively champion and get enacted the trillions of
dollars in taxes needed to balance a federal budget that reflects the NEA's spending agenda is its
position that: "NEA opposes any constitutional amendment imposing limitations on taxes or the
federal budget."<a href="#N_42_"><sup>(42)</sup></a> This opposition to any constitutional limitation on the federal budget can
probably be interpreted as opposition to a federal Balanced Budget Amendment.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>16. Teacher Recruitment and Professional Development Opportunities</strong>

<p>In this section, NEA has an agenda that costs, at a minimum, $700 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>NEA supports, "establishment and funding of professional development opportunities designed
and directed by teachers."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $700 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 2762, 103rd Congress, The Career Development and Teacher Excellence
Plan.  Cost: $700 million.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p align="center"><strong>17. Violence and School Safety</strong>

<p>In this section, NEA has a legislative agenda which costs $287 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>"Federal initiatives to combat violence and drugs in school."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $200 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 538, 103rd Congress, Classroom Safety Act.  This bill provides assistance to
local educational agencies for the prevention and reduction of violent crime in
elementary and secondary schools.  According to the text of the bill, the cost is
$100 million per year.</li>
      <li>HR 987, 103rd Congress, Gun-Free Schools Act.  Estimated cost: $100 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>"Restrictions, including a mandatory waiting period to allow background checks for felony
convictions or mental illness, on the manufacture, distribution, and/or sale of handguns in order
to assure a safer school environment."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $87 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 1321, 104th Congress, Handgun Control &amp; Violence Prevention Act of
1995.  Cost: $87 million.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>18. Vocational Education</strong>

<p>In this section, NEA has a legislative agenda which very conservatively costs $500 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>"The efficient and effective provision of adequate resources to local vocational educational
authorities and/or postsecondary institutions to maintain, enhance, and expand quality
vocational education programs."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $300 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>S 1361, 103rd Congress, School-to-Work Opportunities Act.  According to the
text of the bill, the cost is $300 million.</li>
    </ol>
  </ol>
  <li>"Federal resources for programs that prepare students effectively for the high-technology
environment that will exist throughout their working lives."</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $200 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 5040, 103rd Congress, Education in Vocational Technology Act.  According
to the text of the bill, the cost is $200 million.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

<p align="center"><strong>19. Voting Reform and Election Rights</strong>

<p>The total cost for the NEA agenda in this section is $11 million.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ol>
  <li>Statehood for the District of Columbia</li>
  <ol>
    <li>Cost: $11 million</li>
    <li>Source:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>HR 51, 103rd Congress, A Bill to Provide for the Admission of the State of New
Columbia to the Union.  According to the Congressional Budget Office, the cost
is $11 million.</li>
    </ol>
    <li>Notes:</li>
    <ol>
      <li>By virtue of its status as a federally chartered corporation, NEA has an
exemption from paying property taxes, thereby depriving Washington, D.C. (the
location of its headquarters) of a substantial amount of revenue.  No other union
in the United States has this same privilege, which by one estimate saves the
NEA $2 million a year.<a href="#N_43_"><sup>(43)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">    </ol>
  </ol>
</ol>

