<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>Misplaced Priorities:</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>The Federal Education Budget and School Choice</strong></h3>
<h4 align="center">Gregory A. Fossedal and Paul F. Steidler</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><h4 align="center">AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 134</h4>
<h4 align="center">October 16, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Executive Summary</strong>

<p>Our August 28 study of the Dole school choice proposal found that there was at least $5 billion in
expenditures from the U.S. Department of Education's Fiscal Year 1996 budget that would be
better spent on publicly-financed scholarship programs.  The recent adoption of the U.S.
Department of Education's Fiscal Year 1997 budget has raised this figure to over $5.4 billion. 
<u>Most notably, there has been over a 13 percent increase in spending on 25 programs that in large
part benefit teachers, bureaucracies, students that are not poor, or that are a relatively small
supplement to existing state and local programs</u>.   

<p>The Dole proposal calls for providing $2.5 billion in federal money to allow four million children
to attend the public, parochial, or private school of their parents' choice.  The $5 billion identified
in our August 28 report included $2.6 billion in 27 federal programs meeting the above
description that could be eliminated (two of the programs, albeit small ones, were in fact
discontinued).  In addition, $2.4 billion could be saved from Title I expenditures that would no
longer be necessary if 2.5 million children left the public schools for private ones under the Dole
initiative.   

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For Fiscal Year 1997, the $5.4 billion in potential savings is comprised of $2.9 billion that would
be realized from eliminating programs and $2.5 billion that would be offset from Title I spending.  


<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Review of Changes in Programs</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The 27 programs, and the amounts they have received for fiscal years 1996-97,
follow.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a>Additional details of the scope of these programs can be found in AdTI's August 28
report.<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a> All figures are in millions of dollars.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u>Program</u> <u>FY 1997FY 1996Percentage Change  </u>

<p>Goals 2000    $491.0  $350.0 +40%

<p>School to Work Opportunities $200.0  $180.0 +11%

<p>Impact Aid    $730.0  $693.0 +5%

<p>Eisenhower Professional-

<p>Development Program  $310.0  $275.0 +13%

<p>Law School -- Clinical Experience     -   $  5.5  -100%

<p>Inexpensive Book Distribution $ 10.3   $ 10.3  None

<p>Arts in Education   $  9.0   $  9.0  None

<p>Magnet Schools Assistance  $ 95.0   $ 95.0  None

<p>Education for Native Hawaiians $ 15.0   $ 12.0  +25%   

<p>Ellender Fellowships   $  1.5   $  1.5  None

<p>Foreign Language Assistance  $   5.0   $ 10.0  -50%

<p>Media and Captioning Services $ 20.0   $ 19.1  +5%

<p>Parent Training   $ 15.5   $13.5  +14%

<p>Vocational Education State Grants $514.5  $486.4 +5.8%

<p>(50% of program)          

<p>Tech Prep Education   $100.0  $100.0 None

<p>Adult Education   $345.3  $250.0 38%

<p>Literacy Programs for Prisoners $  4.7   $  4.7  None

<p>Star Schools    $ 30.0   $ 23.0  +30%

<p>Ready to Learn Television  $  7.0   $  6.4  +9%

<p>Eisenhower Professional 

<p>Development -- Federal Activities $ 13.3   $ 18.0  -26%

<p>Javits Gifted &amp; Talented  $  5.0   $  3.0  +67%

<p>National Writing Project  $   3.1   $  3.0  +5%

<p>Civic Education   $  4.5   $  4.0  +12%

<p>International Education Exchange $   5.0   $   5.0  None

<p>Public Library Construction  $ 16.4   $ 16.4  None

<p>Javits Graduate Fellowships  $  -   $  5.9  -100%

<p>Special Grant to Bethune Cookman

<p>College Fine Arts Center  $   1.4   $  3.7  -62%

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Total:  $2,952.5  $2,603.4 +13.4% 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>These figures gain added significance when examined against $5.25 million that is being spent by
the state of Ohio to enable 2,000 poor children in Cleveland to attend private schools this year. 
6,000 students sought these scholarships.  Like many cities, the problems of Cleveland's schools
are daunting.  Only seven percent of Cleveland public high school students will graduate with 12th
grade scholastic proficiency, about the same number who each year are victims of crime in the
school system.<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The U.S. Department of Education is spending nearly as much money on a literacy program for
prisoners as Ohio is spending on scholarships.  In addition, the Department will spend 93 times as
much money on the Goals 2000 program, under which money is appropriated to bureaucracies,
not individual schools.  At nearly 60 times the Cleveland scholarship initiative, the Eisenhower
Professional Development Program will receive $310 million for "professional development
activities in the core academic subjects to help ensure that teachers, administrators and other staff
have access to sustained and intensive high-quality professional development."<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Additional Savings from Title I Program Offsets</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Title I program primarily provides federal funds based on the number of children from
low-income families, to local educational agencies.  If a substantial number of children leave the
public school system because of a scholarship program, there can be a proportional reduction in
Title I aid without negatively impacting those students who remain in the public school system.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>According to the federal Department of Education, the Title I program serves seven million
children.<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a> If two and a half million children were to enroll in private schools under the Dole or a
like-minded scholarship proposal, this would reduce the number of children needing Title I
assistance by 35.7 percent, or $2.5 billion in fiscal year 1997 compared to $2.4 billion in fiscal
year 1996.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Title I funding, it should be noted, rose by 6.8% in the current budget.<a href="#N_6_"><sup>(6)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Recent Comments on School Choice</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>When asked about the Dole school choice initiative at the National Press Club in early September,
the Secretary of Education, Richard Riley responded, "Well, the idea of spending public tax
dollars for private school vouchers I think is a real mistake and I thought that for years."<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This comment is not surprising given the Administration's past statements and the fact that the
teacher unions, two of the Administration's strongest political allies, have been perennially and
fiercely opposed to all publicly-financed school choice measures.  While Secretary Riley then
addressed specifics of the Dole proposal, his initial remarks appear to also encompass state- and
locally-sponsored choice programs.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>What is surprising, however, are comments that President Clinton made in the October 3 debate
with Bob Dole.  While discussing his opposition to a federal school choice proposal such as Dole
has offered, Clinton said:  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"I support school choice.  I support school choice ... But if you're going to have a private voucher
plan, that ought to be determined by states and localities where they're raising and spending most
of the money."<a href="#N_8_"><sup>(8)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The President later added:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"If a local school district in Cleveland, or anyplace else, wants to have a private school choice
plan, like Milwaukee did, let them have at it."<a href="#N_9_"><sup>(9)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The President's support, to be sure, is limited to public school choice.  In cities with systemic
problems, like Cleveland, the benefits would be limited and less immediate.  And while the
President now seems content to stay out of local and state-wide scholarship/voucher debates, this
has not always been the case.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For example, in an October 1993 speech to the AFL-CIO convention the President spoke out
against a state-wide voucher proposition that was on the ballot in California.  <em>The Los Angeles
Times</em> noted, "Clinton's direct involvement in the school voucher issue is unusual, given that
presidents generally stay out of such state matters and that many statewide officials -- most
notably California Gov. Pete Wilson -- have not yet taken a stand on the question."<a href="#N_10_"><sup>(10)</sup></a> 

<p>As school choice seems likely to be discussed much more at the federal, state, and local levels in
the near future, it should be kept in mind that this is not a new or radical concept.  Virtually all
western democracies permit much more freedom of choice in their schooling arrangements than
does the United States.<a href="#N_11_"><sup>(11)</sup></a> Several teacher unions in other countries also support school choice.  

<p>These issues are addressed in AdTI's recently issued study, "Teacher Union 'Concentration' in 21
Countries" and an upcoming study specifically about the range of school choice in industrialized
nations.  

<p><strong>Conclusion</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The current Department of Education budget takes a business as usual approach with regard to
the federal policy on helping poor children at troubled schools.  It significantly increases spending
on federal programs that at best only provide indirect assistance.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Publicly financed scholarship programs, by contrast, would allow a low-income parent the
opportunity to select a private, public, or parochial school that would immediately improve their
child's education.  It is incumbent upon the advocates of the status quo -- most notably the teacher
unions and the Education Department -- to explain why spending on non-essential federal
education programs should be increased by over 13% while troubled children, like those in
Cleveland, receive no direct assistance via publicly-financed scholarships.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
