<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>Making Choices:  A Review of Options for Financing </strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>Bob Dole's School Choice Initiative</strong></h3>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>By:  Gregory A. Fossedal and Paul F. Steidler</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Executive Summary</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In reviewing Bob Dole's recently announced "opportunity scholarships" program, expenditures of
the U.S. Department of Education, and trends in the school choice debate, several findings are
notable.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>Though the Dole campaign has avoided giving specifics, there are at least $5.0 billion in
expenditures from the current Department of Education budget (Fiscal Year 1996) that would
more directly and immediately benefit poor children if used to sponsor a scholarship program,
or that would no longer be necessary if the scholarship program was enacted.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>More than half the savings, $2.6 billion, would come from programs that in large part benefit
teachers, bureaucracies, students that are not poor, or that are a relatively small supplement to
existing state and local programs.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Savings from the Department of Education's management expenses could lead to additional
savings above the $5 billion.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>While critics of the Dole proposal might charge that it is inconsistent with his call for local
control of education and abolition of the Department of Education, such conclusions are
debatable.  The growing appeal of school choice, and its immense potential in the future, has
up to now been largely thwarted by powerful, special interest teacher unions.  Thus, the Dole
proposal's central function might be to serve as the catalyst of school choice, rather than the
largest or central purveyor of it.    </li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p>Under the proposal, scholarships would be provided for up to four million low- and
middle-income elementary and secondary school students.  The program would allow parents to
choose public, private, or parochial schools for their children and would be funded through an
annual $2.5 billion federal grant program matched by $2.5 billion in state funds.  Up to 15 states
and the District of Columbia could participate in the competitive, demonstration program which
would run from Fiscal Years 1997-2000.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>I.  Introduction</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The maximum $2.5 billion in annual demonstration federal scholarships that Senator Dole has
proposed would be broken down as follows.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Scholarships would be $1,000 per child in K-8 schools, with $500 coming from the federal
government and $500 from the state.  For high school students, the scholarships would be $1,500,
with $750 coming from both the federal and state governments.  Private donations could be made
on top of these funds.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In announcing the program, the Dole campaign noted, "This new $2.5 billion federal commitment
to America's children is budget neutral and would not increase the federal deficit.  The funding
offsets include:  eliminating the Goals 2000 program, reducing Department of Education
overhead, bureaucracy and wasteful spending; and adopting certain program terminations and
reductions called for in the Clinton Administration's budget proposals."<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The stated aim of the Dole proposal is to help poor children go to better schools.  Both sides in
the school choice debate agree that inner-city public schools have serious problems.  According to
Keith Geiger, outgoing President of the National Education Association, inner-city public schools
"are absolutely terrible -- they ought to be blown up."<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Overall federal education expenditures are quite substantial, especially when compared to the $2.5
billion Dole scholarship proposal.  The Department of Education's appropriations are expected to
total approximately $29.4 billion in fiscal year 1996.<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a> Other departments and agencies also spend
considerable amounts on education.  According to the National Center for Education Statistics,
federal support for education was an estimated $100.1 billion in Fiscal Year 1995.<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>II. Options for Paying for the Program </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The aim of any choice program is to immediately place poor children in a much better school, one
that parents believe will provide an improved education here and now.  In a book about
Milwaukee's pioneering publicly financed private school choice experiment that began in 1990,
author Dan McGroarty makes clear that low-income parents have championed school choice
because of a "simple and strong desire to do right by their children."<a href="#N_6_"><sup>(6)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The results of the Milwaukee program are quite impressive.  A recent study co-authored by Paul
Peterson of Harvard University's Program in Education Policy and Governance and Jay Greene of
the University of Houston found that after three and four years in the Milwaukee choice program,
reading scores of low-income minority students receiving scholarships/vouchers were,
respectively, an average of three and five percentage points higher than those of comparable
public-school students.  Math scores were five and 12 points higher for third- and fourth-year
students respectively.<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>By contrast, nationwide per pupil spending, in inflation-adjusted terms, has increased by 30%
since 1983.  However, SAT scores have remained basically flat, rising a mere 1.0 percent, and
actually declining in 23 states.<a href="#N_8_"><sup>(8)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Against this backdrop it should be noted that many federal education programs can at best only be
said to indirectly help poor students.  Indeed, there are many programs that primarily benefit
teachers as well as students that are not poor or that supplement existing state or local programs
which provide the preponderance of spending.  The federal share of expenditures to elementary
and secondary educational institutions, in fact, was under nine percent in Fiscal Year
1995.<a href="#N_9_"><sup>(9)</sup></a>Funds for the programs may also be provided based on who writes the best grant
proposal, rather than on where there is the greatest need.     

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The following chart illustrates some specific programs, all from the Department of Education, and
their Fiscal Year 1996 appropriation.<a href="#N_10_"><sup>(10)</sup></a> The value of each program, particularly when  compared
to a direct scholarship for a poor child, is highly questionable.  Some, such as a program to help
law students gain experience, are simply absurd. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A description of the programs can also be found in Appendix A.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Program Fiscal Year 1996 Appropriation

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Goals 2000      $350.0 million

<p>School to Work Opportunities   $180.0 million

<p>Impact Aid      $693.0 million 

<p>Eisenhower Professional-Development Program   $275.0 million

<p>Law School -- Clinical Experience   $    5.5 million

<p>Inexpensive Book Distribution   $  12.0 million

<p>Arts in Education     $  10.0 million

<p>Magnet Schools Assistance    $  95.0 million

<p>Education for Native Hawaiians   $  12.0 million

<p>Ellender Fellowships     $    2.8 million

<p>Foreign Language Assistance    $   10.0 million

<p>Media and Captioning Services   $   19.1 million

<p>Parent Training     $   13.5 million

<p>Vocational Education State Grants   $ 486.3 million

<p>(50% reduction)

<p>Tech Prep Education     $ 100.0 million

<p>Adult Education     $ 250.0 million

<p>Literacy Programs for Prisoners   $     4.7 million

<p>Star Schools      $   23.0 million

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Ready to Learn Television    $    6.4 million

<p>Eisenhower Professional Development --

<p>Federal Activities     $  18.0 million

<p>Javits Gifted &amp; Talented    $    3.0 million

<p>National Writing Project    $   2.9 million

<p>Civic Education     $   4.0 million

<p>International Education Exchange   $   5.0 million

<p>Public Library Construction    $  16.4 million

<p>Javits Graduate Fellowships    $    5.9 million

<p>Special Grant to Bethune Cookman 

<p>College Fine Arts Center    $    3.7 million

<p>Total:   $2.607 billion

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This $2.6 billion, it should be noted, did not include any reductions in some politically sensitive
areas nor from department management expenditures.  This includes:  Title I funds
(Compensatory Education for the Disadvantaged -- Local Funds, FY 1996 appropriation $6.7
billion)<a href="#N_11_"><sup>(11)</sup></a>, Collegiate Student Financial Assistance, including Pell grants, (FY 1996 appropriation
$4.9 billion)<a href="#N_12_"><sup>(12)</sup></a> and management funds for the Department of Education, (FY 1996 appropriation
$417.5 million)<a href="#N_13_"><sup>(13)</sup></a>.  In these three areas alone the Department has been provided over $12.0
billion in new budget (obligational) authority in Fiscal Year 1996.  There are significant savings
that could be obtained here and elsewhere.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>III. Title I Program</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Title I program, for example, primarily provides federal funds based on the number of
children from low-income families, in each county, to local education agencies.  If a substantial
number of children leave the public school system because of the scholarship program,  there can
be a proportional reduction in Title I aid without negatively impacting those students who remain
in the public school system.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>According to the Department of Education, the Title I program serves seven million children.<a href="#N_14_"><sup>(14)</sup></a> If
we assume that two and a half million poor children enroll in private schools under the Dole
scholarship program, this would reduce the number of children needing Title I assistance by 35.7
percent.  A corresponding reduction in Title I spending would amount to $2.4 billion, while
providing the same per capita amount of aid to those students who remain in the public schools.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>There are indications that other substantial savings could be found by revising Title I.  For
example, the fifteen richest counties in the U.S. will receive over $56 million this year in Title I
funds (see chart).<a href="#N_15_"><sup>(15)</sup></a> 

<p>In addition, the nation's five wealthiest states as measured by per capita income -- Alaska,
Connecticut, Hawaii, Massachusetts and Maryland -- are receiving a total of 

<p>$273 million in Title I money in the current fiscal year.   Given the financial strength of these
counties and states, one can question the amount of Title I aid they are receiving.   

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Helping Those in Need?</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The 15 wealthiest counties in the U.S. will receive over $56 million this year from the U.S.
Department of Education's Title I program.  Money is granted to "local educational agencies"
based "primarily" on the number of low-income families in each county.  Given that the vast
majority of education spending is already paid for by local taxpayers, as well as the counties'
significant resources, it is highly questionable whether these areas truly need these funds.  A list of
the counties and the amounts they will receive in Fiscal Year 1996 follows.<a href="#N_16_"><sup>(16)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u>County/StateAmount Received Per Capita Income</u>

<p>Marin, California  $ 1,209,739   $33,175

<p>San Mateo, California $ 5,399,096   $32,660  

<p>Araphahoe, Colorado  $ 3,602,275   $32,569  

<p>Eagle, Colorado  $    207,850   $32,335

<p>Pitkin, Colorado  $       67,001   $32,104

<p>Fairfield, Connecticut $11,821,568   $31,840 

<p>Martin, Florida  $ 1,098,411   $30,654

<p>Blaine, Idaho   $    118,252   $30,508

<p>DuPage, Illinois  $ 3,439,843   $30,418

<p>Lake, Illinois   $ 5,674,750   $28,963

<p>Hamilton, Indiana  $    608,165   $28,547 

<p>Johnson, Kansas  $ 1,932,029   $28,440 

<p>Howard, Maryland  $ 1,068,792   $27,991

<p>Montgomery, Maryland $ 5,483,329   $27,978

<p>Oakland, Michigan  $14,323,604   $27,796 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Total:  $56,054,704

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>IV. Department Management</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>An always tempting target (and one that Bob Dole cited) to call for cutting is the education
bureaucracy's administrative costs.  There undoubably are significant savings here, though we
have omitted them from the $5 billion calculation.     

<p>In Fiscal Year 1996 the Department of Education has a $417.5 million department management
budget.  (One questionable expenditure, in light of the needs of poor children, is the appropriation
of $7 million in Fiscal Year 1996 to renovate the Department's headquarters. The money can be
spent over a three year period.)     

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Assuming that the Department is managed as efficiently as possible, the transfer of two million
students to non-public schools would reduce the overall population of public elementary,
secondary, and post-secondary students by 3.4 percent.  A 3.4 percent reduction in the
Department's management budget would amount to $14.2 million.  If  the assume that the
Department is not managed as efficiently as possible (i.e. it could benefit from a reengineering),
and that it would have less to manage based on the above cuts, the savings in Department
management expenses could be significantly higher.   

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>V. Federalism and Related Issues </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Dole demonstration proposal raises some obvious questions, specifically:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>Is it consistent with Bob Dole's views about the federal role in education?</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Does the federal government need to become involved in school choice?  Should it?  If so, how
extensive should its role be? </li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p>The scholarship program, as we have noted, does not preclude significant overall reductions in
federal education spending, not to mention the myriad of accompanying regulations and mandates. 
At the same time, school choice proposals have been growing rapidly and can be expected to stay
part of many cities' and states' debates on education for some time.  Thus, it is conceivable that
the Dole initiative could serve as the catalyst for school choice programs and transition these
programs over to states after the year 2000. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>We elaborate on these inter-related issues below.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In opposing the creation of the U.S. Department of Education in 1979, Senator Dole stated, "The
business of educating our students must be done close to home, close to the providers of
revenues, and close to the students who reflect the educational process.  Parents, teachers,
students, and administrative officials should all participate in the process."<a href="#N_17_"><sup>(17)</sup></a> This was reiterated
recently when his campaign noted he "supports local control of education, school choice and
eliminating the Department of Education."<a href="#N_18_"><sup>(18)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While the Dole proposal would establish a federal scholarship program, it also comes on the heels
of proposals considered in an increasing number of states over the past two years, including such
large ones as California, Texas, Connecticut, Illinois, Pennsylvania and New Jersey.  Union
opposition has been viewed as a significant factor in defeating or stonewalling these measures.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The issue, however, has inherent and lasting appeal.  In addition to the aspirations of low-income
parents, a growing number of state officials recognize that students in troubled areas can be
educated in private schools often at less than half the per pupil expenditure in public schools.  This
thus saves the taxpayers a significant amount, while allowing the student to attend a school his or
her parents have judged to be superior.  A win-win situation is created for students, parents, and
budget conscious legislators.  The losers are teacher unions who feel a threat to their oligopoly in
providing education.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The unions unrivaled financial and organization strength compared with these groups, has been
pivotal to their winning most of the battles in the school choice debate.  In fact, the largest
teachers union, the National Education Association, has 1,500 field organizers.<a href="#N_19_"><sup>(19)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Some specific examples of the unions' influence are noteworthy:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>Bill Clinton, after initially praising the Milwaukee school choice program, later reversed his
position in what appears to have been an obvious attempt to obtain the endorsement of the
National Education Association<a href="#N_20_"><sup>(20)</sup></a>;  </li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Teacher unions have been involved in numerous lawsuits to stop school choice programs in
Milwaukee and Cleveland, the two major cities where fledgling choice programs have been
established; </li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Vehement teacher union opposition to a scholarship program was a primary obstacle in holding
up the District of Columbia's entire Fiscal Year 1996 appropriations bill.  As <em>U.S. News &amp;
World Report</em> noted, "The Senate sank an aid package for the nearly bankrupt District of
Columbia government, essentially because one part of the plan could have given some poor
D.C. parents vouchers or scholarships for children to attend private schools .... the pressure
(from the NEA) was so intense that the Democrats preferred   </li>
</ul>

<p>'a looming crisis of Congress's own making' as <em>The Washington Post</em> put it, rather than  keep alive
the possibility that some poor Washington children might be able to attend  nonpublic school."<a href="#N_21_"><sup>(21)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>Approximately one out of eight delegates at the 1992 Democratic convention was a member of
the NEA.<a href="#N_22_"><sup>(22)</sup></a> A similar if not greater representation is expected at this year's convention.      </li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>The NEA is the largest and richest American union, with 2.2 million members and an estimated
$785 million in revenues.<a href="#N_23_"><sup>(23)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p>The Dole proposal might thus provide one way to help level the playing field in this emerging
public policy debate. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Another reason the trend toward school choice does not appear likely to abate soon is that the
traditional approach of government control of all facets of education is coming under increased
scrutiny.  In a recent report, the prestigious investment firm Lehman Brothers noted, 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"The shift we see (in public education) is a system going from a government-run  monopoly with
little accountability and, by definition, no competition, to a market-driven system that competes
on price and quality ...  we are certain that the traditional way that  education and childcare have
been delivered and funded will continue to change, and   there is no going back."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>It adds:    

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"The Education Industry represents the final frontier of a number of sectors once  dominated by
public control that have generally failed to achieve the standards of quality  and cost effectiveness
that were originally intended.  These industries have either voluntarily or forcibly (in response to
external pressure) opened themselves up entrepreneurial innovation and public/private
restructuring."<a href="#N_24_"><sup>(24)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>VI. Conclusion</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Dole proposal is an ambitious undertaking as it would aid many students and provide impetus
to the burgeoning school choice movement nationwide.  There is a ample room to fund the
program through reductions in existing Department of Education programs which are not directed
at poor children.  Additional savings could be realized by reducing federal programs that are no
longer necessary because poor children are attending private schools.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Federal involvement in the demonstration program would counter the tremendous power of the
teacher unions whose opposition has largely helped thwart school choice proposals to date.  The
overall appeal of school choice, and general trends in American education, might make the federal
role in this program temporary and truly of a demonstration nature.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Appendix </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Description of Select Federal Education Programs</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Goals 2000:  </strong>A program that provides grants to support state and local education improvement
efforts to help all students reach challenging academic standards.<a href="#N_25_"><sup>(25)</sup></a> The program provides money
to fund bureaucracies, not individual schools, and imposes expensive mandates on states and
localities.<a href="#N_26_"><sup>(26)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>School to Work Opportunities:</strong> States use grants to establish partnerships representing
education, industry, and labor and to develop new assessments and accountability procedures for
their school-to-work systems.  This program does little to benefit students -- it primarily funds
states bureaucracies and duplicates many programs already operated by the states.<a href="#N_27_"><sup>(27)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Impact Aid:</strong> Provides financial assistance to school districts affected by federal activities, the
presence of tax-exempt federal property and/or federally connected children.<a href="#N_28_"><sup>(28)</sup></a> The program was
established during World War II to relieve the sudden financial pressure on school districts in
which enrollment increased sharply because of an influx of relocated military personnel.<a href="#N_29_"><sup>(29)</sup></a> The
program is thus based on the premise that military bases and other facilities are a "cost" for local
communities, a peculiar argument in light of many communities' recent opposition to having
defense bases closed in their areas.   

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Eisenhower Professional-Development Program:</strong> A program that is designed to improve
education through "professional development activities in the core academic subjects to help
ensure that teachers, administrators and other staff have access to sustained and intensive
high-quality professional development."<a href="#N_30_"><sup>(30)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Law Schools Clinical Experience Program:  </strong>Provides grants and contracts to accredited law
schools to help fund up to 90 percent of the cost of continuing, expanding and establishing
programs to provide clinical experience for law students.<a href="#N_31_"><sup>(31)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Inexpensive Book Distribution:  </strong>Supports the distribution of books to children from birth
through high school.<a href="#N_32_"><sup>(32)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Arts in Education:  </strong>Funds support federal leadership activities in arts education as well as the
education activities of the Kennedy Center and Very Special Arts.<a href="#N_33_"><sup>(33)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Magnet Schools Assistance:</strong> Grants are made to local educational agencies to establish and
operate magnet school programs that are part of approved desegregation plans.<a href="#N_34_"><sup>(34)</sup></a> 

<p><strong>Education for Native Hawaiians:</strong> Funds provide supplemental education services to Native
Hawaiians.<a href="#N_35_"><sup>(35)</sup></a> To the extent that native Hawaiians already meet the eligibility criteria that are
applied to all citizens, they are already eligible to participate in existing federal and state
programs.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Ellender Fellowships:</strong> Provides a grant to the Close-Up Foundation to promote knowledge and
understanding of the federal government through fellowships to low-income students and their
teachers, students of migrant parents and to economically disadvantaged older Americans and
recent immigrants.<a href="#N_36_"><sup>(36)</sup></a>

<p><strong>Foreign Language Assistance:</strong> Makes grants available to establish, improve, or expand foreign
language programs.<a href="#N_37_"><sup>(37)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Media and Captioning Services:</strong> Makes available captioned films, including videos, descriptive
videos, and educational media for persons who are hearing impaired; provides transcribed tapes
and cassettes of textbooks and other educational publications and materials.<a href="#N_38_"><sup>(38)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Parent Training:</strong> A program that helps "provide parents with knowledge and skills they need to
participate effectively in their children's education."<a href="#N_39_"><sup>(39)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Vocational Educational State Grants:</strong> Makes grants supporting professional development
activities for vocational teachers and academic teachers working with vocational education
students, including corrections educators and counselors and educators and counselors in
community-based organizations;  development, dissemination, and field testing of curricula; and
assessment of programs funded under the Carl D. Perkins Vocational and Applied Technology
Education Act.<a href="#N_40_"><sup>(40)</sup></a> 

<p><strong>Tech Prep Education:</strong> Provides assistance to enable states to award planning and demonstration
grants to consortia of local education agencies and postsecondary institutions.<a href="#N_41_"><sup>(41)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Adult Education -- State Administered Basic Grant Program:</strong> Provides grants to states to
fund local programs of adult basic education, adult secondary education, and English-as-a-second
language instruction.<a href="#N_42_"><sup>(42)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Literacy Program for Prisoners:</strong> The program provides funds to correctional institutions.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Star Schools:</strong> Funds support the acquisition of telecommunications equipment and the
development of instructional programming for distance learning.<a href="#N_43_"><sup>(43)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Ready to Learn Television:</strong> Funds support the development of educational programming for
preschool and elementary school children and their parents.<a href="#N_44_"><sup>(44)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Eisenhower Professional Development National Activities:</strong> Funds support activities to
promote excellence in teaching.<a href="#N_45_"><sup>(45)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Javits Gifted &amp; Talented:</strong> Funds support projects designed to help educators identify and meet
the special educational needs of gifted and talented students.<a href="#N_46_"><sup>(46)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>National Writing Project:  </strong>This was originally intended as a demonstration project supported
with funds from the National Endowment for the Humanities as well as private foundations.  The
program has proven its viability and can survive without further federal support.<a href="#N_47_"><sup>(47)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Civic Education:</strong> Funds are used to provide an award to the Center for Civic Education to help
educate students about the history and principles of the Constitution.<a href="#N_48_"><sup>(48)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>International Education Exchange: </strong> Funds are used for international exchange programs to
help improve civics and economics education in central and eastern European countries. countries
that were part of the former Soviet Union, and the United States.<a href="#N_49_"><sup>(49)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Public Library Construction: </strong> Provides grants to states to match state and local public library
funds for the construction and renovation of public libraries.<a href="#N_50_"><sup>(50)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Javits Graduate Fellowships:</strong> Program provides graduate fellowships in the arts, humanities and
social studies.  The program is redundant as the federal already provides several billion dollars in
student aid for graduate level programs.<a href="#N_51_"><sup>(51)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>Special Grant to Bethune Cookman College Fine Arts Center:</strong> This institution is based in
Daytona Beach, Florida.   

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
