<head>
<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><h3 align="center"><strong>Who Got It Right?</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>What Proponents and Opponents of the</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>Creation of the Department of Education</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>Promised &amp; Predicted</strong></h3>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><h4 align="center">John E. Berthoud, Ph.D.</h4>
<h4 align="center">Vice President</h4>
<h4 align="center">The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4></h4>
<h4 align="center">January 18, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Foreword by U. S. Representative Steve Chabot</strong>

<p>The difference between what supporters promised at the time the federal Department of
Education was created and what actually has emerged as bureaucratic reality is the difference
between dreamy fiction and dismaying fact.  <em>Who Got It Right?</em> pulls together some fascinating
evidence on the subject.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Now, it's not always easy for those of us whose prognostications are preserved in print to see our
words reexamined after time has passed -- but I just can't summon much sympathy for DoEd
proponents, because I simply cannot understand how anyone ever could have imagined that a
federal Department wouldn't grow, that it wouldn't squander valuable education dollars, or that it
wouldn't impose real burdens on local communities.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Those education advocates who opposed creation of the Department were far closer to the mark. 
Indeed, Representative Pat Schroeder (with whom, it is safe to say, I do not always agree) seems
to have had it right.  Dr. Berthoud quotes her as warning: "No matter what anyone says, the
Department of Education will . . . meddle in everything.  I do not want that."  Nor do I, nor do
parents across the country.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>As a former school teacher and as the father of two schoolchildren, I am committed to improving
the quality of education in this country.  That goal will be accomplished best, I believe, by
eliminating the federal Department and restoring control to parents, teachers, and local
communities.  To that end, I have been proud to work with Representatives Joe Scarborough and
John Boehner in drafting the Back to Basics Education Reform Act, a bill that has attracted wide
support in the House and across the land.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The very pro-education Governor of Ohio, George Voinovich, wants the federal Department
eliminated because its "highly prescriptive and heavily regulated" programs are "substituting
Washington's judgments for those of the states, communities, and families.  This
micromanagement often imposes burdensome mandates on local communities, which can least
afford the intrusion."  That hard truth is very different from the wildly wrong prediction of the
(Republican!) Representative quoted within who claimed in 1979 that the federal Department
"does not create a new education bureaucracy.  In fact, it reduces the bureaucracy."  The
Congressman's claim may never have made much sense, but contrast it with Governor Voinovich's
report today that, "a recent Ohio study determined that a local school may have to submit as many
as 170 federal reports totalling more than 700 pages during a single year, consuming vital
resources without any improvement in the quality of education children receive."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This retrospective analysis is very helpful as we again confront the issue of whether local schools
are helped or hindered by the bureaucratic federal Department.  The research also provides a
useful reminder that even the best intended public policy forays frequently fall victim to the
hazards of unintended but nevertheless predictable adverse consequences. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Introduction</strong>

<p>"The creation of this department is a response, by both the president and the Congress, to one
specific organization, the National Education Association.  The NEA represents many, but not all,
of the people who are employed by public school systems.  It is always questionable policy to
establish a large public agency whose constituency is the same people whose work that agency
oversees." <em>Washington Post</em>editorial, 1979<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While the original fight over the creation of the Department of Education was one of the most
heated political controversies of 1979, after a short period much of the debate died away.  The
recent resurgence in concern about Washington encroaching on the prerogatives of state and local
governments has raised anew the debate about the Department's existence.  Opponents have
argued that the Department is an expensive failure that has added paperwork and bureaucracy but
little value to the nation's classrooms.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>As the above quote from the <em>Washington Post</em> indicates, it is quite interesting and often surprising
to go back in public records to find out what was said about particular legislative action -- what
were the purposes of a given bill and what were the expectations for that bill?  This paper
examines the promises of supporters and the concerns of opponents that were aired during the
debate 16 years ago over the establishment of the Department of Education.  Then it makes an
assessment of what has occurred since the Department's creation.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The main findings are that supporters substantially over-promised on the benefits of a separate
department and failed to acknowledge many potential problems.  On the other hand, opponents
were right on target in terms of many of their fears.  The contrasting projections came in six key
areas: 1) benefits for school children; 2) overhead &amp; bureaucracy; 3) efficiency; 4) local control;
5) cost; and 6) values.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>I. Benefits for School Children</strong>

<p align="center"><em>What Supporters Promised . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Representative Jack Brooks, (D-TX) one of the lead sponsors of the bill in the House, argued
that a separate department, "will enable us to better serve 100 million men, mothers, fathers,
parents, children, and teachers."<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Elliott Levitas (D-GA) argued that a separate department would mean,
"stronger and better educational opportunity for the boys and girls and the young men and
women in America.  There is no question about that."<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Speaker of the House Thomas P. "Tip" O'Neill (D-MA) stated, "We need a special Department
of Education.  We are doing it in the best interests of ourselves, of our children, and of our
Nation's educational future."<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>What Opponents Predicted . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Senator S. I. Hayakawa (R-CA, and former President of San Francisco State College)
passionately argued, "Senator Moynihan and I have joined in opposing this bill.  We have both
been teachers for a long time.  But it appears that our colleagues would rather listen to the
unfounded pleas of people who know only that there are problems in our schools today, but
who do not know how to solve them.  Having this new department is rather like grasping at
straws.  We see there is a problem and attempt to solve it by creating a new department.  I
wish someone would tell me how this new department is going to make our children literate? 
Or how it will erase the violence that has erupted in our schools?  Or how it will ensure that
we get what we pay for with our tax dollars?  Or how it will make our children better prepared
for their futures?"<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-NY) observed, "This is back-room deal, born out of a
squalid politics.  Everything we had thought we would not see happening to education is
happening here."<a href="#N_6_"><sup>(6)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Bob Michel (R-IL) stated, "The establishment of a new department is irrelevant
to the needs of American children."<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Michel also argued that a vote against the bill creating DOE is, "a vote for American children. 
Once this silly idea is consigned to the oblivion it richly deserves, let us have the courage to
admit that the Federal Government does not know what it is doing in education, and we had
better go back to square 1 and begin all over again."<a href="#N_8_"><sup>(8)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Thomas Evans (R-DE) stated, "Very few reasons are even suggested by the
proponents of this bill to demonstrate that a sixth grader in a Delaware elementary school will
receive an improved education as a result of the creation of a Federal Department of
Education.  In fact, there is nothing in this proposal that provides any promise or even any
hope that anyone will learn more, or faster, or more happily."<a href="#N_9_"><sup>(9)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>The Reality</em>
<ul>
  <li>SAT scores since the creation of the Department have basically stagnated: the national average
was a combined 890 in 1980 and 910 in 1995 (428 on verbal and 482 on math).  But even this
small progress may merely reflect changes in methodology in the SAT.  There are now fewer
questions but students have longer to finish.  And, along with other changes, calculators are
now allowed.<a href="#N_10_"><sup>(10)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>In 1978, eight percent of eighth graders failed to complete high school.  By 1992, that figure
had reached 12 percent.<a href="#N_11_"><sup>(11)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<ul>
  <li>According to tests in 1994, 30 percent of high school seniors were not even "basic" readers. 
Only 11 percent achieved satisfactory scores on U.S. history.<a href="#N_12_"><sup>(12)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Almost half of adult Americans are barely literate and literacy rates among younger adults are
falling.<a href="#N_13_"><sup>(13)</sup></a></li>
</ul>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li><em>The Washington Post</em> concluded in a 1994 editorial that, "America's schools are not noticeably
better because a Department of Education was created."<a href="#N_14_"><sup>(14)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Former Secretaries of Education Lamar Alexander and William Bennett observe that the
Department, "has come to contain bad ideas, harmful practices, needless expenditures, obsolete
programs, dysfunctional regulations and the depredations of special interests that care more
about the well-being of education's 'producers' than for its 'consumers.'"<a href="#N_15_"><sup>(15)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Because of the sliding performance of America's children, growing doubts have been raised
about America's public schools.  In a recent study, Public Agenda asked Americans where they
would send their kids if money was not an issue; 57 percent said they'd send them to private
school.<a href="#N_16_"><sup>(16)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Given the dearth of any discernible results from the Department of Education, it is hard to
understand the words of Representative Major Owens (D-NY) writing in 1995 that the idea to
eliminate the Department of Education "represents a headlong plunge back into the dark
ages."<a href="#N_17_"><sup>(17)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>II. Overhead &amp; Growth in the Bureaucracy</strong>

<p align="center"><em>What Supporters Promised . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>The House bill provided for no more than 100 overhead personnel in the new department.<a href="#N_18_"><sup>(18)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<ul>
  <li>Robert Severs, Director of Federal Programs of the Winston-Salem/Forsyth County Schools
claimed, "The charges that a Department of Education would result in greater federal controls
and a larger bureaucracy have little basis in fact.  In reality, the new Department of Education
will greatly improve the management of federal education programs."<a href="#N_19_"><sup>(19)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Senator Birch Bayh (D-IN) stated, "We are not creating a new bureaucracy with the creation
of a Cabinet-level Department which will channel all its energies into education matters. 
Instead, we are reorganizing and streamlining a bureaucracy which already exists.  The
legislation includes prohibitions on allowing the Department to grow in size."<a href="#N_20_"><sup>(20)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Frank Horton (R-NY) stated, "It does not create a new education bureaucracy. 
In fact, it reduces the bureaucracy."<a href="#N_21_"><sup>(21)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>What Opponents Predicted . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Representative Henson Moore (R-LA), who opposed creation of a separate department,
predicted, "We will see increases in [the Department's] number of employees, regulations, and
expense."<a href="#N_22_"><sup>(22)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Ed Bethune (R-AR) stated, "Current estimates indicate that the new
Department could add nearly 1,000 pieces of paperwork to every school district annually.  In
establishing a new department, we become more efficient at producing cumbersome
regulations and increasing Federal redtape, not streamlining our educational system."<a href="#N_23_"><sup>(23)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>The Reality</em>
<ul>
  <li>In FY 1995, the Department of Education will spend $372 million in departmental
management.<a href="#N_24_"><sup>(24)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<ul>
  <li>Growth in personnel has been particularly marked in recent years.  In FY 1990, the department
employed 4,596 people.  By FY 1995, that number had increased to 5,100.<a href="#N_25_"><sup>(25)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>During floor debate, Representative Bob Walker (R-PA) argued that despite promises of
supporters and supposed guarantees in the bill that growth in the bureaucracy would be held in
check, many were already planning its expansion.  He noted, "I have here a letter written by
the President of the United States in which he is already talking about adding a new Assistant
Secretary to this Department.  The bill has not even cleared Congress and they are already
adding high level, top echelon bureaucrats."<a href="#N_26_"><sup>(26)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>During the government shutdown of November 1995, 89.4% of Department of Education 
employees were deemed nonessential.<a href="#N_27_"><sup>(27)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>III. Efficiency</strong>

<p align="center"><em>What Supporters Promised . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Representative Brooks claimed that by creating a separate department, "We will have done
what we always talk about doing; that is, just to make the Federal Government a bit more
efficient, a bit more responsive."<a href="#N_28_"><sup>(28)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Supporters argued that the new department would be more efficient.  James R. Kirkpatrick,
Senior Associate Director of the American Association of School Administrators wrote,
"Local school administrators advise us they find the present structure unwieldy and
unresponsive.  Duplicate regulations generated in different departments are often conflicting;
they are confusing and burden schools with unnecessary paperwork.  AASA members are
convinced that a Cabinet level Department of Education will be a significant improvement. 
AASA's 1979 delegate assembly approved a resolution urging 'establishment of a position of
Secretary of Education at cabinet rank.'  In addition to consolidating education programs, we
believe this would result in a more efficient organization."<a href="#N_29_"><sup>(29)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Levitas said creation of a separate Education Department, "will provide
accountability.  It will actually limit the number of people now in the bureaucracy for the first
time.  For the first time we will have a smaller agency rather than a larger one; we will have a
legislative veto over all of the regulations that come out of this bureaucracy; we will be cutting
back, not increasing Government."<a href="#N_30_"><sup>(30)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Levitas went on to remark that, "We will end up with less bureaucracy, more efficiency, more
economy in Government, and better education."<a href="#N_31_"><sup>(31)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Senator Abraham Ribicoff (D-CT) stated that the new Department of Education would have a,
"lean, tight, simple, and efficient structure."<a href="#N_32_"><sup>(32)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Horton stated, "There will be less redtape and better service to States,
localities, educational institutions, and students."<a href="#N_33_"><sup>(33)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative David Bonior (D-MI) claimed, "By processing regulations faster, by eliminating
layer upon layer of bureaucracy and redtape, by eliminating at least 500 positions by the end of
the first fiscal year after the act becomes effective, and by bringing these Federal education
programs under one roof, we are making our Federal support services more available to serve
local needs."<a href="#N_34_"><sup>(34)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>What Opponents Predicted . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Representative Moore noted, "Redtape will mount as the influence of the Department of
Education grows."<a href="#N_35_"><sup>(35)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<ul>
  <li>Representative Evans stated, "There is absolutely no guarantee that the promised operational
efficiencies from a Cabinet-level department would ever materialize."<a href="#N_36_"><sup>(36)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative John Erlenborn (R-IL) stated during a floor debate, "Here we are again with a
reorganization bill to create a new Department.  We had one not too long ago, a bill to create
the Department of Energy, and I heard the same claims then that I hear today.  It was going to
consolidate programs.  It was going to make Government work better and be more responsive. 
I believed that then.  A lot of us believed that, and we created the Department of Energy.  And
what has happened? I think we all know.  I have heard Member after Member in the Halls of
the House say what a mistake we made to believe those claims.  'Fool me once, shame on you;
fool me twice, shame on me.'  That is an old saying and I think it is one we had better believe. 
We have been fooled once.  Do not be fooled again."<a href="#N_37_"><sup>(37)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>The Reality</em>
<ul>
  <li>One of the driving motivations of supporters of abolishing the Department of Education is the
excessive paperwork burdens that it places on local schools.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>A recent General Accounting Office study of the Department of Education found, "The
Department's history is replete with long-standing management problems."<a href="#N_38_"><sup>(38)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<ul>
  <li>Public policy expert Herbert J. Walberg notes,  "The U.S. Department of Education creates a
great deal of red tape that has little to do with learning."<a href="#N_39_"><sup>(39)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Interestingly, the Heineman Commission of 1967, which looked at reforming government,
argued, "Efforts should be made to reduce, merge and realign the number of departments
substantially in the grip of parochial interests and resist proposals to create additional
departments likely to be dominated by narrow, specialized interests or special
clientele."<a href="#N_40_"><sup>(40)</sup></a>Similarly, the Ash Council of 1971 argued that the number of departments should
be reduced.<a href="#N_41_"><sup>(41)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>IV. Local Control</strong>

<p align="center"><em>What Supporters Promised . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Senator Ribicoff argued, "Without the remedies offered by the Department of Education, the
threat of more Federal intrusion in the local control of education can only increase."<a href="#N_42_"><sup>(42)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Levitas claimed, "There is not one single word in this bill that creates any more
Federal presence in education than currently exists."<a href="#N_43_"><sup>(43)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Levitas also claimed, "Written into this legislation are specific prohibitions
against the new Department's having any control over curriculum, personnel, libraries or
anything else.  Local control is maintained."<a href="#N_44_"><sup>(44)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>According to Representative Brooks, the new department would provide for, "more
involvement of State and local officials in the Federal Government's education programs."<a href="#N_45_"><sup>(45)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>What Opponents Predicted . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Representative Shirley Chisholm (D-NY) noted that by creating the new department, "We will
be minimizing the roles of local and State education officials; we recognize that the States are
responsible for the educational policies of the children in this country."<a href="#N_46_"><sup>(46)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Joseph Early (D-MA) noted, "A national Department may actually impede the
innovation of local programs as it attempts to establish uniformity throughout the Nation."<a href="#N_47_"><sup>(47)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Pat Schroeder (D-CO) predicted, "No matter what anyone says, the
Department of Education will not just write checks to local school boards.  They will meddle
in everything.  I do not want that."<a href="#N_48_"><sup>(48)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Moore warned, "I expect the Department of Education will be oppressive by
usurping control properly administered now by State and local authorities. . . State and local
control will likely continue to erode as the centralized power of the Department of Education
grows."<a href="#N_49_"><sup>(49)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Evans stated, "I am absolutely certain that a new Federal Department of
Education would eventually have the power and the inclination to tamper with areas in both
public and private education that rightfully belong to parents and the local community."<a href="#N_50_"><sup>(50)</sup></a></li>
</ul>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><em>The Reality</em>
<ul>
  <li>Herbert J. Walberg has written, "the U.S. spends 25.1 percent of its public school budget on
non-teaching staff, more than twice the average of other countries surveyed by the OECD. 
Such excess, largely administrative, costs stem primarily from the federal government's clumsy
efforts to interfere with and subsidize local schools.  Although it pays only 7.6 percent of
school costs, the federal government imposes many mandates and regulatory burdens on  state
departments of education and local school boards."<a href="#N_51_"><sup>(51)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Thanks to legislation such as the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1994, federal
guidelines now cover topics such as how schools discipline students, the content of sex
education courses, and the gender of textbook authors.<a href="#N_52_"><sup>(52)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>One of the most prominent examples of the U.S. Department of Education overriding local
control has come in the area of special education.  According to DOE, states and localities
must pay for and continue alternative special education for special education students who are
expelled or placed on long-term suspension for disciplinary infractions -- such as drug dealing
and weapons possession -- that are unrelated to their disability.  States that do not comply with
DOE's policy risk losing millions of dollars in federal educational funding.  The department has
interpreted the law to require that states must provide educational services to all special
education students regardless of their disciplinary profile.  States such as Virginia have fought
the DOE requirements for several reasons: school safety, the ability to provide the proper
learning environment for all students, and the right of state and local authorities -- those closest
to the children -- to make educational decisions.<a href="#N_53_"><sup>(53)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<ul>
  <li>Former Department of Education officials Chester Finn, Jr. and Diane Ravitch write of the
Department of Education that, "the agency and many of its programs -- micromanaged at every
turn by Congressional subcommittees and staffers -- are the captives of Washington-based
education lobbies and special interests.  The country would be better off without it: the
department does little to improve education while imposing countless unnecessary burdens."<a href="#N_54_"><sup>(54)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Former Secretaries of Education Lamar Alexander and William Bennett have stated that the
Department has, "an irresistible and uncontrollable impulse to stick its nose into areas where it
has no proper business.  Most of what it does today is no legitimate affair of the federal
government.  The Education Department operates from the deeply erroneous belief that
American parents, teachers, communities and states are too stupid to raise their own children,
run their own schools and make their own decisions."<a href="#N_55_"><sup>(55)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Interestingly, the National Education Association, when testifying before Congress in 1979
stated that, "the Federal Government ought to be paying as much as a third of the cost of
public education."<a href="#N_56_"><sup>(56)</sup></a> At the time, the federal government was providing only about eight
percent of all education dollars.<a href="#N_57_"><sup>(57)</sup></a> If other supporters of the creation of a separate Department
of Education were promising that the federal government would not become too intrusive, at
least some supporters were hoping it would.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Despite a consensus among Americans to maintain local control of schools, supporters of the
Department of Education persist in their advocacy of centralization.  Representative Major
Owens has written in 1995 that the United States, "has erred by having too meager a federal
government role in the nation's education."<a href="#N_58_"><sup>(58)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>School districts in more than one quarter of all states so dislike federal strings that they have
refused some funding to avoid federal controls.<a href="#N_59_"><sup>(59)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>V. Cost</strong>

<p align="center"><em>What Supporters Promised . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>The House bill called for a budget for the department of $14.5 billion.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Brooks claimed, "We will have a more streamlined operation that will save us
money down the line."<a href="#N_60_"><sup>(60)</sup></a> He also claimed that the department would save taxpayers $100
million.<a href="#N_61_"><sup>(61)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Levitas claimed that with a separate department, "we will get more for the
dollars and a better education for our children."<a href="#N_62_"><sup>(62)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>What Opponents Predicted . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Representative L. H. Fountain, (D-NC) said, "I am opposed to this ill-advised and unnecessary
legislation to establish a department which will grow and grow, cost the taxpayers of this
Nation unnecessary billions of dollars, and ultimately become an unmanageable monster
bureaucracy."<a href="#N_63_"><sup>(63)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Representative Michel said simply that creation of a separate department, "would not do the
taxpayers any good."<a href="#N_64_"><sup>(64)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>The Reality</em>
<ul>
  <li>DOE spending for FY 1995 is $32.9 billion, which is 127 percent more than what was
originally budgeted (23 percent more in real terms).<a href="#N_65_"><sup>(65)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>While real growth of 23 percent over 16 year is not spectacular, this figure should be put in
context: other parts of the budget experienced austerity during the past 15 years.  In the
decade prior to the establishment of the Department of Education, spending on education rose
at only about half the rate of the rest of the non-defense discretionary budget (35% versus
65.4%).  In the period since the establishment of the department, <em>education spending has risen
at a rate over three times as fast as non-defense discretionary programs</em> (29.5% versus
7.9%).<a href="#N_66_"><sup>(66)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Interestingly, <em>The Washington Post</em> observed in a June 5, 1979 editorial, "Of all the claims
being made for the proposed Department of Education, the most incredible is that it would not
grow."<a href="#N_67_"><sup>(67)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<ul>
  <li>With the exception of Switzerland, the United States spends more on education per student
than any other country in the world -- almost 50 percent more than Germany and 85 percent
more than Japan.<a href="#N_68_"><sup>(68)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>K-12 per pupil spending, in inflation-adjusted terms, increased by 36.7% in the 1980's.<a href="#N_69_"><sup>(69)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>VI. Values</strong>

<p>While supporters made few comments on this topic, values were a significant concern for
opponents.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><em>What Opponents Predicted . . .</em>
<ul>
  <li>Representative Evans observed, "The new Department would, over time, have the effect of
shaping the values of future generations of Americans according to the political, social, and
economic values held by a group of faceless bureaucrats in Washington.  The creation of this
Department provides the ripe potential for the centralization and control of ideas."<a href="#N_70_"><sup>(70)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Stanford University President Richard Lyman noted, "The 200 year old absence of a
department of education is not the result of a simple failure during all that time to notice that
virtually every other nation in the world has come to have one.  On the contrary, it derives
from the notion that we do not want the kinds of education systems that such arrangements
seem to produce."<a href="#N_71_"><sup>(71)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Senator Moynihan, in arguing against creation of the department, stated, "we risk the
politicization of education itself, and that it will come about in ways that the system of
education itself will not be able to resist."<a href="#N_72_"><sup>(72)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Many opponents saw the drive for creation of a separate Department of Education as the pet
project of the National Education Association.  In this view, creation of DOE was simply part
of an effort to centralize educational policy.  Representative John Ashbrook (R-OH) argued,
"An integral part of the NEA design is to siphon ever more control of public education from
the grass roots to Washington, closer to its own powerful lobbying influence, farther from the
parents and taxpayers who elect the school boards and pay the bills."<a href="#N_73_"><sup>(73)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><em>The Reality</em>
<ul>
  <li>Today, parents across the country are fighting against educational standards and norms that are
coming down from the Department of Education.  Thomas DeWeese of the American Policy
Foundation has stated that because of federal standards, "The indoctrination methods . . . start
in kindergarten, where students are filled with horror stories of ozone holes, dying species,
homelessness and war."  "Yet many schools today have ceased teaching such basic skills as
spelling and multiplication tables."<a href="#N_74_"><sup>(74)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">  <li>Discussing Goals 2000 and H.R. 6, the two main education efforts of the 103rd Congress,
former Secretaries of Education Lamar Alexander and William Bennett note, "it becomes plain
that their authors want to substitute decisions made in Washington for decisions made by
individual households and communities. . . They use federal funding in a deceptive way that is
designed to elicit the behaviors that other parts of the legislation declare to be 'voluntary.' 
They throw obstacles onto such promising reform pathways as school choice and private
management of public schools."<a href="#N_75_"><sup>(75)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>Conclusion</strong>

<p>As was noted in the introduction of this paper, intense debates over a separate Department of
Education waned after it was established but have been resurrected during the 104th Congress. 
Representative Robin Beard (R-TN) prophesied at the time of the creation of the Department, "A
great deal of attention and debate has centered on the growth, size, cost and efficiency of the
Federal Government -- and rightly so.  That debate stems from the many governmental
departments and agencies that continue to receive matter-of-course funding, in spite of the clear
evidence that many of them have long since outlived their usefulness.  Ten years from now, we
may be saying the same thing about other governmental agencies, including the proposed
Department of Education."<a href="#N_76_"><sup>(76)</sup></a> Mr. Beard's prediction was pretty close to the mark.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Opponents of a separate Department of Education in 1979 were not anti-education.  They had
numerous ideas for bettering education, but with a radically different approach.  Representative
Moore observed, "A constructive alternative to H.R. 2444 [creating the Department] is a
concerted commitment by local communities and their citizens to support local education.  This
may be in the form of approval of bond issues, recommendations for higher tax bases and levies,
or parents taking more of an interest in the education their children receive."<a href="#N_77_"><sup>(77)</sup></a> Representative
Evans and others called for simply a reorganization of the existing Office of Education rather than
creation of the new Department.<a href="#N_78_"><sup>(78)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The same is true today.  Those in Congress wishing to dismantle the Department of Education are
supporting not simply ending all education spending, but turning much of it over to the states and
localities.  For example, the bill sponsored by Representative Joe Scarborough (R-FL), H.R.
1883, would take $11 billion in aid to elementary and secondary schools and aid to colleges and
make it into a single block grant which the states could spend as they wish.  What opponents of
the department then and now want to eliminate are federal controls, red tape and the excess cost
of a federal bureaucracy.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Given the dismal performance of the department over the past sixteen years, were supporters
simply oblivious to the probable consequences of their actions?  Perhaps not.  Representative
Benjamin Rosenthal (D-NY -- who was opposed to creating the department) noted, "In the
history of the Republic, 14 Cabinet-level departments have been created.  We may or may not
create one this afternoon.  If it is created, it will not be on the merits.  It will be because this has
been the most intensely lobbied reorganization bill that has ever appeared in Congress.  There is
nobody who is really for this new Department in this Chamber.  Everybody who says they are
going to vote for it say, 'Well, I made a commitment or a promise to some people back in the
district.'"<a href="#N_79_"><sup>(79)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Similarly, <em>The Wall Street Journal</em> reported one liberal House Democrat admitting, "The idea of
an Education Department is really a bad one.  But it's NEA's top priority.  There are school
teachers in every congressional district and most of us simply don't need the aggravation of taking
them on."<a href="#N_80_"><sup>(80)</sup></a> Representative Bob Michel termed the DOE the "Special Interest Memorial Prize of
1979."<a href="#N_81_"><sup>(81)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But whether or not the creation of the Department of Education was simply a political payoff,<a href="#N_82_"><sup>(82)</sup></a>it
is exacting a steep price today.  The price can, of course, be measured in the billions of dollars
that are annually wasted on the Department but more importantly can be seen in the failure of our
school system to deliver the quality education that America's children deserve.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
