<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>The PAC Partisanship of Major Interest Groups</strong></h3>
<h4 align="center">John E. Berthoud, Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 130</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>August 26, 1996</strong></h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Executive Summary</strong>

<p>Recent concerns about the close relationship of business and other interest groups with the
Republican Party raise the question of how partisan are these groups' campaign contributions
vis-a-vis the campaign contributions of labor unions?

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A review of new Federal Election Commission PAC data for a select list of major business
groups, major labor groups, and several other prominent interest groups reveals:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>While the leading business groups have been pro-Republican in their contributions, they have
still given more than 20 percent of their funds to Democratic candidates.  Their partisanship
ratio (Republican contributions relative to Democratic contributions) is just under 4:1.</li>
  <li>Labor groups are almost completely partisan in their contributions, with barely 2 percent of
their funds going to Republican candidates.  Their partisanship ratio is over 44:1.</li>
  <li>The <em>least partisan</em> of the labor groups analyzed (the Teamsters) is as partisan in their
contributions as the <em>most partisan</em> business group (the NFIB).</li>
  <li>In percentage terms, the NRA has given nine times as much to Democratic candidates (19.9
percent) as these labor groups have given to Republicans (2.2 percent).</li>
  <li>Despite some suggestions that they were going to be more bipartisan in 1996, both major
teacher unions remain just as monolithic in their support of Democratic candidates as they've
been in the past, giving them 99 percent of their PAC funds.</li>
  <li>The trial lawyers are quite partisan in their giving patterns, contributing to Democratic
candidates over Republican candidates at a ratio of about 7:1.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><strong>The PAC Partisanship of Major Interest Groups</strong>

<p align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>I. Introduction</strong>

<p>The role of American business in the 1996 elections has been much commented on.  Critics have
focused on two issues: the amount of money and influence that the business groups hold, and the
extent of their partisanship.  The groups are seen as closely linked with the Republican Party, and
the GOP in turn has been labeled as beholden to these interests in general or specific corporate
interests in particular.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a> The GOP has also been portrayed as closely linked to the National Rifle
Association.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>On the NRA connection, one national pundit recently wrote,  "The Republicans and the
National Rifle Association are as one."<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a></li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>A recent Associated Press story gave key attribution for the fund-raising success of the
Republican Party vis-a-vis the Democratic Party to "the help of some corporate friends."<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a></li>
  <li>Discussing corporate funding of the Republican Party, Marvin Rosen, the finance chairman of
the Democratic National Committee, told <em>The New York Times</em> that, "It's going to be very hard
to match them because of the large corporations and what they're giving to the Republicans."<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p>These claimed links naturally raise the question of relativity -- how close are the party connections
of these groups relative to the connections of other groups?  In particular, this paper seeks to
discover how partisan are these groups' campaign contributions vis-a-vis the campaign
contributions of labor groups.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>II. Partisanship Findings</strong>

<p>To analyze this issue, this paper reviews the partisanship of contributions by the Political Action
Committees (PACs) of five major business groups and five major labor organizations.  Three
other prominent interest groups are reviewed as well.  The information was obtained from the
Federal Election Commission and is the latest data for the 1995-6 election cycle.  The groups
reviewed are:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">Business
<ul>
  <li>Business-Industry Political Action Committee - BIPAC represents a cross-section of corporate
interests.</li>
  <li>Health Insurance Association of America - HIAA is a leading player in the health reform
debate, representing the interests of health insurers.</li>
  <li>American Bankers Association - the ABA's approximately 9,000 members are commercial
banks and trust companies whose assets account for approximately 95% of the U.S. banking
industry.</li>
  <li>Tobacco Institute - the Washington research and representation arm of the major tobacco
firms.</li>
  <li>National Federation of Independent Businesses - NFIB represents 600,000 small business
owners.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center">Unions
<ul>
  <li>American Federation of Teachers - the nation's second largest teacher's union, affiliated with
the AFL-CIO.</li>
  <li>AFL-CIO - while not a union per se, this umbrella organization for labor unions has a total of
13 million members.</li>
  <li>National Education Association - the nation's largest union with 2.2 million members.<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a></li>
  <li>Teamsters - the second largest union in America, with 1.5 million members.  The Teamsters
are affiliated with the AFL-CIO.<a href="pacstudy.gif"><sup>(6)</sup></a></li>
  <li>American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees - AFSCME has 1.3 million
members and is affiliated with the AFL-CIO.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center">Professional &amp; Other
<ul>
  <li>American Medical Association - the AMA represents 375,000 doctors.</li>
  <li>Association of Trial Lawyers of America - ATLA has a membership of 54,000, most of whom
are trial lawyers.</li>
  <li>National Rifle Association - the NRA has approximately 3 million members.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p>The analysis includes only PAC contributions and does not include independent expenditures of
these groups' PACs for or against candidates.  The analysis also does not include contributions
from individual members of these groups (individual companies, individual doctors, local union
affiliates, etc.)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<table border cellpadding=5 width="96%">
<tr>
<td colspan="8" valign="top" width="18%">
<p align="center">Table 1. Profiles of PAC Campaign Contributions</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top" width="14%"><font size="-1">PAC Funds
