<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$4,729,526</font></td></tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="8" valign="top"><font size="-1">Professional &amp; Other</font></td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">AMA</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$820,291</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">80.5%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$198,214</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">19.5%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$0</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">0.0%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$1,018,505</font></td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">Trial Lawyers</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$188,500</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">12.1%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$1,359,475</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">87.5%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$5,000</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">0.3%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$1,552,975</font></td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">NRA</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$577,870</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">80.1%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$143,550</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">19.9%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$0</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">0.0%</font></td>
<td valign="top"><font size="-1">$721,420</font></td></tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="8" valign="top"><font size="-1">Source of data: the Federal Election Commission.</font></td></tr></table>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A review of this PAC data (see Table 1) reveals:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>While the leading business groups have been pro-Republican in their contributions, they have
still given more than 20 percent of their funds to Democratic candidates.  Their partisanship
ratio (Republican contributions relative to Democratic contributions) is just under 4:1.</li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Labor groups are almost completely partisan in their contributions, with barely 2 percent of
their funds going to Republican candidates.  Their partisanship ratio is over 44:1.</li>
  <li>The <em>least partisan</em> of these labor groups (the Teamsters) is as partisan in their contributions as
the <em>most partisan</em> business group (the NFIB).</li>
  <li>The partisan tilt of the National Education Association (99 percent of their funds going to 
Democratic candidates), which is not a member of the AFL-CIO, is as great or greater than
that of the AFL-CIO affiliated labor groups analyzed.</li>
  <li>Despite some suggestions that they were going to be more bipartisan in 1996, both major
teacher unions (the NEA and the AFT) remain just as monolithic in their support of
Democratic candidates as they've been in the past, giving them 99 percent of their PAC funds.</li>
  <li>The trial lawyers are quite partisan in their giving patterns, contributing to Democratic
candidates over Republican candidates at a ratio of about 7:1.</li>
  <li>The AMA and the NRA are far less partisan than these labor groups, each contributing to
Republican candidates over Democratic candidates at a ratio of about 4:1 each.</li>
  <li>In percentage terms, the NRA has given nine times as much to Democratic candidates (19.9
percent) as these labor groups have given to Republicans (2.2 percent).</li>
  <li>Overall, the business groups analyzed, along with the NRA and AMA, tend the most towards
bipartisanship.  Labor is the least bipartisan, followed by the trial lawyers.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p><img src="pacstudy.gif" width="443" height="329" align="bottom" >

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>These findings about the unions being far more partisan than any of these other groups should be
of interest to union members -- especially since these ratios of partisan support by union
leadership are almost certainly not reflective of union rank-and-file.  In the case of the NEA for
example, their internal polls show that 40 percent of union members are Democrats, with the rest
split between Republicans and Independents.<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>III. Conclusion</strong>

<p>To the extent that concerns raised about the partisanship of business groups in general or specific
industries in particular are legitimate, even greater concerns should be raised about the influence
of labor organizations over the Democratic Party.  This is also true to a lesser degree with the trial
lawyers.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">________________________________________

<p>This paper is fifth in a series of AdTI reports on the fiscal, legislative, and political agendas of
special interest groups.  Other titles include:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li>"A Fiscal and Public Policy Profile of The American Federation of Teachers," AdTI Issue Brief
Number 128, August 1996.</li>
  <li>"A Fiscal Analysis of NEA and AFL-CIO Contributions to 1996 Congressional Races," AdTI
Issue Brief Number 126, June 1996.</li>
  <li>"Judging an Interest Group by the Politicians It Keeps: An Analysis of NEA-PAC
Contributions to House Races," AdTI Issue Brief Number 120, May 1996.</li>
  <li>"The Fiscal Impact of the NEA's Legislative Agenda," March 1996.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

