<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>"Why Subsidize Sports?"</strong></h3>

<p align="center">John E. Berthoud

<p align="center">Vice President

<p align="center">The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The past couple of months have witnessed an unprecedented number of sports headlines
trumpeting multimillion dollar deals.  Alonzo Mourning signing with the Miami Heat after
rejecting a seven-year $78.4 million deal from the Charlotte Hornets as inadequate.  Art Modell
accepting a deal from the city of Baltimore after not getting the terms he wanted for his Browns in
Cleveland.  In Washington state, as the Mariners proceeded into post-season, the state legislature
adopted a multi-million dollar package of public financing for the Mariners' stadium under threats
that the now-successful team would otherwise leave the city.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The capitalist spirit felt by players and team owners wouldn't be a problem if it weren't for the fact
that today hard-pressed taxpayers are being continually asked to provide them millions in
subsidies through the financing of stadiums.  These kind of economic development projects which
have become a fact of life in the sporting world are corporate welfare at its worst.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The biggest problem with these corporate giveaways is that our major cities are the ones least able
to afford them.  Urban taxpayers already suffer under a punishing tax burden.  Combined with
fears of crime, high taxes are driving huge segments of the urban tax base fleeing into suburbia. 
During the 1980's, city operating costs rose by 22 percent.  These costs were passed onto
taxpayers.  In the 41 largest cities during that decade, $13 billion more taxes were collected, after
factoring in inflation and changes in population.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>What is worse, often the taxes to pay for the teams are regressive.  For example, Cleveland
residents have been asked to pay special cigarette and alcohol taxes to keep the Browns.  Given
the skyrocketing prices of tickets for many major league sporting events, this has meant franchises
have played a cruel joke on the declining ranks of the urban middle class.  They pay the taxes to
keep these teams in their cities, but then can't afford to go to the games (and don't have access to
corporate sky boxes).  In Washington state, some of the new $300 million in public financing will
come out of a sales tax.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In those cases where stadiums or other economic development projects get tax abatements, if
these aren't paid for by a special surtax, then often they end up simply eroding the tax base.  By
giving special breaks to one group, cities and states, which unlike the federal government can't run
deficits, will have to make up that lost revenue somewhere else.  While it would be nice to
imagine that this means a cut in spending somewhere, in reality, all too often it simply means
higher taxes on businesses that are less visible or have less political clout.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But despite these problems, proponents of stadiums and all economic development projects
always claim that these schemes will pay for themselves because they will create thousands of jobs
and generate millions in revenues for the cities and states that are lucky enough to offer the most
lucrative package of special breaks.  In their view, individuals or businesses should be happy to
pay higher taxes for these teams.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>A key problem with much of the analysis put forward by proponents of economic development
projects like stadiums is that the data presented on job creation or revenue generation is often
only really the gross figures.  This type of analysis often misses much of the picture.  For example,
there is something that economists term the "substitution effect" -- those spending their
entertainment dollars on a football game will not be spending them at the movies or on golf. 
Viewed this way, there may be little economic benefit from such deals.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Indeed, investigations of the question of whether special economic development projects result in
a net economic gain have turned up little.  For example, Robert Baade did a regression analysis of
stadiums and city economics in 48 major U.S. cities for the Heartland Institute and found no
relationship between stadium projects and higher economic growth.  Baade writes, "After a
thorough examination of an unprecedented quantity of data related to professional sports and host
area per capita personal income, the author finds no factual basis for the conventional argument
that professional sports stadiums and teams have a significant impact on a region's economic
growth."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>One of the key reasons why economic development projects end up as a net loser for cities and
states is that these type of projects also open a pandora's box for politicians.  While one project
may sound very justifiable on economic or civic grounds, as David Stockman used to say, "pork
travels in herds."  Economic development soon becomes a way to simply channel dollars into the
favored projects of powerful politicians.  It gets government into the business of picking winners
and losers, which it is ill-equipped to do.  And the politically un-organized businesses always lose
out to the politically astute (usually this means the big guys win out over the little guys), which is
not the way to achieve economic growth.  If supply-side economics has had one enduring lesson
for the nation, it is that the best way to ensure real growth is to treat all businesses in an
even-handed manner with special breaks for none and minimal taxes and regulations for all.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>If stadiums and by implication other great "economic development" projects paid for by corporate
tax rebates are no great economic deals for cities and states, why do they persist in undertaking
them?  The answer is politics.  While the job creation from a big tax subsidy may be a zero sum
(the jobs created on the tax-favored projects are offset by job losses in other industries that have
to pay higher taxes) the jobs created in the tax-favored project are usually more high profile.  A
tax abatement for a large manufacturer allows politicians to claim the credit for creating hundreds
of very visible jobs.  The jobs lost because of higher taxes elsewhere are mostly invisible.  Plus,
when government begins to contemplate getting into the "economic development" racket this
provides politicians with the irresistible opportunity to meddle with the economy.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Now undoubtedly, there are some city pride issues associated with stadiums.  But even still,
asking hard-pressed city taxpayers to subsidize multi-millionaire owners and eight figure-salaries
athletes is hard to justify.  And in an era when teams exhibit no loyalty to local fans, while cable
TV and satellite TV can each week bring in dozens of sporting contests to any household, it
becomes harder to argue that cities and fans need these teams at the taxing price they are
charging.  Like with drugs,  its time that big cities "just said no" to this type of extortion.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">______________________

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This article, slightly edited and abridged, appeared in <em>Investor's Business Daily</em>, November 29,
1995, Page A2.  The same article also appeared in <em>The Indianapolis Star</em>, <em>The Waterbury
Republican-American</em>, <em>The </em>(Colorado Springs)<em> Gazette Telegraph</em>, <em>The Delaware County Sunday
Times</em>, and <em>The New Haven Register</em>.
</body>
</html>
