<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>Federal Civilian Employment Trends in the 1990's</strong></h3>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><h4 align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud</h4>
<h4 align="center">Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center"></h4>

<p align="center"><strong>AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 104</strong>
<h4 align="center"><strong>August 3, 1995</strong></h4>

<p align="center"><hr>

<p>The Clinton Administration is trying to claim credit for substantial cuts in the federal bureaucracy. 
According to the White House, "President Clinton has already cut the federal bureaucracy by
more than 100,000 positions.  Under the recommendations of the National Performance Review,
the federal bureaucracy will be reduced  by 272,000 -- its lowest level since the Kennedy
Administration."<a href="#N_1_">(1)</a> What the Administration has not publicized is that almost all the cuts have
come from the Department of Defense.  Table 1 provides an overview of the facts.
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">

<table border cellpadding=5 width="87%">
<tr>
<td colspan="4" valign="top" width="27%">Table 1. Executive Branch Civilian Full-Time Equivalent Employees: 1990-1996</td></tr>
