<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>These numbers show:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<ul>
  <li><em>In the Clinton era, 83% of the job cuts have occurred in DOD (131,000 out of 157,000).</em>Thus,
while the administration is certainly correct that it has cut "more than 100,000 positions" less
than one in five have been eliminated in non-defense agencies.  It is difficult to reconcile this
fact with the President's statement that, "The New Covenant approach to governing unites us
behind a common vision of what is best for our country.  It seeks to shift resources and
decisionmaking from bureaucrats to citizens."<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a></li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p align="center"><img src="fedemp.gif" width="301" height="233" align="bottom" >

<p align="left">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">

<ul>
  <li><em>Looking at the whole decade, non-DOD civilian employment will actually be higher in 1996
than in 1990</em>.  Over these six years (which also includes changes made by President Bush's
1990 budget agreement), non-defense employment will rise by 13,000.  During the same
period, DOD civilian employment will be cut by 205,000.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p>While the situation may change with the more conservative 104th Congress, to date, the
President's pledge to "cut the federal bureaucracy" has resulted in cuts -- but almost exclusively in
defense personnel.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Endnotes</strong><a name="N_1_">

<p>1. </a> "A Look at President Clinton's Accomplishments," The White House Home Page, downloaded
August 3, 1995.<a name="N_2_">

<p>2. </a> <em>Economic Report of the President</em>, February 1995, Page 7.
</body>
</html>
