<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>Immigration:  The View from City Hall</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>A Survey of Mayors and Officials</strong></h3>
<h3 align="center"><strong>in High-Immigration Cities</strong></h3>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><h4 align="center">by Philip Peters, Senior Fellow</h4>
<h4 align="center"></h4>
<h4 align="center">September 11, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><em><strong>Executive Summary</strong></em>

<p>A survey of mayors and city officials in America's highest-immigration cities shows that these
officials generally believe that immigration has had a positive impact.  Combined "positive" and
"very positive" responses were 77 percent. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>None of the respondents suggested a need to reduce the annual levels of legal immigration to the
U.S. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Sixty-nine percent cited needs for the federal government to increase border enforcement to
reduce the flow of illegal immigration, or to compensate for the costs associated with recent
immigrants.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>We asked whether, if they were given the authority, they would stop funding the education of
children of illegal immigrants.  (A legislative proposal passed by the House of Representatives
would give states that option.)  All but one responded "no;" one deferred to the local school
board.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Immigration:  The View from City Hall</strong>

<p align="center"><strong>A Survey of Mayors and Officials</strong>

<p align="center"><strong>in High-Immigration Cities</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">by Philip Peters, Senior Fellow

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution (AdTI) surveyed mayors and municipal officials in
high-immigration cities to find out how they view the impact of immigration on their communities. 


<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>We surveyed the seventeen American cities that have over 200,000 population and over 20
percent foreign-born residents.  We received thirteen responses from the seventeen cities:  seven
from mayors and six from their designees. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While this is not a large-scale opinion poll, these officials' views do indicate the ways immigration
affects America's largest high-immigration communities, and the ways that managers of local
governments assess the benefits and costs.  While our questions focused almost exclusively on
local impacts, the answers make an interesting contribution to the national debate over
immigration policy.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>High-immigration cities are not homogeneous.   Miami and Hialeah, Florida have absorbed
successive waves of immigrants, while Glendale, California had a pronounced influx that was
largely responsible for a 25 percent population increase from 1985 to 1989.  Some have pools of
generally unskilled immigrants, others (e.g. Fremont, California) have large numbers of
professionals, while the immigrant pools in others (e.g. San Francisco) span the spectrum.  Recent
immigrants to south Florida generally speak Spanish or Haitian Creole; in other cities, extremely
diverse immigrant communities pose enormous challenges for schools and all providers of public
services.  For example, 130 languages are spoken in the home in Fremont, California; 60 in
Glendale, 20 in Boston.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The responses to our survey lead us to the conclusion that sweeping conclusions about the local
impact of immigration are wrong.  The impacts are as diverse as our nation itself and the
immigrants that we receive each year.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>However, there were five general tendencies expressed in the responses:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>1.  Immigration's local impact is viewed as positive.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a></strong> Asked to describe the general impact of
immigration in their communities, our respondents answers were 77 percent "positive" or "very
positive:"  3.5 were "very positive," 6.5 "positive," two "neutral," 0.5 "negative" and 0.5 "very
negative."  (Two split their answers between "positive" and "negative" and "very  positive" and
"very negative.")

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>2.  No recommendation to cut legal immigration.</strong> In response to an open-ended question
seeking recommendations for federal immigration policy actions, none of the respondents called
for a reduction in legal immigration.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>3.  Immigration brings growing pains and adjustment problems.</strong> The officials described a
variety of challenges they face in absorbing new immigrants, including the difficulty of providing
education and public services to new residents, and meeting the cost of incarcerating illegal
immigrants.  Children have language adjustment problems, and parents have language barriers and
difficulty getting involved in school matters when parents are working.  Municipal governments
have to make special efforts to teach immigrants about the use of public services, for example
when to use and when not to use "911," or how to work with the police in reporting crimes.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>4.  Immigrants fill economic niches.</strong> We asked whether immigrants have impacts on sectors of
local economies.  The answers indicated that immigrants do fill particular niches in the
communities where they settle.  The following are examples:

<ul>
  <li>Jersey City:  Latin American and Indian retail businesses, Filipinos in health professions.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>San Francisco:  retail, services, professionals, international trade.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Hialeah:  new small businesses, skilled labor for garment industry. </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>El Paso:  labor for service sector.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>New York:  services, academia, research, home care, international trade.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Anaheim:  new business starts, and labor for light manufacturing industries, such as cellular
phones and other telecommunications equipment.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Miami:  services, international trade.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Los Angeles:  services, new garment manufacturing businesses, international trade.</li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Glendale:   Filipinos in health care professions.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Stockton:  Southeast Asians starting small businesses.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Boston:   service sector.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Fremont:   high-tech entrepreneurs, physicians, health professions.  </li>
</ul>

<ul>
  <li>Santa Ana:  retailers, industrial labor force.</li>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"></ul>

<p><strong>5.  No desire to stop educating children of illegal immigrants.</strong> The Gallegly amendment to the
immigration bill passed by the House this year would give states the option to stop paying for the
education of children of illegal immigrants.  Asked whether they would exercise that option if they
had the authority, none of our respondents said "yes."  Twelve responded "no;" one mayor
deferred to his school board.  Nine respondents (69%) called for the federal government to do
more to reduce illegal immigration or to compensate localities for the costs of absorbing recent
immigrants.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u><strong>Local Impacts</u></strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>We asked respondents to note whether the flow of immigrants into their communities had an
impact on any of a list economic and social indicators, and if so, to characterize that impact.<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a> 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>If they perceived no strong link between immigration and the indicator in the question, they did
not respond, or they replied "neutral." 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Combining "very positive" and "positive" to form a "favorable" rating and "very negative" and
"negative" to form an "unfavorable" rating, these are the impacts mentioned by 30 percent or
more of respondents:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Poverty level   38% unfavorable

<p>New business starts  62% favorable

<p>Property values  31% favorable

<p>Household income  31 % favorable

<p>Job creation   46 % favorable

<p>Crime rates   31 % unfavorable

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For example, five of thirteen respondents believed that immigration increased their city's poverty
level, so we record that 38% of respondents mentioned an unfavorable impact.  (This does not
imply that the remaining 62% believe the impact is opposite.  On this question, of the remaining
respondents, five did not respond, one replied "neutral," and two said immigration reduced the
poverty level.<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a>)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u><strong>Excerpts from Responses</u></strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The following are excerpts from the author's phone interviews with the respondents, with the
exception of Mayor Brown of San Francisco and Mr. Millard of New York, who responded in
writing.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Glendale -- Mayor Sheldon Baker</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"The impact of immigration has been anything but neutral.  Immigration has enriched our
community, broadened the horizons of this city, brought new value systems, made us re-think a
lot of things.  It has also taken us from above to below the county average income.  It has created
a tremendous demand for health care, education and other services such as libraries and parks."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On the strain of Glendale's dramatic population growth:

<p>"It's not because they're immigrants -- you just don't throw that many people into a community,
regardless of who they are, without strains on services and schools.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On federal immigration policy:

<p>"I won't address whether immigration should be tightened or loosened.  But resources need to be
released to the local level.  The federal government's looser policy has caused governments at the
city and county level to face challenging issues of social services, and we haven't had the
resources to adequately meet those challenges."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>San Francisco -- Mayor Willie Brown</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"Immigrants have made this city what it is:  San Francisco is defined by its ethnic neighborhoods
and its diverse population....This is the model of the immigrant city -- we're as diverse as
anyplace, and that's our strength."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"Immigrants have made a positive impact everywhere they have gone...[they] have moved into all
sectors of the economy; they are part and parcel of it, and San Francisco's international trade
benefits from the personal and professional ties our immigrants keep with their homelands."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On federal immigration policy (referring to a bill since signed into law):

<p>"The immediate crisis is the federal welfare bill working its way through Congress, which  I
vehemently oppose.  The bill would deny benefits to millions of <em>legal</em> immigrants, creating
unbearable hardship on families in San Francisco and throughout the nation, as well as shifting an
undue financial burden to local governments for which they are not prepared."

<p><em>Stockton -- Mayor Joan Darrah</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>After enumerating some of the costs of educating and administering city programs for new
immigrants:

<p>"So why do I say the impact [of immigration] has been positive?  This kind of diversity is really
good for a city in the long run.  It's going to pay off.  These are industrious people; they work
hard, they are in our community college system....We're still in the adjustment period, but we're
doing a pretty good job of handling it.  I just believe that diversity enriches a community, it's
going to pay off for us." 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Miami -- Acting Mayor Willie Gort</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"You have to realize it's different here than in other states.  Years ago the immigrants had a lot of
trouble at first, but they got established and this made it easier for the newer immigrants, like the
Central Americans in the 1980's.  The city is bilingual now.  It used to be that it was difficult to
get a license to start a business and get going, but now lots of [city government] departments and
businesses are bilingual."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"[Sometimes in reaction to immigration] established residents move out because they don't want
to see changes."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On federal immigration policy:

<p>"We should ensure that immigrants coming in are not going to be a burden on the state.  If you're
sponsored by a family, then that family should be responsible for you."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Hialeah -- Mayor Raul Martinez</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On labor market impact:

<p>"You always have jobs that people here don't want to do...people on the bottom of the ladder
come up..."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On housing:

<p>"Our first time homebuyers work hard, save, buy their houses...as soon as they move in they start
fixing up.  You can see it immediately on our southeast side -- old wooden homes with additions,
everybody likes to add a pool or a terrace.  They're very proud owners."

<p>On the Gallegly amendment, to permit states to stop funding public education of children of illegal
immigrants:

<p>"The Statue of Liberty would fall over if they did that.  You see kids come here from Cuba and in
6 or 9 months they're speaking English...why deny them the opportunity we all had?  If that were
to happen I would propose creating our own school system in Hialeah and paying for it ourselves
one hundred percent."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Fremont -- Mayor Gus Morrison</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"Our immigrants haven't created a demand for social services because they've been scientists and
professionals, technicians, engineers and entrepreneurs.  We didn't get poor immigrants."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"Speaking as a son of Scottish immigrants, I 'm grateful for the fact that we have open borders so
people can come here to make a new start."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Jersey City -- Mayor Bret Schundler</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"A good number of our immigrants are professionals or highly skilled...their economic life was not
great back home, they come from countries where entrepreneurialism is not easy, so they're
looking to make it...most immigrants come with the American dream."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On immigrants' positive impact on household income:

<p>"They come with little income, but if they weren't here you wouldn't have people coming into the
city."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>On federal immigration policy:

<p>"We should maintain a reasonable level of legal immigration, but we should target and give
greater weight to factors such as skill levels, education and investment capital."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Los Angeles -- Mayor's Deputy Chief of Staff Greg Dawley</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"If managed correctly, immigration is a very important resource for LA.  But we don't like the
fact that the federal government hasn't lived up to its obligation to control illegal immigration. 
There has not been effective reimbursement for impacts we've seen in the last 4-5 years.  This is a
burden we're bearing for the entire country.  The federal government has to focus on the points of
entry, and deport those [illegal immigrants] who commit crimes."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"We're the largest international trade region in the country...immigration creates great trade
relationships in Asia, Europe, Central and South America..."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Santa Ana -- Council Services Manager Lorraine Lazarene</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"I am concerned about crime prevention.  But these are people who want to work hard and
contribute to our community.  They shop downtown, and [our shopping district attracts]
Hispanics from all over the county.  That's very important to our tax base."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"There's a tremendous burden on public school system.  We're strapped for classroom space. 
Many of the kids are poor, they have no quiet study space at home, their parents are both
working.  They need as much assistance as they can possibly get." 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>New York -- Economic Development Corporation President Charles Millard</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"...almost all [New York City] neighborhoods are touched by immigrant settling patterns.  In
areas of high immigrant presence, we see increased occupancy, an entrepreneurial spirit, cultural
and culinary expressions.  More than anything, however, we perceive a sense of hope, promise
and family values.  This may be exhibited in business start-ups and home ownership."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"Immigrants have stabilized the City's population base and prevented the major shrinkage
experienced in other large urban centers."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em> Boston -- Director of Federal Relations Dina Siegal</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"We have had to radically alter the way we do business -- for example everything that goes home
with Boston public schoolchildren has to be translated into 20 languages."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>El Paso -- Executive Assistant to the Mayor Mark Smith</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"We depend on commerce with Mexico.  We want to streamline the process for legal immigrants,
for students at our university, executives in our twin plant industries, diplomats, housewives
visiting relatives -- we want to make it easier for them to move back and forth across the border."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>"But in general the federal government has not provided enough resources on the border.  They
need more supervisors, training and equipment -- and more Border Patrol agents -- to interdict
drugs and for better enforcement against illegal immigration."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><em>Anaheim -- Intergovernmental Relations Officer Christine Thalman</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Thalman has worked on a pilot program where the Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS)
placed an officer in Anaheim to assist in the rapid deportation of criminal aliens.  Anaheim has
been spending an estimated $1 million per year for their incarceration.  She spoke about INS
priorities:

<p>"They (INS personnel) focus on employer verification, spending hours going through
McDonnell-Douglas employee records....  Why focus on those who are working and contributing
to our economy instead of trying to remove the criminal element?  We're not doing a good job of
deportation." 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><u><strong>How This Survey Was Conducted</strong></u>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The author contacted respondents between July 8 and August 22, 1996.  The respondents were
Mayor Sheldon Baker of Glendale, California; Mayor Willie Brown of San Francisco, California;
Mayor Joan Darrah of Stockton, California; Acting Mayor Willie Gort of Miami, Florida; Mayor
Raul Martinez of Hialeah, Florida; Mayor Gus Morrison of Fremont, California; Mayor Bret
Schundler of Jersey City, New Jersey; Mayor's Deputy Chief of Staff Greg Dawley of Los
Angeles, California;  Council Services Manager Lorraine Lazarene of Santa Ana, California; New
York City Economic Development Corporation President Charles Millard; Director of Federal
Relations Dina Siegal of Boston, Massachusetts; Executive Assistant to the Mayor Mark Smith of
El Paso, Texas; and Intergovernmental Relations Officer Christine Thalman of Anaheim,
California.  The mayors of Yonkers, New York and San Diego, Long Beach and San Jose,
California declined to participate in the survey and declined to designate a representative to
participate.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><u><strong>Notes</u></strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><a name="N_1_">
<p>1. </a> Our respondents from Santa Ana and Stockton, California, and Miami are among those who
said immigration's impact was "positive."  These are three of the five high-immigration cities
examined in <em>A Tale of Ten Cities</em>, a 1995 report by the Federation for American Immigration
Reform.  In his foreword, the author of that study was "flabbergasted" by his findings that
high-immigration cities are "overwhelmed" and that less immigration yields "a higher quality of
life for everyone."  AdTI interviewed low-immigration city mayors.  Mayor Larry E. Chavis of
Richmond, Virginia, said immigration has no substantial impact, but that the small and growing
Asian community is "great."  "Diversity adds to a community, makes it more vital.  We need new
ideas, new work ethics," he said.  Asked whether an influx of immigrants would be beneficial to
Jackson, Mississippi, Mayor Kane Ditto said:  "Yes.  In general, I believe immigrants help
wherever they are.  We have a very difficult labor shortage problem in Jackson, across the board,
in construction, white collar work -- most every businessman I talk to talks about it."
<a name="N_2_">
<p>2. </a> In his response, New York City Economic Development Corporation President Charles
Millard noted a lack of data isolating the effect of immigration on the economic and social
indicators in our question, but noted that "from 1980 to 1990,  New York City's foreign-born
population increased 24.7 percent, median household income increased 28.4 percent and the
number of families below the poverty line decreased 6.1 percent.  Crime rates have dropped
dramatically -- 24.5 percent since 1993."
<a name="N_3_">
<p>3. </a> The complete log of results for these questions follows.  

