<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>Five Reasons We Need To Cut Taxes</strong></h3>
<h4 align="center"><strong>Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 135</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>October 18, 1996</strong></h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p></strong>The central policy debate in this fall's election has been about taxes and economic growth.  Bill
Clinton in the past has championed a reduction in federal taxation.  Bob Dole and Jack Kemp
have now made a new and much bolder call for a reduction in both the aggregate amount of
taxation as well as tax rates.  Their tax package is the central part of a plan to boost our current
2.3 percent rate of economic growth.  These calls for cutting taxes are correct, for five key
reasons.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>1.</strong> <strong>Democrats and Republicans Have Made a Commitment to the American People in the
Past Two Elections.</strong> These commitments have been cornerstones around which Bill Clinton built
his electoral victory in 1992 and the Republicans built their Congressional victory in 1994.  For
that matter, George Bush promised to hold the line on taxes in 1988.  The American people voted
for these candidates on the expectation that they would deliver on their tax promises.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Bush and Clinton of course failed to deliver what they promised and in fact produced just the
opposite -- hundreds of billions of dollars in new taxes.  The 104<sup>th</sup> Congress elected in 1994 tried
to deliver on its promise of tax relief, but it was vetoed by President Clinton.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The American people deserve what they have entrusted politicians to deliver -- much needed tax
relief.  And politicians should be mindful of the retaliation voters exacted at the polls after both
the Bush and Clinton reversals.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>2. A Responsible Congress Will Mean That The Tax Cut Will Have the Requisite Spending
Cuts and the Budget Will Balance.</strong> In the past, while tax cuts have generated some new
revenues by virtue of the economic growth they generated, Congress has balked at making the
spending cuts needed to fully pay for these cuts.  Thus, for example, in the 1980's the Congress
passed President Reagan's proposed tax cuts, but then never finished the spending cut job that
was needed.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The 104<sup>th</sup> Congress has shown they are committed and can craft packages to make a significant
reduction in the growth of government.  The new crop of freshmen elected in 1994 recognized the
futility -- proven numerous times in recent years -- of raising taxes to balance the budget.  Last
year, Congress cut tens of billions of dollars in appropriations bills that Bill Clinton signed and
proposed hundreds of billions of dollars more in cuts in the reconciliation bill that the President
vetoed.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>And of course, beyond the fact that we now have a more responsible Congress, the next President
of the United States will have a line-item veto with which he can cut pork barrel spending.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>3. The Take-Home Pay of Too Many Americans Has Been Stagnant Over The Past Several
Decades.</strong> One of the key themes of all major Presidential contenders in 1996 -- from Pat
Buchanan to Bill Clinton to Bob Dole -- has been the need for increasing GDP growth and raising
stagnant incomes.  A good target would be a return to the nearly 4% rate of real GDP growth
during the Reagan years, 1981-1988.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Concerns about aggregate growth are in turn translated down into worries about stagnant wages. 
While incomes have stagnated for many, the same is not true for government.  The "take-home
pay" for the federal government (total revenues) rose 82 percent in real terms from 1973 to 1996. 
All this new revenue, of course, was reflected in spending.  In 1996, the federal government will
spend approximately 89 percent more in inflation-adjusted terms than it did in 1973.  Not many
American families can boast such a staggering increase in their consumption patterns over the past
23 years.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Clearly, part of the "incomes puzzle" that economists have pondered has been caused by the great
increase in societal resources being absorbed by government.  If government can relinquish its
grip on at least some of its share of the economy, numerous studies have shown that higher
growth rates will result.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>4. Taxes On the American Public Are Too High.</strong> While a host of economic arguments can be
made on behalf of the idea of cutting taxing and spending, there is a simple fairness issue as well. 
Government today is taking too much of the money earned by Americans.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In 1996, the federal government will take over $1.4 trillion from taxpayers.  According to new
data from the Department of Commerce, federal, state, and local states consumed a record share
of GDP last year (higher even than at the height of World War II).  Thus, the average American
today pays more in taxes than they do for food, clothing, and housing combined.<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a> And defenders
of big government always forget the fact that the money belongs to the people.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>For the future, over the period 1997 through 2002, absent policy changes, the federal government
will take an estimated <em>$10.2 trillion</em> from taxpayers.<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a> While some have labeled Dole's tax cut
proposal as risky, the real threat to the American economy comes not from trimming taxes by a
total of $550 billion between now and 2002, but by the damage that can be caused by the $10.2
trillion scheduled to be taken.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong>5. We Owe It To Our Children.</strong> Long-term projections for federal entitlement finances are
dismal.  Both the Medicare and Social Security systems will face financing crises after the turn of
the century.  A properly designed tax cut that stimulates a long-term increase in economic growth,
combined with a reduction in government expenditures and entitlement reform is the only path to
restore the long-term financial security of our children.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Proponents of the status quo will argue that we can't cut taxes, because we can't reduce the
growth of government.  Additionally, they will make the claim that economic improvement can be
made through greater government involvement in the economy.  The reality is, however, that the
key to long-term economic growth lies in the hands of the private sector as it always has.  It is
time to shift more of our resources back where they belong.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong><u>Endnotes</strong></u><a name="N_1_">

<p>1. </a> See John Berthoud, "The Moral Imperative for a Tax Cut," Arlington, VA: The Alexis de
Tocqueville Institution, AdTI Issue Brief Number 114, November 1995. <a name="N_2_">

<p>2. </a> Paul Beckner (Citizens for a Sound Economy), "Dole's Plan a Winner," <em>USA Today</em>, August
15, 1996. <a name="N_3_">

<p>3. </a> The Office of Management &amp; Budget, <em>Historical Tables</em>, <em>FY 1997 Budget</em>, Table 1.1.

</body>
</html>
