<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h4 align="center"><strong><u>The Lessons of Gramm-Rudman-Hollings</u></strong></h4>

<p align="center">John E. Berthoud

<p align="center">Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>As the nation grapples with the federal deficit dilemma, it is critical that we understand the nature
of the problem and the limits to statutory remedies for it.  The Gramm-Rudman-Hollings deficit
reduction law provides the best example to date of these limits.

<p>Historically, the whole problem of deficit spending arose because of the Keynesian revolution. 
Keynes work in the 1930's led to the removal of the former taboo on deficit finance by convincing
leaders that governments, unlike households, do not have to maintain budget balance.  He claimed
that much of the debt run by government is burdenless, since we owe it to ourselves.  Government
fiscal policy should, according to Keynes, be counter-cyclical -- deficits or surpluses should be
strategically used to offset the natural oscillations of the economy.

<p>The problem came because while the theory looked good on the blackboards of Cambridge,
politicians got much greater short-term benefit from deficits than they did from surpluses.  Soon
after Keynes introduced his ideas, demands by constituents for spending and low taxes coupled
with little public concern (and often little understanding) about deficits or something called
"counter-cyclical policy" made unbalanced budgets natural for re-election driven politicians. 
Thus, the federal government has run deficits in 31 of the past 33 years.

<p>However, when deficits hit $200 billion in the early 1980's, there was finally motivation for
Congress to seek to reverse this pattern.  Partly out of true concern over such shocking numbers
and partly to have something to show to a public that was finally cognizant of the issue,
Gramm-Rudman was first passed in 1985.  The law altered the federal budget process by
attempting to make fighting deficits the primary consideration in the decisions of politicians.  The
timing and procedures of the budget process were revamped, deficit targets were set and enforced
through a new process called  "sequestration."  Sequestration was the elimination of any excess
deficit solely through spending cuts; half from some domestic programs -- entitlements and many
programs were exempt from cuts -- and half from defense.  Besides the specifics, the law itself
was to aid the fight as a symbol of the determination of the government.  The law was re-passed
in 1987 with rolled back deficit targets.

<p>There was great fanfare surrounding the law and we probably won't do much better statutorily
(even though Gramm-Rudman was flawed because of such problems as exempting large parts of
the budget from sequestration and because of its lack of efficacy once the fiscal year began).  So
the question remains, what did Gramm-Rudman do during its five year history until it met its
untimely death in the 1990 Budget Act?

<p>It is not enough to look at deficit or spending trends during the Gramm-Rudman era and
depending on the pattern one sees conclude that Gramm-Rudman worked or didn't.  After all,
there are too many other variables besides the nature of the budget process itself affecting these
aggregate numbers, including the rate of unemployment, the rate of economic growth, inflation,
and the Soviet military threat to name a few.  The task for social scientists is to isolate the role of
particular casual variables and undertake "counterfactual analysis" -- what would the world have
been like if everything else stayed the same but there was no Gramm-Rudman?  To achieve this,
historical trends of the relationship between relevant independent variables (all variable that
impact taxing, spending and deficits such as the variables for the domestic state of the economy,
variables for the foreign military threat, and variables for the political make-up of the U.S.
government) and dependent variables (taxes, spending and deficits) need to be established,
baselines then have to be created for what budgeting would have been like without
Gramm-Rudman and then the resulting estimates of spending, taxing, and deficits have to be
compared to actual history.

<p>The research for my just-completed dissertation did just this.  Through my regression analyses, a
series of interviews with budget insiders, and borrowing on the regression findings of Sung-Deuk
Hahm, Mark Kamlet, David Mowery and Tsai-Tsu Su, I was able to draw several conclusions:

<p>1. In terms of Gramm-Rudman's impact on deficits, the law possibly did have an effect, but only a
small one, along the lines of $15 billion per year, mainly through limiting spending.  The second
version of the law had more impact on deficits than did the original 1985 version.

<p>2. In terms of budgetary gamesmanship, Gramm-Rudman definitely spawned some, and possibly a
quite significant amount of budgetary chicanery.  Beyond abuse of the annual margin of error,
which was supposed to be a cushion for economic changes, but turned out to be simply a $10
billion extension of the deficit target, there was a statistically significant shift in spending from
programs subject to sequestration to those that were exempt.  Proponents of the former were
simply at a strategic disadvantage vis-a-vis supporters of the latter.  There also were numerous
small games (that I could find no macro statistically significant evidence for, but which interviews
with key budget players linked directly to the law) such as shifting programs off-budget and
shifting government pay days into the previous year when writing a budget so as to meet the
current year Gramm-Rudman target.  One Senate staffer, when discussing a shifted payday stated,
"Clearly the shifted payday was entirely Gramm-Rudman.  That was gamesmanship to deal with
an outlay imbalance.  You shift it into another year to free up space in this year's budget.  It was
part of a pattern of games invented during the Gramm-Rudman age."  Another staffer added,
"The law was the driving force.  The focus became how you meet the targets, not how you reduce
the deficit.  Reducing the deficit became a secondary consideration."

<p>Of course, by far the biggest game, and the downfall of the law, derived from the fact that it was
statutory and thus the targets could be rolled back when the political pressure got too high.  Most
probably, no matter what the scheme, politicians will find a way to play with the numbers to some
degree and not do absolutely the right thing.  But when a budget balancing law is only statutory,
this opens up a whole new dimension of games and can lead to the complete undoing of legislative
intent.  Such is the case here as the original law promised $0 deficits by now but of course we are
saddled with $300 billion-plus deficits, as far as the eye can see.

<p>Thus, proponents of controlling deficits by law should recognize the limits of statutory remedies. 
The meager results of Gramm-Rudman prove this.  If we really want to address the deficit, it is
time to amend the United States Constitution and permanently re-instate on politicians the
discipline of the pre-Keynesian era.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This article, slightly abridged, appeared in <em>The Waterbury Republican-American</em>, June 7, 1993
("The Failure of Gramm-Rudman-Hollings Demonstrates Limits of Statutory Remedies," Page
13A.)
</body>
</html>
