<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">The Moral Imperative for a Tax Cut</h3>
<h4 align="center">Dr. John E. Berthoud, Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No. 114</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center">November 20, 1995</h4>

<p><hr>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Congressional Democrats and some moderate Republicans have tried to make the case that while
the government is going through the "rigors" of lowering the growth of federal spending, it should
not be cutting taxes.  The argument is that at a time when some people have to take the pain of a
lost government job or a cutback in federal benefits, others should not get a reduction in taxes.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This argument fails on two very significant grounds: economic and political.  Either of these
provide sufficient reason for Congress and the President to enact the tax cuts being currently
proposed.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">The Economic Case

<p>In terms of economics, over the past twenty years, about the only grouping in society that has
done truly well in terms of income is government.  While incomes rose during the expansion years
of the 1980's, for many Americans over the entire period since 1973, income growth has been flat. 
Among the lowest forty percent of income earners, between 1973 and 1993, annual income
growth declined by about half a percentage point.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a> President Clinton and Labor Secretary Reich
have made concern for boosting incomes, particularly of the middle-class, a central theme of their
speeches.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>While incomes have stagnated for many, the same is not true for government.  The "take-home
pay" for the federal government (total revenues) rose 58 percent in real terms over the 1973-1993
period.  By 1995, the federal government was collecting approximately $1.346 trillion, 75 percent
more (in real terms) than 1973.  This new revenue, of course, was reflected in spending.  In 1995,
the federal government spent 88 percent more in inflation-adjusted terms than it did in 1973.<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a>
Not many American families can boast such a staggering increase in their consumption patterns
over a comparable period.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><img src="moralimp.gif" width="481" height="374" align="top" >

<p>Clearly, part of the "incomes puzzle" that economists have pondered has been caused by the great
increase in societal resources being absorbed by government.  If government can relinquish its
grip on at least some of its share of the economy, numerous studies have shown that higher
growth rates will result.<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">Politics: Keeping Faith With the American People

<p>In terms of politics, the American people in 1990 and 1993 were sold a bad bill of goods.  Two
Presidents (one Republican and one Democrat) and the Congress proposed a bargain.  If the
American public agreed to hundreds of billions of dollars in new taxes, Washington would cut
spending and bureaucrats.  The end result would be deficit reduction, or so the public was told.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The American people certainly upheld their end of the bargain, forking over ever-greater amounts
of their take-home pay.  What has Washington done?  Adjusting for inflation, non-defense
discretionary spending was 23 percent higher in 1995 than 1990.  The federal government spent
approximately $282 billion on domestic, non-entitlement programs in 1995 which is eight percent
higher in real terms than in 1993 when President Clinton assumed office.  What cuts that have
come over this five year period have come from defense.  In inflation-adjusted terms, the nation
spent 24 percent less on defense in 1995 than in 1990.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Like total spending, the bureaucracy of domestic agencies, far from contracting, has actually
grown over the past five years.   Since 1990, non-DOD employment has risen by 16,000 to a total
of 1,184,000.<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a> This increase has come despite protests from public employee union leaders that
the federal government has already been cutting their ranks to the bone.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Quite simply, in executing these budget deals, Washington politicians once again broke faith with
the American people.  Tax dollars were extorted for deficit reduction, but they ended up simply
fueling the growth of government.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The tax cuts proposed in Congress will only partly offset the hundreds in billions in new taxes
now being taken from the American people because of the 1990 and 1993 budget deals. 
According to the Congressional Budget Office, the 1990 tax hike increased taxes by .54 percent
of GDP.  The 1993 tax hike increased taxes by .73 percent of GDP.  The proposed tax cut would
only lower taxes by .4 percent of GDP.<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a> Thus, these tax cuts will only roll back one-third of the
tax increases that have already been enacted in this decade.  Total federal revenues will rise from
$1.357 trillion this year to $1.820 trillion in 2002 -- hardly a recipe for starving the government.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Bill Clinton and the Republican Congress were both elected on platforms of change.  The best
change they can make is to right the wrongs of these two previous budget deals and follow
through on the promises made in the 1992 and 1994 campaigns to cut taxes.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><u>Notes</u>
<a name="N_1_">
<p>1. </a> John Cassidy, "Who Killed the Middle Class?" <em>The New Yorker</em>, October 16, 1995.
<a name="N_2_">
<p>2. </a> Figures from the Historical Tables of the President's FY 1996 budget.
<a name="N_3_">
<p>3. </a> For findings on the relationship between taxes and economic growth, see Richard Vedder, 
"The Impact of State and Local Taxes on American Economic Growth," Chapter 1 in <em>The Crisis
in America's States Budgets</em>, The American Legislative Exchange Council, 1993; John E.
Berthoud, "Weld vs. Weicker: The Tax Cutter Wins," <em>The Hartford Courant</em>, November 21,
1993, Page C1; "Economists Now Agree: Taxes Have Major Effect on Job Growth and Business
Location," <em>Minnesota Business Views</em>, March, 1988, Page 8; Morgan Reynolds, "Taxation and
Economic Growth: The Emerging Consensus Among the Experts," Texas A &amp; M University,
Paper for The National Center for Policy Analysis, May, 1985; and Eric M. Engen and Jonathan
Skinner, "Fiscal Policy and Economic Growth," Working Paper No. 4223 of the National Bureau
of Economic Research, December, 1992.
<a name="N_4_">
<p>4. </a> See John Berthoud, "Federal Civilian Employment Trends in the 1990's," Arlington, VA: The
Alexis de Tocqueville Institution, AdTI Issue Brief Number 104, August 1995.
<a name="N_5_">
<p>5. </a> Daniel Mitchell, "How Congress's $245 Billion Tax Cut Repeals Just One-third of the 1990
and 1993 Tax Hikes," <em>Heritage Foundation Committee Brief No. 20</em>, October 19, 1995.
