<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">"How Special Interest Politics Slows Tax Reform"</h3>
<h4 align="center"><em>The Indianapolis Star</em>, Sunday, September 1, 1996, Page D3.</h4>
<h4 align="center">John Berthoud, Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The fortunes of the tax reform movement -- based around the idea of flattening marginal tax rates
-- have waxed and waned over the past couple of years since Dick Armey introduced his flat tax
bill in 1994.  The flat tax concept was perhaps the most ballyhooed idea in Washington politics in
1995, but it suffered a slow-down in political momentum in the early part of 1996.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>However, hopes for reformers have been reinvigorated by Bob Dole's tax proposal and his
promise that this package is the first step on the road to meaningful reform.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The idea of tax reform has great appeal, so the natural question arises, why have there been any
slippages in forward movement since 1994?  The answer lies in the politics surrounding the issue. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Most significantly, Washington special interests who believe they benefit from the status quo have
endeavored to slow the progress of tax reform.  And none has had a bigger presence in the battle
over tax reform than the 750,000-member National Association of Realtors.  The NAR's role in
this debate sheds light on what is wrong with business-as-usual in Washington.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The driving force for the Realtors' position is of course the home mortgage interest deduction. 
Such a deduction would disappear under the flat tax proposals of Dick Armey and Steve Forbes
and that has the Realtors' Washington lobbyists worried.  The NAR views the one out of four
households in America that takes the home mortgage interest deduction on their tax return as a
natural constituency and has tried to use this group as leverage.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>During the presidential primary season, an NAR-front group euphemistically called the Coalition
to Preserve Home Ownership spent hundreds of thousands of dollars of ads decrying the effects
on the housing market of a flat tax which would end the home mortgage interest deduction.  The
ads compared the effects of eliminating the home mortgage interest deduction to that of a tornado
or other natural disaster.  The Realtors undertook mailings to home owners (especially in key
primary states), created video tapes, and even made audiotapes peddling their message on the flat
tax.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Inside the 104<sup>th</sup> Congress, besides having to fight Armey's flat tax, the Realtors have had to
contend with other ideas such as a 1995 Senate Finance Committee proposal which would have
paid for a pro-growth tax rate cut by lowering the limit for deductible interest on mortgages from
$1 million to $250,000.  In response to pressure from the Realtors, politicians, including many on
the key Senate tax-writing committees, fell into line and came out against lowering the mortgage
deduction limit.  The NAR, after all, contributes hundreds of thousands of dollars every year to
congressional campaigns.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Besides these special efforts, the Realtors have regularly brought forth studies purporting to show
the beneficial impact on the housing market.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But any adverse impact of a flat tax on the real estate market will be offset by lower interest rates
which will occur because a flat tax ends taxation of all interest.  Professors Robert Hall and Alvin
Rabushka write, "The parallel removal of interest deduction and interest taxation under the flat
tax will bring about lower interest rates.  Lower interest rates reduce monthly mortgage
payments, which offsets the loss of mortgage interest deduction for most taxpayers."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>John Golob, an economist with the Kansas City Federal Reserve Bank, projects mortgage interest
rates would drop from 8% to 6% on 30-year home mortgages under a flat tax.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Will a stronger economy and lower interest rates completely make up for the loss of the
deduction?  Perhaps not in all cases, but consider the example of Canada which has no home
mortgage interest deduction but has a rate of home ownership that is similar to that in the United
States.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The facts notwithstanding, the Washington office of the NAR has fought against the flat tax tooth
and nail.  The actions of the Realtors during the 104<sup>th</sup> Congress should not surprise us.  Their
50-person Washington office has a $7 million budget and their power in past tax reform battles is
legendary.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In the 1986 tax reform effort, brief consideration was given to ending the home mortgage interest
deduction by Treasury officials, but President Reagan, after being brow-beaten by NAR lobbyists,
gave in on the deduction in a speech before the Realtors.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>As the prospects for reform are again on the rise, we should expect a reinvigorated attack by
groups such as the NAR.  As in 1986, it will take real political courage and leadership to face to
the special interests, but if it can be done, the American people will benefit greatly.  And the
consequent political rewards for those who bring us tax reform could be even greater.
</body>
</html>
