<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">Ending State &amp; Local Income Tax Deductibility</h3>
<h4 align="center">John E. Berthoud</h4>
<h4 align="center">Vice President, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Free-market economists have long made the argument that individuals respond to incentives.  This
basic assumption is at the core of the entire flat tax movement.  There are many clear examples of
this in the private sector but the public sector follows the same dictates of rationality.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The 1986 federal tax reform created a disparity in federal tax treatment of state and local income
and sales taxes.  Prior to that, both were deductible on federal tax returns.  The 1986 reform
eliminated deductibility for state and local sales taxes but retained it for income and property
taxes.  For state politicians, many argued that this would create incentives for them to look more
to the income tax (property taxes are primarily local), since the net effect of raising a dollar of
revenue this way would be less painful (on the face of it) to their constituents.  After all,
constituents could continue to write off some of what they paid in state income tax, but this was
no longer true of sales taxes.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Analysis of state revenue legislation in recent years and in the final years before tax reform
indicates that politicians in the states have indeed responded to these incentives and have altered
their preferences between these two tax sources.  When states look to raise taxes, the income tax
has become much more popular relative to the sales tax.  In 1984-1986 (the final three years
before federal tax reform), income tax increases represented 30 percent of all sales or personal
income tax hikes enacted by the states.  By 1992-1994, that figure had risen to 43 percent.  In
1984 for instance, there were 13 sales tax increases adopted by states and only two income tax
increases.  Ten years later, there were 17 income tax increases but only 10 sales tax increases.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Likewise, when states are cutting taxes, prior to tax reform, income tax cuts were far more
popular among state politicians than sales tax cuts, but no more.  In the three years prior to tax
reform, income tax cuts represented 73 percent of all sales or personal income tax cuts.  That
figure dropped to 50 percent for the 1992-1994 period.  Again, 1984 and 1994 illustrate the point
-- in the former year, income tax cuts outnumbered sales tax cuts by a ratio of 2 to 1.  By 1994,
there were exactly as many of each.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>There are two fundamental problems -- economic and political -- with the federal government
leading states by the nose to shift their tax base towards income taxes.  First, this disparity in
deductibility encourages states to utilize taxes on productive activity rather than consumption and
the former are more economically damaging.  Comparative analysis by Dr. Richard Vedder of
Ohio University has shown that there is a very strong inverse statistical relationship between
income tax changes in the states and economic growth.  Vedder found only a weak inverse link
between sales taxes and economic growth.  Vedder's conclusion: "Policymakers can improve the
rate of economic growth by moving towards lower taxes on income."

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>But beyond economics, in leading states to enact one kind of tax over another, the federal
government is engaging in a type of subtle coercion that undermines our federalist system.  As De
Tocqueville argued, if the central government, "after having established the general principles of
government . . . descended to the details of their application; and if, having regulated the great
interests of the country, it could descend to the circle of individual interests, freedom would soon
be banished from the New World."  This type of federal intrusion on state tax decisions is exactly
the type of arrogance that helped fuel the voter rebellion of 1994.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The solution to the problem is not a return to the deductibility of the sales tax, but elimination of
deductibility for all taxes.  Deductibility of any taxes provides incentives for states to tax and
spend more than they should.  By providing approximately $50 billion a year in tax relief to those
paying state and local income and property taxes, the federal government is easing the full impact
imposed by those levies.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Besides burdening citizens with too much government, state government largesse again slows
economic growth.  Vedder and others have clearly shown in cross-state comparisons that higher
state taxing and spending is associated with lower economic growth.  Vedder has demonstrated
this through complex regression analysis, but the findings are clear in more simplistic analysis of
states.  For example, Vedder has looked at the northeast and assessed trends over the past several
decades.  He points out that in 1960 New York levied a higher tax burden on its citizens than
surrounding states and while neighboring states raised taxes over the next three decades, New
York raised them even more, so the differential widened.  The result was that New York's rate of
per capita income growth was less than any of its neighbors.  New Jersey's per capita income,
below New York in 1960, surpassed it by 1990.  High-tax New York politicians in 1986 fought
for deductibility of taxes because there were political benefits from making their tax increases less
onerous.  The people of New York, however, ended up losers.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Should Congress and the President ever get serious about tax reform, there are many special
breaks that must be eliminated.  It is hard to imagine that elimination of many would have greater
overall economic benefit than elimination of the deduction for state and local taxes, most
importantly, the income tax.

<table border cellpadding=5 width="80%">
<tr>
<td colspan="2" align="center" valign="top" width="75%">Table 1. Income Tax Increases &amp; Decreases: Before &amp; After Tax Reform</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">Of all increases before, income taxes were:</td>
<td align="right" valign="top" width="24%">30.0%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">Of all increases after, income taxes were:</td>
<td align="right" valign="top">43.0%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">Of all decreases before, income taxes were:</td>
<td align="right" valign="top">72.6%</td></tr>
<tr>
<td valign="top">Of all decreases after, income taxes were:</td>
<td align="right" valign="top">49.6%</td></tr></table>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>An edited version of this article appeared in <em>Investor's Business Daily</em>: "Subsidizing High Tax
Rates" March 29, 1996, Page A2.
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
