<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>Are Human Health and the Environment Partisan?</strong></h3>
<h4 align="center">John Shanahan</h4>
<h4 align="center">Vice President and Counsel, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No.  136</strong></h4>
<h4 align="center"><strong>October 21, 1996</strong></h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>Summary</strong>

<p>An analysis of Federal Election Commission records and internal Sierra Club documents reveals
the often partisan nature of environmental politics.  Environmental Political Action Committees
have spent $539,720 in the 1995-96 election cycle.  Of total PAC spending, 95.2% was spent to
aid Democrats and Independents, or to defeat Republicans.  In California, which had more
candidates supported by the PACs (37 of them, or 68.5% of the delegation) than any other state,
every candidate receiving aid is Democrat while the only candidate against whom money was
spent is Republican.  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Sierra Club spent $313,326.  Of incumbents it endorsed, 90.9% are Democrat, 4.5% are
Independents, and 4.5% are Republicans. Of incumbents it targeted to defeat, 4% are Democrats
and 96% are Republicans.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>I. Introduction</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The growing rhetoric by the environmental community that they must "take back" Congress raises
the question: take back from whom?  The membership of environmental organizations is made up
of large numbers from both major parties.  For instance, the National Wildlife Federation reports
that thirty percent of its members are Republicans.  To explore if environmental groups are
partisan or bi-partisan in their political support of candidates, this study examines the amount of
money given by environmental Political Action Committees (PACs), as well as the number of
candidates from each party endorsed by the politically active Sierra Club.  The findings indicate
strong leanings by these groups toward Democrats.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>II.  Methodology</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>This paper looks at the funding patterns of environmental PACs as well as internal campaign
strategy documents of the Sierra Club to discern a pattern of partisan support.  Funding was
determined by analyzing the latest  Federal Election Commission (FEC) records available of the
eight environmental groups that expended funds for the 1995-96 election cycle.<a href="#N_1_"><sup>(1)</sup></a> The analysis
includes not only contributions to candidates, but also independent expenditures on behalf of, or
against, candidates.  The groups reviewed were:<a href="#N_2_"><sup>(2)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Sierra Club Political Action Committee

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>League of Conservation Voters Political Action Committee (LCV Earth Fund)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>California League of Conservation Voters Political Action Committee

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>New York League of Conservation Voters Political Action Committee (Education fund)

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Oregon League of Conservation Voters Political Action Committee

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Citizens for Waters Political Action Committee

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Ecology and Environment Committee 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Environment and Political Reform Political Action Committee

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Three internal documents of the Sierra Club also were reviewed.  The first is a June 1, 1996
memorandum on the subject of "Guide on Use of Various Kinds of Money," from the President of
the Sierra Club to "WOE Managers, WOE Team, Field Offices, WOE CSC, Conservation
Government Committee, EVEC Steering Committee, Chapters, and Chapter Staff in joint federal
/ state project locations."  

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The second document is a June 3, 1996 memorandum on the subject of campaign strategy from
the Sierra Club's Conservation Director to the "Chapter Chairs, Chapter Conservation chairs,
Group Chairs, Board of Directors, RCC Chairs, WOE CSC, EVEC CSC, Conservation
Government Committee, Senior Volunteer list, Chapter Staff, and Conservation Staff." 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The third document is a June 3, 1996 list of Congressional candidates entitled "Sierra Club Tier 1
Priority List."  This list identifies candidates that the Sierra Club opposes or supports. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>III.  Results of Analysis </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Federal Election Commission records on PAC money from 8 environmental groups showed:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Total money expended by the eight PACs: <em>$539,720</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Percent Of Contributions directly to or on behalf of campaigns (not including funds spent to
defeat specific candidates):

<p>Democrat <em>90.3%</em>

<p>Republican <strong> <em></strong>6.7%</em>

<p>Independent    <em>3.0%</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Percent of money spent to <em>defeat</em> specific candidates (which equaled <em>28.0%</em> of total PAC
spending) spent against each party:

<p>Democrat       <em>0.0%</em>

<p>Republican <em>100.0%</em>

<p>Independent     <em>0.0%</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Percent of total PAC money spent that was "anti-Republican" (contributions to or on behalf of
Republican opponents or spent independently against Republican candidates):  <em>95.2%<strong></em> </strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>States in which the most PAC funds were expended:

<p>Oregon <em>$311,090   or 57.6%  </em>

<p>California <em>$  53,158 or   9.9%</em>

<p>Illinois <em>$  26,854 or   5.0%</em>

<p>Michigan<em>$  20,706 or   3.8%</em>

<p>New York <em>$  20,391 or   3.8%</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>In California, which had more candidates supported by environmental PACs than any other state
(37 candidates, or 68.5% of the delegation), every candidate receiving aid is Democrat while the
only candidate against whom money was spent is Republican. 

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>IV.  Results of Sierra Club Analysis</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Sierra Club internal documents and FEC records showed:<a href="#N_3_"><sup>(3)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Total money expended: <em>$313,326</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Percent of incumbents endorsed by Sierra Club for reelection, whose seats they want to "SAVE":

<p>Democrat <em>90.9%</em>

<p>Republican   <em>4.5%</em>

<p>Independent  <strong> <em></strong>4.5%</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Percent of incumbents opposed by the Sierra Club for reelection, whose seats they want to
"TAKE BACK":

<p>Democrat  <em>4.0%</em>

<p>Republican <em>96.0%</em>

<p>Independent <strong> <em></strong>0.0%</em>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Internal Sierra Club documents make clear that the impact of environmental political activities is
much more than simply a function of funds expended.  For instance, the Sierra Club's
Conservation Director indicated that not only is the organization running paid advertisements for
and against various candidates, but has been actively seeking to "join with Public Citizen and LCV
to generate free media around the ad buys."  The Sierra Club also is conducting a vigorous
outreach program to groups such as hunters and anglers.<a href="#N_4_"><sup>(4)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>All Sierra Club's expenditures on individual campaigns are merely the second stage of a two part
strategy.  The first part funded by the Sierra Club was the 1996 Environmental Public Education
Campaign (EPEC), which was a large public outreach campaign including media buys.  The
figures reported to the FEC merely indicate those funds which they are required by law to report
as they "now move into an effort to more directly educate voters on the political choices they face
in November."<a href="#N_5_"><sup>(5)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Sierra Club's internal documents indicate their leanings and strategies.  The internal
memorandum from the Sierra Club's Conservation Director stated, "Throughout the Presidential
primaries our volunteers in New Hampshire and Iowa 'bird dogged' the Republican candidates by
appearing at public meetings and calling in to radio shows and asking the candidates pointed
questions about the environment. . . Throughout the remainder of the year we want to encourage
volunteers to bird dog their candidates."<a href="#N_6_"><sup>(6)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The Sierra Club by implication identifies Republicans as "anti-environmentalists."  It criticized the
"Republican Study Conference" for issuing a booklet to members about the environment, stating
"we expect [to continue] to see anti-environmentalists trying to mislead the public with this
'greenscamming.'"<a href="#N_7_"><sup>(7)</sup></a>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><strong>V.  Conclusion</strong>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Environmental groups in general, and the Sierra Club in particular, tend to display strong leanings
in favor of Democrats in their financial support, endorsements, and grassroots efforts in support
of candidates.  At a time when a great deal needs to be done by both parties working together to
refocus EPA on its core mission (protecting human health and cleaning up the environment) and
away from agency proposals driven by flawed science and special interests, it is unfortunate that
major environmental groups have turned this into a partisan issue.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2"><a name="N_1_">
<p>1. </a> The information is current as of October 11, 1996.  Although groups such as the
Environmental Defense Fund, the Natural Resources Defense Council, Friends of the Earth, U.S.
Public Interest Research Group, and World Resources Institute did not contribute directly
through PACs, leaders of these organizations control the Board of Directors of the League of
Conservation Voters, which is one of the two biggest environmental PACS.
<a name="N_2_">
<p>2. </a> These groups represent all the strictly environmental PACs that were identified after a
thorough search.  No attempt was made to include non-single issue groups that devoted money
for environmental issues or media spots, even though substantial amounts of money have been
spent this way; these types of expenditures are not identified in Federal Election Commission
records in a manner that allows them to be broken out.  Note that the bulk of funds from the eight
organizations came from the Sierra Club PAC and League of Conservation Voters PAC.
<a name="N_3_">
<p>3. </a> Based on Sierra Club document No.  3 discussed in the methodology section of text, entitled
"Sierra Club Tier 1 Priority List," June 3, 1996.
<a name="N_4_">
<p>4. </a> Sierra Club document No.  2, discussed in the methodology section of the text, on the subject
of campaign strategy, June 3, 1996.
<a name="N_5_">
<p>5. </a> Ibid.
<a name="N_6_">
<p>6. </a> Ibid.
<a name="N_7_">
<p>7. </a> Ibid.
</body>
</html>
