<title></title>
</head>
<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center"><strong>The EPA vs.  Clean Air</strong></h3>
<h4 align="center">John C. Shanahan</h4>
<h4 align="center">Vice President and Counsel, The Alexis de Tocqueville Institution</h4>
<h4 align="center">AdTI ISSUE BRIEF - No.  133</h4>
<h4 align="center">October 11, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center">Summary

<p align=:left">The Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) last year helped create an innovative state-led group
to deal with the problem of smog in our cities that could have been a model for dealing with
highly technical environmental problems.  Now EPA itself stands as the biggest barrier to the
group's efforts to recommend more effective, cost-conscious, approaches to on-going progress in
reducing the nation's smog. Although the actions taken as a result of this group's work were
supposed to be based on the first comprehensive scientific assessment of the problem and
designed to meet specific air quality goals, EPA has consistently undermined the process.  Now
this initiative, which likely will cost billions of dollars and may be counterproductive, stands as a
model of how not to govern.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p><strong><hr>
</strong>
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>The reinventing government initiative, at least in the environmental arena, has been a failure.  A
classic case in point is the initiative begun last year when the Environmental Protection Agency
(EPA) assembled a group to address America's smog problem (low-level ozone).  To date, the
process has been the fastest, most comprehensive, and decentralized air pollution analysis to date. 
Yet after having created this innovative process, the Administration, through a variety of means,
has undermined what it created.  Now this initiative represents more of a threat to the
environment and economy than a solution.

<p>Smog levels have been falling steadily across the country for some time, with a 12 percent
decrease over the last decade.  Even hazy Los Angeles has 25 percent fewer unsafe ozone days
than a few years ago.  And many major Northeastern cities, including New York City and
Washington, DC, have 70 percent fewer unsafe ozone days than 15 years ago.  In short, air
quality is substantially better across the country and rapid progress continues.  Instead of letting
that progress continue unimpeded, however, EPA last year made the questionable decision to
intervene and may have upset the apple cart. 

<p>EPA set up an advisory group called the Ozone Transport Assessment Group (OTAG), made up
of state environmental officials from the eastern half of the country.  The group has been meeting
since last June to model the way ozone travels across jurisdictions and then develop solutions
based on these models.  The group's recommendations will carry great weight in the directions
taken by States, which must make enforceable commitments by changing their State
Implementation Plans (SIPs) to meet current standards.  So the integrity of the process is
important because implementing OTAG could have enormous implications for both the
environment and economy.

<p>OTAG held promise because it was run outside of Washington -- usually a good idea -- and the
recommendations were supposed to be based on solid science -- always a good idea. 
Unfortunately, what could have been a model for solving other complex, highly technical
environmental problems in the future has become mired in controversy and now represents a good
example of how not to govern.

<p>There are three main reasons OTAG has been undermined.  The first is that EPA may be trying to
skirt the requirements of an important law called the Federal Advisory Committee Act which
applies to groups advising federal agencies.  Industry groups have concerns over the legal
accountability of this unofficial organization and the lack of representation of those most affected
by the deliberations.  The suspicions are compounded by EPA's promise to spend $100,000 to
hire a public relations firm that would sell OTAG's so far nonexistent recommendations to the
public.  The PR firm will "educate" the public and press about the need for and benefits of
whatever measures OTAG comes up with. 

<p>The second problem is EPA's unreasonable timetable.  Due to unforeseen technical problems,
OTAG has fallen behind by a few months in its modeling efforts of how ozone flows, known as
ozone transport.  Illinois EPA Director Mary Gade, who heads up the OTAG effort, recently told
the World Conference on Transportation Fuel Quality that the modeling effort was slowed down
at times to get the science right.  She now expects recommendations incorporating the models will
not be ready until "the March-April timeframe." Yet OTAG has been pressured to develop its
recommendations by this December -- even though they would be without the assistance of the
models upon which OTAG's recommendations are supposed to be based.  If they do not,  EPA
has said it will ignore any belated guidance and impose its own solution, thus encouraging OTAG
to make December recommendations regardless of the science.  EPA watchdogs are very
concerned about this drift into unsound science to set policy, which has been a severe problem in
the bureaucracy for many years.  Since adopting OTAG's recommendation would likely impose
billions of dollars in costs on the economy, it's important that the policy meets the goal of cleaner
air, at a minimum, and not act as an impediment to the progress now being made.

<p>The third problem is that EPA recently announced it will reexamine ozone National Ambient Air
Quality Standards -- which are rules implementing the Clean Air Act -- leading experts to expect
EPA will propose tightening them further based on relatively thin scientific justification.  Even on
the worst days within existing legal limits,  the health effects of smog on the most sensitive people
are now minimal -- and nonexistent for most people.  Yet tightening the standards would
dramatically raise the cost of consumer goods such as electricity, gasoline, and cars. 

<p>Moreover, such a change would mean that OTAG's solutions, which are being designed to meet
the current ozone air quality standards, would be ineffective in reaching the new tighter standards. 
Worse, they may prove counterproductive.  Since pursuing OTAG's approach may preclude
taking another approach later, there would be fewer future choices available to EPA.  For
instance, the flexibility EPA would need to meet much stricter air quality standards could be
hamstrung by agreements EPA or the states reach with industry in implementing OTAG's
recommendations.

<p>If EPA is serious about a clean and healthy environment, it should become a partner in the process
of ensuring our air quality continues to improve, instead of being an active obstacle to that goal. 
Only then would the federal government truly begin to reinvent itself.
</body>
</html>
