<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3 align="center">Firms Contend With Worst 10 Washington Regulations</h3>
<h4 align="center">By John Merline</h4>
<h4 align="center">Investor's Business Daily - August 20, 1996</h4>

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Call it the top-10 list that doesn't leave you laughing.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>Two free- market groups - the Virginia-based Alexis de Tocqueville Institution and the
Lewisville, Texas-based Institute for Policy Innovation - joined forces to ask like-minded experts
to come up with the 10 worst regulations from Washington.

<p>These rules, the report says, do little to improve the lives of Americans while costing taxpayers
and industry billions of dollars.

<p>A sampling:

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>WETLANDS REGULATIONS. The regulatory machinery to protect wetlands stems from a
24-year- old law, the Federal Water Pollution Control Act. It banned dumping dredged materials
into ''navigable'' waters without a federal permit.

<p>The law never mentioned ''wetlands,'' according to Jonathan Tolman, an environmental expert at
the Competitive Enterprise Institute.

<p>Over time, the meaning of the law stretched not only to include wetlands, but areas that aren't
even wet.

<p>Tolman says that permits to do work on wetlands take an average of more than a year to
complete, and then only a third are approved.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>OFF-LABEL DRUG USE REGULATION. Drugs approved for one use often end up getting
prescribed for others - a practice known as ''off-label'' use. It's legal to do so, but the FDA forbids
drug firms from advertising these uses.

<p>Aspirin companies, for example, can't tell people that taking the pain killer regularly can cut the
risk of heart attacks.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''By forbidding manufacturers from spreading the word, needless illnesses and deaths are
occurring,'' said Michael Herson of the de Tocqueville Institution.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>SPECIAL EDUCATION. Federal rules often force local school systems to pay for disruptive kids
who meet special education requirements.

<p>A San Diego student's parents, for example, claimed their son, who had brought a gun to school
and was suspended, was disabled. The child won his readmission.

<p>In Virginia, the U.S. Department of Education forced the state to continue to pay education costs
for expelled special-ed students, although the kids were kicked out for behavior unrelated to their
learning disabilities.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''By getting special treatment for conduct not related to their disability, special education students
are taught that they don't have to be responsible for their own behavior,'' said John Berthoud, vice
president of the de Tocqueville Institution.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>PEANUT PROGRAM. Peanuts are grown under a quota system managed by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture. Prices are supported through price and import controls.

<p>As a result, the domestic peanut market has declined. Since 1990, the food use of peanuts has
declined more than 11%, the report said.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>DRUG APPROVAL. The Food and Drug Administration claims it has sharply cut the approval
times for new drugs and medical devices. Others disagree. They say approval times are still too
long and costly, forcing many U.S. firms to do research overseas.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>SUPERFUND. ''After 15 years of Superfund, the Environmental Protection Agency has not been
able to implement the statute effectively or efficiently,'' said Steven Milloy of the Environmental
Policy Analysis Network.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''The EPA tends to exaggerate site risks, frighten communities and waste public resources,'' he
added.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>TOXICS RELEASE INVENTORY. After the 1986 Bhopal tragedy, where an accident at a
pesticide plant killed 2,000 in India, Congress passed a bill to give people information about
hazardous chemicals in their community.

<p>The law forces industries to report any chemical releases or transfers each year to a federal
inventory.

<p>The EPA says it costs each plant about $3,500 to file a report on one chemical - with a total cost
of the program pegged at $546 million. The problem: the list can include substances that pose
little or no risk to humans.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>''The benefits associated (with the program) have not been quantified, measured, or otherwise
directly or empirically evaluated,'' Milloy said.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>THE 60-40 RULE. The Department of Defense requires that no more than 40% of depot
maintenance work can be done by private firms. The Defense Department spends some $13 billion
on maintenance.

<p>Letting more private firms compete for the business could save up to $2 billion a year, argues
Loren Thompson of the de Tocqueville Institution.

<p>The other two rules on the list deal with second-hand smoke and the Delaney clause, which
banned any level of cancer-causing additives to food. As of yet, no regulations have been issued
on second-hand smoke. Congress repealed the Delaney clause last year.
</body>
</html>
