<body text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#551a8b" alink="#ff0000" bgcolor="#c0c0c0">

<p align="center"><strong><em>John Berthoud</strong></em>

<p>John E. Berthoud is Vice President of the Alexis de Tocqueville Institution in Arlington, VA
where he conducts and directs research on taxation, economic growth, education, and other
issues.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>He is also an adjunct lecturer at George Washington University, teaching graduate level courses
on budgetary politics.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>He is affiliated with several other research institutes around the country and his work and writings
have appeared in publications such as <em>The Wall Street Journal</em>, <em>The Washington Post</em>, <em>Investor's
Business Daily</em>, <em>The Washington Times</em>, <em>Forbes</em>, <em>The Public Interest</em>, and <em>Human Events</em>.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p>He received his Ph.D. from Yale University for his dissertation on the impact and economic
theory of the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings deficit reduction law.  He also holds an M.A. in
International Affairs from Columbia University and a B.A. from Georgetown University.

<br wp="br1"><br wp="br2">
<p align="center"><em><strong>Phone: (703) 351-4969</em></strong>

